captions: Aberts_Towhee, Large, ground-dwelling sparrow with a thick bill and long tail. Brown overall with warm reddish brown undertail. Pale bill contrasts with dark face.
Aberts_Towhee, Found in dry habitats with dense woody vegetation, often along streams or dry streambeds.
Aberts_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow with a restricted range in brushy woodlands of the southwestern U.S. and extreme northwest Mexico.
Aberts_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and long tail. Brown overall with contrasting pale bill and dark face.
Aberts_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow typically found on or near the ground. The black patch around the bill is distinctive.
Aberts_Towhee, Occurs in cottonwood, willow, and mesquite brush mainly along tributaries of the Colorado River; also found in salt cedar and marshes.
Aberts_Towhee, Often uses a "double-scratch" technique to forage, hopping backwards and scratching with both feet to uncover prey underneath litter.

Acadian_Flycatcher, One of the largest members of the Empidonax group. The forehead is rather flat, sloping gently up giving the head a peaked look. Olive above with 2 pale wingbars and a narrow eyering.
Acadian_Flycatcher, Relatively large flycatcher with long wings. Olive above and yellowish below, with 2 pale wingbars, and a thin white eyering.
Acadian_Flycatcher, Song is an explosive, two-parted "ker-chip!" or "peet-sah!"
Acadian_Flycatcher, Olive and yellowish flycatcher with a long and broad bill, especially noticeable from below. Some individuals appear more yellow below than others.
Acadian_Flycatcher, Common flycatcher of deciduous forests often near water.

Acadian_Flycatcher, One of the largest members of the Empidonax group. The forehead is rather flat, sloping gently up giving the head a peaked look. Olive above with 2 pale wingbars and a narrow eyering.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a clownish face. Males have a red cap and whitish forehead. In flight, note white rump and wing patches.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Clown-faced woodpecker with a black back. Females have a black cap and the red is restricted to the back of the head unlike males.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a clownish face. Males have a red cap and whitish forehead. In flight, note white rump and wing patches.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Gathers acorns by the hundreds and wedges them into holes they've made in a tree trunk or telephone pole, storing them for later use.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Males in Colombia have reduced red crowns while females lack red crowns all together. The throat is yellower than individuals farther north in the United States.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a clownish face. Males have a red cap and whitish forehead. In flight, note white rump and wing patches.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Individuals from Costa Rica and Panama have brighter yellow throats. Some individuals also have red feathers on the chest.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Found in oak and pine-oak woodlands. Creates granaries in dead trees, storing acorns and other seeds for later use.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a clownish face. Males have a red cap and whitish forehead. In flight, note white rump and wing patches.
Acorn_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a clownish face. Males have a red cap and whitish forehead. In flight, note white rump and wing patches.
African_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small, round head, thin bill, and square tail. Pale buff-white overall, with black crescent on nape. Note white undertail coverts.

African_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with long, square-tipped tail and thin bill. The tail is dark at the base and white at the tip; white extends all the way to the edges of the tail feathers. Note white undertail.
African_Collared-Dove, Rare in continental North America. Often found around human habitation.
African_Collared-Dove, Plumage can vary from pale gray-white to tawny-buff. Wingtips are only slightly darker than the rest of the wing and back.
African_Collared-Dove, Plumage can vary from pale gray-white to tawny-buff. Wingtips are only slightly darker than the rest of the wing and back.
African_Collared-Dove, Found in arid habitats in native range.
Alder_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a round head. Greenish olive above with 2 pale wingbars and a thin white eyering that is often difficult to see. Note white throat.
Alder_Flycatcher, Greenish olive above with 2 pale wingbars and a thin white eyering, clearly visible on this individual.
Alder_Flycatcher, Song (audible in background) is a buzzy "free beer" or "fee-bee-o," somewhat similar to Eastern Phoebe.
Alder_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a round head. Greenish olive above with 2 pale wingbars and a thin white eyering that is often difficult to see. Note white throat.
Alder_Flycatcher, From the front the white throat stands out against the gray chest band. Sometimes raises crown feathers. Eyering is very thin and sometimes not visible.
Alder_Flycatcher, Breeds in shrubby wetlands or wet thickets with alders. Extremely similar to Willow Flycatcher; song is the most reliable "field mark."
Allens_Hummingbird, Compact and stocky hummingbird. Adult males have a reddish-orange throat and an orange belly.
Allens_Hummingbird, Small and compact hummingbird. Females/immatures have a dull metallic green back and pale coppery flanks.
Allens_Hummingbird, Perched female/immature Allen's Hummingbirds can be difficult to separate from Rufous Hummingbirds.
Allens_Hummingbird, Note the very narrow tail feathers when the tail is spread. Adult males are coppery below and bronze-green above with a coppery tail.
Allens_Hummingbird, Compact and stocky hummingbird. Adult males have a reddish-orange throat and an orange belly.
Allens_Hummingbird, Though difficult to see look for narrow outer tail feathers on flying birds to separate them from Rufous Hummingbirds. This video has no audio.
Allens_Hummingbird, Females/immatures have a bronze-green back. Although subtle, note coppery eyebrow.

Allens_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are bronze-green above with paler coppery sides. They both have bits of bronze spotting on their throats, though females have more spots and a small patch of reddish orange in the center of the throat.
Allens_Hummingbird, The female builds the nest, incubates the eggs, and takes care of the nestlings without help from the male.
Allens_Hummingbird, Compact and stocky hummingbird. Adult males have a reddish-orange throat and an orange belly.

Allens_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are very difficult to separate from females/immatures Rufous Hummingbird. Separated by shape of spread tail; narrow outer tail feathers on Allen's, but wide on Rufous.
Allens_Hummingbird, Compact and stocky hummingbird. Adult males have a reddish-orange throat and an orange belly.
Allens_Hummingbird, Breeds in coastal forest, scrub, and chaparral along a narrow strip that stretches up the coast from California to southern Oregon.
Altamira_Oriole, The largest oriole in the U.S. with a stout and pointed bill. Males and females look similar and are bright orange overall with a black throat, mask, tail, and upper back.
Altamira_Oriole, A large oriole with a stout, pointed bill. Bright orange overall with a black throat, mask, tail, and upper back. Year-round resident primarily in Mexico and Central America.
Altamira_Oriole, Found in dry woodlands, open areas with scattered trees, and arid scrublands.
Altamira_Oriole, The largest oriole in the U.S. with a stout and pointed bill. Males and females look similar and are bright orange overall with a black throat, mask, tail, and upper back.
Altamira_Oriole, The largest oriole in the U.S. with a stout and pointed bill. Males and females look similar and are bright orange overall with a black throat, mask, tail, and upper back.
Altamira_Oriole, Like many other orioles, Altamira Oriole also visit fruit feeders. This video has no audio.
Altamira_Oriole, Found in areas with scattered trees and open riparian woodlands.
American_Avocet, Long-legged shorebird with a long, upturned bill. Breeding birds have a rusty head and neck and a black-and-white body.
American_Avocet, Tall shorebird with an upturned bill. Nonbreeding birds have a grayish white head.
American_Avocet, Forages in shallow wetlands. Sweeps its bill side to side through the water to catch invertebrates.
American_Avocet, In flight, note black patch on the back.
American_Avocet, Swings its long upturned bill through shallow water to catch small invertebrates.
American_Avocet, Slowly walks through wetlands shaking its foot with each step.
American_Avocet, Tall and graceful shorebird with a striking black-and-white body, a rusty head and neck, and an upturned bill. Females tend to have more sharply curved bills than males.
American_Avocet, Young leave the nest within 24 hours. Juveniles are downy with a mottled back, gaining adultlike plumage as they age. Juveniles have a straighter bill than adults.
American_Avocet, Often rests on one leg, tucking its bill under the shoulder.
American_Avocet, Often wades while foraging but also swims. Males tend to have less curve in the bill than females.
American_Avocet, Found in shallow fresh and saltwater wetlands.
American_Avocet, Swipes bill from side to side or pecks into the water to catch aquatic invertebrates and small fish.
American_Barn_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a white heart-shaped face. Gray and cinnamon above and white below, although some have cinnamon colored and spotty chests.
American_Barn_Owl, White heart-shaped face and dark eyes are distinctive.
American_Barn_Owl, During hard winters, or in times of food shortages, American Barn Owls sometimes hunt during the day, often frequenting the same open country habitats used by Northern Harriers.
American_Barn_Owl, The "Galapagos" subspecies group is white to golden-buff below, with small spots or fine brownish lines below.
American_Barn_Owl, Birds in the "Lesser Antilles" subspecies group are dark overall and are sometimes treated as a separate species or as a subspecies of Ashy-faced Owl.
American_Barn_Owl, Pale owl with large, heart-shaped facial disk. Capable of rotating head extensively. This video has no audio.
American_Barn_Owl, Long, rounded wings and short tails contribute to their loping and buoyant flight style.
American_Barn_Owl, Light underparts can make American Barn Owls look exceptionally pale in low light. Broad rounded wings give them a buoyant flight style.
American_Barn_Owl, Nests in holes in trees, cliff ledges and crevices, caves, burrows in river banks, barn lofts, church steeples, houses, and nest boxes.
American_Barn_Owl, Nests and roosts in rock crevices, holes in trees, abandoned barns and other buildings, and dense trees.
American_Barn_Owl, Pale buffy-white underparts with darker spots. Active mainly at night; sleeps in well-hidden locations during daylight.
American_Bittern, Medium-sized heron with a long, thick neck and long, pointed bill. Well camouflaged: buffy and brown, with vertical brown stripes on its neck.
American_Bittern, Medium-sized heron with a long, thick neck and long, pointed bill. Note long, black patch that extends from below the eye down the side of the neck.

American_Bittern, Produces a distinctive "pump-er-lunk" call by repeatedly inflating their throat. These low-pitched calls allow American Bitterns to communicate effectively even when blocked by dense vegetation.
American_Bittern, In flight note dark flight feathers, pale coverts, and hunchbacked look.
American_Bittern, Tucks head into a hunch and slowly lifts its feet with toes spread as it walks slowly through open areas in wetlands.
American_Bittern, Almost exclusively occupies freshwater wetlands with tall vegetation year-round. Rarely occupies coastal tidal marshes or coastal areas with low vegetation.
American_Bittern, Note white throat and long, black patch of feathers that extends from below the eye down the side of the neck.
American_Bittern, Breeds mainly in freshwater wetlands with tall vegetation.
American_Bittern, Flying style is similar to most other herons, with the neck retracted and legs trailing out behind, but American Bitterns have hurried and somewhat ungraceful wingbeats.

American_Bittern, When approached by potential predators, American Bitterns attempt to camouflage themselves by pointing their bill upwards, compressing their body feathers, and remaining as still as the surrounding vegetation.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and dull olive bill.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, In flight shows dark bluish-purple secondaries bordered by black.
American_Black_Duck, In flight shows contrasting white underwings.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, A large dabbling duck with a very dark brown body, pale gray-brown head, purple speculum, and red legs. Male has a bright yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, A large dabbling duck with a very dark brown body, pale gray-brown head, purple speculum, and red legs. Female has a dull olive bill.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, The female has a darker and duller bill than the male, but is otherwise quite similar.
American_Black_Duck, Hybridizes regularly with Mallard. Hybrid male has Mallard's iridescent green on upper part of head and American Black Duck's pale cheek.
American_Black_Duck, Dark brown body contrasting with a pale brown head and yellow bill.
American_Black_Duck, Female leads brood after they leave the nest but ducklings feed themselves.
American_Black_Duck, Often flocks with other ducks, especially Mallards.
American_Black_Duck, Sometimes forms large flocks during migration and winter.
American_Coot, Plump waterbird with a rounded head and a sloping bill. Adults are dark gray overall with a white bill tipped in a ring of black.
American_Coot, On land appears rather chickenlike. Note the long lobed toes that help propel it in the water.
American_Coot, Bulky-bodied, ducklike bird with small, pointed bill. Typically feeds from the surface of the water but sometimes dives.
American_Coot, Juveniles are pale grayish below with a pale bill.
American_Coot, With good views note the red eye and the white shield that is topped with red.
American_Coot, Right after hatching chicks have bare red spots on their heads, rusty-colored down around their head, and a red bill.
American_Coot, To get airborne, coots typically need to beat their wings while running across the water for many yards.
American_Coot, Sometimes gathers in large flocks—which can number in the thousands—during the winter.
American_Coot, Found in ponds, marshes, reservoirs, lake edges, roadside ditches, sewage treatment ponds, and saltwater inlets or salt marshes.
American_Crow, Large, all black bird with a slight gloss to the plumage, and a relatively long and thick bill.
American_Crow, Flies with a distinctive rowing motion, sometimes incorporating glides.
American_Crow, All-black bird with full-throated cawing call. Note fairly short, squared tail.
American_Crow, Darkness and glossiness of the plumage depend on lighting conditions.
American_Crow, Along the coastlines often forages at the water's edge.
American_Crow, Note rounded wings, fairly short, squared tail, and relatively small bill. Flies with a rowing motion and rarely glides.
American_Crow, Will mob raptors and other perceived threats. Note short and rounded or squared tail.
American_Crow, Often mobbed by smaller birds.
American_Crow, Often forages on the ground for invertebrates, small animals, and seeds.
American_Crow, Frequently forages at landfills and other areas with garbage.
American_Crow, Omnivorous: catches and eats small animals; also eats carrion and garbage as well as seeds, fruits, and berries.
American_Dipper, Chunky, round-bodied bird with a short tail. Adults are grayish brown overall. Breeding birds have an all dark bill.
American_Dipper, Chunky, round-bellied bird with a short tail. Some nonbreeding adults can have barred underparts and a yellowish bill.
American_Dipper, North America's only aquatic songbird—found along and in fast-flowing streams in western North America and Central America. A round-bodied bird with a short bill and short tail.
American_Dipper, Chunky, round-bellied bird with a short tail. Juveniles look similar to adults, but have barred underparts and a yellowish bill.
American_Dipper, Chunky, round-bodied bird with a short tail. Adults are grayish brown overall. Breeding birds have an all dark bill.
American_Dipper, Often seen perched on rocks in the middle of a rushing stream where they frequently bob up and down.
American_Dipper, Grayish brown bird at home in rushing streams where it forages underwater for aquatic insects.
American_Dipper, Often holds its short tail up and bounces up and down on rocks in rushing streams.
American_Dipper, Wades and swims in turbulent rocky streams. Dives beneath the water head-first with wings slightly open to forage for insects.
American_Dipper, Builds domed nests on cliff ledges, behind waterfalls, on boulders, and on dirt banks or under bridges, but always above or close to fast moving streams.

American_Flamingo, A large, unmistakable wading bird with extremely long legs, a very long neck often held in an S-shape, and a thick, uniquely shaped bill. Adult has a bright pink head, neck, tail, and wings; paler pink upperparts; a pale yellow eye; and a tricolored bill, with a whitish base, pink midsection, and black tip.
American_Flamingo, Flies with neck fully outstretched. In flight, note the black trailing edge to the wings and intense pink "armpits."

American_Flamingo, A brilliant pink bird with long legs and an exceptionally long, thin neck. Birds stride slowly through shallow water, head submerged, filtering crustaceans, mollusks, and other aquatic invertebrates from the water.
American_Flamingo, The unique bill is used to filter water for small aquatic invertebrates like crustaceans, mollusks, and insect larvae.

American_Flamingo, Juvenile looks like a monochrome version of adult, patterned in white, gray, black, and brown. Legs are gray; bill is mostly gray with a black tip. Young birds acquire full adult plumage after about three years.
American_Flamingo, A highly social species, often occurring in large foraging flocks. In flight, long neck is fully outstretched.
American_Flamingo, A highly social species that forages in large flocks and frequently nests in huge colonies.
American_Flamingo, Vocal birds give gooselike honks. Note striking black flight feathers when birds open their wings.
American_Flamingo, Feeding birds filter out small food items by using their large tongues to push water through comblike structures in their bills.

American_Golden-Plover, The very long primaries, gold-spangled upperparts, black underparts, and broad white stripe on the head and neck help to identify this shorebird in breeding plumage. The white patch does not extend below the chest, and the flanks and undertail are black, which helps to rule out other species of golden-plovers. In breeding plumage, adult males like this are crisply marked with even black on the face.

American_Golden-Plover, A teardrop-shaped shorebird with a large head, slim, short bill, and long legs. In breeding plumage, adult females have pale-mottled faces, giving them a slightly messy look compared to the crisp males.
American_Golden-Plover, Common call is a 2- or 3-parted whistle. Like some other plovers, often pauses while running to bob quickly up and back down again.

American_Golden-Plover, The large eye and bulky head combine to create a gentle expression. Fall juveniles appear scaly because of their complete set of even-aged, fresh feathers. Four primaries extend beyond the gold-spangled tertials at rest, imparting a longer primary projection to the folded wing than is found on Pacific Golden-Plover or Black-bellied Plover.
American_Golden-Plover, When viewed head-on, these slim plovers can appear quite plump, but note the long legs and slim bill. Juveniles show a dark cap that contrasts strongly with a pale eyebrow.
American_Golden-Plover, The underside of the wing is plain gray, lacking the black "wingpits" shown by Black-bellied Plover.

American_Golden-Plover, Golden-plovers have long, pointed wings and blunt tails. The rump and tail blend in with the back, distinguishing this from the pale-tailed Black-bellied Plover. Also, note the extended legs and feet that fall short of the tip of the tail.

American_Golden-Plover, Nonbreeding birds are similar to juveniles but show drabber upperparts with less crisp feather edging. The long-winged look created by four primaries extending beyond the tertials on the folded wing helps to rule out Black-bellied Plover and other golden-plover species.
American_Golden-Plover, Golden-plovers fly quickly in wheeling, well-coordinated flocks. Note the slim, pointed wings and pale gray underwings.
American_Goldfinch, Small finch with a short, conical bill and a short, notched tail. Breeding males are bright yellow with black forehead, black wings with white markings.
American_Goldfinch, Often feeds on small-seeded plants such as thistles. Breeding males have black cap, wings, and tail; bright yellow body.
American_Goldfinch, Breeding females are duller yellow beneath and more olive above than breeding males.
American_Goldfinch, Immatures are brown above and pale yellow below, shading to buff on the sides. Two buffy wingbars mark their dark wings.
American_Goldfinch, Song is long and jumbled; may include mimicked elements of other birds' songs. Males sing from high, exposed perches. Note white in tail, which is conspicuous in flight.
American_Goldfinch, Molting male is a patchy mix of breeding and nonbreeding colors.
American_Goldfinch, Females/immatures are pale yellow below and don't have streaked underparts.
American_Goldfinch, These nimble birds feed on small-seeded plants including sycamores. Females are brownish without any streaking and have distinctive, bold black wings with whitish wingbars.
American_Goldfinch, Breeding males have a black forehead, a yellow back, and black-and-white wings. Some males have more white-tipped (worn) feathers on their wings than others.
American_Goldfinch, Has a bouncy, undulating flight style. Often calls in flight, with a bird sounding like it is saying " po-ta-to-chip."
American_Goldfinch, Despite having a fairly small bill for a finch, goldfinches can crack and remove the hard shells of sunflowers, then crush the seed inside before swallowing.
American_Goldfinch, Breeding female is yellow below, with black wings, but lacks breeding male's black forehead.
American_Goldfinch, Molting male has an incomplete black forehead and a patchy mix of bright yellow and brown.
American_Goldfinch, Breeding male is a stunning mix of yellow, black, and white.
American_Goldfinch, Balances on the seedheads of thistles, dandelions, and other plants to pluck seeds.
American_Goldfinch, Breeds later than most North American birds, waiting until mid-summer when plants have produced fibrous seeds that adults use to build nests and also feed their young.
American_Goldfinch, Frequently feeds in flocks at sunflower and nyjer seed feeders.
American_Goshawk, Large, bulky raptor with a slate gray cap and white eyebrow. The belly is finely barred in gray. Note red eye.
American_Goshawk, Adult has dark head, bold white eyebrow, underparts with fine gray barring, and conspicuous white undertail coverts.
American_Goshawk, American Goshawk is vocal and fiercely defensive around the nest.
American_Goshawk, Juvenile is brownish overall with a brown crown, streaky belly and speckled back. Note the white eyebrow and yellow eye. Most frequently found in mature forests.
American_Goshawk, Juvenile is speckled brown above with narrow banding on the tail. Note pale eyebrow.
American_Goshawk, An immature goshawk "mantling" over a recently killed jackrabbit. American Goshawks eat a wider range of prey than other accipiters, including birds, mammals, and reptiles.
American_Goshawk, Adult appears light below when soaring. Note broad wings and long dark tail contrasting with white undertail coverts.
American_Goshawk, In flight note long tail and broad, rounded wings. Juvenile is brown and streaky, with narrow dark bands in the tail.
American_Goshawk, Flying style is similar to most accipiters with stiff and powerful wingbeats. While soaring, goshawks can resemble buteos, but their long tail separates them from buteos.
American_Goshawk, Stocky raptor with a barrel chest and a long, rounded tail and broad wings. Adult in flight looks pale below with a dark tail and fluffy white undertail coverts.

American_Herring_Gull, Large gull with a somewhat large, but slim bill and robust body. Breeding adults have clean white heads and underparts with pale gray backs and wings. Note pale legs and yellow eye.
American_Herring_Gull, Nonbreeding adults have extensive tan streaking on their neck. Note the pale gray upperparts and the pale eye.

American_Herring_Gull, A large, barrel-chested gull with pink legs in all plumages. Breeding adult has light gray upperparts, clean white underparts, a white head, yellow eyes, a fairly slim bill with a red mark, and mostly black wingtips with some white markings.
American_Herring_Gull, Third winter birds start to acquire pale gray feathers on their back, but still have extensive tan streaking on their head and neck. Note pale yellow eye.
American_Herring_Gull, This more advanced third winter bird looks nearly like an adult, with its pale gray back, but it still has streaking on the neck and a black band around its bill.
American_Herring_Gull, Characteristic "long call" and display involves leaning forward, lowering the head, and giving an extended series of loud cries.
American_Herring_Gull, The second winter gull is heavily streaked throughout with a few gray back feathers coming in. Note dark primaries, lacking white tips.
American_Herring_Gull, Some second winter birds have less streaking on their necks and look very pale overall, but note its pale eye and pink legs.

American_Herring_Gull, Pairs often feed each other as part of courtship. Females are usually smaller than males; this one is soliciting food from her partner using begging motions similar to those used by chicks.
American_Herring_Gull, Juveniles are tan overall with tan-and-white checker boarding on their back. Juveniles have an entirely dark bill and a dark eye.
American_Herring_Gull, In flight, they look barrel-chested and broad-winged. Pale gray above with dark wingtips with only small white spots (aka "mirrors") on the dark tips.

American_Herring_Gull, Juveniles are brown with black bills. This one begs and receives regurgitated food from a parent, as the other parent moves in and also eats the food. Afterward, the two adults perform "long calls."
American_Herring_Gull, Juveniles in flight have dark primaries without the white spots or mirrors and a thick dark band across their tail.

American_Herring_Gull, Found along both coasts and near large reservoirs, lakes, and major rivers. They feed in habitats as diverse as open water, mudflats, plowed fields, and garbage dumps, and gather in almost any open space near food.
American_Kestrel, Small falcon about the size of a Mourning Dove. Females are rusty overall with black barring on the wings and back. They have two black slashes on their face and a gray crown.
American_Kestrel, Often hunts by flapping into the wind to hover in place, scanning the ground below.
American_Kestrel, In flight, note long, pointed wings, slender body, and deep wing beats. Males in flight have a thicker black band on the tail.
American_Kestrel, Females have orange-and-black barring on the upperparts and tail.
American_Kestrel, Flies with quick, light wingbeats interspersed with glides. At distance, note slim body with long tail.
American_Kestrel, Males' wings are blue-gray and black; their tail is mostly orange, with a broad black band bordered by a thin white tip.
American_Kestrel, Two color morphs of resident birds occur in Cuba: a pale and a dark morph. This pale morph has more white on the face and is very pale below.
American_Kestrel, Nests in holes in trees; also in nest boxes. Note how kestrels often pump their tails after landing. This video has no audio.
American_Kestrel, Dark morph residents in Cuba have a dark rusty belly.
American_Kestrel, Resident females in Cuba have rusty wings with black barring and pale underparts with rusty spots.
American_Kestrel, Male may feed female as part of courtship. Note distinctive habit of pumping tail while perched.
American_Kestrel, Adult males on Hispaniola are variable, with breast color ranging from chestnut (as in this individual) to white.
American_Kestrel, Adult males in South America are paler than "Northern" males, with white underparts and more white on the head.
American_Kestrel, Males and females have pairs of black vertical slashes on the sides of their pale faces—sometimes called a "mustache" and a "sideburn."
American_Kestrel, The smallest falcon found in the U.S. and Canada.
American_Kestrel, Pairs nest in cavities, including nest boxes, old woodpecker holes, natural tree hollows, rock crevices, and nooks in buildings.
American_Kestrel, Found in open areas from deserts and grasslands to alpine meadows. Often seen perching on telephone wires along roadsides or fence posts.
American_Oystercatcher, Large and chunky shorebird with a bright red bill and yellow eye.
American_Oystercatcher, Chunky shorebird. Juveniles are duller than adults with a dark-tipped bill.
American_Oystercatcher, Males and females incubate eggs laid in a small scrape on the ground.
American_Oystercatcher, In flight, note white wing and tail stripe. Flying birds often give piercing calls.
American_Oystercatcher, Conspicuous shorebird with a bright red bill and yellow eye.
American_Oystercatcher, Walks or runs along beaches and rocky shorelines.
American_Oystercatcher, Courting birds walk side by side giving single piping notes with their outstretched necks bobbing up and down.
American_Oystercatcher, Nests on the ground on sand dunes, marsh islands, or oyster shell mounds.
American_Oystercatcher, Found along beaches, rocky shorelines, and mudflats.
American_Oystercatcher, Found in coastal habitats including sand or shell beaches, dunes, saltmarsh, marsh islands, mudflats, and dredge spoil islands made of sand or gravel.
American_Oystercatcher, Forages for aquatic invertebrates hiding in cracks of rocks. This video has no audio.
American_Pipit, A small, slim songbird with a short, thin bill. Nonbreeding/immature birds are gray to brown above with variable amounts of streaking below.

American_Pipit, Small and slender with a small head and bill. Grayish brown above with variable amounts of streaking below (from none to heavy). Color of underparts also varies from yellowish to cinnamon across their range.
American_Pipit, A small, slim songbird with a short, thin bill. Brownish or grayish above, pale below, typically with streaks on the breast and sides, especially in winter. Bobs tail frequently.
American_Pipit, In flight, note prominent white outer tail feathers and listen for "pi-pit" call.

American_Pipit, Nonbreeding/immature birds have variable amounts of streaking on the breast. Note clean throat, white eyering, and small bill. Walks along the ground bobbing its tail. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.
American_Pipit, An inconspicuous songbird, recalling a sparrow, but lacking a sparrow's heavier bill. Often first detected, both on the ground and in flight, by its strident "pi-pit" call.

American_Pipit, Slender ground-dwelling bird with a short bill and small head. Grayish brown above with a pale eyering and eyebrow. Underparts vary from yellowish to cinnamon with variable amounts of streaking.
American_Pipit, Forages on the ground, walking quickly, strutting, and often changing direction to inspect the ground and low vegetation for food.
American_Pipit, Forages on the ground in wet areas and bare fields. Note that it walks rather than hops.
American_Pipit, Nonbreeding/immature birds are grayish brown above with variable amounts of streaking below. Note short, thin bill, eyering, and pale eyebrow. Walks along the ground bobbing its tail.

American_Pipit, In migration and winter uses coastal beaches and marshes, stubble fields, recently plowed fields, mudflats, and river courses. Often seen in large groups with other pipits during the winter.
American_Pipit, Generally found in relatively barren places. Nests on the ground.
American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and a fairly long, expressive tail. Adult males are mostly black with bright orange patches on the sides, wings, and tail.

American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and fairly long, expressive tail. Females have yellow patches on the sides, wings, and tail, a gray head, and an olive back.
American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and a fairly long, expressive tail. Adult males are mostly black with bright orange patches on the sides, wings, and tail.
American_Redstart, Immature males have yellow patches on the sides, wings, and tail with a variable amount of black on the face and chest.
American_Redstart, Tends to forage at middle levels in the forest where it grabs insects midair or plucks them from vegetation.
American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and a fairly long, expressive tail. Adult males are mostly black with bright orange patches on the sides, wings, and tail.
American_Redstart, Females have a gray head and yellow patches on the sides, wings, and tail.
American_Redstart, Often fans tail to expose yellow or orange tail feathers.
American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and a fairly long, expressive tail. Adult males are mostly black with bright orange patches on the sides, wings, and tail.
American_Redstart, Breeds in open wooded habitats, particularly those dominated by deciduous trees.
American_Redstart, Immature males have yellow patches on the sides, wings, and tail and a variable amount of black on the face and chest.
American_Redstart, A medium-sized warbler with a relatively wide, flat bill and a fairly long, expressive tail. Adult males are mostly black with bright orange patches on the sides, wings, and tail.
American_Robin, Large round-bellied thrush. Males have a dark head, yellow bill, black streaks on the throat, and a rusty belly.
American_Robin, Eats berries in the winter. Some individuals not easily separated by sex.

American_Robin, Calls with a cuck or tuk to communicate with each other or a sharp yeep or peek as an alarm call. They also make a repeated chirr that rises in volume and can sound like a laugh or chuckle.
American_Robin, The "San Lucas" American Robin, found only in Baja California Sur, is much paler than birds across the rest of American Robin's range.
American_Robin, Often seen tugging worms from yards.

American_Robin, Females build the nest from the inside out, pressing dead grass and twigs into a cup shape using the wrist of one wing. Once the cup is formed, she reinforces the nest using soft mud gathered from worm castings to make a heavy, sturdy nest.
American_Robin, Female/immature birds are paler than males and many birds in the West are paler than those in the East and Northwest.
American_Robin, Female/immature birds are paler than males with more white on the belly and throat.
American_Robin, Runs on the ground with short rapid steps, pausing frequently to scan for prey and/or predators. Uses its bill to probe the ground and pull out earthworms.
American_Robin, Juveniles have spotting on the back and chest.
American_Robin, Chubby thrush with grayish back and darker tail.
American_Robin, Pulls earthworms out of the ground by using its strong legs.
American_Robin, Builds nests of twigs and grasses held together with mud.
American_Robin, Note orange underwing coverts in flight.
American_Robin, During the winter, often found feasting on berries.
American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized mostly black woodpecker with white spots in the wings and barred flanks. Males have a yellow crown patch.

American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Black-and-white woodpecker with barred flanks and a barred black-and-white patch down the back. The amount of barring on the back varies regionally. Rocky Mountain birds have less barring.

American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Excavates nest holes in dead trees, usually conifers. As young approach fledging, they chip noisily from the entrance of the cavity. Juveniles of both sexes have a small yellow crown patch.
American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Mostly black woodpecker with variable barring on the back. Adult males have a yellow crown patch.
American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Found in evergreen forests often where disturbances such as fire or disease outbreaks have increased the numbers of standing dead trees and insects.
American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Black-and-white woodpecker with barring on the back and flanks. As the name implies, has 3 instead of 4 toes.
American_Three-toed_Woodpecker, Juveniles are similar to adults but duller overall and often have shorter bills. Juveniles of both sexes usually have a small yellow crown patch.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Rather plump sparrow with a long tail. A rusty cap and eyeline mark the gray face. Note bicolored bill, white wingbar, and unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Occurs in hedgerows, weedy fields, and shrubby areas during migration and winter.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Rather plump sparrow with a long tail. A rusty cap and eyeline mark the gray face. Note bicolored bill, white wingbar, and unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Small, round-headed birds that often fluff out their feathers, making their plump bodies look even chubbier. Note rusty crown and eyeline on a gray face.
American_Tree_Sparrow, A rusty crown and eyeline mark its gray face. Note unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Rather plump sparrow with a long tail. A rusty cap and eyeline mark the gray face. Note bicolored bill, white wingbar, and unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Plump sparrow with a rusty cap, bicolored bill, and a dark central breast spot.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Eats seeds including birdseed during the winter. Note rusty crown and eyeline on a gray face.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Rather plump sparrow with a long tail. A rusty cap and eyeline mark the gray face. Note bicolored bill, white wingbar, and unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Often forages on the ground in search of seeds.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Heavily streaked juvenile plumage is rarely seen outside of Arctic breeding grounds.
American_Tree_Sparrow, Rather plump sparrow with a long tail. A rusty cap and eyeline mark the gray face. Note bicolored bill, white wingbar, and unstreaked underparts.
American_Tree_Sparrow, In winter, found in weedy fields with hedgerows or shrubs, along forest edges, or near marshes. Note central breast spot on an unstreaked belly.
American_White_Pelican, Huge snow-white waterbird with a long neck, and a massive bill. A yellow plate forms on the upper bill of breeding adults.
American_White_Pelican, Huge snow-white waterbird with a long neck, and a massive bill. A yellow plate forms on the upper bill of breeding adults.

American_White_Pelican, Often occurs in flocks. The vertical plate near the tip of the bill indicates breeding individuals. All white when on the ground, but note black flight feathers when wing is spread.
American_White_Pelican, Large waterbird with a long yellow bill with an extendable pouch used to scoop fish out of the water.
American_White_Pelican, Large but graceful flyer with black flight feathers and a white body.
American_White_Pelican, Soars gracefully on very broad, stable wings. Often soars using thermals.
American_White_Pelican, Often travels and forages in large flocks, sometimes traveling long distances in V-formations.
American_White_Pelican, Frequently seen in groups whether it be loafing, migrating, or foraging.
American_White_Pelican, Typically breeds on islands in shallow wetlands in the interior of the continent. They spend winters on coastal waters, bays, and estuaries.
American_Wigeon, A compact duck with a short, pale bill and a round head. Breeding males have a brownish gray head with a wide green stripe behind the eye and a white cap.
American_Wigeon, Females have a warm brown body with a brownish gray head and a dark smudge around the eye. Note the pale bill tipped in black.
American_Wigeon, Dips bill in water to pick up aquatic plants and insects from the surface or tips up to pluck submerged vegetation.
American_Wigeon, In flight males show a prominent white patch on the upperwing, green secondaries, and white under the wing.

American_Wigeon, Nonbreeding males have a reddish brown body with a brownish gray head and a dark smudge around the eye. The prominent white patch in the wing and green secondaries may not always be visible.
American_Wigeon, Eats primarily vegetation such as duckweed, pond weed, water milfoil, and wigeon grass during the nonbreeding season.
American_Wigeon, In flight, female has a dark speculum bordered by a thin white wing stripe.
American_Wigeon, In some lights the green head stripe can look bronzy.
American_Wigeon, Uses its short gooselike bill to pluck vegetation and seeds from fields and pastures.
American_Wigeon, A small number of males have white on the cheeks and throat, which hunters often refer to as a "storm wigeon."
American_Wigeon, When startled, erupts in flight from the water's surface, flying rapidly and erratically.
American_Wigeon, Pairs form on the wintering ground and stay together throughout most of incubation.
American_Wigeon, Often occurs in flocks during the nonbreeding season. Found in a wide variety of wetland habitats including lakes, wetlands, and flooded farm fields.
American_Woodcock, Plump, short-legged and short-necked shorebird with a long, straight bill. Note cinnamon underparts and gray collar.
American_Woodcock, On spring nights, males perform conspicuous displays, giving a buzzy peent call, and launching into the air.
American_Woodcock, Plump, short-legged and short-necked shorebird with a long, straight bill. Note cinnamon underparts and gray collar.
American_Woodcock, Stocky, short-necked shorebird with a long bill that blends in well with vegetation. Note gray stripes down back.
American_Woodcock, Chunky, short-legged shorebird of forests. Walks along the ground in a rocking pattern while probing for earthworms.
American_Woodcock, Plump, short-legged and short-necked shorebird with a long, straight bill. Note cinnamon underparts and gray collar.
American_Woodcock, Found in forests, forest edges, old fields, and wet meadows of eastern North America.
American_Woodcock, Males deliver a buzzy "peent" call from the ground at dusk on early spring evenings.
American_Woodcock, Plump, short-legged and short-necked shorebird with a long, straight bill. Note cinnamon underparts and gray collar.
American_Woodcock, Males perform courtship displays in old fields, while females typically nest in nearby shrubby deciduous forest.
American_Woodcock, Plump, short-legged and short-necked shorebird with a long, straight bill. Note cinnamon underparts and gray collar.
Ancient_Murrelet, Small and slightly more slender seabird. Breeding birds have white, fluffy-looking eyebrows.
Ancient_Murrelet, Small and slightly more slender than similar species with a pale bill. Nonbreeding birds have a grayish throat, white breast, and a bit of white on the side of the neck.
Ancient_Murrelet, Small and slightly more slender seabird. Breeding birds have white, fluffy-looking eyebrows.
Ancient_Murrelet, Small and slightly more slender seabird. Breeding birds have white, fluffy-looking eyebrows.
Ancient_Murrelet, Slender seabird that flies on stiff, narrow wings. Underwings are bright white.
Ancient_Murrelet, Small and slightly more slender seabird. Breeding birds have white, fluffy-looking eyebrows.
Ancient_Murrelet, Nonbreeding birds have a grayish throat, white breast, and a bit of white on the side of the neck.
Ancient_Murrelet, Juveniles have a gray back with gray-and-white scalloping on its sides. Note pale bill.
Ancient_Murrelet, Flies with stiff wingbeats, banking side to side. Note white underwings.
Anhinga, Large waterbird with a long tail, a long S-shaped neck, and a daggerlike bill. Adult males are black with silvery to white streaks on the back and wings.
Anhinga, Females/immatures have pale head, neck, and breast and a dark belly. Note long S-shaped neck and daggerlike bill.
Anhinga, Nests in trees often overhanging water where it builds a bulky platform of sticks. This video has no audio.
Anhinga, Large waterbird with large, broad wings. Flies with neck outstretched. Sometimes soars high in the sky riding thermals.
Anhinga, Holds wings out to dry after being in the water.
Anhinga, Swims low in the water often with its body partly or mostly submerged with only its neck or bill visible.
Anhinga, Nests in loose groups. Usually nests in a tree near water.
Anhinga, Found in shallow, slow-moving, sheltered waters and uses nearby perches and banks for drying and sunning.
Annas_Hummingbird, Stocky for a hummingbird with a straight bill. Adult males have a rose-pink throat and crown.
Annas_Hummingbird, Somewhat stocky for a hummingbird. Females/immatures are metallic green above with some reddish-pink feathers on the throat.
Annas_Hummingbird, Stocky for a hummingbird with a straight bill. Adult males have a rose-pink throat and crown.

Annas_Hummingbird, Males perform spectacular courtship displays in which they climb up to 130 feet into the air before swooping to the ground with a burst of noise that they produce through their tail feathers.
Annas_Hummingbird, Immature males are duller than adult males and lack a full gorget on the throat.
Annas_Hummingbird, Stocky for a hummingbird with a straight bill. Adult males have a rose-pink throat and crown.
Annas_Hummingbird, Females/immature males have greenish upperparts, blackish wings, a small pinkish patch on the throat, and a white spot behind the eye.
Annas_Hummingbird, A small shift in head position changes the color and intensity of a male's gorget and crown feathers.
Annas_Hummingbird, Stocky for a hummingbird with a straight bill. Adult males have a rose-pink throat and crown.
Annas_Hummingbird, Females are metallic green above and grayish below with bits of reddish spotting on the throat. Note pale line over the eye.
Annas_Hummingbird, Adult males have a brilliant reddish-pink crown and throat and grayish underparts.
Annas_Hummingbird, Stocky for a hummingbird with a straight bill. Adult males have a rose-pink throat and crown.
Annas_Hummingbird, Immature males have a blotchy rose-pink crown and throat.
Annas_Hummingbird, Adult males' iridescent throat and crown feathers can appear blackish depending on the lighting.
Annas_Hummingbird, Common in yards, parks, residential streets, eucalyptus groves, riverside woods, savannahs, and coastal scrub.

Antillean_Nighthawk, A medium-sized nightbird with long, pointed wings, white wingbars, and a notched tail. Male has a white throat patch, white band across the tail, and a larger wingbar than female.

Antillean_Nighthawk, On the ground, well-camouflaged with an intricate pattern of black, gray, and brown. Male has a bold white throat patch and a prominent white wingbar sometimes visible on a bird at rest.
Antillean_Nighthawk, A long-winged, tiny-billed nightbird, patterned in shades of black, gray, and brown. During the day, nighthawks rest on tree branches, posts, or on the ground.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Female lacks male's white throat patch and is generally warmer colored overall.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Often roosts on tree limbs, usually with the body parallel to the limb. Also roosts on the ground, as well as on fence posts and power lines.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Nests in open, rocky areas where chick and adult are well camouflaged.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Often seen in flight at dusk and dawn, flying buoyantly and erratically in search of flying insects.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Lays eggs directly on the ground, often in open areas with rocks or pebbles.
Antillean_Nighthawk, Sometimes seen in large numbers at dusk, with birds maneuvering agilely in pursuit of flying insects.
Aplomado_Falcon, Individuals in the U.S. and northern Mexico have thicker breast bands that extend all the way across the breast. Note the long black-and-white tail and rusty lower belly.
Aplomado_Falcon, Flies on long pointed wings. Note the barred underwings and long black-and-white tail.
Aplomado_Falcon, When perched in a tree, tends to perch on the inner branches. Note the long tail that extends beyond the wings when perched.
Aplomado_Falcon, Individuals in the U.S. and northern Mexico have thicker breast bands that extend all the way across the breast. Note the long black-and-white tail and rusty lower belly.
Aplomado_Falcon, A medium-sized falcon with a bold black-and-white facial pattern. Individuals in the Andes of South America tend to have darker backs and have a narrow, incomplete breast band.
Aplomado_Falcon, Found in dry grasslands with mesquite or yucca.
Aplomado_Falcon, Individuals in the U.S. and northern Mexico have thicker breast bands that extend all the way across the breast. Note the long black-and-white tail and rusty lower belly.
Aplomado_Falcon, Immatures are browner overall with streaking on the chest.
Aplomado_Falcon, A lean and long-legged falcon that often hunts from the ground and drinks from small pools of water.
Aplomado_Falcon, Adults are dark brown to slate blue above and tricolored below; a dark band separates the white or buffy chest from the rusty lower belly.
Aplomado_Falcon, Note that the tail extends well beyond the wings when perched.
Aplomado_Falcon, Individuals in the U.S. and northern Mexico have thicker breast bands that extend all the way across the breast. Note the long black-and-white tail and rusty lower belly.

Arctic_Loon, A medium-sized loon with a thick neck and straight bill. Breeding adult has a pale gray crown and hindneck, black-and-white stripes on the side of the neck, a dark chin and throat, very fine black lines on the breast, and prominent white marks on dark upperparts. Note the prominent white flank patch just above the waterline.
Arctic_Loon, Note the white flank patch, which is the best way to identify vagrant individuals in North America.
Arctic_Loon, A medium-sized loon with intricate black, white, and gray breeding plumage. Birds across Europe and most of northern Asia have a deep purple throat in good light.
Arctic_Loon, Nonbreeding adult has blackish upperparts and neck that contrast strongly with white throat and chin. Bill is mostly gray, with a dark line along the top and a black tip.
Arctic_Loon, Juvenile is similar to nonbreeding adult, but paler and browner. At close range, upperparts appear scaly due to light feather edges.
Arctic_Loon, Nonbreeding adult is mostly dark overall, with strongly contrasting white cheeks, throat, and flank patches.
Arctic_Loon, In good light, breeding adults in Europe and most of Asia show a purplish shine on the throat.
Arctic_Loon, Flies strongly on long, narrow wings with neck outstretched and feet extended beyond body.
Arctic_Loon, Pairs nest along large freshwater lakes across the boreal forest of northern Europe and Asia.
Arctic_Loon, Juvenile is paler and browner than nonbreeding adult, with a duskier transition between the neck and throat.
Arctic_Loon, White flank patch is present in all plumages, but can be difficult to see depending on an individual's posture.

Arctic_Loon, Juvenile is lighter colored and browner than nonbreeding adult, with a light scaly pattern on upperparts. The diagnostic white flank patch is mostly concealed while this individual is swimming, but is evident when it dives.
Arctic_Loon, Often gathers in small groups outside of the breeding season.
Arctic_Tern, Small, slender tern with angular wings that are silvery below. Breeding adults have a thin red bill and a gray belly. Note long forked tail.
Arctic_Tern, Short-legged tern with a long tail that extends beyond the wingtips while at rest on breeding adults. Bill and legs are bright red on breeding adults.
Arctic_Tern, Adults frequently give a high-pitched kip when foraging or while at the breeding colony.
Arctic_Tern, Small tern with a long, forked tail and pointed all gray wings. Plunge dives for small fish, aquatic insects, and crustaceans.
Arctic_Tern, Short-legged, slender tern. Nonbreeding birds have a reduced black cap that extends back from the eye. The legs and bill are black during the nonbreeding season.
Arctic_Tern, Males often feed females small fish during courtship and to maintain pair bonds.
Arctic_Tern, Juveniles have a scaly-looking back and a smudgy black crown with a white forehead.
Arctic_Tern, Nests on the ground in open tundra, boreal forest, or on rocky islands and beaches.
Arctic_Warbler, Small, plain olive Old World warbler. Note long buffy eyebrow and dark eyeline.
Arctic_Warbler, Small, plain Old World warbler with a long buffy eyeline. Some individuals are browner than others.
Arctic_Warbler, Small, drab warbler with a small bill and long buffy eyebrow. Upperparts vary from olive to brown.
Arctic_Warbler, In Alaska, found mainly in stands of dwarf willow, often along streams.
Arizona_Woodpecker, Brown-and-white woodpecker that is barred brown-and-white in front and solid brown on the back. Males have a small patch of red at the back of the head.
Arizona_Woodpecker, Spotted and barred brown and white below and solid brown above. Note brown cheek patch. Females lack red on the head.
Arizona_Woodpecker, Excavates a hole, often in a dead tree, where they raise the young. Males and females bring larvae and other insects to the nestlings.
Arizona_Woodpecker, Brown-and-white woodpecker that is barred brown-and-white in front and solid brown on the back. Males have a small patch of red at the back of the head.
Arizona_Woodpecker, The only solidly brown-backed woodpecker in the United States. Females do not have a red patch at the back of the head.
Arizona_Woodpecker, Found in pine–oak woodlands from southeastern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico and along Mexico's Sierra Madre Occidental.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, A slender flycatcher with a long tail and peaked crown. The face is ashy gray with a whitish throat.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, A slender flycatcher with a long tail and peaked crown. The face is ashy gray with a whitish throat.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, Calls include a variety of gurgling, burry notes.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, The underside of the tail has a broad stroke of cinnamon down the center bordered by brownish gray.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, Nests in holes in trees, birdhouses, or other holes or crevices.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, A slender flycatcher with a long tail and peaked crown. The face is ashy gray with a whitish throat.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, Found in dry scrub, open woodlands, and deserts in western North America.
Ash-throated_Flycatcher, A slender flycatcher with a long tail and peaked crown. The face is ashy gray with a whitish throat.
Atlantic_Puffin, Stout black-and-white seabird with a huge, red, yellow, and gray bill.
Atlantic_Puffin, Pairs often remain together for many years. Courtship displays involve head bobbing and rubbing the bills together.
Atlantic_Puffin, Huge triangular bill is noticeable in flight. Black collar separates white belly and whitish face. Note dark underwings.
Atlantic_Puffin, Nonbreeding birds have a grayer face and the bill lacks the yellow highlights.
Atlantic_Puffin, The bill on juveniles is reddish orange and gray, but it is smaller and not as pronounced. The face is gray.
Atlantic_Puffin, An unmistakable black-and-white seabird with a huge, multicolored bill, and a grayish white face.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a long, straight bill. Adults have a black tail, head, and wings and are yellow below and yellow-olive above.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.
Audubons_Oriole, Larger oriole with a straight bill. Males and females look similar, though females tend to be paler. Adults have a black head with lemon yellow bellies and yellow-olive backs.

Audubons_Oriole, Predominantly found in Mexico. In the U.S. only found in southern Texas. Rather secretive oriole, living in denser vegetation than most other orioles and singing from inconspicuous perches.

Bachmans_Sparrow, A larger sparrow with a long, round tail. It is brownish gray above with rusty-streaked feathers and a rusty crown. The throat is buffy with sparse rusty streaks that are not always visible.
Bachmans_Sparrow, A grayish brown sparrow with a thin dark line extending behind the eye and a pale eyebrow. Note the long and round bill and tail.
Bachmans_Sparrow, A spectacular songster found only in the pine woodlands of the southeastern United States.
Bachmans_Sparrow, A rather portly sparrow with a long, rounded tail and a long, rounded bill. Grayish brown overall with rusty streaks above.
Bachmans_Sparrow, Juveniles look similar to adults, but have streaky underparts and tan edges on the wing feathers.
Bachmans_Sparrow, Starts song with a single clear note followed by a trill. Sings from elevated perches typically less than 10 feet above the ground.

Bachmans_Sparrow, A larger sparrow with a long, round tail. It is brownish gray above with rusty-streaked feathers and a rusty crown. The throat is buffy with sparse rusty streaks that are not always visible.

Bachmans_Sparrow, A larger sparrow with a long, round tail. It is brownish gray above with rusty-streaked feathers and a rusty crown. The throat is buffy with sparse rusty streaks that are not always visible.
Bachmans_Sparrow, Found in open pine woodlands with wiregrass and saw palmetto in the understory
Bairds_Sandpiper, Slender shorebird with broad breast, short legs, and very gently drooping, black bill. Stands with a horizontal posture and wingtips extend beyond the tail.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Medium-sized sandpiper with a broad breast, short legs, and ever so slightly drooping bill. Long wings extend past end of tail. Juveniles have a buffy breast and scaly upperparts.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Forages for invertebrates both at the water's edge and away from it, in grassy marshes and wet fields.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Slender shorebird with broad breast, short legs, and very gently drooping, black bill. Stands with a horizontal posture and wingtips extend beyond the tail.
Bairds_Sandpiper, In flight, note the long wings and weak whitish wing stripe. Also note there is a dark stripe from the lower back to the center of the tail.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Slender shorebird with broad breast, short legs, and very gently drooping, black bill. Stands with a horizontal posture and wingtips extend beyond the tail.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Graceful, somewhat short-legged shorebird with a horizontal posture. Juveniles are scaly above with a buffy breast. Wingtips extend beyond the tail.
Bairds_Sandpiper, Breeding adults have dark spotting on the back. Breeds in arctic tundra.

Bairds_Sandpiper, In flight, note the long wings and weak whitish wing stripe (compare with Western Sandpiper, second from the right). Also note dark stripe from the lower back to the center of the tail.
Bairds_Sparrow, Medium-sized, relatively short-tailed sparrow with a necklace of brown streaks and a buffy eyebrow and ear patch.
Bairds_Sparrow, Sings a series of light ringing notes followed by a thin trill from the tops of grass clumps and small shrubs.
Bairds_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow of grasslands. Note necklace of streaks on the chest and the buffy wash on the face.
Bairds_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a buffy eyebrow and ear patch, and fine streaking on the nape. Note the "broken" eyeline and mustache stripe, neither of which fully extend across the face.
Bairds_Sparrow, Uncommon sparrow of grasslands. Identified by the streaky necklace and buffy eyebrow and ear patch.
Bald_Eagle, Very large raptor with long, broad wings. Dark brown body contrasts with its white head and tail.
Bald_Eagle, Juveniles have a brown body with brown and white mottled wings. The tail is also mottled with a dark band at the tip.
Bald_Eagle, Voice is a high, weak-sounding whinny.
Bald_Eagle, Second year birds are strongly mottled brown and white.
Bald_Eagle, Often scavenges food or eats carrion.
Bald_Eagle, When perched appears very large, with brown body and contrasting white head and bright yellow bill.
Bald_Eagle, Will hunt for fish when near water.
Bald_Eagle, Builds huge stick nests in trees, usually some distance below the top of the tree. Juveniles are mottled brown and white, with dark heads.
Bald_Eagle, Second year birds are strongly mottled brown and white.
Bald_Eagle, In flight, notice very long, broad wings held fairly flat. Large head just out ahead of the wings as far or farther than tail trails behind.
Bald_Eagle, The amount of white feathering can be highly variable on juveniles and second year birds.
Bald_Eagle, Second year birds have a mostly white belly, with some brown mottling, a brown chest, and a broad brown mask on the face.
Bald_Eagle, Will form groups during the nonbreeding season, when different age classes can be seen together.
Bald_Eagle, Constructs enormous stick nests, usually in large trees.

Baltimore_Oriole, Medium-sized, sturdy-bodied songbird with a thick neck, long legs, and pointed bill. Adult males have an entirely black head and back with an orange rump and orange outer tail feathers.

Baltimore_Oriole, Thick-necked songbird with a long, pointed bill. Adult female plumage is highly variable ranging from a brownish to yellowish head and back. Note yellow tail and yellow undertail coverts.

Baltimore_Oriole, Note fairly long, sharply pointed bill—a useful feature to identify members of the blackbird family. Males are brilliant orange and black, with orange shoulder patch and broad white wingbar.
Baltimore_Oriole, Female plumage is highly variable. Some have brownish heads and backs. Note yellow tail and undertail coverts.
Baltimore_Oriole, Immature females have a grayish back with faint streaking and a pale yellow wash on the head and breast. Note yellow tail.
Baltimore_Oriole, Song is a rich whistle, rising and falling in a few phrases.
Baltimore_Oriole, Females and immature males are variable, but note pointed bill, yellowish-orange underparts, and two white wingbars.
Baltimore_Oriole, Flashes yellowish to orange outer tail feathers in flight.
Baltimore_Oriole, Orioles often come to oranges offered at backyard feeding stations.
Baltimore_Oriole, Found in open woodland, forest edge, orchards, and stands of trees along rivers, in parks, and in backyards.
Baltimore_Oriole, Eats berries, other fruits, nectar, and insects.
Baltimore_Oriole, Usually forages in treetops among fine twigs and leaves, where it can be hard to see despite its bright colors.
Baltimore_Oriole, Often visits fruit feeders. Note orangish outer tail feathers and black hood.

Bananaquit, A small songbird with a curved, pointed bill; pinkish gape; bold white line above the eye; yellow underparts; and dark upperparts. The widespread "Continental" subspecies group, found from Mexico to Argentina, has a grayish throat, but some Caribbean subspecies groups have a black or whitish throat.
Bananaquit, The "Puerto Rico" subspecies group has a dark gray throat, blackish back, and prominent white wing patch (present in some other subspecies groups and absent in others).

Bananaquit, A small, fidgety songbird with a curved, pointed bill; yellow underparts; dark upperparts; and a strong white stripe above the eye. Throat color (white, gray, or black), upperpart color (gray to black), and presence of white wing spot varies between subspecies groups.
Bananaquit, The "Bahamas" group has a whitish throat and upper breast.
Bananaquit, The "Grenada" subspecies group includes individuals that are nearly all-black as well as more typically plumaged birds with a yellow breast and white eyestripe.
Bananaquit, Feeds mainly on nectar, using the sharp, curved bill to reach into flowers or pierce them at the base.
Bananaquit, Juvenile has a yellowish eyestripe, limited pale yellow on the underparts, and drab upperparts.
Bananaquit, Feeds primarily on the nectar of flowering plants.
Bananaquit, Builds messy, globe-shaped nests, both for breeding and to serve as "dormitory nests" for roosting birds.
Bananaquit, Often occurs in pairs or small family groups. Note the yellow rump, found on all subspecies groups.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with small head and long tail. Young birds lack the white crescent on the neck and have light scalloping on the back.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Note the white band and iridescent green scaly-looking feathers on the back of the neck.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with thick-based, pointed wings. In flight, look for the light band at the end of the tail.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, A relatively quiet pigeon of oak woodlands and evergreen forests.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Travels in large groups of dozens to hundreds of individuals. This video has no audio.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Adults have delicate pink-purple underparts, visible at close range. Bill is yellow with a dark tip. Sometimes visits feeders for seeds.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Unobtrusive woodland pigeon that feeds on seeds, fruits, and nuts.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Large pigeon with grayish upperparts and purplish gray underparts. White crescent on back of neck and pale tip to tail are distinctive.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Often found in flocks; forages in trees for many kinds of fruits and nuts including berries, acorns, and pine nuts.
Band-tailed_Pigeon, Forms large flocks of up to 300. Often found in forests, including the wet forests of the Pacific Coast and mountain forests of the southwestern U.S., Mexico, and Central America.
Bank_Swallow, Small songbird with a small head and tiny bill. Adults are brown above with a brown breast band and a white swoosh on the neck.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.
Bank_Swallow, In flight, note pale belly and darker wings with a brown band across the chest.
Bank_Swallow, Brown above and white below with a brown band across its chest.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.
Bank_Swallow, Adults are brown above with a white throat that wraps up around the side of the neck. Note slightly forked tail.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows; forages for insects fairly low over fields, water, and other open areas.
Bank_Swallow, Nests in burrows excavated using its feet and bill, placed along banks and bluffs of rivers and streams, as well as gravel quarries and roadcuts.

Bar-tailed_Godwit, A large shorebird with a long, slightly upturned bill. Breeding male has rich rufous underparts and dark brown upperparts with some rufous and white markings. Bill is mostly black during the breeding season.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Female is larger than male, with a longer bill. Breeding female is less colorful than male, with a buffy neck and breast and a whitish belly with some barring.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, A large, long-legged shorebird with a long, slightly upturned bill. Breeding male has rufous underparts and a rufous face.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Juvenile has a finely streaked, buffy breast that gives way to white lower underparts. Upperparts have a strongly patterned, checkered appearance.

Bar-tailed_Godwit, Nonbreeding adult has grayish-brown upperparts. Individual feathers have dark central lines, yielding a streaked look. Breast is grayish, with fine streaking, and lower underparts are white. Bill is pinkish at the base and black at the tip.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Uses its long bill to probe mudflats for mollusks, crustaceans, and worms.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Birds in the "European" subspecies group have a mostly white rump, with the white extending up onto the back, and whitish underwings.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Birds in the "Siberian" subspecies group have heavy barring on the rump and underwings.
Bar-tailed_Godwit, Occurs on mudflats or sand flats along bays, estuaries, and ocean shorelines.

Barn_Swallow, The most widespread and abundant swallow in the world, recognizable by its long, deeply forked tail and dark blue upperparts. Different subspecies groups vary in size, throat and underpart color, and length of tail streamers.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "American" Barn Swallows have a rusty forehead and throat, an incomplete breast band, and cinnamon underparts.
Barn_Swallow, Upperparts are usually steely blue, but color changes with angle of light. Note long wings. At some times of year, some individuals lack the long tail streamers.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "White-bellied" Barn Swallows breeding in Europe, North Africa, and western Asia have a whitish belly and a thick blue band across the chest.
Barn_Swallow, Males and females are similar in appearance, but males have longer outer tail feathers than females
Barn_Swallow, Both males and females help build the nest, using pellets of mud combined with dry grasses.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "Buff-bellied" Barn Swallows breeding in East Asia are similar to "American" Barn Swallows in appearance, but have a larger rusty throat patch.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "Tytler's" Barn Swallows breeding in Siberia and northern Mongolia have reddish-orange underparts and a narrow, sometimes-broken breast band.
Barn_Swallow, Often forages in flocks, fairly low to the ground. Flight is very light and agile, with quick turns and little gliding.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "Levant" Barn Swallows breeding in western Asia have rich orange underparts and a thick blue breast band.
Barn_Swallow, Adult "Egyptian" Barn Swallows have dark reddish-orange underparts and a thick dark blue breast band.
Barn_Swallow, Nests are made of mud and grass and usually placed under eaves, barn rafter, bridges, and culverts.
Barn_Swallow, Slender-bodied with a long, deeply forked tail. From below, the underparts vary from pale cinnamon or tawny to bright cinnamon.
Barn_Swallow, Flies with fluid wingbeats making quick turns and dives; rarely glides. Tail is long and deeply forked with a white band across it.
Barn_Swallow, In flight, note "White-bellied" Barn Swallows' white underparts and white underwing coverts.
Barn_Swallow, Juvenile "American" Barn Swallows are dark above and pale cinnamon below with a rich rusty throat and forehead. Their tail is also shorter without the deep fork.
Barn_Swallow, Immatures are duller than adults and have shorter tails.
Barn_Swallow, Juvenile "White-bellied" Barn Swallows have a white belly and tawny throat. The tail is also shorter without the deep fork.
Barn_Swallow, Preferred nest sites include eaves, rafters, and cross beams of barns, sheds and stables, as well as the undersides of bridges, wharfs, and culverts.

Barn_Swallow, Long and slender with a deeply forked tail. In "American" Barn Swallows, the color of the underparts varies from buffy to rich cinnamon with the females typically having paler underparts.
Barn_Swallow, Collects mud in bill to build a mud and grass nest—often tucked under the eaves of barns and stables, on structures near playing fields, or under bridges.
Barn_Swallow, Often seen in flocks in open habitats from fields, parks, and roadway edges to marshes, meadows, ponds, and coastal waters.

Barnacle_Goose, A small, compact goose with a short, stubby bill. The head is mostly white, with a black crown and a black line between the eye and bill. The neck, throat, and breast are black, contrasting with the white face and grayish-white belly. The upperparts are light gray, with heavy black barring. The legs and bill are black.
Barnacle_Goose, In flight, note the silvery upperwings, two-toned underwings, and black breast.
Barnacle_Goose, A small goose with a mostly white head; black neck, throat, and breast; grayish-white underparts; and silver upperparts with black barring.
Barnacle_Goose, Forms large flocks while foraging, on migration, and on wintering grounds.
Barnacle_Goose, Juveniles quickly develop the general color pattern of this species, but their plumage is duller overall.
Barnacle_Goose, Both parents care for the young, which can walk, feed, and swim as soon as they leave the nest.
Barnacle_Goose, Easily identified among Graylag Geese and other "gray geese" by small size and black, gray, and white coloration.
Barnacle_Goose, In Svalbard, Greenland, and northwestern Russia, nests on rocky outcrops or cliffs.
Barnacle_Goose, Wintering birds across Europe forage on tidal mudflats, saltmarshes, meadows, and pastures.
Barnacle_Goose, A highly social species, often forming huge flocks during migration and on wintering grounds.
Barred_Owl, Fairly large, with dark eyes and a yellow bill. Buffy below with dark streaks, and brown on the back with white mottling.
Barred_Owl, Upperparts are brown with mottling, and the tail is brown with white barring.
Barred_Owl, A large, stocky owl with a rounded head and no ear tufts. Song is a distinctive hooting described as "Who cooks for you? Who cooks for you-all?"
Barred_Owl, Juveniles are gray and fluffy with darker brown barring and mottling throughout.
Barred_Owl, Often occurs as pairs throughout the year.
Barred_Owl, Mostly nocturnal, but sometimes active in morning and evening. Tends to sit quietly, swiveling head to listen for prey. Note round head and brown eyes.
Barred_Owl, Hunts for a variety of prey, including amphibians and fish.
Barred_Owl, Typically occurs in well wooded habitats, but will come to edges and more open areas.
Barred_Owl, Typically conceals itself amid branches and foliage to sleep during the day. Sometimes discovered by forest birds and mobbed or scolded; their calls can be a good way to find owls.
Barred_Owl, Flies with broad, rounded wings. Big head and flat face gives a blunt-headed appearance in flight that can help distinguish from hawks.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a triangular head, steep forehead, and rather straight bill. White patch behind bill is usually crescent shaped. Small white spots along mostly black wing.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a triangular head, steep forehead, and rather straight bill. White patch behind bill is usually crescent shaped. Small white spots along mostly black wing.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Jumps up slightly before diving underwater in search of aquatic invertebrates, fish eggs, and plant material.
Barrows_Goldeneye, In flight, white panels on wing don't reach the leading edge. White face patch is crescent shaped.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a steep forehead that meets bill at an abrupt angle. Bill is blackish (female's is yellowish). White facial patch is crescent shaped.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Female has white collar that can be hidden depending on posture. Brown head contrasts with gray body. Ducklings are dark with white throats.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a triangular head, steep forehead, and rather straight bill. White patch behind bill is usually crescent shaped. Small white spots along mostly black wing.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a large head, steep forehead, and fairly straight, mostly yellow bill. Warm brown head contrasts with gray body.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Can form large flocks, in which males often display for females. Occurs on inland lakes and rivers as well as coastal waters.
Barrows_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a triangular head, steep forehead, and rather straight bill. White patch behind bill is usually crescent shaped. Small white spots along mostly black wing.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, A long-winged warbler with thick, white wingbars. This breeding male shows a dark-streaked back, butter yellow neck patch, black mask, and a rich dark bay color on the crown, throat, and flanks. Generally found in trees, preferring conifers during the breeding season, but may be found on the ground during migration.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, This long-winged, short-tailed warbler shows bold white wingbars and a dark-streaked back. Females are more subtly patterned than males. Note the color of the lower flank and undertail coverts: buff instead of white. This particularly drab individual has just a hint of bay color below the cheek.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, A long-winged warbler with thick, white wingbars. This breeding male shows a dark-streaked back, butter yellow neck patch, black mask, and a rich dark bay color on the crown, throat, and flanks. Generally found in trees, preferring conifers during the breeding season, but may be found on the ground during migration.
