Bay-breasted_Warbler, The stout bill, prominent pale neck patches, and bold white wingbars are useful for ID in all plumages. Breeding females show a variable amount of bay or chestnut on the crown, face, upper chest, and flank.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, Fall migrant females and immatures often show only faint bay or chestnut coloration, so instead focus on the bright yellow-green head and back, plain face lacking a strongly contrasting eyeline, bold white wingbars, and buff-olive (not white) undertail coverts. Additionally, the legs and feet are nondescript and dark, lacking strongly contrasting yellow soles to the feet.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, A long-winged warbler with thick, white wingbars. This breeding male shows a dark-streaked back, butter yellow neck patch, black mask, and a rich dark bay color on the crown, throat, and flanks. Generally found in trees, preferring conifers during the breeding season, but may be found on the ground during migration.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, The stout, dark bill variably marked pale and the bold contrast created by the thick white wingbars against the dark gray wing are useful keys to identifying this messy-looking, nonbreeding male. The pale yellowish neck patch and bold swath of bay on the flank help to lock down the species ID.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, In late summer and fall, females and immatures are best identified by the low contrast yellow-green head, bold white wingbars, and plain, buff flanks and undertail coverts. Many also show a large amount of pale pink in the otherwise dark bill.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, A long-winged warbler with thick, white wingbars. This breeding male shows a dark-streaked back, butter yellow neck patch, black mask, and a rich dark bay color on the crown, throat, and flanks. Generally found in trees, preferring conifers during the breeding season, but may be found on the ground during migration.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, Nonbreeding individuals can be hard to identify. When viewed from below, look for plain, unstreaked yellow-green plumage with buff-olive tones on the flanks and undertail coverts. Also, the largely pale bill and low contrast face pattern with just a slight dark eyeline are subtly distinctive.
Bay-breasted_Warbler, The combination of a yellowish neck patch, black mask, and dark chestnut crown, throat, and flanks make the breeding male nearly unmistakable.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, A long-winged warbler with thick, white wingbars. This breeding male shows a dark-streaked back, butter yellow neck patch, black mask, and a rich dark bay color on the crown, throat, and flanks. Generally found in trees, preferring conifers during the breeding season, but may be found on the ground during migration.

Bay-breasted_Warbler, Breeds in boreal spruce and fir forests. Though the black mask, yellowish neck patch, and chestnut throat and flanks create a very distinctive look for this breeding male, also note the buff tones of the undertail coverts and black-and-white tail pattern - these features are useful for ID in all plumages.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head, short bill, and long tail. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head, short bill, and long tail. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head, short bill, and long tail. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Gray head contrasts with the streaky brown back. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head, short bill, and long tail. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head and long tail. Juveniles are more uniformly brown, lack the gray head, and are streaky beneath.
Bells_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a round head, short bill, and long tail. Key field marks include the central breast spot, white eyering, and black-and-white mustache stripes.
Bells_Sparrow, Often sings from high perches in scrubby sagebrush and chaparral areas.
Bells_Sparrow, In the summer months, males often sing from prominent perches in sagebrush, chaparral, and other scrubby areas.

Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with a bill larger than a warbler's but fairly small for a vireo. Brownish-gray overall with two pale wingbars, the upper one less distinct than the lower one. Flanks are usually washed yellow.

Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with a heavier bill than a warbler. Brownish-gray overall with two whitish wingbars. "Least" subspecies (endangered) occurs in California and is the grayest form, with almost no green or yellow.
Bells_Vireo, Song has been described as "the musical equivalent of a scribble"—jerky warbling phrases, the first ending on an upslur, the next on a downslur.
Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with pale arcs around the eye, interrupted by dark line through eye. Brownish-gray overall with two wingbars, the lower one more prominent.

Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with a heavier bill than a warbler's. "Eastern" subspecies is the brightest, with greenish back, yellow flanks, and gray head with dark line through eye and broken white eyering.
Bells_Vireo, Occurs in shrubs and thickets, often fairly low. "Arizona" subspecies is mostly gray-brown with wingbars that can be indistinct. Flanks can show faint yellow.

Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with fairly small bill for a vireo. Grayish overall with pale arcs around the eye, broken by a dark line through the eye. Wingbars can be indistinct. Yellow wash on flanks is often faint.
Bells_Vireo, Small songbird with bill thicker than a warbler's. "Eastern" subspecies can have bright yellow underparts. Pale eyering is broken by dark line through eye.
Bells_Vireo, Occurs in tangled shrubby and brushy areas including wetlands, regenerating woods, thickets, brushy fields, mesquite, and chaparral.
Belted_Kingfisher, Stocky, large-headed bird with a shaggy crest and a thick daggerlike bill. Females are blue-gray with a chestnut belly band and flanks.
Belted_Kingfisher, Large, crested fish-eating bird. Males are blue-gray with a white collar and blue-gray breast band.
Belted_Kingfisher, Typically forages by perching on a high branch or telephone wire before plunging headfirst into a shallow water body. Pursues fish, amphibians, reptiles, and other aquatic prey.
Belted_Kingfisher, Immatures' upper breast band is a mix of rufous and slate gray.
Belted_Kingfisher, Large, big-headed bird with a hefty bill. Females are more colorful than males with a chestnut belly band and flanks.
Belted_Kingfisher, Catches fish by plunging directly into the water from a perch, or by hovering over the water and diving in.
Belted_Kingfisher, In flight, note the large white patch in the outer wings.
Belted_Kingfisher, Belted Kingfishers spend much of their time perched alone along the edges of streams, lakes, and estuaries, searching for small fish.
Belted_Kingfisher, The only kingfisher across all of Canada and most of the United States. Easily recognizable by heavy bill, large head, slate gray head and upperparts, and white collar.
Belted_Kingfisher, Found near streams, rivers, ponds, lakes, and estuaries.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Like other thrashers has a long tail, but bill is shorter and straighter. Uniformly pale brown overall without obvious wingbars.
Bendires_Thrasher, Large songbird, but smaller than similar thrashers. Triangular spots mark the breast forming distinct streaks. Bill is shorter and straighter than similar Curve-billed Thrasher.
Bendires_Thrasher, Found in open grasslands, shrublands, or woodlands with scattered shrubs or trees. Usually not found in areas with dense vegetation.
Bewicks_Wren, Medium-sized brown wren with a long tail that is often held up. The bill is long and slightly curved. Note white eyebrow and dark barring on the tail.
Bewicks_Wren, Boisterous and curious medium-sized wren with a bold white eyebrow stripe. Plumage varies regionally from rusty-brown in humid regions to gray in drier regions in the U.S.
Bewicks_Wren, Holds tail up over the back, often flicking it from side to side or fanning it as they skulk through tangles of branches and leaves searching for insects.

Bewicks_Wren, Plumage color varies regionally from rusty in more humid regions to gray in desert regions. Birds from San Francisco Bay south to Monterey, California, have less rusty coloring than birds farther north.
Bewicks_Wren, Males and females build a cup-shaped nest with grasses, rootlets, and leaves inside a hole in a tree or on a protected ledge.
Bewicks_Wren, Occurs in brushy areas, scrub and thickets in open country, and open woodland.
Bewicks_Wren, A highly vocal species. Males sing from a repertoire of 10–20+ songs. Some calls are female-specific, others are given only by males, and some calls are delivered by both sexes.

Bewicks_Wren, Found in dry brushy areas, chaparral, scrub, thickets, and open woodlands near streams. They are at home in gardens and parks in cities and suburbs. Nests in holes in trees or on protected ledges.
Bicknells_Thrush, Medium-sized brown thrush with a plain (unstreaked) brown face and little to no eyering. Extremely similar to Gray-cheeked Thrush and best distinguished by voice.
Bicknells_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a plain brown face. Breeds in mountain forests with windblown and stunted balsam fir.
Bicknells_Thrush, Plain brown thrush that usually shows very little eyering. Tail is slightly warmer brown than the back. Nests in stunted evergreen forests on mountaintops.
Bicknells_Thrush, Slender brown thrush that breeds in mountains of eastern Canada and winters in the Greater Antilles.
Bicknells_Thrush, Spotted below with a brown face. Often stays hidden among dense vegetation.

Bicknells_Thrush, Plain brown thrush with thin eyering and bold spots on the breast. Breeding range does not overlap with Gray-cheeked Thrush, but during migration the two species can occur together and are best distinguished by voice.
Bicknells_Thrush, Medium-sized brown thrush with a plain (unstreaked) brown face and little to no eyering. Extremely similar to Gray-cheeked Thrush and best distinguished by voice.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Small songbird with a thin, slightly curved bill. Striped black and white overall. Males have a black ear patch.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Females are often paler, with a white throat, a grayish ear patch, and sometimes a wash of buff on the flanks.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Typically forages on trunks and main branches, like a nuthatch. Note black-spotted undertail coverts.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Small songbird with a slightly curved bill. Immature and female birds have a whiter throat and a grayish ear patch.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Creeps up and down trees and main branches like a nuthatch.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Song is a thin whistle that sounds like a squeaky wheel spinning. The other, louder song audible here is a Common Yellowthroat.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Heavily streaked black and white. Tail is dark with white spots on outer tail feathers.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Small songbird that is heavily streaked black and white.
Black-and-white_Warbler, White undertail coverts with black spots are a distinctive field mark of Black-and-white Warblers.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Creeps up and down trees and main branches like a nuthatch.
Black-and-white_Warbler, Picks insects from bark of twigs, branches, and tree trunks. Much less likely to forage among leaves than other warblers.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a solid black back, single white stripe on the face, and barred flanks. Males have a yellow crown patch.

Black-backed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized, mostly black woodpecker with single white cheek stripe and barred flanks. Wings have reduced white spotting. Like the American Three-toed Woodpecker, has 3 instead of 4 toes.

Black-backed_Woodpecker, A medium-sized woodpecker with a long, powerful bill; inky black back; and fine black barring on the flanks. Male has a yellow crown patch, lacking in adult female but present in juvenile.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Male has a yellow crown patch, solid black back, and barred flanks. Sometimes appears dingy gray on the underparts from feeding on soot-blackened trees.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Almost entirely black from behind, save for the small white spots on the wings and fully white outer tail feathers.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Best known as a specialist in burned forests, but also forages in unburned forest, particularly on trees infested with bark beetles.

Black-backed_Woodpecker, Females have a black crown, a white stripe on the face, and barred flanks. Found across the boreal forest and in the mountains of western North America, particularly in recently burned forests where wood-boring insects are abundant.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Unhurried foraging style. Typically stays in one spot for long periods, first stripping away bark and then pecking into wood-boring beetle tunnels to extract the larvae.
Black-backed_Woodpecker, Often seems to explore for food, stopping to test the bark with a few exploratory pecks to find out whether beetle larvae lie inside.
Black-bellied_Plover, Heavy-bodied shorebird with a short, thick neck and a stubby bill. Nonbreeding birds have variable amounts of brownish mottling on the back and a smudgy face and breast.
Black-bellied_Plover, Males and females equally share the responsibility of nest incubation, which usually lasts from the end of May to the end of June.
Black-bellied_Plover, Short-necked shorebird with a stubby bill. Juveniles have a crisply marked salt-and-pepper look to them with a streaked breast.
Black-bellied_Plover, In flight, all ages show distinctive black armpits. Note mostly white tail.
Black-bellied_Plover, During the nonbreeding season on the Atlantic Coast, Black-bellied Plovers forage for larger prey items such as marine worms, bivalves, and shrimp.
Black-bellied_Plover, Heavy-bodied shorebird with a short, thick neck and a stubby bill. Breeding males have a black belly and a mottled black-and-white back.
Black-bellied_Plover, Juveniles have a salt and pepper look to them with a streaked breast.
Black-bellied_Plover, Commonly forages on lake shores or flooded agricultural fields during migration.

Black-bellied_Plover, Heavy-bodied shorebird with a short, thick neck and a thick but stubby bill. Nonbreeding birds have variable amounts of brownish mottling on the back and a smudgy face and breast.
Black-bellied_Plover, Heavy-bodied shorebird with a short, thick neck and a stubby bill. Breeding males have a black belly and a mottled black-and-white back.

Black-bellied_Plover, Black-bellied Plovers perform distraction displays including running, faking wing injuries, and head bowing to draw a predator's attention toward themselves and away from the nest.
Black-bellied_Plover, During migration and winter found on beaches, estuaries, lake margins, and flooded pastures.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Long-necked duck with a red bill and long pink legs. Its body is mostly chestnut, with a black belly and a gray face. The white patch in the wings appears as a stripe down its wing while at rest.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, In flight shows a large white patch on the upperwings. Flies with large pink feet projecting beyond the tail tip and head and neck head slightly down, imparting a kinked appearance.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Long-necked duck with a red bill and long pink legs. Its body is mostly chestnut, with a black belly and a gray face. The white patch in the wings appears as a stripe down its wing while at rest.
Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Juveniles are browner than adults and lack the black belly. Note also the black bill and pale legs shown by juveniles.
Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, South American adults (subspecies autumnalis ) show a wide, pale gray-brown band separating the rich brown neck from the black belly.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Long-necked duck with a red bill and long pink legs. Its body is mostly chestnut, with a black belly and a gray face. The white patch in the wings appears as a stripe down its wing while at rest.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, The long, slender neck, plank-like wings, and long legs projecting beyond the tail make this recognizable as a whistling-duck. Juveniles show a pale brown belly, gray bill, and pale pink legs and feet.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, The stout bill and slim neck help create the whistling-duck "look." The pink-orange bill, white eyering, and large black belly patch that extends up the flanks combine to rule out other similar species.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Long-necked duck with a red bill and long pink legs. Its body is mostly chestnut, with a black belly and a gray face. The white patch in the wings appears as a stripe down its wing while at rest.
Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Very young chicks show a highly distinctive black-and-yellow bumblebee pattern with highly contrasting head stripes.
Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Nests in large holes or hollows in trees as well as nest boxes. Often perches in trees or on rooftops, sometimes well away from water.

Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, Long-necked duck with a red bill and long pink legs. Its body is mostly chestnut, with a black belly and a gray face. The white patch in the wings appears as a stripe down its wing while at rest.
Black-bellied_Whistling-Duck, These gregarious waterfowl occur in flocks year-round. Frequently seen perching on fence posts or wires, especially near agricultural fields.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Slender, long-tailed bird with a red ring around the eye and a long black bill. From below, note small white tips on the tail feathers.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Slender, long-tailed bird with a hunchbacked look. Brownish above with little rusty color in the wings. Note black bill and red ring around the eye.

Black-billed_Cuckoo, Plain brown above and white below, with a red ring around the eye and a black bill. Males and females sing a staccato series of 3 to 5 toots on the same pitch, often going on for several minutes.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Slender and long-tailed with narrow white tips on the tail feathers.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Slender, long-tailed bird with a hunchbacked look. Brownish above with little rusty color in the wings. Note black bill.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Sluggish and secretive it often perches motionless in trees and shrubs.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Secretive birds. Found in woodlands and thickets.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Tends to stay hidden in dense foliage and remains motionless for long periods.
Black-billed_Cuckoo, Eats larger insects such as caterpillars, katydids, cicadas, and grasshoppers, often focusing on insect outbreaks.
Black-billed_Magpie, Jaylike bird with a long tail and a heavy bill. Appears entirely black and white, but in good light the wings and tail shine with a blue-green iridescence.
Black-billed_Magpie, Flies with a bounding and rowing wingbeats, flashing its white primaries in flight. Note the white bars down its back and long diamond-shaped tail.

Black-billed_Magpie, Long-tailed black-and-white bird of open country. Often forages on the ground and perches on posts and small trees. Blue-green iridescence in wings and tail is not always visible.
Black-billed_Magpie, Striking black-and-white bird with blue wings and a long graduated tail.
Black-billed_Magpie, A conspicuous and gregarious bird with a long tail and white braces down its back.
Black-billed_Magpie, Flies with deep, rowing wingbeats interspersed with short glides or shallower strokes. Note very long tail and large white patches in wings in flight.
Black-billed_Magpie, Found in meadows, grasslands, and sagebrush plains of the West as well as towns and other open areas.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Small and compact, with a thin, short bill. Black cap and bib contrast with white cheeks, gray back and wings, and light buffy underparts.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Often moves acrobatically through small branches, and can perch sideways or upside-down.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Song is a 2-noted, clear whistle, with the second note lower than the first.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Bold black-and-white head pattern strongly contrasts with the rest of the plumage.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Small bill and long tail impart a compact, rotund look. Note white-edged secondaries.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Both male and female chickadees excavate a cavity in a site usually selected by the female.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Forages for seeds both on wild plants and bird feeders.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Nests in holes in trees and nest boxes. Occurs in a wide variety of wooded and shrubby habitats.
Black-capped_Chickadee, Often visits feeders, including suet feeders. Note the extensive white edging to the feathers of the wing.

Black-capped_Chickadee, When agitated, chickadees scold with their chick-a-dee calls, or sometimes shorten the calls to a string of "dee" notes. These birds are responding to the call of an Eastern Screech-Owl.

Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, A small gray songbird with a long tail and long bill. Upperparts are blue-gray and underparts are grayish-white. Adult male in breeding plumage has a black cap that extends from the bill to behind the eye.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Female and nonbreeding male lack a black cap. Note the white outer tail feathers contrasting with the black inner feathers.

Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, A small, fidgety songbird that frequently flicks and cocks its long tail. Grayish-white below with darker gray upperparts. Adult male in breeding plumage has a black cap that stretches from the base of the bill to behind the eye. Gives a variety of nasal mewing calls.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Female and nonbreeding male have a full white eyering. Note the long, dark bill.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, The underside of the tail appears white when the tail is closed.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Nearly endemic to northwestern Mexico, but also occurs annually in southeastern Arizona in small numbers.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Frequently cocks its tail like other gnatcatchers.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Tail is strongly graduated, with central feathers longer than outermost feathers. The two outer tail feathers are mostly white.
Black-capped_Gnatcatcher, Occurs in thorn scrub, dry forest, and in the northern part of its range, in woodland along creeks and rivers.
Black-capped_Petrel, A medium-sized seabird with a black cap, white underparts, and mostly white underwings with black tips and broad black edges.

Black-capped_Petrel, The "White-faced" form has a smaller black cap bordered by a large white neck collar and a thin white line running through the eye. Note also the weaker chest spur (nearly absent here) than on the "Dark-faced" form.
Black-capped_Petrel, Strikingly patterned above, with the large white rump patch and white neck collar contrasting with the otherwise dark upperparts.
Black-capped_Petrel, In stronger wind, flies in a roller coaster pattern, with high arcs alternating with descending glides.
Black-capped_Petrel, The "Dark-faced" form has a larger black cap that surrounds the dark eye, a wide brownish spur that extends onto the side of the chest, and a brownish hindneck.
Black-capped_Vireo, Small songbird with a forward perching posture. Males have a black head and white spectacles that surround their red eye. White below with yellow washed flanks.
Black-capped_Vireo, Small, somewhat stocky songbird with a hooked bill. Females have a gray head and white spectacles. Mostly white below with yellow washed flanks.

Black-capped_Vireo, Sings throughout its territory during the breeding season, often perching on an exposed branch or dead twig just below the canopy of trees and shrubs. Song described as "drink yur, drink yur or drink yur teee."
Black-capped_Vireo, Uniquely marked vireo with a black head and white spectacles surrounding a red eye. Yellow-olive above.
Black-capped_Vireo, Small songbird with a forward perching posture. Males have a black head and white spectacles that surround their red eye. White below with yellow washed flanks.
Black-capped_Vireo, Small songbird with a forward perching posture. Males have a black head and white spectacles that surround their red eye. White below with yellow washed flanks.
Black-capped_Vireo, Breeds in oak-juniper scrublands in Texas, Oklahoma, and northern Mexico.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, A small, slender hummingbird with a long, straight bill. Adults males have a dull black head and a deep black throat bordered below by iridescent purple (in good light).
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are dull metallic green above with a whitish throat and underparts. Note white tips on outer tail feathers.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Perches on exposed twigs to survey territory and chase off intruders. Often returns to these perches over and over.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Fairly long and slender hummingbird with a long black bill. Adult males have a purple throat that often looks black. Note white spot behind the eye.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Females/immatures have whitish underparts with some dull metallic green on the flanks. The outer tail feathers are tipped in white.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Slender hummingbird with a straight black bill. Adult males have a purple band in the throat that most often appears black.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Immature males typically show a few iridescent purple throat feathers.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Females and immature males have white tips to the three outermost tail feathers.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Adult males have a black head and throat with a limited purple gorget. Note also the small white spot behind the eye.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are dull metallic green above with whitish underparts. Perched birds often show a pale collar.
Black-chinned_Hummingbird, Found in lowland deserts and mountainous forests in natural habitats as well as very urbanized areas as long as there are tall trees and flowering shrubs and vines.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A slender sparrow with a pink conical bill. Breeding males are gray with brown wings and a black throat patch.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A slender sparrow with a pink conical bill. Breeding males are gray with brown wings and a black throat patch.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, Males often sing from conspicuous perches during the breeding season.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A long-tailed sparrow with a pink conical bill. Nonbreeding birds lack the breeding male's black throat.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A slender sparrow with a pink conical bill. Breeding males are gray with brown wings and a black throat patch.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A gray sparrow with a pink bill, brown wings, and brown streaks down its back.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, A slender sparrow with a pink conical bill. Breeding males are gray with brown wings and a black throat patch.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, Females look like males, but lack the black chin and throat patch.
Black-chinned_Sparrow, Found in dry brushlands and chaparral along rugged hillsides.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stubby round bill. Gray above and whitish below with peach-colored flanks. Note white forehead and black crest.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small chickadeelike bird with a black crest. Gray above and whitish below with peach sides.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Adult
Black-crested_Titmouse, Acrobatic forager that uses its strong feet to hang from branches.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small songbird that appears larger than it is due to its crest and long tail. Gray above and white below with peachy sides. Note black crest and white forehead.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stubby round bill. Gray above and whitish below with peach-colored flanks. Note white forehead and black crest.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stubby round bill. Gray above and whitish below with peach-colored flanks. Note white forehead and black crest.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees created naturally or excavated by woodpeckers. Also uses nest boxes.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stubby round bill. Gray above and whitish below with peach-colored flanks. Note white forehead and black crest.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Found in evergreen and deciduous forests and woodlands, especially those with mesquite or oak. Also found in orchards, parks, and suburban areas.
Black-crested_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stubby round bill. Gray above and whitish below with peach-colored flanks. Note white forehead and black crest.

Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Stocky and compact heron. Often tucks neck into its body creating a hunchbacked look. Adult has a black cap and back that contrasts with its whitish to pale gray belly and gray wings.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Thick-necked heron with a thick bill. Juvenile is brown and streaky overall. Note pale yellowish bill.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Squat heron with hunchbacked posture, flat head, and fairly short legs.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Juvenile is brown overall with heavy blurry streaking on the neck and white spotting on the wings.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Immature has a mix of juvenile and adult plumage. This individual has faint streaking on the chest, a dark gray cap, and a nearly complete dark gray back.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, The most widespread heron in the world. The "Eurasian" subspecies group breeds in parts of Europe, Asia, and Africa.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, The "Eurasian" and "American" subspecies groups are similar in appearance, but birds in Europe, Asia, and Africa are smaller than birds in the Americas.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Flies with its neck tucked in with only part of its feet trailing behind. In flight, note pale underparts.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Residents in southern South America are darker brown overall with a gray cap.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Often stands motionless while watching for prey. Individuals in southern South America are darker below with a paler gray cap.
Black-crowned_Night_Heron, Found in wetland habitats including estuaries, marshes, streams, lakes, and reservoirs.

Black-footed_Albatross, Large seabird with long, narrow wings. Mostly dark except for a white ring around its long, thick bill. The amount of white around the bill varies from a thin ring to a wide band around face.
Black-footed_Albatross, Large seabird with a long, thick bill. Feeds on the surface of the water.
Black-footed_Albatross, Large seabird with long, narrow wings. Flies low over the surface of the water with stiff wings.
Black-footed_Albatross, Large, dark seabird with a long, thick bill. Wanders widely across the northern Pacific for most of the year, and is regularly seen off the west coast of North America.
Black-footed_Albatross, Large, bulky seabird with long, narrow wings. The amount of white around the bill and on the rump varies with age and feather wear.

Black-footed_Albatross, Large seabird with long, narrow wings. Mostly dark except for a white ring around its long, thick bill. The amount of white around the bill varies from a thin ring to a wide band around face.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Hefty songbird with a very thick conical bill. Adult males are rich orange-cinnamon with a black head and black-and-white wings.

Black-headed_Grosbeak, Relatively large-headed with a short, thick neck and a short tail that imparts a compact, chunky look. Females/immatures have warm orange or buff on the breast. Some have streaks on the sides of the breast.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Thick-bodied songbird with a very large, triangular bill. Perches, sings and forages at middle and high levels in trees along edges.

Black-headed_Grosbeak, A medium-sized songbird with a heavy bill. Adult males have a black head, orange underparts, and black wings with white patches. Note also the white spots on the underside of the black tail.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Chunky songbird with a hefty bill. Females/immatures are brown and streaky above with orangish underparts. Note buffy eyebrow and neck.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Females and immatures are warm buff on the undersides with a strongly striped head, huge bill, and brown-and-white back and wings.

Black-headed_Grosbeak, The amount of streaking on the underparts varies among individuals. This individual has streaked flanks. Note buffy eyebrow and neck, and bicolored bill (dark on top, pale on bottom).
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Adult males have a streaky black-and-orange back and black wings with white patches.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, The whistled song rises and falls like an American Robin's, but is longer, sweeter, more varied, and less choppy in its phrases. Both males and females sing.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a hefty bill. Females/immatures have a warm orange breast with variable amounts of streaking.

Black-headed_Grosbeak, Females/immatures have buffy-to-orange underparts with variable streaking on the flanks, streaky brown upperparts, and brown wings with two white wingbars. Note the dusky mask behind the eye and a white-to-buffy eyebrow bordered above by a dark head stripe.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Often comes to backyard feeders to eat sunflower seeds; may also visit hummingbird or oriole feeders.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Adult male has light yellow underwing linings and a prominent white wing patch.
Black-headed_Grosbeak, Found in mixed woodlands and edges, mountain forests, thickets along desert streams, backyards, and gardens.

Black-headed_Gull, Adult in breeding plumage has a dark brown hood covering about two-thirds of the head, thin white crescents above and below the eye, pale gray upperparts, and white underparts. The legs and slender bill are both dark red.

Black-headed_Gull, A common species across much of Europe and Asia, often found in flocks. Adults in breeding plumage have a dark brown hood covering about two-thirds of the head, thin white crescents above and below the eyes, pale gray upperparts, white underparts, and dark red legs and bill.
Black-headed_Gull, Nonbreeding adult has dark smudging above and behind the eye and a dusky-tipped red bill.

Black-headed_Gull, Immature has two dark marks on the head, one above the eye and the other behind it. The back is pale gray, like an adult, but the wings show some brown feathers, like a juvenile. The legs are orange, and the bill is orange with a dark tip.
Black-headed_Gull, Some pairs nest on emergent vegetation in shallow water, with others nesting on the ground among vegetation.

Black-headed_Gull, Juvenile has mostly brown upperparts, with some lighter feathers and pale feather edging mixed in. The head has a hint of a hood, with two stronger marks in front of and behind the eye. White eye crescents are detectable at close range. The bill is bicolored, with a black tip. The legs are pinkish.
Black-headed_Gull, In flight, breeding adult's underwing shows a white leading edge contrasting strongly with adjacent black primaries.

Black-headed_Gull, Often gathers in flocks outside of the breeding season. Nonbreeding adults have dark smudges above and behind the eye. Immatures have brown coverts and tertials and a black band near the tip of the tail.
Black-headed_Gull, Adult in flight has a white leading edge on both the upperwing and underwing; the white on the upperwing is bordered by a black trailing edge.

Black-headed_Gull, In all plumages, the upperwing has a white leading edge bordered by a black trailing edge. Immature has the head and back pattern of an adult, and the wing and tail pattern of a juvenile (including brown upperwing coverts and a black band at the tip of the tail).
Black-headed_Gull, Typically forages by walking and then seizing prey.

Black-headed_Gull, In all plumages, the upperwing has a white leading edge bordered by a black trailing edge. Juvenile has a brown back, dark tail band, bicolored bill, dusky head, and brown upperwing coverts.
Black-headed_Gull, Black-headed Gulls nest in colonies and often gather in large flocks during the winter.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Small gull with short black legs. Breeding adults have a thin yellow bill.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Nonbreeding adults have a black smudge behind the eye, but retain the yellow bill. Note the short black legs.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Adults have clean gray backs while juveniles have a black bar on the wing that becomes a bold "M" pattern in flight.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Small gull with short black legs. Breeding adults have a thin yellow bill.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Immature Black-legged Kittiwakes have a striking "M" pattern on the back and a black mark across the back of the neck. Note black terminal band on the tail.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Wings are more rounded than other gull species, and they tend to beat their wings more rapidly. Note the solid black wingtips.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Flies with stiff and rapid wingbeats. Note the small amount of black on the tips of the wings.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Small gull with short black legs. Breeding adults have a thin yellow bill.
Black-legged_Kittiwake, Nests on cliff ledges of offshore islands, sea stacks, or inaccessible areas of coastal mainland. Spends the winter at sea.
Black-necked_Stilt, Tall and lanky shorebird with a delicate-looking body. Black above and white below with pink legs.
Black-necked_Stilt, Lanky, delicate looking shorebird. Individuals in South America (White-backed) have a white collar across upper back that North American birds lack.
Black-necked_Stilt, Forages in shallow water wetlands, picking the surface for small aquatic invertebrates and flies.
Black-necked_Stilt, Resident individuals on the Hawaiian Islands have more black on the forehead and cheeks than individuals breeding in North America.
Black-necked_Stilt, In flight, its long pink legs stick out far beyond the tail. Note black wings and a white V on the back.
Black-necked_Stilt, Juveniles look similar to adults but are slightly browner with faint scalloping on the back and paler pink legs.
Black-necked_Stilt, Tall and slender shorebird with pink legs and a thin black bill.
Black-necked_Stilt, Found in shallow wetlands gracefully foraging for aquatic invertebrates. Note dainty appearance and pink legs.
Black-necked_Stilt, Nests on the ground on matted vegetation, on small mounds above the water, or on floating mats of vegetation.
Black-necked_Stilt, Found in shallow water wetlands often foraging with other Black-necked Stilts.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Tiny, slim songbird with a thin, straight bill, and a long tail. Gray overall with a mostly black tail. Breeding males have a black cap.

Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Tiny songbird with a thin bill and long tail. Females are grayish above and whitish below. Their tail is mostly black with white tips on the outer tail feathers that are visible in flight and from underneath when perched.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Quickly hops from branch to branch in search for insects among desert trees and shrubs.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Small and dainty with a small bill and long tail. Grayish above and white below. Note black line above the eye on nonbreeding males.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Breeding males have a black cap. Note the white ovals on an otherwise black tail.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Found in thorny scrublands featuring mesquite, creosote bush, ocotillo, and cactus in southwestern U.S. and northern Mexico.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Tiny, slim songbird with a thin, straight bill, and a long tail. Gray overall with a mostly black tail. Breeding males have a black cap.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Tiny, slim songbird with a thin, straight bill, and a long tail. Gray overall with a mostly black tail. Breeding males have a black cap.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Tiny grayish songbird with a black tail that it often flicks. This video has no audio.

Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Small energetic bird with an expressive tail. The tail is mostly black except for white spots on the outer tail feathers. Those white edges form ovals on a closed tail as seen from beneath.
Black-tailed_Gnatcatcher, Found in desert scrub with ocotillo, prickly pear, cholla, and mesquite as well as washes densely lined with creosote and salt bush.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Fairly large, distinctive black-and-blue warbler. Males have a blue head and back with a black face and throat. Note white square on wings.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Females are plain grayish olive overall, although some have blue tints on the wings and tail. White square on the wing is distinctive.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Males sing "I am so lazzzy" in the understory of eastern deciduous forests.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Fairly large, distinctive black-and-blue warbler. Birds in the Appalachian region have black streaking on the back. Note white square on wings.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Females are plain grayish olive with unstreaked underparts. Note pale eyebrow and white crescent under the eye.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Note the diagnostic white wing check.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Fairly large, distinctive black-and-blue warbler. Males have a blue head and back with a black face and throat. Note white belly and undertail coverts.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Females are rather plain looking, but the white square on the wing is diagnostic.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, On the wintering grounds they inhabit dense tropical forests, woodlands, shade-coffee plantations, and second growth areas with woody trees.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Breeds in mature deciduous and mixed evergreen-deciduous woodlands with a thick understory.
Black-throated_Blue_Warbler, Eats insects, which they typically pick from the undersides of leaves.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Small warbler with a black-and-white face, gray back, and black side streaks. Adult males have black throat and a yellow spot in front of the eye.

Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Small warbler with a black-and-white face and gray back. Adult females have variable amounts of black on the throat and are often paler than males. Note small yellow spot in front of the eye.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, The female builds a deep cup nest on top of a branch, using dried grasses or weeds and lined with feathers or animal hair.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Immatures are pale gray overall, but have the same facial pattern including the yellow spot in front of the eye.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Small warbler with a black-and-white face, gray back, and black side streaks. Adult males have black throat and a yellow spot in front of the eye.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Forages for caterpillars and other arthropods at middle levels in trees and shrubs, including oaks, Douglas-firs, pinyon pines, juniper, sagebrush, and bitterbrush.
Black-throated_Gray_Warbler, Found in pinyon-juniper, pine, and mixed oak-pine forests.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a bright yellow face with a dusky ear patch, a black throat, and a green back. Note heavy black streaking on the sides.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Adult females have a yellow face with a dusky ear patch, a white throat, and a green back. Note yellow wash across vent and black streaked sides.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Song is a buzzy series of about five notes, with the second to last usually lower in pitch. It's often described as "zee-zee-zee-zoo-zee."
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Immatures have pale yellow faces with a dusky ear patch and white throat. Streaking on the side can be crisp or messy as on this individual.

Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Adult females have a yellow face with a dusky ear patch and a green back. Some females have bits of black on the throat. Note yellow wash across vent and black streaked sides.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Forages nimbly in small outer twigs of mature trees.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Females/immatures have a yellow face with a dusky ear patch and a green crown and back.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Breeds in boreal evergreen forests and evergreen-deciduous forests.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Males have bright yellow heads and extensive black on the throat and chest.
Black-throated_Green_Warbler, Females and immatures lack the extensive black on the front. Note the two white wingbars.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, A boldly marked sparrow of arid regions of western North America. Adult has a gray mask, bordered by two white lines, and a black throat that extends to the breast.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Juveniles lack the adult's black throat and have faint streaking above and below.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Plump, barrel-chested sparrow with a thick bill and striking head pattern. Call is a thin chip.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Note the white outer tail feathers. Found in desert scrub, canyons, and washes with scattered shrubs.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Males and females look the same. Adults have 2 white stripes on the face and a black throat, which separates them from other sparrows.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-throated_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a striking face pattern: a white stripe above and below the eye and a black throat.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Large for a vireo with a long, hooked bill. Gray crown contrasts with white eyebrow. Dark "whisker" borders the throat, but can be difficult to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Stocky, thick-necked songbird with a long, hooked bill. Underparts are whitish or washed yellow on brighter individuals. Black "whisker" not always noticeable.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Large for a vireo with a long, hooked bill. Gray crown contrasts with white eyebrow. Dark "whisker" borders the throat, but can be difficult to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Large for a vireo with a long, hooked bill. Gray crown contrasts with white eyebrow. Dark "whisker" borders the throat, but can be difficult to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Underparts are whitish with pale yellow undertail coverts that are hard to see on duller individuals. Dark "whisker" mark also not always easy to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Large for a vireo with a long, hooked bill. Gray crown contrasts with white eyebrow. Dark "whisker" borders the throat, but can be difficult to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Large for a vireo with a long, hooked bill. Gray crown contrasts with white eyebrow. Dark "whisker" borders the throat, but can be difficult to see.
Black-whiskered_Vireo, Individuals in the West Indies are browner above. Note white eyebrow and dark "whisker." Found in mangroves and lowland coastal hardwood forests.
Black_Guillemot, Medium-sized black-and-white seabird with a thin and sharp bill. Note red legs.
Black_Guillemot, Nonbreeding birds have whitish heads and underparts.
Black_Guillemot, Forages by diving, using its wings to propel itself underwater. Catches fish, worms, and other prey from near the bottom.
Black_Guillemot, Nonbreeding birds in the high arctic (mandtii subspecies) are whiter overall than nonbreeding birds in the Atlantic.
Black_Guillemot, Potbellied black seabird with white underwings bordered in black.
Black_Guillemot, Medium-sized black-and-white seabird with a thin and sharp bill. Note red legs.
Black_Guillemot, Nests on rocky coastlines.
Black_Guillemot, Black seabird with white wing patches and bright red legs and feet. Forages in waters close to shore.
Black_Oystercatcher, Stocky, all-dark shorebird with a red bill and yellow eye.
Black_Oystercatcher, Juveniles are all dark with a dark-tipped red bill.
Black_Oystercatcher, Typically found on rocky shores. All-dark body and long, orange-red bill are distinctive.
Black_Oystercatcher, Dark overall in flight. Eats molluscs, especially mussels and limpets.
Black_Oystercatcher, Pairs often engage in "piping display" to greet mates or threaten intruders. Pairs rotate in place or run side by side with short, quick steps while giving piping notes.
Black_Oystercatcher, Large, conspicuous, noisy shorebird of the Pacific Coast. Found along rocky seacoasts and islands, less commonly on sandy beaches.
Black_Oystercatcher, Nonbreeding birds often roost together on rocky shorelines above the high water mark.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large, peaked head. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Phoebe, Individuals from eastern Panama and farther south into South America are almost entirely sooty gray with white edging on the wings.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large, peaked head. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Phoebe, Juveniles look similar to adults, but have buffy wingbars.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large head and a medium-long, squared tail. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large, peaked head. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Phoebe, Individuals from eastern Panama and farther south into South America are almost entirely sooty gray with white edging on the wings.
Black_Phoebe, Found along streams, rivers, and lakes. Frequently pumps tail up and down while perched.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large, peaked head. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Phoebe, Individuals in eastern Panama through South America entirely sooty gray with white wing edging. Found near water.
Black_Phoebe, Small, plump songbirds with a large, peaked head. Dark sooty gray overall with a white belly.
Black_Rail, Tiny, short-tailed rail. Head is gray with a red eye and black bill. Upper back is rusty and the rest of the back has white speckling. Very secretive.
Black_Rail, Tiny, short-tailed rail. Head is gray with a red eye and black bill. Upper back is rusty and the rest of the back has white speckling. Very secretive.
Black_Rail, Tiny and very secretive—most often detected by voice, a squeaky kee-kee-krrr.
Black_Rail, Tiny, short-tailed rail. Head is gray with a red eye and black bill. Upper back is rusty and the rest of the back has white speckling. Very secretive.
Black_Rail, Tiny, very difficult to see rail. Occurs in tidal marshes and freshwater wetlands in North and South America. Subspecies in Junin, Peru is heavily barred above.
Black_Rail, Tiny, short-tailed rail. Head is gray with a red eye and black bill. Upper back is rusty and the rest of the back has white speckling. Very secretive.
Black_Rail, Tiny, short-tailed rail. Head is gray with a red eye and black bill. Upper back is rusty and the rest of the back has white speckling. Very secretive.
Black_Rail, Tiny rail that appears all dark in flight.
Black_Rail, Tiny rail of freshwater marshes and tidal wetlands in North and South America.

Black_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized finch of alpine areas. Blackish brown overall with a gray crown and pink highlights on the wings and lower belly. The bill is yellow during the nonbreeding season and black during the breeding season.

Black_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized finch of alpine areas. Blackish brown overall with a gray crown and pink highlights on the wings and lower belly. The bill is yellow during the nonbreeding season and black during the breeding season.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Forage for seeds and insects along the margins of melting snow or in areas blown free of snow.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Breeding birds are darker black overall with a small gray crown, pink highlights on the wings and lower belly, and a dark bill.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized finch with a conical seed-eating bill. Nonbreeding birds are grayish overall, some with little or no pink highlights on the wings or lower belly.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Walks and hops along the ground while foraging for seeds and insects.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Juveniles are brownish overall with buffy wingbars.

Black_Rosy-Finch, Chunky finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are blackish below with a gray crown, blackish cheeks, and a yellow bill. The amount of pink on the lower belly varies among individuals.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Breeds in alpine areas above treeline, usually near rock piles and cliffs.
Black_Rosy-Finch, This nonbreeding adult has extensive pink on the belly unlike some others that show much less pink. Note blackish brown back, chest and cheeks that contrast with the gray crown.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Forms flocks during the winter, sometimes with other rosy-finches. Note that it is much darker overall than Brown-capped Rosy-Finches.
Black_Rosy-Finch, Breeds in alpine areas, usually near rock piles, and cliffs. Winters in open country, including mountain meadows, high deserts, valleys, and plains.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with a fairly small, straight bill. All black except for yellow knob at base of bill.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with a fairly small, straight bill. Brownish overall with pale face and neatly delineated dark cap.
Black_Scoter, Often found in small flocks, sometimes with other scoter species. Call is a soft whistling. Female lacks yellow knob on bill and has pale cheek with neat dark cap.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with a straight, thin bill. In flight, wings are all dark. Breeding males have yellow knob on bill; females have pale cheeks with neat, dark cap.
Black_Scoter, Brownish sea duck with dark-capped head pattern reminiscent of female but yellowish knob at base of bill like adult male.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with a fairly small, straight bill. All black except for yellow knob at base of bill.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with a fairly small, straight bill. All black except for yellow knob at base of bill.
Black_Scoter, Medium-sized brownish sea duck with a small, straight bill. Distinctive face pattern: pale cheeks and sharply defined dark cap.
Black_Scoter, May occur in flocks with other scoter species. Bill considerably smaller and straighter than Surf Scoter's (second from left).
Black_Scoter, Found mainly in saltwater along rocky coastlines.
Black_Skimmer, Long-winged coastal waterbird. Black above and white below with a bicolored bill. Often flaps with its wings held above its body.
Black_Skimmer, The upper bill is shorter than the lower bill. Note the long body and short red-orange legs.
Black_Skimmer, Larger than terns but with similarly elegant, streamlined proportions. Sharp black-and-white contrast and red-and-black bill are distinctive.
Black_Skimmer, Immature birds look similar to adults but have more white on the neck and brown on back and wings.
Black_Skimmer, Often rests with its body flat on the ground and neck extended.
Black_Skimmer, Long-winged coastal waterbird. Black above and white below with a bicolored bill. Often flaps with its wings held above its body.
Black_Skimmer, A buoyant and graceful flier typically seen low over the water. Note dark wingtips and white tail with a black line down the center.
Black_Skimmer, Flies low with its lower bill slicing through the water. When the bill touches a fish, the upper bill snaps down instantly to catch it.
Black_Skimmer, Long-winged coastal waterbird. Black above and white below with a bicolored bill. Often flaps with its wings held above its body.
Black_Skimmer, Long-winged coastal waterbird. Black above and white below with a bicolored bill. Often flaps with its wings held above its body.

Black_Skimmer, Found on open sandy beaches, on gravel or shell bars with sparse vegetation, or on mats of sea wrack (tide-stranded debris) in saltmarshes. Often forms large flocks outside the breeding season.
Black_Swift, A large and entirely dark swift with long sickle-shaped wings.
Black_Swift, Nests on cliffs or behind waterfalls. Close-up views show the white spots in front of the eye.
Black_Swift, Builds a cup nest out of moss and mud on cliff ledges in dark an inaccessible places.
Black_Swift, A large swift with long, pointed wings and a relatively long square-tipped tail that sometimes shows a slight notch.
Black_Swift, An entirely dark swift with small white spots on the head that can sometimes be seen on flying birds. Forages for flying insects high in the sky, but descends on cloudy days.

Black_Swift, When gliding the wings often look broad and less sickle-shaped, but note length of wings and fairly long squared off tail. Flies with slower and less fluttery wingbeats than the smaller swifts.
Black_Swift, Nests on cliffs and behind waterfalls.
Black_Swift, A large and entirely dark swift with long sickle-shaped wings.
Black_Tern, Small tern with fairly broad wings; flies with light, buoyant wingbeats. Breeding adults have very distinctive pattern of black head and body with dark gray wings.
Black_Tern, Small tern with slender bill and dark gray wings. Breeding adults have black head, breast, and belly.

Black_Tern, Black head and underparts make this graceful tern easy to identify in breeding plumage. Note also the dark gray back and wings—darker than almost all other terns and distinctive in all plumages.
Black_Tern, Small tern with dark gray wings. Nonbreeding adults have a dark ear spot on a mostly white head.
Black_Tern, When molting, can show a messy, mottled pattern of black and white.
Black_Tern, Juveniles have dark gray-brown back and wings with faint paler bars. Head and underparts are white with black skullcap and ear mark.
Black_Tern, Small tern with fairly broad wings; flies with light, buoyant wingbeats. Breeding adults have very distinctive pattern of black head and body with dark gray wings.
Black_Tern, Small tern with dark gray wings. Molting birds can be a mixture of black and white on the head and underparts.
Black_Tern, Small tern with shallow fork in tail. Juveniles have brownish tinges to back feathers, marked with pale barring. Note black skullcap and ear mark.
Black_Tern, Breeds in inland freshwater marshes; migrates cross-country and over open ocean to wintering grounds. During migration may be found in flocks with other terns.
Black_Turnstone, Stock, short-legged shorebird with a stout, slightly upturned bill. Breeding birds are blackish overall with a white spot behind the bill.
Black_Turnstone, Stocky shorebird of rocky coastlines. Nonbreeding birds are brownish black with a white belly.
Black_Turnstone, Commonly inhabits the intertidal zone of rocky or sandy coastlines during the wintering season.
Black_Turnstone, Distinctive pattern in flight. Note white stripe down the back, a black tipped tail, and white stripes on the wings.
Black_Turnstone, Legs usually dark, but occasionally dark red or pinkish. Note stout slightly upturned bill.
Black_Turnstone, In flight, black-and-white pattern on back is distinctive. Note white stripe down the back, a black tipped tail, and white stripes on the wings.
Black_Turnstone, Dark shorebird of rocky coastlines.
Black_Vulture, Large with broad wings, a short tail, and a small head. Entirely black except for silvery patches on the underside of the wingtips. Note splayed wingtips or "fingers" in flight.
Black_Vulture, Outermost primaries show extensive white shafts on the upperwings.
Black_Vulture, Compact, almost all-black vulture with unfeathered black head and white flashes or "stars" in the wing.
Black_Vulture, Hefty black bird with an unfeathered head and a pale bill.
Black_Vulture, Feeds almost exclusively on carrion, locating it by soaring high in the skies on thermals.
Black_Vulture, Soars on flat wings. Note short tail. White "stars" in underwing can be hard to see at distance.
Black_Vulture, Perched birds are entirely black with a gray and unfeathered head.
Black_Vulture, Often roosts in stands of tall trees including sycamores, pines, hickories, oaks, junipers, and bald cypress.
Black_Vulture, Roosts in large groups, sometimes with Turkey Vultures, which are slightly larger with red heads (at right of frame).
Black_Vulture, Often spreads its wings to cool down or warm up by exposing the underwings.
Black_Vulture, Typically roosts in groups in wooded areas and soars above open areas looking for food. Congregates around carcasses.
Black_Vulture, May occur around towns and buildings, where it can be quite bold, investigating dumpsters and other possible food sources.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Small warbler with a long body. Adult males have a brilliant orange throat and face with a black crown and triangular ear patch.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Females/immatures are paler and yellower overall with 2 white wingbars. Note distinctive triangular ear patch and yellow eyebrow.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Hops around in vegetation and nervously looks around. This video has no audio.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Small warbler with a long body. Note triangular ear patch, pale eyebrow, and white wingbars.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Females/immatures lack the orange coloration, showing tones of yellow instead. Note triangular ear patch, pale eyebrow, and white wingbars.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Hops among branches and gleans insects from the undersides of leaves.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Flame orange throat quickly identifies adult males.
Blackburnian_Warbler, The brilliant orange throat and head pattern is distinctive on adult males although the intensity of orange varies among individuals.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Females/immatures have a distinctive dull black triangular ear patch and bold wingbars. This video has no audio.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Breeds in mature evergreen and mixed evergreen-deciduous forests.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Found in all types of wooded areas during migration.
Blackburnian_Warbler, Males often sing from the tops of trees and branches. This video has no audio.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Small songbird with a short tail and a small thin bill. Breeding males have a black cap, a white cheek, and black streaking on the back and flanks. Note orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Breeding females look similar to males, but have a finely streaked cap. Note broken eyering, dark eyeline, and orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Small songbird with a short tail and a small thin bill. Breeding males have a black cap, a white cheek, and black streaking on the back and flanks. Note orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Some breeding females have a yellow wash on the breast and head. Note finely streaked cap, broken eyering, dark eyeline, and orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Nonbreeding females/immatures are washed in pale yellow with blurry streaking on the flanks. Note bold white wingbars.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Small songbird with a short tail and a small thin bill. Breeding males have a black cap, a white cheek, and black streaking on the back and flanks. Note orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Nonbreeding females/immatures are washed in pale yellow with blurry streaking on the flanks. Picks insects and larvae from leaves and twigs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Nonbreeding females/immatures are washed in pale yellow with blurry streaking on the flanks. Note bold white wingbars and orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Small songbird with a short tail and a small thin bill. Breeding males have a black cap, a white cheek, and black streaking on the back and flanks. Note orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Uses evergreen and deciduous forests during migration. Breeding males have a distinctive black cap and white cheeks.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Breeding males have dark streaking down the back.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Small songbird with a short tail and a small thin bill. Breeding males have a black cap, a white cheek, and black streaking on the back and flanks. Note orangish legs.
Blackpoll_Warbler, Breeds mainly in spruce and tamarack forests in Canada's boreal forests.
Blue-black_Grassquit, A very small songbird with a cone-shaped bill. Adult male in breeding plumage is dark blue-black overall, with dull black wings.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Female is warm brown above and buffy-white below with streaks on the breast. Wings are darker brown, with two faint buffy wingbars.
Blue-black_Grassquit, A very small songbird with a conelike bill and a rounded tail. Adult male is iridescent blue-black overall.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Immature male has a mix of blue-black and brownish feathers on the head and body, creating a distinctive splotchy look.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Uses pointed, cone-shaped bill to feed primarily on the seeds of grasses.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Female is brownish above and whitish below, with streaks across the breast and down the flanks.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Female is buffy-white below, with streaks forming a band across the breast.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Male performs frequent display flights from conspicuous low perches.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Male performs frequent display flights—jumping up from a perch, flapping his wings, and then singing just before landing.
Blue-black_Grassquit, Typically found in grassy, weedy areas, such as roadsides and field edges.
Blue-black_Grassquit, In slow motion, additional details of male's display flight—including the flashing of white underwing patches—become more apparent.
Blue-footed_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a long daggerlike bill. Adults have distinctive blue feet. Note dark bill.
Blue-footed_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a long daggerlike bill. Immatures are dark overall with variable amounts of white mottling on the back. Note paler head and white belly.
Blue-footed_Booby, The underwings on immatures are mostly dark. Note pale head and white belly.
Blue-footed_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with long pointy wings. In flight, note mostly dark underwings on immature birds.
Blue-footed_Booby, Nests on the ground on islands. Forages at sea.
Blue-footed_Booby, Immatures are mostly brown with a dark bill and a white belly. Often roosts on rocky islands.

Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Tiny and slim with long legs, a long tail, and a thin, straight bill. Blue-gray above and white below. Breeding males have a black V on their foreheads extending above their eyes. Note black tail with white outer tail feathers and white eyering.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Tiny songbird with a long, dark tail with white outer tail feathers. Females/nonbreeding birds are gray above with a thin white eyering.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Builds a tiny nest on top of a branch, using spiderweb, plant fibers, and lichens. Call is a sharp, nasal note.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Energetic and fluttery bird that often cocks its tail up or to the side. Note thin white eyering and white outer tail feathers.

Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Often holds its tail up over its back. The outer tail feathers are white, but birds in western North America have black at the base of the outer tail feathers, whereas birds in the East have entirely white outer tail feathers.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Tiny songbird with a thin bill. Females/nonbreeding birds are grayish above and paler below with a thin white eyering.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Tiny grayish songbird that conspicuously flicks its white-edged tail from side to side. Note thin white eyering.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Birds in the southwestern U.S. tend to be paler and grayer than birds in eastern North America, but these differences can be difficult to see in the field.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, A vocal, energetic little songbird that often cocks its long black-and-white tail.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, The "Cozumel" Blue-gray Gnatcatcher, resident on Mexico's Cozumel Island, has darker upperparts than other populations.
Blue-gray_Gnatcatcher, Found in deciduous forests and mixed woodlands, often in moister areas and near edges.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with thick bill. Blue-gray head contrasts with olive-green back and with bold white "spectacles." Breast and belly are clean white with yellow flanks.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Like most vireos, head is large, neck is short, and bill is thick with a slight hook at the tip. Bold white "spectacles" on rich gray head; two whitish wingbars.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Both sexes help build the nest, which is suspended in a horizontal fork, fairly low in the outer slender branches of trees or shrubs.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Small songbird with large head and thick bill. Blue-gray head and bold white spectacles contrast with olive-green back. Two whitish wingbars.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with thick bill. Blue-gray head with bold white "spectacles." Some individuals are gray on the upper back, grading to olive-green on the lower back.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with thick bill. Blue-gray head contrasts with olive-green back and with bold white "spectacles." Breast and belly are clean white with yellow flanks.
Blue-headed_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with thick bill. Blue-gray head contrasts with olive-green back and with bold white "spectacles." Breast and belly are clean white with yellow flanks.

Blue-headed_Vireo, Breeding habitat is mature forest, where they tend to forage high among small branches and leaves. In eastern North America uses deciduous or hardwood forests; in northwestern range more often found among conifers.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Large hummingbird. Males have a blue gorget, a white stripe behind the eye, and another one below the eye. White spots in tail flash in flight.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Large hummingbird. Males have a blue gorget, a white stripe behind the eye, and another one below the eye. White spots in tail flash in flight.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, These large hummingbirds aggressively defend nectar sources, including feeders.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Large hummingbird with white outer tail feathers. Note blue throat and gray belly.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Large hummingbird. Males have a blue gorget, a white stripe behind the eye, and another one below the eye. White spots in tail flash in flight.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, The large white spots in the tail are distinctive in flight.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Distinctive hummingbird in the southwestern United States with a blue throat, gray belly, and dark tail with white spots.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Typically nests under an overhang such as a rock wall or streambank, but also nests under eaves of buildings.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Large hummingbird. Males have a blue gorget, a white stripe behind the eye, and another one below the eye. White spots in tail flash in flight.
Blue-throated_Mountain-gem, Found in edges of evergreen forests in the highlands of Mexico and in the shady understory of deciduous forests near creeks in the southwestern United States.
Blue-winged_Teal, Most of the body is buffy colored with dense black speckles. Bluish-gray head with bold white crescent in front of eye, black bill, and black wings and rear.
Blue-winged_Teal, Coarsely marked brown body with darker cap and eyeline on the head, and black bill.
Blue-winged_Teal, Forages in shallow water by dabbling, reaching underwater to grab aquatic vegetation, seeds, midge larvae, and other food items. Does not dive.
Blue-winged_Teal, In flight the wings show green secondaries and powdery-blue shoulder patches.
Blue-winged_Teal, Most of the body is buffy colored with dense black speckles. Bluish-gray head with bold white crescent in front of eye.
Blue-winged_Teal, Often occurs in flocks, and in a variety of wetland habitats including flooded fields and shallow ponds.
Blue-winged_Teal, Sometimes flocks with other duck species.
Blue-winged_Teal, In flight, all plumages show a powder-blue patch on the upperwing coverts.
Blue-winged_Teal, Occurs in wetland habitats including flooded fields and shallow ponds.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, pointed black bill. Adult males have two obvious wingbars and a black eyeline.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Females are often paler than males with a grayer eyeline and a more olive crown, but some are not separable from males.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Song consists of a thin, high buzz followed by a trill; a beee-buzz as if the bird was inhaling and then exhaling.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Small songbird with a thin, pointed bill. Immature birds have a pinkish bill, yellow undertail coverts, and very thin (almost invisible) wingbars.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Males are bright yellow below with a thin black eyeline.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Females pull off strips of bark from vines and other shrubs to build a cup-shapped nest.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Males are bright yellow below with white undertail coverts. The wings are steely blue-gray with 2 prominent wingbars. Note thin black eyeline.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Picks insects off foliage often while hanging upside down. Note white undertail coverts.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Males sing a beee-buzz from exposed perches; inhaling on the beee and exhaling on the buzz.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Often forages at the outer edges of branches where it takes insects from vegetation. Some individuals cannot be accurately sexed.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Found in areas with shrubby undergrowth.
Blue-winged_Warbler, Females nest on or near the ground and sit tight on the eggs for 11–12 days.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a very large, triangular bill that seems to cover its entire face. Breeding males are deep blue overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky fincklike songbird with a hefty bill. Females/immatures are cinnamon overall with brown wingbars. Note unstreaked underparts.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a very large, triangular bill that seems to cover its entire face. Breeding males are deep blue overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Grosbeak, Full-bodied with a large triangular-shaped bill. Nonbreeding males are patchy blue and cinnamon overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Grosbeak, Sings a warbling song while perched at high points in shrubs and small trees. Combination of large bill and deep blue color with chestnut wingbars is distinctive.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a very large, triangular bill that seems to cover its entire face. Breeding males are deep blue overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Grosbeak, Females/immatures are cinnamon brown overall with brown wingbars and unstreaked underparts. Note large triangular-shaped bill.
Blue_Grosbeak, Found in old fields, hedgerows, and scrubby areas that are starting to grow back into woodlands. In drier regions, often found in shrubby areas along watercourses.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a very large, triangular bill that seems to cover its entire face. Breeding males are deep blue overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a very large, triangular bill that seems to cover its entire face. Breeding males are deep blue overall with chestnut wingbars.
Blue_Jay, Blue above and white below, with a prominent crest and a bold black necklace. The wings and tail are barred with black, and it has a bold white wingbar.
Blue_Jay, White throat is bordered by a black necklace. Grayish breast and flanks fade to a white belly.

Blue_Jay, Blue Jays often come to feeders where they eat many types of seeds, especially sunflower. They hold seeds between their feet and hammer them open. Note the mostly blue tail with white tips, which can be distinctive in flight.
Blue_Jay, Spectacular blue color is caused by the scattering of light through specialized feather structures.
Blue_Jay, Large white tail corners are prominent in flight, along with a black necklace and white underparts.

Blue_Jay, Jays are noisy birds; this one is visibly agitated and calling frequently along with chickadees, cardinals, woodpeckers, nuthatches, and other birds. It's likely they've discovered an owl or hawk and are mobbing it to try to make it leave.
Blue_Jay, When viewed head on the black necklace and feathering around the base of the bill are especially prominent.
Blue_Jay, Eats fruits, acorns, nuts, seeds, and insects.

Blue_Jay, Nests are made mostly of twigs and well hidden in trees. Both sexes build the nest; the female usually spends more time arranging twigs and lining the nest with rootlets, grass, and sometimes mud.
Blue_Jay, Often visits feeders, sometimes in flocks.
Blue_Jay, A bird of forest edges, woodlots, yards, and parks.
Blue_Jay, Note the strong, straight bill and the crest which can be raised or lowered at will. The pale-blue iridescent patches in the wing can glitter or look dull, depending on the angle of light.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small thrush with an upright posture. Females have a ghosting of the male's throat pattern—a faint orange and blue band below the throat. Brown above with thick white eyebrow.
Bluethroat, Sings a large array of vocalizations and often mimics the songs of other species. Typically sings from a low perch or during flight.
Bluethroat, Immature birds have a white throat with dark spots or streaks across the breast and a whitish eyebrow. In flight, note orange base on tail.
Bluethroat, Juveniles are heavily streaked above and below with orange upper tail feathers.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
