Bluethroat, Adult males have an unmistakable blue and orange throat.
Bluethroat, Small, slim thrush with an upright posture. Immatures birds are brown above with a white throat bordered by dark markings. Note orange upper tail feathers.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.
Bluethroat, Small, thin thrush with a round belly. Adult males have a uniquely marked blue and orange throat. Flashes orange upper tail feathers in flight.

Boat-tailed_Grackle, Large, lanky songbird with a long V-shaped tail, long legs, and a long, pointed bill. Adult males are glossy black overall with an iridescent purple sheen on the head. Individuals in Florida and along the Gulf Coast have a dark eye.

Boat-tailed_Grackle, Large and lanky with a long tail and bill. Females are dark brown above and russet below, with a subtle face pattern made up of a pale eyebrow, dark cheek, and pale mustache stripe.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, Adult males perform a variety of displays, often in pairs or larger groups.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, Immature males are pale below and dark above with a dark eyeline and pale mustache stripe.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, Eye color ranges from dull brown along the western Gulf Coast to bright yellow along the Atlantic Coast.

Boat-tailed_Grackle, Walks slowly over the ground or in shallow water, pecking or probing at soil, litter, or low vegetation typically near salt and freshwater areas along the Atlantic and Gulf coasts.

Boat-tailed_Grackle, Large and lanky with a long tail and bill. Females are dark brown above and russet below, with a subtle face pattern made up of a pale eyebrow, dark cheek, and pale mustache stripe.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, Males display by holding their bills straight into the air. Gregarious year-round.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, Long-legged blackbird with a long bill. In good light, adult males have a greenish-blue iridescence.
Boat-tailed_Grackle, A coastal species associated with saltwater through most of its range, but in Florida often found well away from the immediate coast.
Bobolink, A small songbird with a large flat head, a short neck, and a short tail. Breeding males are black below and black and white above with a yellowish patch on the back of the head.
Bobolink, Females and nonbreeding males are warm buffy brown, with bold brown stripes on the crown and dark brown streaking on the back and flanks. The bill is pinkish.
Bobolink, Males sing from perches just above the tops of the grass, or during display flights. Song is bubbly and rambling, with a mixture of sharp high notes and buzzy low pitches.
Bobolink, Long-bodied with a short tail and flat head. From behind breeding males have a white rump, white shoulders, and a yellowish patch on the back of the head.
Bobolink, Rather big headed and short necked. Breeding males are entirely black below with a straw colored patch on the back of the head.
Bobolink, Males sing while flying low over fields with exaggerated, fluttery wingbeats.

Bobolink, Small songbird with a pointed bill, flat head, and short tail. Females/nonbreeding birds are warm brown below with streaking on the flanks. Note pinkish bill, unstreaked nape, and dark eyeline.
Bobolink, Females/nonbreeding males have bold buffy and brown streaks down the back, but have an unstreaked nape. Note dark eyeline and brown stripes on the crown.
Bobolink, Females and nonbreeders are buffy with bold dark streaks and strong dark stripes on the crown and through the eye.
Bobolink, Females and nonbreeding males are sometimes confused for sparrows, but note Bobolink's larger size, golden-yellow plumage, and unstreaked nape.
Bobolink, In spring, male Bobolinks give conspicuous display flights low over grasslands, fluttering their wings while singing. Note white rump in flight.
Bobolink, Somewhat sparrowlike in appearance, but note overall warm buffy tone, dark streaks, and bigger bill than sparrows.
Bobolink, Found in tall grasslands, uncut pastures, overgrown fields, meadows, and prairies.
Bohemian_Waxwing, A prominent crest and a black mask over its "blushing" peachy face are characteristic marks of adults. Rusty undertail feathers can be hard to see.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Adults are gray overall with rusty undertail feathers and a "blushing" peachy face. Note the yellow tipped tail and white rectangles on the wings.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Often perches on exposed branches from which it flies out and back after flying insects.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Large, full-bodied songbird with a prominent crest. Two white rectangles are often visible on the wings of perched birds.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Foraging birds often perch acrobatically at the tips of thin branches to reach fruit, which they swallow whole.
Bohemian_Waxwing, During the nonbreeding season forms large and noisy flocks in search of fruit.
Bohemian_Waxwing, In flight, note broad, starling-like wings and fairly short, yellow-tipped tail.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Juveniles are grayer overall with a smudged breast. They lack the adult's peach blushing around the face and the red-tipped secondaries.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Breeds in open evergreen forests where it often perches on exposed branches.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Forms large foraging flocks during the nonbreeding season, following fruiting trees.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Often in large groups, especially during the winter months, and sometimes flocks with Cedar Waxwings.
Bohemian_Waxwing, Bohemian Waxwings are social birds that occur in tight knit groups during the nonbreeding season.
Bonapartes_Gull, Small gull with a thin black bill. Breeding adults have an entirely black head with thin white eye crescents and red legs.
Bonapartes_Gull, Small and delicate looking gull with a thin black bill. Nonbreeding adults have a black smudge behind the eye and pink legs.
Bonapartes_Gull, Found along lakes, rivers, marshes, bays, and beaches. Note thin black bill, dark hood on the adult, and black ear patch on the immature.
Bonapartes_Gull, First winter birds have a black smudge behind the eye and a black bar across the wings that is visible on resting and flying birds.
Bonapartes_Gull, Juveniles are a patchwork of brown and gray, but note the dark spot behind the eye.
Bonapartes_Gull, In flight, nonbreeding adults have a white tail and black tips on the primaries.
Bonapartes_Gull, First winter birds show the characteristic "M" pattern on the back and have pale underwings, only showing black on the tips of the feathers. Note black tail band.
Bonapartes_Gull, Juveniles have a black "M" pattern with a mottled brown-and-gray body.
Bonapartes_Gull, First summer birds start to acquire black feathers on the head. Note dark spot behind the eye.
Bonapartes_Gull, Breeds around lakes and marshes in the boreal forest. Winters along lakes, rivers, marshes, bays, and beaches along the coast.
Boreal_Chickadee, Tiny, big-headed songbird with a round belly and a short bill. Distinguished by its brown cap, gray collar, small white cheek patch, and cinnamon flanks.
Boreal_Chickadee, Brownish gray overall with a brown crown, a small white cheek patch, and cinnamon flanks.
Boreal_Chickadee, The "chick-a-dee" call is buzzier and slower than the call of the Black-capped Chickadee.
Boreal_Chickadee, Dainty with a small bill. Unlike other chickadees, it has a brown crown and a gray nape with a small cheek patch.
Boreal_Chickadee, Acrobatic forager that stores seeds and insects for the winter months. Note brown cap, gray collar, and small white cheek patch.
Boreal_Chickadee, Found in boreal forests with young and old evergreen trees, especially spruce.
Boreal_Owl, Small owl with large square head and yellow eyes. Grayish white facial disc framed by dark border. Underparts are streaky.
Boreal_Owl, Usually hunts at night. A sit-and-wait predator that hunts from exposed perches for forest rodents and other small animals.
Boreal_Owl, Juveniles lack the adult's back and crown spotting.
Boreal_Owl, Roosts in aspen, birch, or conifer trees around 15–20 feet above the ground and sits close to the tree trunk.
Boreal_Owl, Hunts using keen hearing; sometimes plunges talons through snow to attack prey moving below.
Boreal_Owl, Small square-headed owl with a spotted crown and a whitish facial disc.
Boreal_Owl, Found in stands of spruce, aspen, poplar, birch, and fir in the boreal forest.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a heavy bill, an unstreaked belly, and rather plain face. Note faint eyebrow.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Botteris_Sparrow, Rather plain looking for a sparrow, brown and gray overall with a faint eyebrow.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Botteris_Sparrow, A plain sparrow of Mexican grasslands with a long bill and flat head.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Botteris_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a long tail and bill. Adults have a dark crown, an unstreaked belly, and a plain face.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.

Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with a long and slender neck that is held straight out in flight. Juveniles are brownish overall with a paler neck and breast that forms a V shape on the breast (often visible on resting birds).
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large, long-necked waterbird with a long bill with a hooked tip. Juveniles are brown overall with a pale chin patch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Large waterbird with an oval body and slender neck. Breeding birds are black overall with a purple sheen on the head and a blue skin patch on their chins called the gular pouch.
Brandts_Cormorant, Found in inshore coastal waters, especially areas with kelp beds; also large bays and coastal lagoons.

Brant, A compact goose with a black neck, brownish back, and pale underparts. Adult "Atlantic" Brant has an incomplete white necklace and a pale belly that contrasts strongly with the black chest and neck.

Brant, A dark, compact goose with a short bill. Adult "Black" Brant shows a broad white necklace and extensive dark markings on the belly (creating an area of low contrast between the chest and the belly).

Brant, A compact goose with a black neck, brownish back, and pale underparts. Adult "Atlantic" Brant has an incomplete white necklace and a pale belly that contrasts strongly with the black chest and neck.

Brant, A compact goose with strongly contrasting white vent. The "Dark-bellied" Brant of Europe has a darker gray belly and bold white collar that appears intermediate between "Atlantic" Brant and "Black" Brant of North America.

Brant, "Gray-bellied" Brant is intermediate between "Black" Brant and "Atlantic" Brant. This population typically winters in coastal Washington state and appears like a blended version of the two named North American subspecies. This individual shows a reduced white necklace and paler underparts than "Black" Brant.

Brant, A compact goose with a black neck, brownish back, and pale underparts. Adult "Atlantic" Brant has an incomplete white necklace and a pale belly that contrasts strongly with the black chest and neck.
Brant, These geese often fly in densely packed flocks instead of well-organized lines or V-formations. In flight, note the large white "V" on the rump that contrasts with the dark upperparts.
Brant, Juvenile has an all-black neck and pale scalloping on the wings and back.

Brant, A compact goose with a black neck, brownish back, and pale underparts. Adult "Atlantic" Brant has an incomplete white necklace and a pale belly that contrasts strongly with the black chest and neck.
Brant, Juvenile often lacks the white necklace typical of adult and has pale tips on the rounded upperpart feathers.
Brant, Flocks forage in the intertidal zone along rocky coasts during migration and winter.

Brant, A compact goose with a black neck, brownish back, and pale underparts. Adult "Atlantic" Brant has an incomplete white necklace and a pale belly that contrasts strongly with the black chest and neck.

Brant, Smaller and more compact than Canada Goose (right). Occasionally joins flocks of other geese when foraging on grass. Juvenile has a reduced white collar and crisp, pale edging to the upperpart feathers.

Brewers_Blackbird, Medium-sized blackbird with a full body, round head, and straight bill. Males are glossy black with a piercing yellow eye and a purple sheen on the head grading to greenish iridescence on the body.
Brewers_Blackbird, Females are a nondescript grayish-brown. Eye is typically dark (but occasionally pale yellow).

Brewers_Blackbird, Forages primarily on waste grain and grass seeds during winter, but prioritizes insects and other invertebrates during the breeding season. Brewer's Blackbirds are opportunistic foragers—supplementing their diet with stockyard spillage and scraps.
Brewers_Blackbird, Full-bodied blackbird with a straight bill. Females are plain brown, darkest on the wings and tail. Some show metallic greenish sheen on the back in the right light.
Brewers_Blackbird, In good light, males show off beautiful purplish and greenish iridescence.
Brewers_Blackbird, A common and conspicuous species, often seen perched on posts, fences, and power lines.
Brewers_Blackbird, Males glossy black with a piercing yellow eye and a purple iridescence on the head grading to blue-green iridescence on the body depending on lighting conditions.
Brewers_Blackbird, Medium-sized blackbird with fairly long legs and a rounded tail. Females are plain brown, darkest on the wings and tail, with a dark eye, though some females have a pale eye.
Brewers_Blackbird, Found in open habitats, such as coastal scrub, grasslands, fields, meadows, lawns, golf courses, parks, and city streets.

Brewers_Sparrow, Dainty and slim, with a long, notched tail, short rounded wings, and a small, sharply conical bill. Adults are dusky gray-brown, with grayish underparts, a thin white eyering, and a streaked nape.

Brewers_Sparrow, The northern subspecies ("Timberline Sparrow") breeds at high elevations in mountains of northwestern North America. Note darker upperparts and bill, with more contrast to the underparts and facial pattern.
Brewers_Sparrow, Note relatively long tail, thin eyering, and subtle face pattern with stripe over eye with darker cheek patch.
Brewers_Sparrow, Juveniles are dusky gray-brown overall with a pale eyebrow and a streaked belly.
Brewers_Sparrow, A somewhat drab and finely streaked sparrow. Note streaked crown and nape and thin white eyering.

Brewers_Sparrow, Dainty and slim, with a long, notched tail, short rounded wings, and a small, sharply conical bill. Adults are dusky gray-brown, with grayish underparts, a thin white eyering, and a streaked nape.

Brewers_Sparrow, Dainty and slim, with a long, notched tail, short rounded wings, and a small, sharply conical bill. Adults are dusky gray-brown, with grayish underparts, a thin white eyering, and a streaked nape.

Brewers_Sparrow, Dainty and slim, with a long, notched tail, short rounded wings, and a small, sharply conical bill. Adults are dusky gray-brown, with grayish underparts, a thin white eyering, and a streaked nape.

Brewers_Sparrow, Dainty and slim, with a long, notched tail, short rounded wings, and a small, sharply conical bill. Adults are dusky gray-brown, with grayish underparts, a thin white eyering, and a streaked nape.
Brewers_Sparrow, Found in the arid sagebrush steppe of interior western North America.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small chickadeelike bird with a small bill, a crest, and a striking head pattern. Grayish overall with black stripes marking the crest, eye, and cheek.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small chickadeelike bird with a small bill, a crest, and a striking head pattern. Grayish overall with black stripes marking the crest, eye, and cheek.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small chickadeelike bird with a small bill, a crest, and a striking head pattern. Grayish overall with black stripes marking the crest, eye, and cheek.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small bird that looks rather elongated due to its long tail and crest. Gray above and pale grayish below with "bridled" face pattern.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small and feisty bird of oak woodlands. Some individuals have a buffy wash on the underparts.
Bridled_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees excavated by other woodpeckers or created naturally. Also uses nest boxes.
Bridled_Titmouse, Small chickadeelike bird with a small bill, a crest, and a striking head pattern. Grayish overall with black stripes marking the crest, eye, and cheek.
Bridled_Titmouse, Found in oak woodlands in southern New Mexico, southern Arizona, and Mexico.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, A large shorebird with a striped head and curved bill. Upperparts brownish with buffy marks. Underparts buffy with fine brown streaking on the neck and breast.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Sings and calls in flight. Note the conspicuous cinnamon-buff rump, which distinguishes this species from the similar Whimbrel.

Bristle-thighed_Curlew, A large shorebird with a striped head, curved bill, brownish upperparts, and buffy underparts. This curlew's distinctive whistled "chiu-eet" or "cheeooeet" is one of the best ways to distinguish it from the similar Whimbrel.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Bill color varies from all black to mostly pink, with the amount of black decreasing during the nonbreeding season.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Spends the nonbreeding season in the Hawaiian Islands and other remote Pacific islands.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Male performs elaborate flight displays, flying upward on quick, shallow wingbeats and then gliding on fixed wings, often singing.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Probes for invertebrates year-round, but also uses other techniques to obtain food.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, In flight, note the cinnamon-buff rump and tail and limited dark barring on the tail.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Adaptable foragers, Bristle-thighed Curlews use a technique known as "slamming" to break open the shells of crabs and snails.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, Breeds on upland Arctic tundra in two remote areas in Alaska.
Bristle-thighed_Curlew, A tundra nester, this species is also at home in open, grassy habitats on its nonbreeding grounds on Pacific islands.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Slender hummingbird with dingy underparts and a notched tail.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.

Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small and slenderhummingbird with a long notched tail. Bill is red with a dark tip. Adult males have an iridescent green belly with white undertail coverts (obscured in this photo) and a dark tail.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Immature males have the female's white facial line that curves down from the eye. Their underparts are dingy with patches of iridescent blue-green feathers coming in.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Females/immatures have dingy underparts and a white line that curves down behind the eye.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Found in desert scrub, along canyon bottoms with sycamore, cottonwoods, and mesquite, in thorn forests, and in tropical deciduous forests.
Broad-billed_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a bright red bill tipped in black and a notched tail. Adult males have a blue throat and a bluish green belly.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are metallic green above with buffy flanks. They have green spots on their throats and cheeks and a pale eyering.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.

Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks. The tail feathers are broader than other hummingbirds, but tail details can be hard to see.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Slender-bodied and big-headed for a hummingbird. Immature males have a few magenta feathers coming in on the throat.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, On perched birds, the tail extends beyond the wingtips.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, In flight, broad and rounded tail feathers are distinctive. Note rusty color at the base of the tail feathers and white tips on the outer tail feathers.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Big-headed for a hummingbird. Adult males have a rose-magenta throat, a white breast, and green and buffy flanks.
Broad-tailed_Hummingbird, Breeds in meadows and open woodlands, especially pinyon-juniper, pine-oak, evergreen, and montane scrub and thickets.

Broad-winged_Hawk, Small hawk with broad wings that come to a slight point at the tips. Light morph adult has barred underparts and a strongly banded tail. Note dark outline to trailing edge of wings.
Broad-winged_Hawk, A small forest raptor, often best detected during the breeding season by its loud, piercing whistled call.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Small hawk with short tail and broad wings with pointed tips. Soars on steady wings, typically turning in tighter circles than other raptors.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Light morph adult has a brown head with variable amounts of barring on the breast.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Small, compact hawk with brown upperparts. Adult has a broad white band on the tail.
Broad-winged_Hawk, A small hawk of wooded habitats. Adults have a brown head and chest, barred underparts, and dark tail with a broad white band.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Rare dark-morph adult is uniform dark brown overall, except for a broad white band in the tail.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Juvenile light morphs have variable amounts of brown barring on the breast.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Forms enormous flocks during fall migration, particularly as the birds funnel through Mexico and Central America. Sometimes flocks with other raptors, including Swainson's Hawk.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Some juvenile light morphs have more heavily streaked underparts.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Juvenile light morph has brown upperparts with some white markings.

Broad-winged_Hawk, Juvenile light morphs have variable amounts of brown on the breast and lack a dark trailing edge to the wing. The tail has many narrow bands, usually with a stronger dark band at the tip. The gaps in the wing indicate this bird is molting its primary feathers.

Broad-winged_Hawk, In flight, both adult and juvenile dark morph have silvery flight feathers that contast with dark brown underwing coverts. Juvenile's tail has several dark bands, while adult dark morph's tail is similar to adult light morph's.

Broad-winged_Hawk, This immature bird is replacing juvenile tail pattern (visible in outer tail feathers) with adult pattern (inner feathers). Typically does not breed until more than one year old, but yearling birds (especially males) sometimes mate with adults.
Broad-winged_Hawk, A small, compact hawk with broad wings, a large head, and a fairly short tail.
Broad-winged_Hawk, A hawk of forests, breeding in large deciduous or mixed deciduous-evergreen forests.
Broad-winged_Hawk, Forms large flocks on migration, sometimes numbering in the tens of thousands or more. Sometimes flocks with other hawk species.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky and big-headed. Adult males are black overall with bluish wings and tail, and a red eye. Often fluffs up its neck feathers.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky with a hefty bill. Females are brownish overall with fine streaking on the belly. Note red eye.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Forages on the ground in pastures and fields. Males display by tipping the head down, ruffling the neck feathers, and extending the wings.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky and big-headed. Adult males are black overall with bluish wings and tail, and a red eye. Often fluffs up its neck feathers.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky and big-headed. Adult males are black overall with bluish wings and tail, and a red eye. Often fluffs up its neck feathers.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky with a hefty bill. Juveniles look like females with heavier streaking on the belly and a dark eye.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky and big-headed. Adult males often fluff up the feathers around their neck.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Found in open fields, pastures, scrubby areas, lawns, golf courses, and agricultural areas. Often forages in flocks with other cowbirds.
Bronzed_Cowbird, Stocky and big-headed. Adult males are black overall with bluish wings and tail, and a red eye. Often fluffs up its neck feathers.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized finch. Breeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlights on the lower belly and wings. The bill is black during the breeding season and yellow during the nonbreeding season.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.
Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Juveniles are pale brown overall with buffy edging on the wings and often pink highlights.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.
Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Chunky brown finch. Nonbreeding birds have brown cheeks and a grayish brown, scaly looking crown.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.

Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky, medium-sized finch with a conical bill. Nonbreeding birds are brown overall with variable amounts of pink highlighting in the wings and belly. Note grayish crown and brown cheeks.
Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Stocky finch with a long notched tail. Breeding birds have a brown chest and cheeks with a pinkish lower belly.
Brown-capped_Rosy-Finch, Winters in open areas, including alpine tundra during fair weather, and in high parks, meadows, and open valleys of grass or open shrubland between mountain ranges.

Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Large brown, yellow, and gray flycatcher with peaked head and heavy bill. Note rufous in wings and tail. Best separated from other Myiarchus species by voice and range, along with large size.

Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Large flycatcher with brown crest, gray chest, and yellow belly. Note extensive rufous in tail. Best separated from other Myiarchus species by voice and range, along with large size.
Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Perches in upper canopy of open woodlands to scan for insects and sing or call. Note long, heavy bill.
Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Large flycatcher with peaked head and large bill. Note rufous edging in primary feathers of wing, and pale wingbars.

Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Large, large-billed flycatcher with gray chest, yellow underparts, and rufous highlights in wings and tail. Brown-crested is larger than many other Myiarchus species, and about the same size as Great Crested Flycatcher.
Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Call is a high, rising whit , less shrill than in Great Crested Flycatcher.
Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Large, large-billed flycatcher, brown above with two pale wingbars. Sometimes crest is lowered and head appears rounded.
Brown-crested_Flycatcher, Occurs in open, dry woodlands, often along streams; also in giant cactus stands, thorn scrub, mangroves, and lowland tropical deciduous forests.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Chunky blackbird with a thick, conical bill. Adult males have black bodies and brown heads, which can appear all black in poor light.

Brown-headed_Cowbird, Stocky blackbird with a short tail and a thick, conical bill. Female Brown-headed Cowbirds are plain brown, lightest on the head and underparts, with fine streaking on the belly and a dark eye.

Brown-headed_Cowbird, Often ruffles neck feathers when singing. Song includes thin, high notes and a liquid burbling sound (other calls in background are Red-winged Blackbirds.) Note thick, sharply pointed bill.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Juveniles are brown overall with a scaly-looking back and streaked underparts.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Immature males molting into adult plumage are patchy brown and black.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Females are plain brown with very little streaking. The short, thick-based, sharply pointed bill is a key mark.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Lays eggs in the nest of other birds, which raise cowbird young. Here a Chipping Sparrow feeds a juvenile cowbird as if it were her own.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Adult male has a brown head, glossy black upperparts, a short tail, and a heavy bill.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Highly social: forages and displays on the ground in open areas. Displaying males puff out feathers, point bill at the sky, and bow forward and raise tail.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Typically forages on the ground, often in mixed flocks of blackbirds, grackles, and starlings. Males also gather on lawns to strut and display for mates.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Female does not build a nest, instead laying her eggs in the nest of other species.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Originally lived around herds of bison, foraging on insects stirred up as the animals grazed. Now often seen on and around cows and other livestock.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Highly gregarious. Males often raise their back and chest feathers, lift their wings, spread their tail feathers, and bow forward when singing.

Brown-headed_Cowbird, Found in open habitats such as fields, pastures, meadows, forest edges, and lawns. When not displaying or feeding on the ground, they often perch high on prominent tree branches.
Brown-headed_Cowbird, Originally associated with bison on the Great Plains, but now found around horses and cattle.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny and compact with a short tail and a sharp bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray upperparts, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Zigzags up and down tree trunks and branches high in the canopy, squeaking like a rubber duck as it goes.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Tiny, compact nuthatch with a chisel-like bill. Note brown cap, blue-gray back, and whitish underparts.
Brown-headed_Nuthatch, Found in pine forests of the southeastern United States, especially in mature forests with an open understory.
Brown_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are dark brown above with a white belly and yellow feet. Note pale yellow bill.
Brown_Booby, Large seabird with a bullet-shaped body. Adults have an all dark back and tail.
Brown_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are dark brown above with a white belly and yellow feet. Note pale yellow bill.
Brown_Booby, Birds along the Pacific Coast of Mexico have a paler head, but still have a dark brown back and tail.
Brown_Booby, Large seabird with a bullet-shaped body and daggerlike bill. Brown above with a brown neck and a white belly.
Brown_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are dark brown above with a white belly and yellow feet. Note pale yellow bill.
Brown_Booby, Immature birds look like adults but have a dingy brown belly.
Brown_Booby, Heavy-bodied dark brown seabird with a white belly. Note pale yellow bill and feet.
Brown_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are dark brown above with a white belly and yellow feet. Note pale yellow bill.
Brown_Booby, Immature birds look similar to adults but have a dingy brown belly.
Brown_Booby, Plunge-dives into the ocean, sweeping its wings backward and slicing through the water like an arrow.
Brown_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are dark brown above with a white belly and yellow feet. Note pale yellow bill.
Brown_Creeper, Tiny and delicate songbird. It has a long, spine-tipped tail, a slim body, and a slender, decurved bill. Its back is mottled brown and the underparts are white.
Brown_Creeper, Tiny with a long tail and a sharp, curved bill. Its cryptically colored back helps it blend in with the trees.
Brown_Creeper, Spirals up tree trunks holding its legs on either side of its body and its long, curved claws hooked into the bark. Braces itself with its stiff tail as it probes crevices for insects.
Brown_Creeper, Feeds mainly on insect larvae, adult insects, and spiders during the breeding season.
Brown_Creeper, Spirals up trees moving with short, jerky motions using their stiff tails for support.
Brown_Creeper, Typically builds nest between the trunk and a loose piece of bark on a large, dead or dying tree.
Brown_Creeper, Note prominent wing stripe in flight.
Brown_Creeper, Streaked brown upperparts help to blend in well with bark. Uses stiff tail for support while hitching upward in a spiral around tree trunks.
Brown_Creeper, Found primarily in mature evergreen or mixed evergreen-deciduous forests during the breeding season.
Brown_Pelican, Large and stocky seabird with a long neck and giant bill. Breeding adults have a dark neck and a pale yellow head. Birds from the Atlantic Coast have brown skin on their throat pouch.
Brown_Pelican, Heavy bodied seabird with a giant bill. During the breeding season their heads have a light golden wash. Breeding adults along the Pacific Coast have red skin on their throat pouch.

Brown_Pelican, Typically forages for schooling fish by diving head-first into shallow waters of coastal estuaries or oceans. Occasionally forages from the water's surface when the water is too murky or shallow for diving.
Brown_Pelican, Juveniles look similar to adults, but are brown above with a brown neck and grayish bill.
Brown_Pelican, Does not carry food in its pouch; instead it scoops up fish and releases the water before swallowing them whole.

Brown_Pelican, Parents begin feed nestlings a few hours after hatching until young are capable of flight at around 11–12 weeks old. After the young leave the nest, parents rarely continue feeding them.
Brown_Pelican, Graceful flier often seen flying low over the waves, gathering lift as the waves break.
Brown_Pelican, Scoops fish out of the water using expandable throat pouch. Before swallowing the fish, they drain the water out of the pouch.
Brown_Pelican, Brown Pelicans regularly form large groups year-round. They often preen or loaf on sand bars or open beaches in groups.
Brown_Pelican, Often rests with its head on its shoulder. Nonbreeding birds have a slight yellow wash on their head and a white neck.
Brown_Pelican, Plunges head first into water, scooping up fish with its expandable throat pouch.
Brown_Pelican, Often flies just above water's surface in small flocks. While in flight, predominant gliding is interspersed with strong, steady wingbeats.
Brown_Pelican, Found year-round in estuaries and coastal marine habitats, often in flocks.
Brown_Pelican, Common coastal bird often seen standing on rocks or pilings near shore.

Brown_Thrasher, Large songbirds with long proportions—long, sturdy legs, a long tail, and a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with thin black-and-white wing bars and bold dark streaking below.
Brown_Thrasher, Large songbird with a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with a yellow eye.

Brown_Thrasher, Large songbirds with long proportions—long, sturdy legs, a long tail, and a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with thin black-and-white wing bars and bold dark streaking below.
Brown_Thrasher, Exuberant and accomplished songsters that may sing more than 1,100 different song types.
Brown_Thrasher, Sometimes difficult to see in dense shrubbery, despite its size and bold patterning.

Brown_Thrasher, Large songbirds with long proportions—long, sturdy legs, a long tail, and a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with thin black-and-white wing bars and bold dark streaking below.
Brown_Thrasher, Slender and long-tailed with bold streaking down the breast.
Brown_Thrasher, Found in scrubby fields, dense regenerating woods, thickets, hedgerows, and forest edges.

Brown_Thrasher, Large songbirds with long proportions—long, sturdy legs, a long tail, and a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with thin black-and-white wing bars and bold dark streaking below.

Brown_Thrasher, Large songbirds with long proportions—long, sturdy legs, a long tail, and a long, slightly curved bill. Reddish brown above with thin black-and-white wing bars and bold dark streaking below.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.
Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Upperparts metallic bronze green with a rusty tail and dark wings. Note red bill, tipped in black.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.
Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Individuals in the Yucatan have bright rusty bellies.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.
Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Bronze-green above with a green gorget (not always well defined) and a rusty tail. Underparts are buffy. Note red bill.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.

Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Medium-sized hummingbird with a red bill that is black at the tip. Males have an iridescent green throat that can appear dark depending on the light and a buffy belly. Tail is rusty.
Buff-bellied_Hummingbird, Found in scrubby woodlands, forest edges, parks, and gardens.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with cinnamon underparts, a short bill, and a white eyering.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Worn individuals only show a hint of cinnamon on the breast. Note small size, eyering, and short bill.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with cinnamon underparts, a short bill, and a white eyering.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with cinnamon underparts, a short bill, and a white eyering.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small, cinnamon washed flycatcher with a brownish back and 2 pale wingbars. Intensity of cinnamon wash varies among individuals.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with cinnamon underparts, a short bill, and a white eyering.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with cinnamon underparts, a short bill, and a white eyering.
Buff-breasted_Flycatcher, Breeds in open pine and oak forests.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Small round head and short bill give it a dovelike appearance. Adults are buffy with less scaly above than juveniles.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, A delicate shorebird with a dovelike head and a short bill. Stands tall on its yellow legs. Juveniles are scaly brown above with darker spots on the breast.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Holding their wings in an outstretched position, males perform a unique mating display on leks to attract mates.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Small round head and short bill give it a dovelike appearance. Adults are buffy with less scaly above than juveniles.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Small round head and short bill give it a dovelike appearance. Adults are buffy with less scaly above than juveniles.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Underwings are gleaming white with a buffy bar at the top.
Buff-breasted_Sandpiper, Small round head and short bill give it a dovelike appearance. Adults are buffy with less scaly above than juveniles.

Buff-collared_Nightjar, A typical nightjar with large eyes, a small bill surrounded by whiskerlike rictal bristles, and an intricate mix of gray, brown, black, and rufous markings. Note the buffy-cinnamon neck collar that connects with a thin white throat collar.
Buff-collared_Nightjar, Spends the day roosting on the ground, typically under small bushes on hillsides, with the head pointed downslope.
Buff-collared_Nightjar, This nightjar's bold cinnamon collar is more prominent than in other similar species.
Buff-collared_Nightjar, Adult male has extensive white in the outer three tail feathers (visible in one feather here), while female has limited buffy tips and no white in the tail.
Buff-collared_Nightjar, Nonbreeding birds often perch on and make foraging flights from the ground.

Bufflehead, Small duck with large head and short bill. Large white patch on head, dark back, and white chest and flanks are visible from long distances. Purple-green iridescence on head can be hard to see.
Bufflehead, Small brownish duck with large, rounded head and a distinctive, single white patch on the cheek.
Bufflehead, Buffleheads forage for aquatic insects, crustaceans, and molluscs by diving staying submerged for about 13 seconds and consuming prey underwater.
Bufflehead, Small duck with distinctive flight pattern: dark upperparts crossed by white stripes at the shoulder and in the wings.
Bufflehead, Small duck with large head and single white cheek patch.
Bufflehead, Usually forms small to medium-sized flocks during the nonbreeding season.
Bufflehead, Small brownish duck with large, rounded head and a distinctive, single white patch on the cheek.
Bufflehead, May occur in flocks. Female lacks male's large white wingstripe, but has a smaller white wing patch sometimes visible at rest.
Bufflehead, Buffleheads require a running start when taking flight off water, but can achieve this over a shorter distance than most other duck species due to their small size.
Bufflehead, In flight, note male's white head patch, wing patches, and underparts contrasting with black upperparts and outer wings.
Bufflehead, Small duck with fast wingbeats. In flight, female lacks male's shoulder stripes and large white wing stripe, but has a smaller white wing patch sometimes visible at rest.
Bufflehead, Buffleheads perform self-maintenance activities on the water such as preening, stretching, and bathing.
Bufflehead, Male departs breeding site during incubation in order to molt, leaving female alone to raise young.
Bufflehead, Fairly common on lakes, ponds, and coastal waters.

Bullocks_Oriole, Slim but sturdy songbirds with a medium-long tail and a sharply pointed bill. Adult males are bright orange with a black back and large white wing patch. Note black line through the eye and black throat.
Bullocks_Oriole, Coloration is variable, ranging from lemon yellow to bright orange yellow, with at least some of this variability reflecting diet.
Bullocks_Oriole, A nimble oriole that often perches and forages at the tips of twigs. This video has no audio.
Bullocks_Oriole, Females have a yellowish-orange head and tail, a grayish back, a whitish belly, and white wingbars.
Bullocks_Oriole, Often visits sugar water feeders. This video has no audio.
Bullocks_Oriole, Immature males show some black on the chin, crown, and between the bill and eye.
Bullocks_Oriole, Typically a bird of western North America, but stray individuals regularly appear in the East.
Bullocks_Oriole, Picks insects from leaves and twigs and sometimes takes nectar from flowering plants.
Bullocks_Oriole, Breed in riparian and open woodlands, including urban parks.
Bullocks_Oriole, Immature males look like females, but have a black throat and a dark eyeline.
Bullocks_Oriole, Builds a gourd-shaped nest that is suspended from the ends of flexible branches.This video has no audio.
Bullocks_Oriole, Found in open woodland along streams, particularly among cottonwoods. They also occur in orchards, parks, and oak or mesquite woodlands.

Burrowing_Owl, Small, long-legged owl that is active during the day. Adults are mottled brown and white with yellow eyes and a yellow bill. Birds in Florida and the Caribbean tend to have whiter spots than western Burrowing Owls.
Burrowing_Owl, Long-legged owl with a flat headed look. Mottled brown and white with yellow eyes and a yellow bill.
Burrowing_Owl, A small owl with long legs and a rounded head without ear tufts. Active during the day, spending most of the time on or near the ground.
Burrowing_Owl, Hunts on or near the ground during the day.
Burrowing_Owl, Juveniles lack the streaked crown, barred underparts, and heavily spotted upperparts of adults.
Burrowing_Owl, Burrowing Owls use open grasslands, deserts, prairies, and agricultural areas throughout North and South America.
Burrowing_Owl, Nests in underground burrows. Juveniles stick together near the nest burrow for several weeks after hatching. Note unmarked pale belly.
Burrowing_Owl, Nests in underground burrows in open, treeless areas with low, sparse vegetation.
Burrowing_Owl, When developing, young birds can stand upright and walk at about 2 weeks of age. Juveniles typically stay near the nest burrow until they join the parents to forage at dusk .

Burrowing_Owl, Found in grasslands, deserts, sagebrush flats, golf courses, pastures, agricultural fields, airport medians, road embankments, cemeteries, and urban vacant lots. Often perches on fence posts or other elevated structures.
Burrowing_Owl, Burrowing Owls typically self-preen, although it is not uncommon for mates to preen each other.
Bushtit, Tiny, kinglet-sized birds. Plump and large-headed, with a long tail and a short, stubby bill. Plain brown and gray overall, but plumage color varies geographically.
Bushtit, Tiny with a long tail and short bill. Individuals in the interior are paler gray and have gray crowns with tan cheeks while those closer to the coast have brown crowns.
Bushtit, Nervously flits around from branch to branch in the understory of oak forests, evergreen woodlands, dry scrublands, streamsides, and suburbs.
Bushtit, Males in southwest Texas southward through Mexico have black masks and females have brown masks. The mask color tends to get darker as one moves farther south.
Bushtit, Tiny bird that looks like a ping-pong ball with a long tail. Females have pale eyes while males and juveniles have dark eyes.
Bushtit, Males and females help build a hanging socklike nest made from spider webs and plant material.
Bushtit, Individuals in the interior have grayer crowns and brown cheeks. Females have pale eyes while males and juveniles have dark eyes.
Bushtit, Adult females are distinguishable in all subspecies groups by their light-colored eyes.
Bushtit, Parents feed fledglings for up to 2 weeks after they leave the nest.
Bushtit, Females in southwest Texas southward through Mexico have brown masks while males have black masks, the color of which become darker as one heads farther south.
Bushtit, Juveniles are similar to adults, but this individual's fleshy gape indicates it is a juvenile.
Bushtit, Sprightly, social songbirds often seen in constantly twittering flocks.
Bushtit, Found in open woods or scrubby areas, particularly pine-oak woodlands and chaparral, as well as suburbs and parks.

Cackling_Goose, Small and compact with a short neck, small bill, and steep forehead. Head and neck are black with a large white cheek patch. Some, including most adult Aleutian birds (subspecies leucopareia), have a white collar at the base of the black neck sock.
Cackling_Goose, Head shape ranges from rounded to boxy, but the small, triangular bill and short neck are constants. Also note the neatly barred upperparts.
Cackling_Goose, Small goose best identified by head shape: note short bill and fairly abrupt transition to steep forehead.
Cackling_Goose, The smallest subspecies minima is tiny (roughly the size of a male Mallard) and shows a dark breast.
Cackling_Goose, In flight shows a prominent white "U" on the dark uppertail, contrasting with the black tail. Otherwise mostly brown with black neck and head, with a white cheek.

Cackling_Goose, Small and compact with a short neck, small bill, and steep forehead. Head and neck are black with a large white cheek patch. Some, including most adult Aleutian birds (subspecies leucopareia), have a white collar at the base of the black neck sock.
Cackling_Goose, Often flocks with Canada Goose (right). Note Cackling's shorter bill with more abrupt transition to steep forehead.
Cackling_Goose, Often occurs in large flocks, and forages in grassy habitats. The smallest subspecies, minima , is notably dark-breasted.

Cackling_Goose, Small and compact with a short neck, small bill, and steep forehead. Head and neck are black with a large white cheek patch. Some, including most adult Aleutian birds (subspecies leucopareia), have a white collar at the base of the black neck sock.
Cackling_Goose, Often flocks with other species of geese. In comparison to Snow Goose, smaller and shorter-billed.

Cackling_Goose, Small and compact with a short neck, small bill, and steep forehead. Head and neck are black with a large white cheek patch. Some, including most adult Aleutian birds (subspecies leucopareia), have a white collar at the base of the black neck sock.
Cactus_Wren, Large chunky wren with a long heavy bill, a long, rounded tail, and short, rounded wings. Speckled brown bird with a bright white eyebrow and cinnamon sides.
Cactus_Wren, Large chunky wren with a long heavy bill and a long, rounded tail. The back is brown with heavy white streaks, and the tail is barred white and black—especially noticeable from below.
Cactus_Wren, Inquisitive and bold wren that often perches out in the open. Does not cock its tail like other wrens.
Cactus_Wren, Hefty wren with dark spotting on the the breast often concentrated around the throat. Note white eyebrow stripe and long barred tail.
Cactus_Wren, Bold and inquisitive. Often perches atop tall vegetation, but does not cock its tail the way other wrens do.
Cactus_Wren, Large wren with a bold white eyebrow and white streaks down its brown back. Its long tail is barred black and white.
Cactus_Wren, Large chunky wren with a long heavy bill, a long, rounded tail, and short, rounded wings. Speckled brown bird with a bright white eyebrow and cinnamon sides.
Cactus_Wren, Builds large football-shaped nests with tunnel-shaped entrances in cacti or other thorny shrubs. Uses nests as roosting sites even during the nonbreeding season.
Cactus_Wren, Found in deserts, arid foothills, coastal sage scrub, and urban areas throughout the Southwestern deserts, especially in areas with thorny shrubs, cholla, and prickly pear.
California_Condor, Very large with long, broad wings with long "fingers." Adult is black with striking white patches under the wings.
California_Condor, Immature has a dark head and mottled patches under the wings.

California_Condor, North America's largest bird species. Adult is black with a pinkish head and neck. A captive breeding program started in the 1980s, when only 22 California Condors remained, brought this species back from the brink of extinction.
California_Condor, North America's largest bird, weighing over 15 pounds and with a wingspan of 9 feet.
California_Condor, Soars on very long and broad wings with its "fingers" extended and rarely flaps.
California_Condor, Immature birds take 6–8 years to reach full maturity.
California_Condor, Adult has a bare pink-and-orange head surrounded by a "feather boa."
California_Condor, Often perches on cliff edges, where this massive bird can more easily take flight.
California_Gnatcatcher, A tiny bird with a long, slender tail. Male California Gnatcatchers are gray with a black cap and a black tail narrowly edged in white.
California_Gnatcatcher, Females are gray overall with a thin white eyering and a black tail narrowly edged in white.
California_Gnatcatcher, A tiny bird with a long, slender tail. Male California Gnatcatchers are gray with a black cap and a black tail narrowly edged in white.

California_Gnatcatcher, A small, slender songbird with a long black tail narrowly edged in white. Males have a black cap. Individuals in the northern part of the range are darker gray than those farther south.
California_Gnatcatcher, A tiny bird with a long, slender tail. Male California Gnatcatchers are gray with a black cap and a black tail narrowly edged in white.
California_Gnatcatcher, Females are grayish overall with a brownish wash on the sides, wings, and undertail.
California_Gnatcatcher, A tiny bird with a long, slender tail. Male California Gnatcatchers are gray with a black cap and a black tail narrowly edged in white.
California_Gnatcatcher, Found in coastal sage scrub, desert scrub, and coastal dune scrub.
California_Gull, Medium-sized white-headed gull. Breeding adults have yellow legs, a dark eye, and a red spot on the lower bill.
California_Gull, Nonbreeding adults have a heavily streaked head, but still have yellow legs, a dark eye and a red spot on the lower bill.
California_Gull, Often eats insects along lake and stream edges during the breeding season. Breeding adults have yellow bill with black and red spot.
California_Gull, Second winter birds start to acquire gray feathers on their back and have a bluish bill with a black tip. Note dark eyes and a bluish tint on the upper legs.
California_Gull, Second summer gulls start to resemble adults but may still retain some brown feathers.

California_Gull, First winter gulls are checkered in tan and white with a few gray feathers appearing on the back. The bill is pink with a black tip. Note darker brown patches on the greater coverts (lower part of the folded wing).
California_Gull, Juveniles are mottled brown and white. Some individuals have a bit of cinnamon color on the back. Note thin bill with a pink base.
California_Gull, Medium-sized white-headed gull. Breeding adults have yellow legs, a dark eye, and a red spot on the lower bill.
California_Gull, In flight, note the dark primaries seen from above and below. The amount of black in the primaries is more extensive compared to similar gulls.
California_Gull, Second summer gulls often show lighter inner primary feathers in flight. Note slim bill and dark eye.
California_Gull, Juveniles in flight have a wide dark brown tail band, dark primaries, and dark greater covert feathers. Note slim bill.

California_Gull, Found in any open area where they can find food including garbage dumps, scrublands, pastures, orchards, meadows, and farms. In winter, found along the Pacific Coast mostly in marine areas including mudflats, estuaries, deltas, and beaches.
California_Quail, Plump, short-legged game bird with forward-facing, comma-shaped crest. Look for scaled black-and-white belly, chestnut belly patch, and fine black-and-white markings on neck.
California_Quail, Females are brownish-gray on the neck and face, lacking the male's strong head markings.
California_Quail, Although they spend most of their time on the ground, males often call from elevated perches.

California_Quail, Plump, short-legged game bird with unusual forward-facing crest. Belly is scaled black and white with a chestnut patch at the center. Black face is sharply outlined in white and the crown is rich brown.
California_Quail, Often found on the ground near shrubs or other cover. Female has plainer gray-brown upperparts than male.
California_Quail, Typically occurs in flocks or coveys of males, females, and young birds. Coveys can consist of 20 to 100 or more birds.
California_Quail, Each covey usually posts a lookout—often an adult male—to watch for predators while the rest of the group feeds or rests.
California_Scrub-Jay, Large and lanky songbird with a long tail and stout bill. Adults are rich azure blue and gray above, with a clean, pale underside broken up by a partial blue necklace.
California_Scrub-Jay, Juveniles are gray above with a blue tail and bits of blue coming in on the wings.

California_Scrub-Jay, Acorns are a main part of the diet; their bill is thick and hooked for carrying and opening acorns; slightly different from the straight, pointed bill of Woodhouse's Scrub-Jay, which eats mainly pinyon pine seeds.
California_Scrub-Jay, Inquisitive birds that often perch out in the open. Adults are pale below with a partial, but wide blue necklace.
California_Scrub-Jay, Boldly hops around trees and shrubs looking for food; they almost always look like they are up to something.
California_Scrub-Jay, Adults are rich azure blue and gray above with a darker cheek patch and a thin white line just above the eye.
California_Scrub-Jay, Found in open habitats, oak woodlands, and chaparral along the west coast of North America, as well as in backyards, pastures, and orchards.
California_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed songbird with a long curved bill. Brownish above and brownish to peachy below depending on lighting conditions. Often runs along the ground with a raised tail.
California_Thrasher, Forages primarily on the ground by tossing its long bill in arcs to uncover insects buried in leaf and ground litter. Note long, downward curved bill, white throat, and dark eye.
California_Thrasher, Song is a long series of warbled, variable phrases, some musical and others harsh; each element may be repeated once or twice.
California_Thrasher, Large and long-tailed songbird with a long curved bill. Brown above with a white throat and pale peachy washed underparts.
California_Thrasher, Sings almost year-round from the tops of shrubs.
California_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed songbird with a long curved bill. Brownish above and brownish to peachy below depending on lighting conditions. Often runs along the ground with a raised tail.
California_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed songbird with a long curved bill. Brownish above and brownish to peachy below depending on lighting conditions. Often runs along the ground with a raised tail.
California_Thrasher, Found in lowland and coastal chaparral, riparian woodland thickets, and parks and gardens with dense shrubs.
California_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed songbird with a long curved bill. Brownish above and brownish to peachy below depending on lighting conditions. Often runs along the ground with a raised tail.
California_Towhee, Large sparrow with a plump body and a long tail. Note rusty brown eyering and tinges to face. Plumage color varies from grayish brown to dark brown.
California_Towhee, Often perches on exposed shrubs, rooftops, or branches and calls for long periods.
California_Towhee, Often found in suburban areas with a mix of lawns and shrubs.
California_Towhee, Found in dense shrubby vegetation including chaparral, coastal sage, and thickets along streams.
California_Towhee, Hops along the ground looking for seeds and insects.
California_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Grayish brown overall with a rusty brown patch under the tail and around the bill.
California_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Brownish overall; found in dry, brushy habitats such as chaparral as well as suburban and residential areas.
California_Towhee, Drinks water from small pools and forages on the ground.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Smallest hummingbird in the United States and Canada, with short wings and tail. Females/immatures have a peachy wash across their underparts and a bronze-green back.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Male performs U-shaped display dives for females in which he makes a sputtering buzz with tail feathers and gives a sharp zinging call. Often seen perched on exposed branches.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Very small hummingbird. Females/immatures have peachy washed underparts and green stippling on the throat.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a hunched posture. Adult males have magenta rays on the throat and wear a greenish vest.
Calliope_Hummingbird, Breeds in mountain meadows, aspen thickets near streams, and open forests that are regenerating from a forest fire or logging.
Canada_Goose, Large with a long black neck and white cheek patch. Body brown with paler chest and white undertail. Legs and feet black.
Canada_Goose, Evenly dark brown body with limited contrast with the black neck.
Canada_Goose, Individuals can vary greatly in size. Note smoothly sloping transition between bill and forehead. Forages by dabbling, or reaching into shallow water to eat vegetation.
Canada_Goose, When alert sits with neck stretched up straight.
Canada_Goose, In flight shows a prominent white "U" on the dark uppertail, contrasting with the black tail.
Canada_Goose, Gathers in large flocks that communicate via raucous honking. Note considerable size variation among flock members.
Canada_Goose, Chicks are fluffy and yellowish, with black legs and bill.
Canada_Goose, Often found near human habitation, and can be aggressive when threatened.
Canada_Goose, The female lines the nest with down feathers plucked from her own breast.
Canada_Goose, Sometimes nests on raised platforms or in trees.
Canada_Goose, Often found in large flocks on a variety of water bodies.
Canada_Goose, In addition to foraging in the water, both adults and chicks forage on land, eating grass as well as seeds, berries, waste corn, and other plant foods.
Canada_Jay, Large, round-headed songbird with a long tail and a short bill. Adults are gray overall, paler on the belly with a white cheek, throat, and forehead.
Canada_Jay, Juveniles are dark gray overall with a paler gray mustache. Some juveniles may be paler gray.
Canada_Jay, A fairly small, short-billed jay with overall gray plumage and a strong head pattern with white cheeks, black partial cap, and white forehead.
Canada_Jay, Residents in the Rocky Mountains are paler gray overall with a mostly white head (only small spot on the back of the head is gray).
Canada_Jay, Highly curious bird always on the lookout for food. Gray overall with a whitish chest, cheek, and forehead.
Canada_Jay, A hardy species that lives in boreal habitats including high elevations in the western U.S. Rocky Mountain individuals tend to have paler heads, with gray instead of black on the cap.
Canada_Jay, Rather fluffy looking with a round head and a long tail. Gray overall with a a paler head and breast.
Canada_Jay, Generally fearless of humans and will often take food right out of people's hands.
Canada_Jay, Juveniles are dark gray, without the bold head pattern of adults.

Canada_Jay, Found in evergreen (especially spruce) and mixed evergreen-deciduous forest across the boreal forest of the northern U.S. and Canada, as well as in high mountain ranges of the western U.S.
Canada_Warbler, Medium-sized warbler with a long tail, bold eyering, and black necklace on a yellow breast.
Canada_Warbler, Adult females/immature males are dull gray above and yellow below with a faint necklace and a small amount of black on the face.
Canada_Warbler, Medium-sized warbler with a long tail, bold eyering, and black necklace on a yellow breast.
Canada_Warbler, Immature females are dull gray with a white eyering and a very faint necklace. Note lack of black in the face.
Canada_Warbler, Adult males have a yellow throat and belly separated by a distinctive black necklace. Often appears as if wearing yellow goggles.
Canada_Warbler, Quickly hops between branches picking insects from the vegetation in a flurry of activity.
Canada_Warbler, Adult males have a yellow throat and belly separated by a distinctive black necklace. Note white undertail coverts and darker tail.
Canada_Warbler, Breeds in mixed evergreen-deciduous forests with a well-developed understory.
Canada_Warbler, Hops through vegetation picking insects off twigs and leaves.
Canada_Warbler, Bathes in shallow puddles, dipping its head down and shaking the water through its feathers.
Canvasback, Large diving duck with a sloping forehead and a stout neck. Breeding males have black chests and rears with a white body.
Canvasback, Large diving duck with a sloping forehead and a stout neck. Females have pale bodies and dark chests and rears.
Canvasback, Note gracefully sloping forehead transitioning to bill, and clean white back.
Canvasback, In flight, note dark neck, head, and rear with white body and underwings.
Canvasback, Nonbreeding males are browner than breeding males.
Canvasback, Sloping head shape and paler body distinguishes Canvasback (middle) from similar Redhead (left).
Canvasback, Large brownish duck with gracefully sloping forehead and bill.
Canvasback, Breeds in small lakes, deep marshes, sheltered bays of large freshwater and alkali lakes, ponds, sloughs, potholes, and shallow river impoundments.
Canvasback, In flight, note male's dark head and neck contrasting with whitish back.
Canvasback, In winter found in deep freshwater lakes and coastal waters including brackish and saltwater estuaries, shallow bays, and harbors. Often in large groups.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Brownish overall with buffy eyering and warm rufous patch under the tail. Throat is lighter buffy brown; crown usually warm brown.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with long tail. Grayish brown with warm rufous patch under tail.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Brownish overall with buffy eyering and warm rufous patch under the tail. Throat is lighter buffy brown; crown usually warm brown.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow usually seen on or near the ground. Often has a dark spot in the center of the breast. Warm reddish brown crown and undertail.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with long tail, often found on the ground in arid areas. Whitish belly with dark spot in center of breast.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Brownish overall with buffy eyering and warm rufous patch under the tail. Throat is lighter buffy brown; crown usually warm brown.
Canyon_Towhee, Found on or near the ground in desert habitats including arroyos, mesquite thickets, desert grasslands, pinyon-juniper-oak woodland, and pine-oak.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Brownish overall with buffy eyering and warm rufous patch under the tail. Throat is lighter buffy brown; crown usually warm brown.
Canyon_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Brownish overall with buffy eyering and warm rufous patch under the tail. Throat is lighter buffy brown; crown usually warm brown.
Canyon_Wren, Stocky-chested with a long tail and bill. Rusty brown overall with barring on the wings and tail. Its throat and chest are white.
Canyon_Wren, Sings a descending cascade of liquid notes that echoes through rocky canyons.
Canyon_Wren, Sings a descending cascade of liquid notes. Note white throat and chestnut belly with varying amounts of black and white speckling.
Canyon_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and bill. Rusty brown overall with barring on the wings and tail and a white throat and chest.
Canyon_Wren, Found near cliffs, canyons, rocky outcrops, and boulder piles often bobbing up and down.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult females/immature males have a grayish cheek patch, an olive-gray crown, and a paler yellow collar and breast. The breast streaking is also paler.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Females have a grayish cheek patch, an olive-gray crown, and a paler yellow collar and breast. The streaking on the breast is paler and not as crisp and the streaking on the back is absent.
Cape_May_Warbler, Immature females are grayish overall with blurry streaking down the flanks and thin white wingbars.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.
Cape_May_Warbler, Adult females/immature males have a grayish cheek patch, an olive-gray crown, and a paler yellow collar and breast. The breast streaking is also paler. Note white undertail coverts.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.

Cape_May_Warbler, Short-tailed warbler with a thin bill and white undertail coverts. Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.
Cape_May_Warbler, Adult males have a distinctive chestnut cheek patch and yellow collar. Black streaks mark the yellow breast and continue down the flanks.
Cape_May_Warbler, Breeds across the boreal forest of Canada and the northern United States, where it feeds on spruce budworms.

Carolina_Chickadee, Tiny, approachable bird with a short neck and large head, giving it a distinctive spherical body shape. Stark white cheeks contrast with black cap and throat. Note grayish nape or collar and grayish edging on secondaries.
Carolina_Chickadee, Gleans insects from foliage and tree bark, often hanging upside down to do so.
Carolina_Chickadee, Song is a distinctive 4-noted whistle, longer than songs of other chickadees.
Carolina_Chickadee, Tiny and round with a short bill. Gray overall with a black cap and throat, and stark white cheeks. Note gray-edged secondaries.
Carolina_Chickadee, Acrobatic forager found in deciduous and mixed deciduous-evergreen woodlands, swamps, riparian areas, open woods and parks, and also in suburban and urban areas.
Carolina_Chickadee, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes.
Carolina_Wren, Reddish-brown upperparts contrast with buffy underparts and white throat and eyebrow. Wings and tail have bold darker barring, and bill is long and thin.
Carolina_Wren, Both males and females are a bright, unpatterned reddish-brown above and warm buffy-orange below, with a long white eyebrow stripe, dark bill, and white chin and throat.

Carolina_Wren, A small but chunky bird with a round body and a long tail that it often cocks upward. Both males and females are a bright, unpatterned reddish-brown above and warm buffy-orange below, with a long white eyebrow stripe. Only males sing.
Carolina_Wren, The loud, cheerful song is often heard before the bird is seen.
Carolina_Wren, Often found in brushy thickets in wooded residential areas.
Carolina_Wren, Males sing a series of several quick, whistled notes, repeated a few times. The notes usually sound three-parted, as in "tea-kettle-tea-kettle" or "germany-germany."

Carolina_Wren, Sensitive to cold weather, with northern populations decreasing markedly after severe winters. Gradually increasing winter temperatures over the last century may have been responsible for the northward range expansion seen in the mid-1900s.
Carolina_Wren, Forages fairly low in thick tangles of shrubs and vines; also on the ground.
Carolina_Wren, Visits feeders, especially during the colder months.
Carolina_Wren, Individuals from southern Mexico and Central America are dingy white below with cold brown upperparts.
Carolina_Wren, Note long, curved bill, strong white eyebrow stripe, and rich cinnamon underparts. Often holds tail cocked upward.
Carolina_Wren, The "White-browed" group, found from the Yucatan Peninsula to northern Nicaragua, is sometimes treated as a separate species.
Carolina_Wren, Found in dense woodlands and shrubby habitats.
Caspian_Tern, The largest tern in the world. Note large red bill, tail with only a shallow fork, and black on the underside of outer primary feathers. Breeding adults have a fully black cap.
Caspian_Tern, Note massive, bright-red bill, sometimes with black tip. Breeding adults have fully black cap, sometimes raised in a short crest.
Caspian_Tern, Note big, thick-based red bill, thick neck, and squared off or slightly crested head. Juveniles are camouflaged with grayish or brownish markings on the back.
Caspian_Tern, Large tern with very large bill. Nonbreeding adults have a grayish crown and reduced black on the head.
Caspian_Tern, Large tern with large reddish bill. Juveniles have brownish markings on the back and a brown-black crown that is often streaky on the forehead.
Caspian_Tern, The largest tern in the world. Note large red bill, tail with only a shallow fork, and black on the underside of outer primary feathers. Breeding adults have a fully black cap.
Caspian_Tern, The largest tern in the world. Note large red bill, tail with only a shallow fork, and black on the underside of outer primary feathers. Breeding adults have a fully black cap.
Caspian_Tern, Large tern with massive, red, pointed bill. The large head can look smoothly rounded, squared off, or slightly crested. The outer primaries are dark, especially on the undersides.

Caspian_Tern, Very large tern with broad wings and large, red bill. Undersides of outer primary feathers are dark. Nonbreeding adults and immatures have variable amounts of white on the forehead. Gaps in the wings usually are a sign that the bird is molting.
Caspian_Tern, The largest tern in the world. Note large red bill, tail with only a shallow fork, and black on the underside of outer primary feathers. Breeding adults have a fully black cap.
