Caspian_Tern, Occurs along seacoasts, barrier islands, estuaries, and saltmarshes, as well as some inland lakes and rivers.
Cassia_Crossbill, A small but stocky songbird with a notched tail and a characteristic crisscrossed bill. Males are a patchy mix of reds, yellows, and oranges.
Cassia_Crossbill, Females/Immature males are grayish-green overall with a bit more yellow on the belly.
Cassia_Crossbill, A small but stocky songbird with a notched tail and a characteristic crisscrossed bill. Males are a patchy mix of reds, yellows, and oranges.
Cassia_Crossbill, A small but stocky songbird with a notched tail and a characteristic crisscrossed bill. Males are a patchy mix of reds, yellows, and oranges.
Cassia_Crossbill, Often seen foraging on lodgepole pine cones in trees, but also eats seeds that have fallen to the ground.
Cassia_Crossbill, Often seen foraging on lodgepole pine cones in trees, but also eats seeds that have fallen to the ground.
Cassia_Crossbill, A small but stocky songbird with a notched tail and a characteristic crisscrossed bill. Males are a patchy mix of reds, yellows, and oranges.
Cassia_Crossbill, Found in lodgepole pine forests in Cassia County, Idaho.
Cassia_Crossbill, A small but stocky songbird with a notched tail and a characteristic crisscrossed bill. Males are a patchy mix of reds, yellows, and oranges.
Cassins_Auklet, Small dark gray seabird with a round head. With close views note pale eye, white crescent above the eye, and pale spot at the base of the bill.
Cassins_Auklet, Small dark gray seabird that shows a thin whitish stripe on the underwing in flight.
Cassins_Auklet, Small dark gray seabird with a round head. With close views note pale eye, white crescent above the eye, and pale spot at the base of the bill.
Cassins_Auklet, Small, chunky dark gray seabird with light gray flanks.
Cassins_Auklet, Small seabird with a small dark bill (pale base not always visible).
Cassins_Auklet, Small dark gray seabird with white crescents above and below the eye. Able to take flight directly from the water.
Cassins_Finch, Small, somewhat chunky finch with a conical bill and a notched tail. Adult males have a brighter red peaked crown. Note nearly unstreaked underparts.
Cassins_Finch, Stocky looking finch. Females/immature males are brown overall with short, crisp streaks on the underparts.
Cassins_Finch, Visits sunflower seed feeders, especially during winter. Uses the heavy conical bill to crack sunflower seeds with ease.
Cassins_Finch, The peaked crown is brighter red than the rest of the body.
Cassins_Finch, Females/immature males have short, crisp streaks on the belly and heavy streaking on the back.
Cassins_Finch, Adult males have a brighter red crown and red washing down the heavily streaked back. Like other finches, the tail is notched.
Cassins_Finch, Stocky finch with a peaked crown. Females/immature males are streaky brown overall with heavy streaking on the back.
Cassins_Finch, Small, somewhat chunky finch with a conical bill and a notched tail. Adult males have a brighter red peaked crown. Note nearly unstreaked underparts.
Cassins_Finch, Found in evergreen forests in the mountains up to about 10,000 feet elevation. Feeds heavily on seeds of pines and quaking aspen.
Cassins_Kingbird, Large, hefty flycatcher with a thick bill. The head and chest are dark gray with a white mustache.
Cassins_Kingbird, Note dark tail with pale tips as opposed to pale outer tail feathers on similar species. White mustache not always visible, especially on birds with worn plumage.
Cassins_Kingbird, Perches on branches, wires, or posts to watch for flying insects. Sallies out from its perch to grab an insect in flight.
Cassins_Kingbird, Large, hefty flycatcher with a thick bill. The head and chest are dark gray with a  white mustache. Note pale edging on the tip of the tail.
Cassins_Kingbird, Often perches on exposed branches or wires where it waits for insects. Note dark gray head and white mustache.
Cassins_Kingbird, Large, hefty flycatcher with a thick bill. The head and chest are dark gray with a white mustache.
Cassins_Kingbird, Found in open country with scattered trees or open woodlands.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.
Cassins_Sparrow, Rather plain, grayish-brown sparrow with a thin white eyering, a darker line extending beyond the eye, and a finely streaked crown. The breast is finely streaked.
Cassins_Sparrow, Song is a loud trill followed by two descending whistles.
Cassins_Sparrow, Some individuals have rusty tones, while others are drabber gray. Inhabits arid grasslands in the south-central United States and northern Mexico.
Cassins_Sparrow, Rufous birds are brighter overall with more rufous upperparts, wing and tail edgings, and uppertail coverts. Note white eyering and fine streaking on the crown.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.
Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.

Cassins_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with a round head and conical bill. Grayish brown overall with a plain face.

Cassins_Vireo, Small songbird with fairly thick bill. Olive-brownish overall with grayer head and bold white "spectacles." Two white wingbars. Whitish underparts are washed with yellowish on the flanks.
Cassins_Vireo, Small songbird with fairly thick bill. Gray head with bold white "spectacles" and clean white throat.

Cassins_Vireo, Small songbird with fairly thick bill. Olive-brownish overall with grayer head and bold white "spectacles." Two white wingbars. Whitish underparts are washed with yellowish on the flanks.
Cassins_Vireo, Olive-brown vireo with gray head and bold white "spectacles." Two whitish wingbars and yellowish wash on flanks. Moves deliberately through twigs while foraging.
Cassins_Vireo, Chunky small songbird with heavy bill. Birds from southern Baja California, Mexico, have more extensive yellow on the flanks than other forms.

Cassins_Vireo, Small songbird with fairly thick bill. Olive-brownish overall with grayer head and bold white "spectacles." Two white wingbars. Whitish underparts are washed with yellowish on the flanks.
Cassins_Vireo, Can appear fairly drab with less contrast between gray head and brownish back, and reduced wingbars, but white spectacles are usually still distinctive.

Cassins_Vireo, Typically breeds in mountain forests up to about 8,000 feet elevation; winters at lower elevations, often in woodland along streams. Moves slowly and deliberately through twigs and outer branches while foraging.
Cave_Swallow, Small and compact swallow with small head and bill. Adults have dark blue backs, brownish wings, and pale chestnut cheeks and forehead.
Cave_Swallow, Builds nest out of globs of mud, brought one by one in the bird's bill, to create a sturdy structure placed underneath an overhang.
Cave_Swallow, Adults have a pale chestnut face and throat with a slightly darker chestnut forehead.
Cave_Swallow, In flight, note squared tail, broad wings, and chestnut rump. Birds in the Caribbean are generally brighter and darker with a richer chestnut rump than mainland birds.
Cave_Swallow, Compact swallow with a small head, broad wings, and squared tail. Adults are pale below with a pale chestnut throat.
Cave_Swallow, Juveniles look similar to adults but are more brown overall and have a paler throat and cheeks.
Cave_Swallow, Nests and forages in groups. Here, members of a flock use their bills to collect mud to build a nest.
Cave_Swallow, Builds a mud nest, which it cements to natural or human-made structures such as caves, sinkholes, buildings, silos, bridges, and culverts.

Cedar_Waxwing, A silky smooth songbird with a black mask, tan head and breast, yellow belly, and grayish-brown upperparts. The tail has a yellow band at the tip, and some wing feathers have waxy red tips.
Cedar_Waxwing, Frequently sits on high, exposed perches, where easily seen and heard.

Cedar_Waxwing, A sleek, medium-sized songbird with a prominent crest. Adults have a pale brown head and chest, black mask, soft gray wings, a pale yellow belly, and a dark tail with a bright yellow tip. During courtship, males and females pass a fruit or other small item back and forth.
Cedar_Waxwing, Prominent crest. Black mask with peachy brown head and chest, pale yellow belly, and yellow tip to dark tail. Sometimes has red tips to the secondaries of the wing.
Cedar_Waxwing, Juveniles are more heavily marked than adults, with dusky streaks below, and have a fainter dark mask.
Cedar_Waxwing, In the fall and winter Cedar Waxwings gather by the hundreds to eat berries, which they swallow whole.
Cedar_Waxwing, Some birds are less intensely colored, and lack the red feather tips in the wing.
Cedar_Waxwing, Yellow tail band is influenced by diet—birds that feed on exotic honeysuckle berries develop orange tail bands.
Cedar_Waxwing, Often perches at the tops of trees with bare twigs.
Cedar_Waxwing, Foraging birds often perch acrobatically at the tips of thin branches.
Cedar_Waxwing, Juvenile is grayish-brown above, with coarsely streaked underparts. It lacks the adult's crest and waxy red wingtips.
Cedar_Waxwing, Sings a very high pitched, thin song. Its long, slender body and crested head helps separate it from other species.
Cedar_Waxwing, Flocks sometimes descend to puddles to drink and bathe.
Cedar_Waxwing, Gathers in large flocks in autumn and winter, filling the air with high, thin, whistles.
Cedar_Waxwing, Feeds on fruiting trees.
Cedar_Waxwing, Often in large flocks, especially during the winter months.
Cerulean_Warbler, Small, sky-blue warbler with a horizontal posture. Males have 2 white wingbars and dark streaking on the back. Note blue streaking on the sides.
Cerulean_Warbler, Females are bluish green above with a slight yellow wash below. They have a whitish eyebrow, and 2 white wingbars.
Cerulean_Warbler, Song is a buzzy series of notes that rise in pitch and end in a louder buzzy trill. Males typically sing from perches high in the canopy.
Cerulean_Warbler, Males are blue above and white below with blue streaks on the flanks and a thin blue neck band.
Cerulean_Warbler, From below, males are mostly white save for a thin blue band around the neck and blue streaking on the flanks. Breeds in the canopy of mature deciduous forests.
Cerulean_Warbler, Hops along branches plucking insects from foliage.
Cerulean_Warbler, Females have an unstreaked yellow-washed belly and a pale eyebrow. Typical females are greenish blue above, but some are considerably paler above.
Cerulean_Warbler, Females have an unstreaked belly and lack the neck band.
Cerulean_Warbler, Males sing while foraging within the canopy. From below, note the clean white underparts and blue streaking on the sides of males.
Cerulean_Warbler, A canopy dwelling warbler that sings, forages, and breeds in the canopy of older deciduous forests.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Tiny, with a big head, a small bill, and a round belly. Similar to other chickadees, but with a chestnut back and sides.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Most have dark chestnut sides, but birds from the central California coast (from Marin County southward) have gray sides with limited chestnut toward the tail.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Rarely stands still even while perched as they are often twitching side to side. This video has no audio.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Active and acrobatic, clings to small limbs and twigs or hangs upside down from cones.

Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Individuals in California from Marin County south have grayish sides unlike those farther north that have chestnut sides. Note dark brown crown, which sometimes looks black.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Tiny bird with a descriptive name. Its dark brown crown, which sometimes appears black is set off by a white cheek.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Regularly visits bird feeders, eating peanuts, suet, black oil sunflower seeds, and more.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Tiny, with a big head, a small bill, and a round belly. Similar to other chickadees, but with a chestnut back and sides.
Chestnut-backed_Chickadee, Found in dense evergreen and mixed evergreen forests along the Pacific Coast. Also found in city parks and suburbs.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black belly, yellowish throat, and a rusty nape. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.

Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Nonbreeding birds are grayish buff overall with dusky streaks on the back. Underparts are grayish with blurry streaks. Note rather plain face with faint marks around the ear.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Males sing a descending melodious warble, resembling a Western Meadowlark, from exposed perches such as tall blades of grass, small shrubs, or fencing wire.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird that walks or runs along the ground. Adult males have a black belly, a chestnut nape, and a yellowish throat.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Nonbreeding birds are grayish buff overall with dusky streaks on the back and blurry streaks on the belly. Note rather plain face with faint marks around the ear.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Outer tail feathers are white while inner tails are dark, forming a distinct triangle.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black belly, yellowish throat, and a rusty nape. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black belly, yellowish throat, and a rusty nape. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black belly, yellowish throat, and a rusty nape. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.
Chestnut-collared_Longspur, Stocky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black belly, yellowish throat, and a rusty nape. Flashes white outer tail feathers in flight.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Somewhat stocky and stout billed for a warbler. Often holds tail up above wings. Breeding males have a yellow crown, black mask, white cheeks, and chestnut sides.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Breeding females are paler than males with less streaking on the back. Note yellow crown and chestnut sides.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Sweet whistled song ends abruptly; often likened to saying "pleased-to-pleased-to-meet-you."
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Often holds tail up above wings. Females/immature males have bright yellow-green crown and white eyering on a gray face. They have little to no chestnut on the flanks.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Stout-billed for a warbler. Nonbreeding males have chestnut sides, a yellow crown and back, and a pale face with a white eyering.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Somewhat stocky and stout billed for a warbler. Often holds tail up above wings. Breeding males have a yellow crown, black mask, white cheeks, and chestnut sides.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Chestnut sides and yellow crown are distinctive. Extent of chestnut on the sides varies among individuals. Often holds tail up above wings.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Breeds in scrubby woodlands, forest edges, and other thick, regrowing areas.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Somewhat stocky and stout billed for a warbler. Often holds tail up above wings. Breeding males have a yellow crown, black mask, white cheeks, and chestnut sides.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Breeds in early successional deciduous woods. Uses a variety of forested and shrubby areas during migration.
Chestnut-sided_Warbler, Somewhat stocky and stout billed for a warbler. Often holds tail up above wings. Breeding males have a yellow crown, black mask, white cheeks, and chestnut sides.
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, Medium-sized songbird with long thin bill, short tail, and long legs. Upperparts are light brown; underparts are yellow. Sides are whitish with thin dark streaking.
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, In the fall and early winter, new feathers are edged with buff, dampening the intensity of the yellow underparts and black "V."
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, In flight, the three outermost tail feathers are nearly pure white, and the fourth is mostly white, with limited barring and a small black mark.

Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, Breeding adults have a black "V" on a yellow breast, whitish sides, and light brownish upperparts. A white mustache stripe and cheek, together with a black eyeline and dark crown stripe, create a striking head pattern.
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, Breeding adults in central Mexico ( S. l. auropectalis ) are similar to the separate northern population ( S. l. lilianae ) but have an orangish wash across the breast.
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, Nonbreeding adults and immatures show extensive buffy feather edges on the black "V" and yellow breast, contributing to an overall pale appearance.
Chihuahuan_Meadowlark, In Arizona, New Mexico, Texas, and northern Mexico, occurs in dry desert grasslands with limited shrubs.
Chihuahuan_Raven, Large, entirely black corvid with a hefty bill and long nasal bristles.
Chihuahuan_Raven, In flight, note the diamond-shaped tail and broad, round wings.
Chihuahuan_Raven, Often flies closer to the ground with strong and shallow wingbeats. Note the wedge-shaped tail.
Chihuahuan_Raven, The base of the feathers around the neck are white, but they are only visible when the wind exposes them or if the individual is fluffing their feathers.
Chihuahuan_Raven, Large corvid with long nasal bristles and a hefty bill.
Chihuahuan_Raven, Social bird often seen in small groups or large flocks. Uses power poles for perching as well as nesting.
Chihuahuan_Raven, Found in dry, open grasslands with scattered trees and shrubs, and unbroken desert scrub.
Chimney_Swift, Small with slender tube-shaped body and very long, narrow, curved wings. Dark gray-brown overall with a slightly paler throat.
Chimney_Swift, Tube or cigar-shaped body with long curved wings and a short tail. Dark gray-brown overall.
Chimney_Swift, Flies fast, often in loose feeding flocks, with very stiff wingbeats and almost no bend at the wrist. Often gives a chittering call while in flight.
Chimney_Swift, Calls frequently in flight, giving a fast, twittering series of high-pitched chip notes.
Chimney_Swift, Flies almost constantly except when at the nest or roosting.
Chimney_Swift, Does not perch, clings to the walls of chimneys and other vertical surfaces with its tiny feet.
Chimney_Swift, Nests in chimneys and on other vertical surfaces in dim, enclosed areas, including air vents, wells, hollow trees, and caves.
Chipping_Sparrow, Bright rusty crown, black eyeline, and unstreaked grayish belly are distinctive. Gray rump visible in flight.
Chipping_Sparrow, Nonbreeding birds are paler than breeding birds, but note brownish crown, dark eyeline, and unstreaked neck and belly.
Chipping_Sparrow, Bright rusty crown, black eyeline, and unstreaked grayish belly are distinctive. Gray rump visible in flight.
Chipping_Sparrow, Immature birds have a brown crown with thin dark streaks and buffy gray underparts with thin streaks. Note dark eyeline.
Chipping_Sparrow, Juveniles have streaked underparts and a streaked brown crown.
Chipping_Sparrow, Bright rusty crown, black eyeline, and unstreaked grayish belly are distinctive. Gray rump visible in flight.
Chipping_Sparrow, Sharply marked sparrow with a rusty cap, black eyeline, and unstreaked gray underparts.
Chipping_Sparrow, Immature birds have a brown crown with thin dark streaks and buffy gray underparts with thin streaks. The rump is finely streaked cinnamon, which gradually changes to gray.
Chipping_Sparrow, Bright rusty crown, black eyeline, and unstreaked grayish belly are distinctive. Gray rump visible in flight.
Chipping_Sparrow, Nonbreeding birds have the same general pattern as breeding birds, but more subdued colors, especially on the head. Note also the pink bill (versus black in breeding birds).
Chipping_Sparrow, Found in open woodlands and forests with grassy clearings across North America.
Chipping_Sparrow, Bright rusty crown, black eyeline, and unstreaked grayish belly are distinctive. Gray rump visible in flight.
Chuck-wills-widow, Large, flat-headed nightjar. Upperparts are mottled brown, buff, and black. In flight, males flash thin stripes of white on the tail.
Chuck-wills-widow, Flat-headed nightjar with a long tail and long wings. Females have a buffy spot on the tips of the outer tail feathers.
Chuck-wills-widow, Roosts during the day on a branch or on the ground. Tends to roost in the same location night after night.
Chuck-wills-widow, Extremely well camouflaged. Lays eggs on the ground among dead leaves, pine needles, or bare dirt.
Chuck-wills-widow, Occurs in woodlands, hedgerows, and thickets in southern Florida, the Caribbean, Central America, and northwestern South America during the nonbreeding season.
Chuck-wills-widow, Incessantly sings its name at night.
Chuck-wills-widow, Often roosts on low tree limbs.
Chukar, Chickenlike with a small round head and a plump body. Note bold striping on the sides, red bill and creamy throat bordered in black.
Chukar, Chickenlike with a small round head and a plump body. Note bold striping on the sides, red bill, creamy throat, and black eyeline that extends down around the throat.
Chukar, Runs and walks along the ground while searching for leaves and seeds. Introduced to the United States (including Hawaii) and Canada from southern Eurasia.
Chukar, Chickenlike with a small round head and a plump body. Note bold striping on the sides, red bill and creamy throat bordered in black.
Chukar, Chickenlike with a small round head and a plump body. Note bold striping on the sides, red bill and creamy throat bordered in black.
Chukar, Introduced to North America from southern Eurasia as a game bird.
Chukar, Found in steep rocky grasslands and shrublands in the West.
Chukar, Chickenlike with a small round head and a plump body. Note bold striping on the sides, red bill and creamy throat bordered in black.
Cinnamon_Teal, Breeding males have a deep brownish-red body with a long black bill, red eye, and a black back and rear.
Cinnamon_Teal, Females and nonbreeding males have a coarsely marked brown body with faint darker eyeline and cap, and a long black bill.
Cinnamon_Teal, Typically found in shallow freshwater wetlands such as marshes, flooded fields and ditches, ponds, and slow streams.
Cinnamon_Teal, Occurs in freshwater marshes with emergent vegetation and other types of wetlands.
Cinnamon_Teal, In flight note the green secondaries and powdery-blue shoulder.
Cinnamon_Teal, Males in nonbreeding plumage are more subdued in coloration. Their red eyes help to differentiate them from similar nonbreeding Blue-winged Teal.
Cinnamon_Teal, Males have bright powder blue wing patches in breeding and nonbreeding plumages.
Cinnamon_Teal, Average clutch size ranges from 8–11.
Clapper_Rail, Large, slender chickenlike rail with a long, slightly curved bill and short tail. Note gray cheek patches. Plumage color varies from cinnamon to grayish depending on location.

Clapper_Rail, Large, slender chickenlike rail with a long, slightly curved bill. Note gray cheek patches. Plumage color varies from cinnamon to grayish depending on location. Breeds in coastal marshes and wetlands with emergent vegetation.
Clapper_Rail, Typically stays hidden in dense marsh vegetation. Look for them at edges and openings as they pause to look around.
Clapper_Rail, Chickenlike rail that often holds its tail up. Cheek patches are gray while the rest of the plumage varies from cinnamon to grayish depending on location.
Clapper_Rail, Slender, chickenlike rail that often holds its tail up.
Clapper_Rail, Tall, slender rail with a long, slightly curved bill. Cheeks are gray. Overall color varies from cinnamon to gray depending on location.
Clarks_Grebe, Large, slender grebe with a long, thin, straight bill. Black crown does not reach eye, and the bill is bright yellow-orange, especially in summer.
Clarks_Grebe, Large, slender grebe with a long, thin, straight bill. Black crown does not reach eye, and the bill is bright yellow-orange, especially in summer.
Clarks_Grebe, Dives underwater for fish and other marine invertebrates.
Clarks_Grebe, Pairs bond using several displays, including synchronized "running" on the water.
Clarks_Grebe, Pairs perform elaborate displays during courtship, including a synchronized running dance. This video has no audio.
Clarks_Grebe, Large, slender grebe with a long, thin, straight bill. Black crown does not reach eye, and the bill is bright yellow-orange, especially in summer.
Clarks_Grebe, Elegant large grebe with a snakelike neck, puffy head, and a long, straight bill. Black cap does not cover the eye.
Clarks_Grebe, Primarily consumes small fish, which they pinch between the bill several times before swallowing it hole.
Clarks_Grebe, Black line on back of neck is narrow. Tufts of feathers on crown can make the head seem much wider than the neck.
Clarks_Grebe, Breeds on freshwater lakes; winters mainly on seacoasts.
Clarks_Grebe, Chicks hitch rides on their parent's backs after hatching until they are too big to fit.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Jay-sized bird with a long daggerlike bill and a short tail. Dark gray overall with black wings and white undertail coverts.
Clarks_Nutcracker, In flight its white outer tail feathers are noticeable and distinctive. Also note white trailing edge on the secondaries.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Uses its long, sharp bill to dig into pine cones and extract the seeds. Buries large numbers of seeds to use as winter food.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Hefty bird of evergreen forests with a long, slightly curved, sharply pointed bill. Gray overall with black wings.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Uses its sharp bill to extract seeds from pine cones.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Gray overall, sometimes with a paler face, and black wings. Note the daggerlike bill.
Clarks_Nutcracker, Found in higher elevation evergreen forests in western North America, especially those with whitebark and limber pine.

Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite, trim sparrow with a small bill, slender body, and fairly long, notched tail. Mostly a pale, tan-and-gray bird with a contrasting face pattern. The pale gray collar is a helpful mark at all times of year.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite sparrow with a small bill. The broad, buffy eyebrow, pale area in front of the eye, pale mustache, and gray collar are good field marks. Note pale central crown stripe.

Clay-colored_Sparrow, A petite sparrow with a small, pale bill and fairly long, notched tail. Mostly pale, with a light gray collar. The crown is finely streaked, with a pale stripe over the eye and darker cheek.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Small sparrow with a small bill. Note broad buffy eyebrow, pale mustache, and gray collar.

Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite, trim sparrow with a small bill, slender body, and fairly long, notched tail. Mostly a pale, tan-and-gray bird with a contrasting face pattern. The pale gray collar is a helpful mark at all times of year.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Song is a simple series of 2–8 high buzzes, sounding very insectlike.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite sparrow with a small bill. Note pale area in front of the eye and gray collar.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, At the eastern edge of their range, look for them in Christmas tree farms and grassy areas with short, scattered conifers.

Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite, trim sparrow with a small bill, slender body, and fairly long, notched tail. Mostly a pale, tan-and-gray bird with a contrasting face pattern. The pale gray collar is a helpful mark at all times of year.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Breeds in shrublands, field edges, and thickets across the northern prairies. Winters in desert grasslands, upland plains, thorn scrub, fields, and brushy hillsides.

Clay-colored_Sparrow, Petite, trim sparrow with a small bill, slender body, and fairly long, notched tail. Mostly a pale, tan-and-gray bird with a contrasting face pattern. The pale gray collar is a helpful mark at all times of year.
Clay-colored_Sparrow, Small sparrow with a tan cheek patch and broad buffy eyebrow. Note unstreaked belly.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Adult is brown above and slightly lighter below, with fine streaking on the throat, orange brown eyes, and a yellowish tip to the bill.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Found in yards, gardens, parks, and other open wooded habitats.
Clay-colored_Thrush, A medium-sized songbird. Brownish overall. Note yellow bill, orange eye, and fine streaking on throat. Often feeds on berries and fruits.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Juvenile has fine buffy markings on the wings and upper back, and has a darker eye than adult.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Juvenile's underparts are marked with dark splotches.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Visits feeding stations, where it eats bananas and other fruits.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Eats mainly invertebrates as well as fruit from trees or feeding stations. Some individuals appear uniformly brown, with no contrast between upperparts and underparts.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Clay-colored Thrush's musical caroling song is a cherished sound in Costa Rica, where it is the national bird.
Clay-colored_Thrush, Common calls include a series of soft "chup" notes.

Cliff_Swallow, Compact swallow with pointed, broad pointed wings, a small head, and a squared tail. In good light, adults have metallic, dark-blue backs and pale, cinnamon rumps. Their face is rusty with a white forehead.

Cliff_Swallow, Compact swallow with pointed, broad pointed wings, a small head, and a squared tail. In good light, adults have metallic, dark-blue backs and pale, cinnamon rumps. Their face is rusty with a white forehead.
Cliff_Swallow, Builds nests made of mud, which they cement to the walls of cliff ledges, under bridges, eaves, and culverts.
Cliff_Swallow, Compact swallow with a small head and squared tail. In flight note, pale rump patch and collar.
Cliff_Swallow, Juveniles look like messy adults with rusty or brown faces and a dingy breast.
Cliff_Swallow, Adults are dark blue above, but appear black in poor light. Key identification features include the pale rump and forehead and rusty cheeks.

Cliff_Swallow, Compact swallow with pointed, broad pointed wings, a small head, and a squared tail. In good light, adults have metallic, dark-blue backs and pale, cinnamon rumps. Their face is rusty with a white forehead.

Cliff_Swallow, Compact swallow with pointed, broad pointed wings, a small head, and a squared tail. In good light, adults have metallic, dark-blue backs and pale, cinnamon rumps. Their face is rusty with a white forehead.
Cliff_Swallow, Groups gather mud in their bills along streambanks, lakesides, or puddles to build their nests.
Cliff_Swallow, Builds mud nests in colonies on cliff ledges or under bridges, eaves, and culverts.

Colima_Warbler, A medium-sized warbler with a long bill and long tail. White eyering stands out against gray head. Upperparts brownish-gray, sides buffy brown. Undertail and uppertail coverts bright yellow.
Colima_Warbler, Gray head and breast contrast with brownish upperparts and flanks. Bright yellow undertail and uppertail coverts cover base of long tail.
Colima_Warbler, A grayish-brown warbler with bright yellow undertail coverts. Moves deliberately from branch to branch as it searches for insects and spiders.
Colima_Warbler, Rusty orange crown patch is obvious when head feathers are raised, but inconspicuous at other times.
Colima_Warbler, Light gray breast is bordered by buffy-brown flanks, giving way to whitish belly and yellow undertail coverts.
Colima_Warbler, Breeds in pine-oak woodlands in the mountains of northeastern Mexico, with range just extending into the U.S. in Big Bend National Park.
Colima_Warbler, Hops between leaf clusters to glean arthropods from leaves, twigs, and flowers.
Colima_Warbler, Male often sings from exposed perches in the upper parts of bushes and short trees.
Common_Black_Hawk, Large hawk with very broad wings and short tail. Adults are overall black with a prominent white band in the tail and a white tail tip.
Common_Black_Hawk, Large hawk with short tail and very broad wings. Juveniles are mottled brown and buff, with black wingtips and many narrow bands on the tail.
Common_Black_Hawk, Large, long-legged hawk. Adults are sooty black with yellow bill and legs.
Common_Black_Hawk, Note very broad wings, especially secondaries, and short tail. Juveniles are mottled brown and buff, and show pale panels in the outer wing, with dark wingtips.
Common_Black_Hawk, When perched, note yellow base of bill and prominent white band in the tail and white tail tip.
Common_Black_Hawk, Immatures retain some juvenile-like mottling and narrow tail bands, while acquiring adult black plumage. Note long yellow legs.

Common_Black_Hawk, Juveniles can be strongly mottled with black; note narrow bands on tail and long yellow legs. The "Mangrove" subspecies group occurs in mangroves of Central and northern South America; it tends to be slimmer and smaller than other Common Black Hawks.

Common_Black_Hawk, Large, broad-winged and long-legged hawk. Juveniles are a mix of brown and buff and usually show a strong face pattern with line through the eye and dark malar stripe continuing down sides of neck. Note white panels in the outer wing (visible in folded wing; prominent in flight).
Common_Black_Hawk, Large dark hawk usually found near water in wooded habitats such as canyon bottoms, flooded forests, mangroves, and freshwater swamps and marshes.
Common_Eider, Large-bodied sea duck with a sloping profile to the forehead. Note white back, dark sides, black cap, and greenish sides of neck.
Common_Eider, Large-bodied sea duck with a sloping forehead. Females are rich reddish brown overall with fine blackish barring.

Common_Eider, Breeds on coastal islands or along ponds and lagoons near the ocean. Chicks leave the nest within 24 hours after hatching and can feed themselves, though the female often stays with the young for several weeks.
Common_Eider, Immature males have the distinctive sloping eider forehead shape, a dark head, a white breast, and white mottling on the back.
Common_Eider, When molting into breeding plumage, shows dark mottling on back and breast.
Common_Eider, In flight, bulky body and color pattern—dark belly with white upperparts—are distinctive.
Common_Eider, Large-bodied, bulky sea duck with a black cap and greenish sides of neck, white back, and black belly.
Common_Eider, Distinctive sloping profile to the forehead and bill. Females are grayish brown overall with a pale head and fine dark barring on the body.
Common_Eider, Females are brownish overall with fine dark barring on the back and sides.
Common_Eider, Large-bodied sea duck with a sloping profile to the forehead. Note white back, dark sides, black cap, and greenish sides of neck.
Common_Eider, Large-bodied sea duck with a sloping profile to the forehead. Note white back, dark sides, black cap, and greenish sides of neck.
Common_Eider, First winter males are dark brown with variable white mottling and pale or yellow tip to the bill. Females are lighter or more reddish brown with a gray bill.
Common_Eider, Often forms large flocks with both males and females.

Common_Gallinule, Medium-sized marsh bird with long yellow legs and toes. Adults are charcoal gray with a bright red bill and forehead shield. Note white stripe down the side and white outer tail feathers.
Common_Gallinule, Forages in shallow wetlands, taking aquatic vegetation from the surface or just below, or picking snails and other invertebrates from submerged plants.
Common_Gallinule, Juveniles are pale brown overall, with paler underparts and a dull greenish bill and shield. Note the characteristic white stripe down the side.
Common_Gallinule, Chicks are covered in black down and are capable of swimming within one day of hatching.
Common_Gallinule, Long toes make it possible to walk on soft mud and floating vegetation. Often walks with its tail cocked up, showing the white sides.
Common_Gallinule, Despite not having webbed feet, it swims with ease.
Common_Gallinule, Medium-sized marsh bird that appears dark overall. The red bill, white flank stripe, and white stripe on the tail separate it from similar species.
Common_Gallinule, Smaller than an American Coot (right) with a bright red bill and shield.
Common_Gallinule, Found in freshwater or brackish marshes with tall emergent vegetation, ponds, canals, and rice fields.

Common_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a triangular head and a sloping bill. Adult males are mostly white with white windows along the folded wing. Head is iridescent green (often looks black), with a round white spot behind the bill.

Common_Goldeneye, Medium-sized grayish-brown duck with a triangular head and a sloping bill. Females have a warm brown head that contrasts with its gray body. Bill is mostly blackish, with yellow at the tip only.

Common_Goldeneye, Found on inland lakes and rivers as well as coastal waters. Feeds mainly along shorelines in relatively shallow water where it dives under water for aquatic invertebrates, fish, and fish eggs.
Common_Goldeneye, Medium-sized duck with a forehead the slopes downward to meet the bill. Immatures show less white in the wings than adult males. White face patch is round.
Common_Goldeneye, Medium-sized, mostly brown duck; immatures lacks golden eye of adults.
Common_Goldeneye, When around females, males frequently display by stretching the head backward against the back and then popping forward.
Common_Goldeneye, Females occasionally show mostly yellowish bill (usually mostly blackish with yellow tip). Forehead slopes gradually to meet the bill. Warm brown head contrasts with grayish body.
Common_Goldeneye, Fairly high, peaked head with a forehead that slopes gradually to meet the mostly blackish bill. Adults' golden eyes can be visible from fairly long distance.
Common_Goldeneye, Females have white collar around the neck that can be obscured depending on the bird's posture. Ducklings have dark heads with fluffy cream-white throats.
Common_Goldeneye, In flight, note adult male's large white wing patches on black wings and mostly dark head contrasting with white neck and underparts.
Common_Goldeneye, Fairly common on inland lakes and rivers as well as coastal waters. Forms flocks.
Common_Grackle, Large, lanky blackbirds with long legs, a long tail, and a long and heavy bill. Adult males appear dark overall, but have an iridescent bluish head and bronzy body in good light.
Common_Grackle, Lanky blackbird with a long tail and heavy, long bill. Females are slightly less glossy than males.

Common_Grackle, The typical song, made by both males and females, is a guttural squeak accompanied by high-pitched, clear whistles. It lasts just less than a second and is often described as sounding like a rusty gate. While singing, males puff up their body feathers and spread their tails.
Common_Grackle, Struts on long legs, pecking for food rather than scratching.
Common_Grackle, Noisy and conspicuous blackbird with a long tail.
Common_Grackle, Females of the purple form can be similarly colored to males, but note the shorter tail that lacks a paddle shape.
Common_Grackle, Females can be very dark, notably those of the bronze form.
Common_Grackle, Lanky blackbird with a long tail and hefty bill. Immatures are brownish overall, with a dark eye, and less glossy than adults.
Common_Grackle, Comes to bird feeding stations, where it often feeds on seeds on the ground.
Common_Grackle, Found in agricultural fields, feedlots, city parks, and suburban lawns. They're also common in open habitats including woodland, forest edges, meadows, and marshes.
Common_Ground_Dove, Tiny dove with a small head and short tail. Pinkish brown underparts with grayish head and scaled pattern on neck and breast. Often has pink or red base of bill.
Common_Ground_Dove, Tiny dove with a small head and a short, square-tipped tail. Head is grayish; back and wings are brown with dark spots in the wings.
Common_Ground_Dove, A small plump dove often seen on the ground foraging for seeds.
Common_Ground_Dove, Tiny dove with a small head and a short bill. Extensive scaled pattern on neck and breast. Head is paler than rest of body.
Common_Ground_Dove, Tiny dove with a short tail. In flight shows chestnut patches in the wing and dark sides of the tail with small white corners.
Common_Ground_Dove, Flushes quickly into flight, flashing rusty-colored underwings.
Common_Ground_Dove, Outer wing feathers are bright rufous above and below.
Common_Ground_Dove, Degree of scaling varies among individuals.
Common_Ground_Dove, Common Ground Doves are at home in open woodlands, desert areas as well as urban landscapes. Often perches in trees when not foraging.
Common_Ground_Dove, Forages on bare ground, usually keeping close to cover, in grasslands, scrubby areas, desert washes, and open woodlands. Flushes with a whirring sound from the wings.
Common_Ground_Dove, Walks on the ground with a nod of its head at every step. This video has no audio.
Common_Loon, Long-bodied waterbird with a hefty bill. Sits low in the water. Breeding birds have a black-and-white striped collar and a checkerboard back.
Common_Loon, Hefty daggerlike bill. Nonbreeding/immature birds often have a pale collar as seen on this bird—a spur of white extending on the dark neck.
Common_Loon, Feet are positioned far back on the body to aid in diving, but this makes walking on land very difficult. Nests are close to the water's edge on undisturbed freshwater lakes.
Common_Loon, In flight, has a bulky profile with large feet trailing behind.
Common_Loon, Winters along ocean coasts, usually fairly close to shore and in bays and estuaries.
Common_Loon, Flies with steady, shallow wingbeats. Note narrow, pointed wings and long trailing feet.
Common_Loon, Large-bodied loon with a hefty bill and flat head. Breeding birds have a black-and-white striped collar and a checkerboard back.
Common_Loon, Nonbreeding birds are often brownish above and show a pale partial collar on the neck.
Common_Loon, Feeds by diving; may dip head into water to look for prey while sitting on the surface. This video has no audio.
Common_Loon, Chicks accompany adults for several weeks and often ride on the back of an adult when very young.
Common_Loon, Breeds in freshwater lakes.
Common_Loon, Young chicks often ride on the backs of adults.
Common_Loon, A bulky loon with a hefty bill and a rather flat head.
Common_Loon, Breeds on clear lakes across Canada and the northern United States.
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long body and long, straight bill. Mostly white, with green head and orange-red bill.
Common_Merganser, Female is mostly gray with a reddish-brown head. Note the shaggy crest, white chin patch, and sharp break between the reddish-brown head and whitish upper breast.
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long body and long, straight bill. Mostly white, with green head and orange-red bill.
Common_Merganser, In North America, both sexes have dark outer wings with white patch on secondary flight feathers. Male also shows white on leading edge of wing.

Common_Merganser, In Europe and Asia, Common Merganser is known by the common name Goosander. Male Goosander has a darker, blood-red bill, and in flight shows a pure white wing patch (North American male's wing patch is interrupted by a thin black bar).
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long body and long, straight bill. Mostly white, with green head and orange-red bill.
Common_Merganser, Male typically abandons the nest during incubation, leaving the female to care for ducklings on her own.
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long, slender bill. Warm reddish head has ragged crest, white chin, and sharp border with white chest.
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long body and long, straight bill. Mostly white, with green head and orange-red bill.
Common_Merganser, Female has gray body contrasting with cinnamon-red, crested head. May be seen with large numbers of ducklings in summer.
Common_Merganser, Immature male shows a mix of female and adult male features.
Common_Merganser, Large duck with long body and long, straight bill. Mostly white, with green head and orange-red bill.
Common_Merganser, Fairly common on freshwater, especially rivers. Often rests on boulders or logs in midstream.
Common_Merganser, Similar to female, but with reduced crest, lighter head color, more extensive white on face, and thin brownish line extending from base of bill onto face.
Common_Merganser, Typically nests in a natural cavity or woodpecker hole in a live or dead tree.
Common_Merganser, Fairly common along freshwater lakes and rivers; rarer in saltwater or brackish water.
Common_Murre, Large black-and-white seabird with a long, thin bill. Breeding birds have an entirely black head.
Common_Murre, In water, looks rather ducklike with a long and slender body and bill. Nonbreeding birds have a white throat, chin, and cheek that wraps up behind the eye.
Common_Murre, Nests in colonies on steep, cliff ledges, slopes, and rocky outcrops. Constantly makes guttural calls at the colony.
Common_Murre, Large black-and-white seabird with a long, thin bill. Breeding birds have an entirely black head.
Common_Murre, Large black-and-white seabird with a long, thin bill. Breeding birds have an entirely black head.
Common_Murre, Large black-and-white seabird with a long, thin bill. Breeding birds have an entirely black head.
Common_Murre, Stands upright like a penguin. "Bridled" form in the Atlantic region has a white eyering that extends across the side of its face.
Common_Murre, Large black-and-white seabird with a long, thin bill. Breeding birds have an entirely black head.
Common_Murre, At sea often congregates in large rafts. Long-necked seabird with a long, thin bill. In good light appears dark brown and white.
Common_Murre, Large, black-and-white penguinlike seabird. Breeds in dense colonies on island cliff ledges, slopes, and rocky outcrops.
Common_Myna, A medium-sized songbird with a blackish hood, maroon-brown body, and short, white-tipped tail. The stout bill, legs, and bare skin behind the eye are all bright orange-yellow.
Common_Myna, In flight from below, note rounded wings with white lining and large white patch in primaries. Note also white tip to black tail.
Common_Myna, A medium-sized songbird with a blackish hood, brownish breast, bold white wing patch, stout yellow bill, and bright yellow patch behind the eye.
Common_Myna, In flight from above, white wing patch contrasts with dark outer wings.
Common_Myna, Some individuals have a light-yellow patch on the upper breast.
Common_Myna, A loud, aggressive species, with birds sometimes coming to physical blows.
Common_Myna, Typically lives around people. Native to central and southern Asia but introduced and established in many other parts of the world.
Common_Myna, Feeds mainly on the ground, probing the soil and often hopping sideways in pursuit of insects.
Common_Myna, Feeds largely on the ground, walking and hopping about and using the strong bill to probe for insects.
Common_Myna, Molting individuals frequently have bald patches or a completely featherless head.
Common_Myna, Also forages in trees and bushes for fruit and nectar.
Common_Nighthawk, Medium-sized, slender bird with long, pointed wings. Note white patch on the wings located closer to the bend in the wing.
Common_Nighthawk, Extremely short-legged with a tiny bill and small flat head. Well camouflaged in gray, white, buff, and black. Note white patch on lower edge of the wing.
Common_Nighthawk, Medium-sized, slender bird with long, pointed wings. Note white patch on the wings located closer to the bend in the wing.

Common_Nighthawk, Long-winged and flat-headed with a tiny bill. Plumage color varies across the range with some individuals having more rusty tones while others are grayer. Note white patch on lower edge of the wing.
Common_Nighthawk, Nests on the ground in open areas such as gravel bars, forest clearings, coastal sand dunes, or sparsely vegetated grasslands.
Common_Nighthawk, Medium-sized, slender bird with long, pointed wings. Note white patch on the wings located closer to the bend in the wing.
Common_Nighthawk, Hunts on the wing at dawn and dusk, catching an array of flying insects.

Common_Nighthawk, Adult male—told by distinct white throat patch, wide wing patches, and white tail band (not visible here)—courts females by diving through the air, making a booming sound as air rushes over his wings.
Common_Nighthawk, Medium-sized, slender bird with long, pointed wings. Note white patch on the wings located closer to the bend in the wing.

Common_Nighthawk, Has a huge mouth for catching insects in flight. Opening the mouth is one of several defense mechanisms—including hissing, raising wings, and fluffing feathers—used when facing an intruder.
Common_Nighthawk, Most active at dusk and dawn. During the day roosts in trees, on the ground, or on a flat roof.
Common_Nighthawk, Medium-sized, slender bird with long, pointed wings. Note white patch on the wings located closer to the bend in the wing.
Common_Nighthawk, Frequently seen roosting on fence posts in western North America.
Common_Pauraque, Long-tailed nightjar. Male's outer tail feathers are white. They are reduced on females, but noticeable in flight. Wings also have a white band that is visible in flight.
Common_Pauraque, Well-camouflaged, brown and gray nightjar. Feathers on the shoulder have buffy tips. Individuals in Texas and lower Rio Grande Valley are grayer than others.
Common_Pauraque, Forages at dawn and dusk near clearings for insects. Rests on the ground and becomes "immobilized" in spotlights.
Common_Pauraque, Throat patch, which is often very difficult to see, is buffy on females and white on males.
Common_Pauraque, Long-tailed nightjar. Male's outer tail feathers are white. They are reduced on females, but noticeable in flight. Wings also have a white band that is visible in flight.
Common_Pauraque, Active at dawn and dusk, but can become motionless when spotlighted.
Common_Pauraque, During the day roosts on forest floor where it is nearly invisible.
Common_Poorwill, A small, flat-headed nightjar with a short tail. White band marks the throat, but it is often difficult to see on roosting birds.
Common_Poorwill, Typically roosts on the ground, where camouflaged plumage can make it very difficult to see.
Common_Poorwill, A small, densely camouflaged nightjar with a neat white band on the throat. Often roosts on the ground during the daytime.
Common_Poorwill, In flight, male's white tail tips are visible. Tail tips on females are buffy and not as obvious. Note short tail.
Common_Poorwill, Typically roosts on the ground or among rocks. Note thin white neck band.
Common_Poorwill, During the breeding season, the male sings a repeated, whistled poorwillip at night.
Common_Poorwill, Inhabits mostly shrubby, open areas in dry environments.
Common_Raven, Large, thick-necked bird with a hefty bill and a shaggy neck.
Common_Raven, In flight, note wedge-shaped tail.
Common_Raven, Often pushes its head forward and fluffs up its throat feathers when calling.
Common_Raven, The world's largest songbird—even larger than most Peregrine Falcons.
Common_Raven, Often seen alone or in pairs, but many may gather in larger groups at a carcass or landfill.
Common_Raven, Juveniles are browner than all-black adults.
Common_Raven, Has elongated throat feathers, known as "hackles," that are raised in threat and dominance displays.
Common_Raven, Flies with heavy, slow wingbeats and interspersed glides. Note the wedge or diamond-shaped tail in flight.
Common_Raven, Bill is long and heavy with feathers extending down bill.
Common_Raven, Larger than an American Crow with a wedge-shaped tail.
Common_Raven, Eats almost anything it can find, including carrion. Note the shaggy feathers on the neck and hefty bill.
Common_Raven, Nests on cliffs, in trees, and on structures such as power-line towers, telephone poles, billboards, and bridges. Found in North America, Europe, Asia, and North Africa.
Common_Raven, Large, entirely black bird. Occurs over most of the Northern Hemisphere in nearly any habitat.
Common_Raven, Often forms communal nocturnal roosts and forages in groups especially at landfills or near a carcass.
Common_Raven, Occurs from desert floors to alpine summits.

Common_Tern, Medium-sized tern with deeply forked tail. Breeding adults across most of the range have a gray belly, full black cap, and reddish bill. The upper side of the outer primaries is dark gray, creating a dark wingtip.

Common_Tern, Medium-sized tern with a slender, straight bill. Tail is about the same length as the folded wings. Breeding adults in the widespread "hirundo/tibetana" subspecies group (which occurs in the Americas, Europe, Africa, and parts of Asia) usually have a grayish chest, a bright red, black-tipped bill, and red legs.

Common_Tern, Breeding adults have a neat black cap and red bill with black tip. In this image, note the long crossed wingtips (above) about the same length as the forked tail (below). Nests in the open on beaches.

Common_Tern, Breeding adults in the "longipennis" subspecies group have a black bill and black (or dark brown) legs. This subspecies group breeds in northeastern Asia and occurs as a vagrant in western Alaska.

Common_Tern, Nonbreeding adults lose the front portion of their black cap, showing a white forehead and black hindcrown. Legs and bill turn blackish as winter progresses. Note tail does not extend beyond wingtips at rest.
Common_Tern, Immatures and nonbreeding adults have a distinctive black bar on the leading edge of the wing, known as a carpal bar. Tail does not extend beyond wingtips.
Common_Tern, Immature birds in the "longipennis" group have a black bill, white forehead, dark carpal bar on the wing, and dark legs.
Common_Tern, Juveniles have a faint brownish wash to the back and a partial black cap that extends to the crown. They also have a dark leading edge to the wing, or carpal bar.

Common_Tern, Flies with wingtips swept back with rowing wingbeats. Nonbreeding adults have a white forehead and black on the crown and behind the eye, with blackish bill. Note the black wedge on the upper side of the wingtips.
Common_Tern, Medium-sized tern with deeply forked tail. Outer primaries form a dark wedge on the upper side of the wingtips. Wings are slender, swept back, and narrow at the base.
Common_Tern, Immature birds lack the long tail feathers of breeding adults and appear darker in flight, with more black in the wings and tail.

Common_Tern, Nonbreeding "longipennis" adults develop a white forehead but are otherwise similar to breeding adults. This subspecies group spends the nonbreeding season in the eastern Indian Ocean, Southeast Asia, and along the Australian coast.
Common_Tern, Terns fly gracefully with rowing wingbeats over open waters, diving down to pick fish from or just below the water's surface.
Common_Tern, Occurs along shorelines, barrier islands, and estuaries, as well as on large inland lakes. In coastal areas, typically less numerous in brackish areas than along the ocean shore.

Common_Wood-Pigeon, A large pigeon with a gray head, grayish-brown upperparts, a lilac breast, an orange-red bill, and a bold white neck patch. Perched birds usually show at least a hint of white along the edge of the wing.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, In flight, white wing markings and neck patches are visible at long distances. Note also the broad black band on the tail.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, A large pigeon with a lilac breast, gray head, white neck patch bordered by iridescent green, and brownish-gray wings with a large white patch.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, Juvenile is duller than adult and lacks a white neck patch.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, "Cinnamon-necked" Common Wood-Pigeons of Central Asia are similar to the "White-necked" birds in Europe, but have a cinnamon neck patch, rather than white.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, Forages mainly on the ground, but also feeds on fruits and seeds in trees.

Common_Wood-Pigeon, Iridescent green neck feathers, adjacent to the white neck patch, are visible in good light. Mauve coloration is most intense on the breast, then fades to grayish white on the belly.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, "Cinnamon-necked" Common Wood-Pigeons of Central Asia sport a cinnamon (rather than white) neck patch.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, Both sexes care for young birds, which remain dependent for at least a week after fledging.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, The white neck patch is bordered by iridescent green and purple feathers. Adult has a pale iris.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, Often forages in open agricultural areas.
Common_Wood-Pigeon, Forages mainly on the ground, and often drinks from the edge of puddles and ponds.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, Females are brownish above with a yellow throat and breast. The brightness of yellow varies geographically.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, The black mask on immature males is faint and patchy.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, Resident males around Lake Chapala, Jalisco, Mexico have a larger black mask that is bordered by yellow instead of white like Common Yellowthroats farther north.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask bordered by white and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, Females are brownish above with a yellow throat and undertail coverts, the intensity of which varies geographically.
Common_Yellowthroat, Found in open areas with thick, low vegetation, ranging from marshes to grasslands to open pine forests.
Common_Yellowthroat, Small songbird with a round belly and long tail. Males have a black mask and a yellow throat and undertail coverts.
Common_Yellowthroat, Spends much of their time skulking low to the ground in dense thickets and fields where they can be difficult to see.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.

Connecticut_Warbler, Breeds in spruce and tamarack bogs. During migration uses a variety of woodlands, forests, and thickets, but it is often difficult to see due to its secretive and skulking nature.
Connecticut_Warbler, Immature birds are olive above and drab yellowish below with a complete white eyering.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.
Connecticut_Warbler, Immatures appear drab yellowish olive overall with a distinctive complete white eyering. Note long legs and bulky appearance.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.
Connecticut_Warbler, Large, skulking warbler with a complete white eyering, a pale bill, and a gray hood. Males and females look similar, but females are often paler than males.

Coopers_Hawk, Upright posture with a long tail. Bluish-gray upperparts with a contrasting black cap and a red eye. Underparts are pale with dense reddish barring. Bill is fairly small and strongly hooked.
Coopers_Hawk, Bluish-gray upperparts contrast with the paler cheek and dark cap. Note the long rounded tail with a wide white terminal band.
Coopers_Hawk, Adult Cooper's Hawks have gray backs, reddish-barred chests, and reddish eyes. Note the sharp division between the black cap and gray nape (neck).
Coopers_Hawk, Immature has brown upperparts, white underparts with brown streaking, and yellow eyes.
Coopers_Hawk, Immature is brownish above, and like adults, has a large head and long, banded tail.

Coopers_Hawk, Accipiters like Cooper's Hawk have rounded wings and very long tails. In flight, look for Cooper's Hawk's large head that projects out ahead of the wings. The long tail often appears slightly rounded at the tip.
Coopers_Hawk, Upright posture with a long tail. Immatures have brown upperparts that contrast with white underparts that have strong brown streaking. Note the yellow eye.
Coopers_Hawk, In flight shows relatively short, rounded wings and a long, rounded tail with thick bands. Note that its head projects well beyond its wings.
Coopers_Hawk, Note the very long tail compared to the wings—a distinctive feature of accipiters. The sharp black cap contrasting with the gray nape is a good ID feature for Cooper's Hawk.
Coopers_Hawk, In flight shows relatively short, rounded wings and a long, rounded tail with thick bands. Note the wide white terminal band on tail, which can sometimes help with identification.
Coopers_Hawk, In flight from above, upperparts on immatures are brown with paler barring in the wings and tail. Note the larger head that sticks out well beyond the wings.
Coopers_Hawk, Accipiters are specialist predators that eat mostly birds. They sometimes hunt at backyard feeders.
Coopers_Hawk, From some angles white undertail contrasts with the reddish barred underparts and bluish-gray upperparts.

Costas_Hummingbird, Small and compact hummingbird with a hunched posture and a short tail. The male's iridescent purple gorget (throat patch) flares out along the sides of the neck like an overgrown mustache.

Costas_Hummingbird, When perched the wings barely extend beyond the tail on this tiny, compact hummingbird. Females are greenish above with a white eyebrow stripe, a grayish cheek patch, and whitish underparts.
Costas_Hummingbird, Gorget color is dark purple, and feathers extend off the sides of the throat. Fairly short wings; wingtips barely extend past the tail.

Costas_Hummingbird, Males repeatedly perch at 3–4 favorite spots within their territory, usually a dead twig in a palo verde, acacia, or ironwood, and sing a thin high-pitched whistle to proclaim ownership and keep intruders out.
Costas_Hummingbird, Immature males have variable amounts of adult gorget feathers coming in on the neck. Note whitish underparts and green washing on the sides.

Costas_Hummingbird, Small and compact hummingbird with a hunched posture and a short tail. The male's iridescent purple gorget (throat patch) flares out along the sides of the neck like an overgrown mustache.

Costas_Hummingbird, Small and compact hummingbird with a hunched posture and a short tail. The male's iridescent purple gorget (throat patch) flares out along the sides of the neck like an overgrown mustache.
Costas_Hummingbird, A compact hummingbird. When perched, its wings barely extend beyond the tail. Females are greenish above with a white eyebrow stripe and a grayish cheek patch.

Costas_Hummingbird, Found in desert scrub in the Sonoran and Mojave Deserts, and chaparral and sage scrub areas in coastal California where they drink nectar from many desert plants, especially chuparosa and ocotillo.
Couchs_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a heavy bill and a long tail. Note gray head with slightly darker ear patch and whitish throat.
Couchs_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a bright yellow belly and a long, notched tail. Often perches conspicuously in shrubby areas, clearings in tropical forests, and some rural and suburban areas.
Couchs_Kingbird, Best told from Tropical Kingbird by its call, a single "pik" or an intensifying, "pik-pik-pikweer," both with a nasal quality.
Couchs_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a heavy bill and a long tail. Note gray head with slightly darker ear patch and whitish throat.
Couchs_Kingbird, Bright yellow below with a gray head and darker ear patch. Note long, notched tail.
Couchs_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a heavy bill and a long tail. Note gray head with slightly darker ear patch and whitish throat.
Crested_Caracara, Large, long-legged and flat-headed falcon. Adults have a black body and cap with a white neck and cheeks. Note yellow legs and bare orangish skin around the face.
Crested_Caracara, Long-legged falcon with a long neck and flat head. Juveniles are brown instead of black with a whitish neck and cheeks.
Crested_Caracara, In flight, note dark body and white neck, wingtips, and tail.
Crested_Caracara, Juveniles are similar to adults, but are brown instead of black.
Crested_Caracara, Large, long-legged and flat-headed falcon. Adults have a black body and cap with a white neck and cheeks. Note yellow legs and bare orangish skin around the face.
Crested_Caracara, Regularly walks along the ground when foraging for insects, carrion, small mammals, reptiles, and amphibians. This has a full crop.
Crested_Caracara, Perches on top of trees or posts that offer a good view of the surroundings.
Crested_Caracara, Found in open country, including pastureland, grasslands, cultivated areas, and semi-desert with scattered trees and posts.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large with a long tail and curved bill. Brownish gray overall with a black and white mustache stripe.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large with a long tail and cinnamon undertail coverts. Brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.
Crissal_Thrasher, Found in desert washes, riparian thickets, and dry scrubby areas. Usually found on or near the ground in dense vegetation, but will perch up to sing during the breeding season.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.
Crissal_Thrasher, Large, long-tailed bird with a curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a black and white mustache stripe. The undertail coverts are a rich cinnamon color.

Curlew_Sandpiper, A medium-sized shorebird with a long, downcurved bill and long, black legs. Breeding adult ranges from brick-red to chestnut on the face, neck, breast, and belly, with a white vent and undertail coverts, and spangled rufous, black, and white upperparts. In fresh breeding plumage, underparts can have a scalloped look due to fresh white feather tips.
Curlew_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding adult has gray upperparts, white underparts with some gray streaking across the breast, and a prominent white eyeline bordered by a gray cap.

Curlew_Sandpiper, A medium-sized shorebird with a long, downcurved bill and long wings that give an overall "stretched out" look. Juvenile has scaly brown upperparts, a prominent white line above the eye, and mostly white underparts with limited streaking on the breast.

Curlew_Sandpiper, Juvenile has scaly upperparts (due to white edges on dark feathers), a buffy wash and fine streaking on the side of the breast, a dark line running from the base of the bill to the eye, a white line above the eye, and a dark cap.
Curlew_Sandpiper, In flight in all plumages, note the white rump, gray tail, and white wing stripe.
Curlew_Sandpiper, Nests on arctic tundra, where the female typically incubates four eggs in a shallow depression on dry ground.
Curlew_Sandpiper, Molting birds in late summer are a patchwork of breeding and nonbreeding plumages.
Curlew_Sandpiper, Frequently occurs on tidal mudflats during migration and the nonbreeding season.

Curlew_Sandpiper, Often occurs in large flocks during migration and on nonbreeding grounds. Uses its long bill to probe for prey on tidal mudflats, salt pans, sandy beaches, rice fields, lake edges, and sewage lagoons.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Long-bodied slim bird about the size of a robin with a long, curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a whitish throat and spotted belly.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Long-tailed with a long, curved bill. Grayish brown overall with grayish flanks and pale peach undertail coverts. Note yellow eye.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Aptly named bird of the desert scrub regions. Drinks water from bird baths, dripping faucets, and areas where water collects.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Long and slender with a curved bill. The underparts are spotted and the undertail coverts are a pale peachy color.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Slender with a long curved bill and long tail. Grayish brown overall with a whitish throat and spotted underparts. Note yellow eye and pale peachy undertail coverts.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Long-bodied slim bird about the size of a robin with a long, curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a whitish throat and spotted belly.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Forages on the ground using its bill and strong legs to toss vegetation out of the way in search of insects.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Long-bodied slim bird about the size of a robin with a long, curved bill. Grayish brown overall with a whitish throat and spotted belly.
Curve-billed_Thrasher, Found in thorny brush and scrublands, semi-desert areas (especially where mesquite or cholla cactus are present), shrubby areas, open brushy woodlands, and around towns.

Dark-eyed_Junco, Medium-sized sparrow with round head, long tail, and fairly small, pale bill. All juncos have prominent white outer tail feathers. Male "Slate-colored" form is mostly gray with white belly.

Dark-eyed_Junco, Medium-sized sparrow with round head, small, pale bill, and long tail with white outer feathers. "Oregon" form of western North America has dark brown hood, light brown back, buffy sides, and white belly.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Breeds in forests; "Slate-colored" form is mostly clean gray with white belly. White outer tail feathers (present even in juvenile) and high, thin chip notes are distinctive.

Dark-eyed_Junco, All juncos have pale bills and white outer tail feathers that they flash in flight. "Pink-sided" form around Rocky Mountains has a slate-gray head, brown back, and pinkish-brown sides.

Dark-eyed_Junco, Medium-sized sparrow with white outer tail feathers and small bill. "Red-backed" form of southwestern U.S. has gray head, dark face, and bright reddish brown back. Upper mandible of bill is darker gray than lower.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Pale bill is distinctive for all forms of juncos. "Oregon" form has dark hood and brown back. Often feeds on ground; also comes to feeders.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Medium-sized sparrow with small bill. "Gray-headed" form has gray head, dark face, and bright reddish brown back; very similar to "Red-backed" form but with all-pale bill.

Dark-eyed_Junco, Medium-sized sparrow with small, pale bill and white outer tail feathers. "White-winged" form is slightly paler gray than "Slate-colored" form, with faint white wingbars and a dark face.

Dark-eyed_Junco, White outer tail feathers are very prominent in flight but inconspicuous on ground. "Gray-headed" form of interior western North America has mostly gray head and body with reddish-brown back. This video has no audio.
Dark-eyed_Junco, The "cismontanus" subspecies breeds in the Yukon Territory and British Columbia. It has a dark brown head, brown back, and white belly.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Female and young "Slate-colored" form are variable; can be much browner than the males.
Dark-eyed_Junco, "White-winged" form resembles "Slate-colored" form but has two white wingbars. It occurs in a small range in the central United States. This video has no audio.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Juvenile juncos are streaky, but note the white outer tail feathers and round-headed, small-billed general appearance.
Dark-eyed_Junco, "Slate-colored" males have a gray head, throat, and breast that contrasts with a white belly.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Juncos are among the most common songbirds of North America. They typically live in forest understories but often visit feeders, especially during winter.
Dark-eyed_Junco, Females and immatures of the "Oregon" form have less contrast than the males, with a grayish hood and brown back and sides.
Dickcissel, Large sparrowlike bird. Breeding males have a black V on the throat, a yellow breast, and rusty shoulders.
Dickcissel, Large sparrowlike bird with a conical bill. Females have a pale yellow breast and rusty shoulders. Note pale yellow eyebrow.
Dickcissel, Named for its song: one or two sharp introductory notes followed by a fast, high warble, "dick-cissel."
Dickcissel, Chunky sparrowlike bird. Females have a pale yellow breast, rusty shoulder patches, and a pale yellow eyebrow.
Dickcissel, Immature birds have streaking on the breast and a pale yellowish eyebrow. Note heavy conical bill.
Dickcissel, Large sparrowlike bird. Breeding males have a black V on the throat, a yellow breast, and rusty shoulders.

Dickcissel, Often makes irregular movements outside of its core breeding range to surrounding areas where extensive grassland can be found. Note large size, dark streaks on upper back and yellow eyebrow.
Dickcissel, Note heavy streaks down the back, rusty shoulders, and yellow eyebrow.
Dickcissel, Large sparrowlike bird. Breeding males have a black V on the throat, a yellow breast, and rusty shoulders.
Dickcissel, Found in tall grasslands, including prairie, hayfields, lightly grazed pastures, and roadsides.
Dickcissel, Forms large flocks on the wintering grounds in open grasslands, savannas, and croplands.
Dickcissel, Large sparrowlike bird. Breeding males have a black V on the throat, a yellow breast, and rusty shoulders.

Double-crested_Cormorant, Large waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds have small tufts on the side of the head, but can be difficult to see. Note orange-yellow skin around the base of the bill and chin.

Double-crested_Cormorant, Large, gangly waterbird with a long, hooked bill. Juveniles have orange-yellow skin around the bill and a paler neck and breast. After fishing, stands on docks, rocks, and tree limbs with wings spread open to dry.
Double-crested_Cormorant, "Wing-spreading" is a technique Double-crested Cormorants use to dry their feathers after swimming, as they lack waterproof feathers.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Flies with a bend in its neck. Dark overall.

Double-crested_Cormorant, Large waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds have small tufts on the side of the head, but can be difficult to see. Birds in the north west tend to have whiter tufts. Note orange-yellow skin around the base of the bill and chin.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Individuals rest and preen in large groups on rocky or sandy islands.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Juveniles have a pale neck and breast that gradually blends into its darker belly.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Sits low in the water. Nonbreeding birds are dark overall with orange-yellow skin around the bill and chin.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Migratory flocks form over both land and water in irregular V-formations. Double-crested Cormorants constantly flap their wings and have a bulky appearance when flying.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Breeds in colonies on the coast as well as on large inland lakes. Builds stick nests high in trees or on the ground.
Double-crested_Cormorant, Dives for underwater prey such as schooling fish or aquatic invertebrates. A long, hooked bill aids in capture.
Dovekie, A small, chunky black-and-white bird. Appears rather tailless with no neck. Nonbreeding birds have a white throat and ear patch.
Dovekie, Breeds in rocky terrain along high arctic coasts. Stocky with a no-neck look and a compact bill. Black above and white below.
Dovekie, A small, chunky black-and-white bird. Appears rather tailless with no neck. Nonbreeding birds have a white throat and ear patch.
Dovekie, Short-tailed and short-necked pelagic bird. Often sits low in the water. Nonbreeding birds have a white throat and ear patch.
Dovekie, A small, chunky black-and-white bird. Appears rather tailless with no neck. Nonbreeding birds have a white throat and ear patch.
Dovekie, Flight is rapid and insectlike. Body looks like a football in flight.

Downy_Woodpecker, Small with a short bill. White below, upperparts mostly black with a white back and bold white spots in the wings. Head striped black and white, with a red nape. Note spotting on white outer tail feathers.
Downy_Woodpecker, Birds along the Pacific coast are dingy brownish-gray below.
Downy_Woodpecker, Picks and probes bark for insects and larvae.
Downy_Woodpecker, Small and short-billed. Females lack the red nape found on males.
Downy_Woodpecker, Birds along the Pacific coast are dingy brownish-gray below. Females lack the red spot on the nape.
Downy_Woodpecker, Males and females drum steadily on trees to defend their territory, attract mates, or maintain contact with their mate.
Downy_Woodpecker, Juveniles have red feathering on the cap.
Downy_Woodpecker, White outer tail feathers with some black spots.
Downy_Woodpecker, Common visitor to backyard bird feeders, especially suet feeders.
Downy_Woodpecker, Will sometimes perch on branches like a songbird, and occurs in a wide variety of wooded habitats.
Downy_Woodpecker, Nests in cavities.
Downy_Woodpecker, Males and females feed their young up to 3 weeks after they leave the nest.
Downy_Woodpecker, Found in open woodlands, especially deciduous woods, and in suburban yards, parks, and orchards.
Dunlin, Stocky, medium-sized shorebird with a long, drooping bill. Breeding adults have a distinctive black belly and a rusty mottled back. Note black legs.
Dunlin, Chunky shorebird with a short neck and a long drooping bill. Nonbreeding birds have a grayish brown hood and a brownish back.
Dunlin, During the nonbreeding season, forages in mudflats and shallow water. Probes, picks, and jabs at aquatic invertebrates often with the bill open.
Dunlin, Breeds in wet coastal tundra.
Dunlin, Medium-sized, short-necked sandpiper with a long drooping bill. Breeding birds have a black belly patch.
Dunlin, Stocky, medium-sized shorebird with a long, drooping bill. Breeding adults have a distinctive black belly and a rusty mottled back. Note black legs.
Dunlin, Stocky, short-necked shorebird. Juveniles have mottled backs and brownish faces. Black belly feathers grow in as they age.
