Dunlin, In flight, note darker line of feathers down the center of the tail and white outer tail feathers.
Dunlin, Breeding adults have a rusty mottled back. In flight, note dark stripe down the center of the tail and white outer tail feathers.
Dunlin, Winters along mudflats, estuaries, marshes, flooded fields, sandy beaches, and shores of lakes and ponds.

Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, A medium-sized flycatcher with a slim build and a large bill for its size. Breast is gray, belly is pale yellow. Note rusty highlights in wings. In northern parts of range, Dusky-capped shows less rufous in the tail compared to other Myiarchus species.

Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Large-headed flycatcher with erect posture and heavy, straight bill. Compared to other Myiarchus flycatchers, not small size overall, bulky bill, and reduced rusty color in the tail (especially in northern parts of range).
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Large-headed flycatcher with a peaky crown and long bill. Often forages within tree foliage, where it can be hard to see.
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Large-headed flycatcher with gray breast and yellow belly. Forages at many levels but often remains within tree foliage.
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Individuals from Central America have darker caps showing more contrast with the back and wings.
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Makes short flights to catch flying insects or pick prey from leaves while hovering. Flights often remain within tree foliage.

Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Large-headed flycatcher that usually shows contrast between dark crown and browner back (especially in Central and South American individuals). Note the wingbars are less distinct than on other Myiarchus species. Rufous in the tail is more common in the southern parts of the range.

Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Slim flycatcher with a large bill, gray breast, and yellow belly. Brownish wingbars can be indistinct. Note rufous highlights in primaries and secondaries. Rufous in the tail is more common in the southern parts of the range.
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Note head color is darker than the back; wingbars indistinct and brownish.
Dusky-capped_Flycatcher, Occurs along wooded canyon streams and in pine-oak woodland in the southwestern U.S. and northern Mexico. Also uses many types of tropical forests farther south in range.

Dusky_Flycatcher, A small, round-headed flycatcher with relatively short wings and a long tail. The grayish head contrasts subtly with olive back, though note that plumage color is variable. Vocalizations are extremely important in identifying Empidonax flycatchers.

Dusky_Flycatcher, The small bill, white eyering, spindly legs, and thin pale wingbars and wing edging help to identify this small flycatcher as an Empidonax. The long tail and short primary projection create a lanky look characteristic of this species. The contrast between the grayish head and olive back is also useful, as is the teardrop-shaped white eyering.
Dusky_Flycatcher, Sometimes pumps its tail during aggressive interactions. Note the short primaries and longer-tailed look.

Dusky_Flycatcher, The long-tailed appearance and "surprised" look imparted by the teardrop-shaped eyering are characteristic. Underparts coloration is often a streaky mix of olive and gray. Bill color is variable.
Dusky_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a grayish olive back and a pale grayish belly. The primary feathers are shorter than Hammond's Flycatcher, giving it a long-tailed look.
Dusky_Flycatcher, Found in willow thickets, aspen groves, and open evergreen forests.

Dusky_Flycatcher, This bird's rounded head, teardrop-shaped eyering, and combination of short wingtips and relatively long tail suggest Dusky Flycatcher. Vocalizations are extremely important when identifying Empidonax flycatchers, and some individuals cannot be identified by visual characteristics alone.

Dusky_Grouse, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long, dark tail tipped in gray. Males have a yellow eyebrow that turns red during courtship. Reddish bare neck patches are visible when displaying.
Dusky_Grouse, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long, dark tail. Females have brownish gray barred upperparts.
Dusky_Grouse, Walks along the ground thrusting its head forward with each step.

Dusky_Grouse, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long, dark tail tipped in gray. Males have a yellow eyebrow that turns red during courtship. Reddish bare neck patches are visible when displaying.

Dusky_Grouse, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long, dark tail tipped in gray. Males have a yellow eyebrow that turns red during courtship. Reddish bare neck patches are visible when displaying.
Dusky_Grouse, Chunky grouse with a small head. Males are mottled gray and brown overall with a pale gray band on the tail.
Dusky_Grouse, Males have a yellow eyebrow that turns red during courtship. Reddish bare neck patches are visible when displaying.

Dusky_Grouse, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long, dark tail tipped in gray. Males have a yellow eyebrow that turns red during courtship. Reddish bare neck patches are visible when displaying.
Dusky_Grouse, During breeding season, found in dry grasslands and shrublands as well as dry mountainous forests and subalpine habitats.
Dusky_Grouse, During the nonbreeding season, found in evergreen forests where it is mainly arboreal, walking and hoping through tree branches.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with peaked head and thin, straight bill. Breeding adult has black head and neck with golden feathers fanning out behind eye. Sides are chestnut.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with small head and thin, straight bill. Black cap extends downward into a smudge on the cheek. Grayish neck accentuates white chin patch.
Eared_Grebe, Breeding adults have a fan of golden feathers at the "ear," with a sooty body and cinnamon-red sides. Grebes have lobed rather than fully webbed feet that sit at the rear of their body.
Eared_Grebe, Small grebe with slender neck and rounded or peaked head. Immatures have brownish smudged necks.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with peaked head and thin, straight bill. Breeding adult has black head and neck with golden feathers fanning out behind eye. Sides are chestnut.

Eared_Grebe, Eared Grebes have an elaborate courtship. The dance starts with an advertising call and progresses into a series of dives, feather raising, exaggerated body positions, and "running" across the water with neck extended.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with slender bill. At distance, breeding adults can appear all dark.
Eared_Grebe, In nonbreeding plumage, note peaked or rounded head, gray wash on cheeks, and white chin. Lacks a clear dividing line between hindneck and crown.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with peaked head and thin, straight bill. Breeding adult has black head and neck with golden feathers fanning out behind eye. Sides are chestnut.
Eared_Grebe, Note very different shape compared to ducks (even small ones like the Bufflehead at left): slender neck and small head with short, thin, bill.
Eared_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with peaked head and thin, straight bill. Breeding adult has black head and neck with golden feathers fanning out behind eye. Sides are chestnut.
Eastern_Bluebird, Small thrush with a round head and big belly. Males are blue above with a rusty throat and chest.
Eastern_Bluebird, Females are grayish above with bluish wings and tail, and a subdued orange-brown breast.
Eastern_Bluebird, Typically sits on fairly low perches and scans the ground for food. Note round head and small, straight bill.
Eastern_Bluebird, Juveniles have spotting on their backs and chest with variable amounts of blue in the wings and tail.
Eastern_Bluebird, Small thrush with a round head and belly. Females are dull bluish gray above with varying amounts of blue on the wings and tail.
Eastern_Bluebird, Females are mostly brown above, but note the blue tinges to the wings and tail.
Eastern_Bluebird, Small thrush with a round head. Males are deep blue above and rusty or brick-red on the throat and breast.
Eastern_Bluebird, On males the rusty color wraps up the side of the neck.
Eastern_Bluebird, Song is a low, somewhat squeaky warbling that lasts about 2 seconds.
Eastern_Bluebird, Small thrush with a round belly and head. Females are paler than males with a rusty chest and throat that wraps up the side of the neck.
Eastern_Bluebird, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes.
Eastern_Bluebird, Often nests in nest boxes. Males may bring food items to females during courtship.
Eastern_Kingbird, Large-headed flycatcher with an upright posture and a white-tipped square tail. Blackish above (darker on the head) and white below.
Eastern_Kingbird, Sturdy flycatcher with a black head and blackish back. Note white-tipped square tail.
Eastern_Kingbird, Broad-shouldered and big-headed flycatcher with clean pattern of dark upperparts and white underparts, with white tip to tail.
Eastern_Kingbird, Perches upright on wires or exposed perches. White below and blackish above with a white-tipped tail.
Eastern_Kingbird, Blackish back combined with white-tipped tail is distinctive. Found in open areas.
Eastern_Kingbird, Breeds in open habitats such as yards, fields, pastures, grasslands, or wetlands.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Chunky, medium-sized songbird with a short tail, and a long, spear-shaped bill. Breeding birds are bright yellow below with a black V on the chest.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Chunky, flat-headed grassland bird with a long, pointed bill. Nonbreeding birds are paler yellow below.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Males sing a flutelike whistle in open areas, usually from an exposed perch.
Eastern_Meadowlark, In flight, note the conspicuous white outer tail feathers.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Sings from exposed perches, including treetops, fenceposts, and utility lines.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Forages for insects such as grasshoppers and caterpillars or seeds by probing ground with their shear-shaped bill.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Note the white mustache bordering the yellow throat—a combination that helps distinguish this species from Western Meadowlark.
Eastern_Meadowlark, The "Cuban" subspecies of Eastern Meadowlark is restricted to Cuba, where it is a year-round resident.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Heavy streaking on their backs help Eastern Meadowlarks to hide from predators when foraging or walking on the ground.
Eastern_Meadowlark, The "Cuban" subspecies is smaller than Eastern Meadowlarks found in the eastern U.S. and Canada.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Found in farm fields, grasslands, and wet fields.
Eastern_Meadowlark, Preens and stretches frequently in the morning or following incubation.
Eastern_Phoebe, Plump songbird with a large head that often looks peaked. Grayish brown above with a darker head and whitish below.
Eastern_Phoebe, Plump songbird with a large head that often looks peaked and a medium length squared tail. Grayish brown above and whitish below.
Eastern_Phoebe, Dark-headed flycatcher without distinct wingbars. Habitually pumps tail when perched.
Eastern_Phoebe, Juveniles are similar to adults, but have variable reddish-brown wingbars and a paler head.
Eastern_Phoebe, Plump songbird that often has a peaked head. Grayish brown above and whitish below with a smudgy breast.
Eastern_Phoebe, Frequently wags tail down and up when perched.
Eastern_Phoebe, Found in open woods such as yards, parks, woodlands, and woodland edges.
Eastern_Phoebe, Build nests in niches or under overhangs, where the young will be protected from the elements.

Eastern_Screech-Owl, Small, with short ear tufts and a dark bill. Gray overall, with dark vertical streaks and fine dark barring. Yellow eyes often hard to see during the day. The McCall's form in southern Texas and northern Mexico has a pale bill, and lacks a red morph.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Red morph is bright reddish brown with darker vertical streaks and some white feathering on the underparts.

Eastern_Screech-Owl, A small, large-headed owl with prominent ear tufts. Occurs in both gray and red morphs. Males and females both sing, giving a mellow tremolo (heard here) and a shrill, descending whinny.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Brown morph is grayish brown overall with dark streaks and some white feathering on the underparts. Some birds have a pale bill.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Juveniles are fluffy and gray with very fine barring throughout.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Typically sleeps during the day with feathers pressed against edge of roost hole to create excellent camouflage. Red morph is rich reddish brown with vertical streaks.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Nests in cavities, including artificial nest boxes.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Usually occurs in well-wooded habitats, and roosts in cavities.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Nests and roosts in tree cavities and nest boxes.
Eastern_Screech-Owl, Juveniles are fluffy and finely barred. They often move from nest to nearby branches before they can fly (a behavior known as "branching").
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Male has black throat, head, and upperparts. Sides are rufous; belly is white. Tail corners are white and especially visible in flight.
Eastern_Towhee, Females have brown head, throat, and back; white belly; rufous sides. In most of range, eye is dark.
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Male has black throat, head, and upperparts. Sides are rufous; belly is white. Tail corners are white and especially visible in flight.
Eastern_Towhee, Individuals in Florida and parts of Alabama through North Carolina have pale eyes instead of dark or reddish eyes.
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with long tail. Juveniles are brownish and heavily streaked from hatching into their first fall.
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Male has black throat, head, and upperparts. Sides are rufous; belly is white. Tail corners are white and especially visible in flight.
Eastern_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow typically found on the ground. Females have brown head, throat, and back; white belly; rufous sides.
Eastern_Towhee, Males sing loud, short songs, often transcribed as Drink your tea , but varying considerably.
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Male has black throat, head, and upperparts. Sides are rufous; belly is white. Tail corners are white and especially visible in flight.
Eastern_Towhee, Note white flashes in tail corners and white check mark in folded wing. In most of range, eye is dark or reddish.
Eastern_Towhee, This individual has the streaked underparts of a juvenile but is developing the black upperparts of male plumage.
Eastern_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Male has black throat, head, and upperparts. Sides are rufous; belly is white. Tail corners are white and especially visible in flight.
Eastern_Towhee, "Red-eyed" Eastern Towhees have extensive white tips to the outer tail feathers.
Eastern_Towhee, Occurs in dense shrubby habitats and forest edges. Usually forages on the ground by scratching in thick leaf litter.
Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Round-headed nightjar with a stout chest. Patterned with a complicated mottling of gray and brown, which provides good camouflage. Note gray line of feathers on the back.
Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Note blackish throat bordered by thin white collar, large eyes, small bill, and whisker-like rictal bristles around the mouth.

Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Intricately patterned in gray and brown, which provides nearly perfect camouflage on leaf litter or tree bark. Blackish throat and white bib are conspicuous on singing birds on the rare occasion when they are observed during daylight.
Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Round-headed nightjar with line of gray feathers on the back. Females have small buffy tail corners and males have large white tail corners, visible in flight.
Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Typically roosts on limbs close to ground with body parallel to branch.
Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Active during the night; typically sleeps during the day, when its camouflaged plumage can make it very hard to spot.

Eastern_Whip-poor-will, Can turn up in a variety of habitats, including dense undergrowth, during migration. Breeding habitat, however, is typically dry deciduous or mixed forest with little or no understory.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked head and two wingbars. Note long wings and tail.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, An inconspicuous flycatcher, frequently detected and identified by its namesake pee-a-wee! song.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked head and two wingbars. Note long wings and tail.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, From the front, looks like it's wearing a gray or dusky vest.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Long, thin flycatcher that perches upright in the canopy.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked head and two wingbars. Note long wings and tail.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Perches upright in the canopy where it flycatches for insects and repeatedly returns to the same or similar perch.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked head and two wingbars. Note long wings and tail.
Eastern_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked head and two wingbars. Note long wings and tail.

Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, A small, slender songbird with a long tail. Breeding males vary across the range, but all have bright yellow underparts, greenish upperparts, a yellow throat, and a black tail with white outer tail feathers. Breeding "Eastern" male has a gray crown, white line above the eye, and grayish to blackish mask.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, The mask behind the eye of breeding "Eastern" males varies from gray to blackish.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, A small, slender, terrestrial songbird. Nonbreeding/immature has paler yellow underparts than breeding male. Frequently wags long tail.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Breeding "Green-headed" male has a greenish crown, yellow stripe above the eye, and black mask through the eye.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Breeding "Manchurian" male has a slaty gray crown and black mask around the eye.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Typically forages on the ground, often in wet areas, walking and running in pursuit of insects.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Forages mostly on the ground, feeding on insects.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Some first-winter birds are gray above and white below, with a conspicuous white line above the eye.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Nonbreeding/immature birds often have a brownish crown and mask, a white or yellow-and-white throat, and a brownish wash across the breast.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Nonbreeding/immature birds have a similar pattern to breeding adults, but typically have a less distinct head pattern and are less colorful overall.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, A small, slender songbird with extensive geographic and seasonal plumage variation.

Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Identification to subspecies group can be challenging (or impossible) during the nonbreeding season, but this individual's greenish crown, yellow stripe above the eye, blackish mask, and yellow throat identify it as a "Green-headed" Eastern Yellow Wagtail.
Eastern_Yellow_Wagtail, Typically found on the ground in open habitats, often near water.

Egyptian_Goose, Uniquely marked, medium-sized waterfowl with a distinctive reddish-brown mask surrounding an orangeish eye. Underparts are light gray, while upperparts are darker grayish brown with a prominent chestnut patch near the black tail.
Egyptian_Goose, In flight, note the large white patches contrasting with otherwise black wings.

Egyptian_Goose, A distinctively patterned waterfowl species with grayish-brown underparts, darker brown upperparts, a dark mark on the breast, pink legs, a pink bill, a white wing patch, and a reddish-brown mask around the eye.
Egyptian_Goose, Found in open areas, where it feeds on agricultural crops and other plants.
Egyptian_Goose, Both adults and young birds have a pink bill and pink legs, but immatures lack the distinctive eye mask of adults.
Egyptian_Goose, Found on large ponds, lakes, reservoirs, marshes, rivers, estuaries, and other bodies of water.
Egyptian_Goose, Found near water bodies. Often occurs in family groups or flocks outside of the breeding season. Note the dark breast mark—a typical field mark on adults—on the middle individual.
Egyptian_Goose, Often found in pairs. Male is larger and brighter than female.
Egyptian_Goose, Occurs in family groups and flocks outside of the breeding season. Birds forage both on land and in shallow water by pecking and dabbling at food.
Elegant_Tern, Long, drooping orange bill and shaggy black crest around the back of the head are key features. Also note dark primaries in flight.
Elegant_Tern, Medium-sized tern with pointy wings. Long, slender yellow to reddish orange bill, appears to droop at tip. Breeding birds have a black crest that is shaggy at the rear.
Elegant_Tern, A sleek tern with a thin orange bill, shaggy black crest, and a touch of pink to the underside during the breeding season.
Elegant_Tern, Long, drooping orange bill and shaggy black crest around the back of the head are key features. Also note dark primaries in flight.
Elegant_Tern, Long, drooping orange bill and shaggy black crest around the back of the head are key features. Also note dark primaries in flight.
Elegant_Tern, While migrating or during the wintering season, Elegant Terns take rest on coastal mudflats, sandy beaches, or rocky shorelines.
Elegant_Tern, Long, orange bill droops slightly at the tip. Nonbreeding birds have a shaggy black band around the back of head.
Elegant_Tern, Long, drooping orange bill and shaggy black crest around the back of the head are key features. Also note dark primaries in flight.
Elegant_Tern, The bill on immatures is yellower than on adults. Juveniles have a shaggy black band around the back of the head and variable amounts of dark mottling on the back and wings.
Elegant_Tern, Long, drooping orange bill and shaggy black crest around the back of the head are key features. Also note dark primaries in flight.
Elegant_Tern, Congregates on rocky outcrops, beaches, or pilings in the water. Note long shaggy crest at the rear of the head on nonbreeding birds.
Elegant_Tern, Moves northward for a short period after breeding where they form large flocks.
Elegant_Trogon, Hunchbacked bird with a long, square-tipped tail. Males have a red belly, a white chest band, a dark green head, a red eyering, and a yellow bill. Undertail is finely barred.
Elegant_Trogon, Usually stays very still while foraging, perched on a limb at middle height in the understory, and scanning the surroundings with slow movements of the head.
Elegant_Trogon, Females have a gray head and chest, a white teardrop mark by the eye, and a red lower belly. Undertail is finely barred and square tipped.
Elegant_Trogon, Hunchback posture. From behind, males have a green back and a square tail. Birds north of Mexico have a coppery uppertail. Note yellow bill and red eyering.
Elegant_Trogon, Long-tailed, hunchbacked bird. Males have a brilliant red belly, a white chest band, a green head (darker around the face), a red-ringed eye, and a yellow bill.
Elegant_Trogon, Found in woodlands with oaks and sycamores near streams. Note hunchbacked posture and brilliant colors.
Elf_Owl, Tiny owl without ear tufts. Note yellow eyes with white eyebrow markings and diffuse brown-gray streaks on underparts.

Elf_Owl, Tiny, short-tailed owl that lacks ear tufts. Spotted and speckled with gray, rufous, brown, and white. Rows of white-tipped scapular and covert feathers create two white stripes on the upperparts.
Elf_Owl, Tiny owl without ear tufts; nests in abandoned woodpecker holes. Note yellow eyes and light eyebrow markings.
Elf_Owl, Tiny owl with yellow eyes and no ear tufts. Face is warm brown with white eyebrow stripes.
Elf_Owl, Individuals can range from grayish overall to warmer cinnamon or rufous. Note short tail.
Elf_Owl, Call is a series of high-pitched yapping notes, reminiscent of a puppy.
Elf_Owl, Juveniles are grayer than adults, with little buff or brown coloration. Light eyebrow stripes, yellow eyes, short tail, and small size are distinctive.
Elf_Owl, Nests in abandoned woodpecker holes in giant cactus as well as a variety of trees.
Elf_Owl, Hunts at night; eats mostly insects.
Elf_Owl, Tiny owl without ear tufts and with yellow eyes. Call is a series of high-pitched yapping notes.
Emperor_Goose, Small and stocky goose with a short pink bill, clean white head, and orange legs. Body is dark silver-gray except for white tail feathers.
Emperor_Goose, Small stocky goose with a small pink bill and orange legs. Some adults have their white heads stained orange from feeding in iron-rich substrates. Note white tail feathers.
Emperor_Goose, Small and stocky goose with a short pink bill, clean white head, and orange legs. Body is dark silver-gray except for white tail feathers.
Emperor_Goose, Small stocky goose with a short bill. Juveniles have a dark bill, gray neck, dull yellow-orange legs, and show gray mottling on the head.
Emperor_Goose, Small goose with a small pink bill, white head, and blackish neck.
Emperor_Goose, Small and stocky goose with a short pink bill, clean white head, and orange legs. Body is dark silver-gray except for white tail feathers.
Emperor_Goose, In flight, the upperwing is mostly silver and contrasts with the blackish trailing edge. Note white tail feathers bracketed by dark feathers above and below.

Emperor_Goose, Stocky goose that is similar in size to Greater White-fronted Goose (left). Body is scalloped silver and dark except for white tail feathers. Head and back of the neck are white mottled with gray—this pattern is less crisp than on an adult.
Emperor_Goose, Small and stocky goose with a short pink bill, clean white head, and orange legs. Body is dark silver-gray except for white tail feathers.

Emperor_Goose, These geese don't migrate very far away from their breeding grounds. In winter, they gather in flocks to feed in the rocky intertidal zones along Alaska's coastline in places like Kodiak Island, the Aleutian Islands, and the Alaska Peninsula.
Emperor_Goose, Immatures in their first winter look like adults but have variable dark speckling on the face and head.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Adult male is black, with a striking orange-yellow bill and eyering.

Eurasian_Blackbird, Female is dark brown overall, with some rufous tones. Pale, sometimes whitish throat is finely streaked, while browner underparts have coarser smudging. Bill ranges from dark brown to yellow.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Adult male in breeding season is all black, with a bright yellow-orange bill and eyering. Both sexes care for the nestlings—typically 3–4 chicks in a large cup nest.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Immature male is duller than adult male, with brownish wings and a darker bill.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Juvenile is similar to female, but often more rufous. Note also the buffy streaks on the upperparts.

Eurasian_Blackbird, Female is brown overall. A white throat with brown streaking gives way to darker, spotted underparts. Blackbirds frequently feed on the ground, often in search of invertebrates, but also taking advantage of fruit when available.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Male sings mellow, slow-paced song from treetops, rooftops, and other conspicuous perches.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Feeds on berries and fruits (especially in the fall), as well as earthworms, insects, and other invertebrates.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Often uses bill to flip over leaves in search of insects and other invertebrates in leaf litter.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Common in city parks and backyard gardens.
Eurasian_Blackbird, Often feeds on worms.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, A small songbird with a blue cap, white face, thin black eyeline, yellowish underparts, greenish upperparts, blue wings and tail, and short black bill.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, From behind, shows a bluish-black collar, greenish back, blue wings and tail, white wingbar, and broad white tips to folded inner wing feathers.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, A small songbird with a white face, thin black eyeline, and blue crown, wings, and tail. Underparts are yellow, divided by a vertical grayish-black line.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, Juvenile shares the same general pattern as adult but is paler yellow below, with a yellow cheek and a grayish crown.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, Note the black throat patch and blackish line running down the middle of the belly.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, Visits bird feeders, often in the company of other species like Great Tit (seen here).
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, Found in parks and gardens in urban areas, as well as deciduous woodlands, orchards, thickets, hedgerows, and other habitats.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, A social species, often seen in family groups or flocks.
Eurasian_Blue_Tit, Juvenile is paler yellow below, with a yellow cheek and a gray crown. This species is an agile forager that often hangs upside down from plants in search of insects.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and long, square-tipped tail. Upperparts mostly sandy brown with a black crescent on the back of the neck.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and thin, dark bill. Head and underparts are pale, almost frosty brown. Black collar on back of neck.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and long, square-tipped tail. Upperparts mostly sandy brown with a black crescent on the back of the neck.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with pale underparts, gray undertail coverts, and broad white band at tip of tail.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Immature is similar to adult, but lacks a complete black neck collar.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and long, square-tipped tail. Upperparts mostly sandy brown with a black crescent on the back of the neck.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, In flight, note the rounded tail with extensive white tips to the outer feathers.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Note dark primaries (wingtips). Native to Eurasia but introduced to Florida, where it spread rapidly across North America beginning in the 1990s.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and long, square-tipped tail. Upperparts mostly sandy brown with a black crescent on the back of the neck.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Often found in small groups in residential areas. Note square-tipped tail, black collar at back of neck, and plain, unmarked face.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Often seen in flocks in residential or developed areas. White band at end of tail is best seen from below.
Eurasian_Collared-Dove, Fairly large dove with small head and long, square-tipped tail. Upperparts mostly sandy brown with a black crescent on the back of the neck.

Eurasian_Jackdaw, A small crow with a pale eye and a short, slender bill partially covered with feathers. Front of head is black, contrasting with light gray back of head. Body is dark gray. Wings and tail are darker, with wings showing a purplish or bluish sheen in good light.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, Typically has a prominent light gray "half hood," but this can vary based on location, lighting, age, sex, and time of year.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, A small crow with a pale eye, black face, light gray back of the head, and charcoal upperparts.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, When seen well, underparts are dark gray, contrasting subtly with the paler gray head, black face, and blackish wings and tail.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, Immature is duller than adult, with a darker eye, a brownish tinge to some feathers, and less contrast between the back of the head and the rest of the body.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, Jackdaws may gather in large groups of thousands of birds as they go to roost in the nonbreeding season. Flocks twist and turn in unison, a bit like European Starling murmurations.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, A very social species, often gathering in flocks, including with other members of the crow, jay, and magpie family.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, An agile flyer, with flocks performing coordinated acrobatic movements.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, Typically nests in cavities, including nest boxes, chimneys, rock crevices, and used woodpecker cavities.
Eurasian_Jackdaw, Usually forages on the ground. Pairs stay close together year-round.

Eurasian_Magpie, A medium-sized songbird with a very long tail. Predominantly black plumage interrupted by a white belly and white scapulars. In good light, the wings are blue to glossy green, and the long black tail—which makes up more than half an adult's overall length—has a greenish sheen.
Eurasian_Magpie, In flight, note the large white patches in the short, rounded wings.
Eurasian_Magpie, A striking black-and-white bird with iridescent blue and green highlights and a very long tail.
Eurasian_Magpie, Juvenile is duller than adult, with some bare skin around the eye.
Eurasian_Magpie, Often found in family groups or other small groups around farms and open country.
Eurasian_Magpie, Primarily feeds on the ground, consuming insects, carrion, and other foods. Often walks or hops while foraging. Note the prominent white patches when the birds open their wings.
Eurasian_Magpie, Plucks ticks and other parasites from cattle and sheep.
Eurasian_Magpie, Calls loudly in response to cats and other predators.
Eurasian_Magpie, Opportunistic feeders that readily consume carrion when it is available. Often seen in family groups or other small groups.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, White cheek with black ear patch is distinctive. Small population introduced from Europe now breeds in a small part of the midwestern U.S.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Chunky sparrow with a chestnut crown, black throat, and black ear patch.
Eurasian_Tree_Sparrow, Found in large groups except during breeding season.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Round-headed duck with a short, blue-gray bill with a black tip. Females have a mostly brown to gray-brown body, with a white belly that is visible in flight.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Short neck and round headed with a fairly short, black-tipped bill. Note chestnut head and large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Mostly brown to reddish-brown, often mottled along flanks. Usually shows white wing stripe, but lacks black tail and undertail coverts.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wigeon, Adult males have a chestnut head with a buffy crown that contrasts with a mostly gray body. Note large white patch in the wing.
Eurasian_Wren, A small brown bird with a short tail, white line behind the eye, and barring on the wings, tail, and flanks.
Eurasian_Wren, Coloration, size, and barring on the underparts vary across range. Birds in the Himalayas are darker than those found across much of mainland Europe.
Eurasian_Wren, A tiny bird with a big voice. Males sing a loud, fast-paced song with a mix of warbling notes and rapid trills, usually lasting 4–6 seconds.
Eurasian_Wren, An energetic species, seen probing for food, flicking wings, bobbing up and down, and frequently raising tail.
Eurasian_Wren, A small bird with a round body, thin bill, and short tail.
Eurasian_Wren, Typically forages on or near the ground, feeding mainly on insects and other invertebrates.
Eurasian_Wren, Male sings loud, long, complex songs much of the year. Female sings whisper songs when incubating or caring for young.
Eurasian_Wren, A vocal species often detected by loud songs (males) or noisy, chattering calls (both sexes).
Eurasian_Wren, A small, active bird. Frequently cocks tail and bobs entire body up and down.
Eurasian_Wren, Frequently holds short, stubby tail upright.
Eurasian_Wren, Typically forages on or near the ground.
Eurasian_Wren, Often takes cover low in shrubby areas, bushes, hedgerows, overturned trees, and brush piles.
Eurasian_Wren, Sometimes perches prominently, especially when singing.

European_Goldfinch, A small finch with a long, pointed bill; black wings; large yellow wing patch; and strongly notched black tail. Adult has a striking red, white, and black head; tan upperparts; mostly white underparts; and a light brown wash across the breast.
European_Goldfinch, Juvenile is duller than adult, with a plain brownish-gray head, streaked brownish upperparts, and finely streaked underparts.
European_Goldfinch, A small finch with a long, pointed bill. Adult has a showy red, white, and black head; light brown across the breast and on the back; and black wings with a bold yellow patch.
European_Goldfinch, Adult has brown upperparts, a bright yellow patch on black wings, a white rump; and a strongly notched black tail with white spots near the tip.
European_Goldfinch, During the breeding season, occurs in open woodlands, forest edges, orchards, parks, gardens, and other habitats with scattered trees and shrubs.

European_Goldfinch, Adults eat mainly seeds, using their long, pointed bill to extract seeds from thistles, teasels, burdocks, and other plants. Note the prominent yellow wing stripe when bird takes flight (at end of video).
European_Goldfinch, Often gathers in large flocks during the winter. In flight, note the black wings and bold yellow wing stripe.
European_Goldfinch, Both sexes sing a lively song of tinkling notes, trills, and buzzes.
European_Goldfinch, Juvenile shares adult's black wings and yellow wing patch, but is otherwise duller, with streaky brown head, breast, and upperparts.
European_Robin, A small, plump songbird with an orange breast and face, a whitish belly, and brownish upperparts. Stands upright on long legs.
European_Robin, Often forages on the ground.
European_Robin, A small songbird with an orange face and breast, gray sides, white belly, and olive-brown upperparts.
European_Robin, A narrow band of gray feathers separates the orange-red face and breast from the olive-brown upperparts.
European_Robin, Juvenile lacks adult's bright colors and crisp pattern. It has fine buffy streaks on its upperparts and head and has a mottled look below.
European_Robin, Feeds mainly on ants, beetles, and other invertebrates found on the ground.
European_Robin, Perches unobtrusively in thickets, hedgerows, and forest undergrowth.
European_Robin, Forages with quick hops followed by pauses to scan for, or pick at, invertebrates on the ground.

European_Starling, Chunky dark bird with a finely pointed bill. Nonbreeding birds have spots on their back and underparts. The bill is dark in winter, but begins to turn yellow as breeding season approaches.
European_Starling, Makes a bewildering variety of sounds, from thin whistles to rattles to imitations of birds, including Red-tailed Hawks, American Robins, and many others.
European_Starling, Juveniles are pale brown overall with a dark bill. Adult feathers with white tips are growing in on the flanks of this individual.
European_Starling, Juveniles are pale brown overall.
European_Starling, Walks quickly, in hunched posture with head down, as it forages on lawns and grassy areas.

European_Starling, Native to Europe, but introduced into New York's Central Park in the late 1890s, European Starling is one of North America's most common birds, with an estimated 200 million individuals.

European_Starling, New feathers grown in the fall have bold white tips, giving birds a spotted appearance. By spring, these tips have worn away, and the rest of the feather is dark and iridescent brown.

European_Starling, Forms very large flocks in winter, sometimes with other species including blackbirds, grackles, and cowbirds. Note spotted plumage and blackish bills, characteristic of fresh winter plumage.

European_Starling, Nests in holes in trees, birdhouses, or other artificial structures with holes or crevices. Nonbreeding adults are spotted above and below. The bill color changes from black to yellow and the spots are lost as the breeding season nears.
European_Starling, Forms large flocks coordinating their movements with the flockmates nearest them, in a giant cloud called a murmuration.
European_Starling, Gathers in large, noisy flocks during nonbreeding season, sometimes with blackbirds, grackles, and cowbirds.
Evening_Grosbeak, Large, heavyset finch with a very thick, conical bill. Adult males are yellow and black birds with a prominent white patch in the wings. Note bright-yellow stripe over the eye.
Evening_Grosbeak, Large and stocky finch with an enormous bill. Females/immatures are mostly gray, with white-and-black wings and a greenish-yellow tinge to the neck and flanks.

Evening_Grosbeak, Large, heavyset finches with very thick, powerful bills. Adult males are yellow and black with a prominent white patch in the wings. Females are mostly gray, with white-and-black wings and a greenish-yellow tinge to the neck and flanks.
Evening_Grosbeak, Heavy-bodied finch with a hefty bill. Adult males are mustard yellow below with a brighter yellow eyebrow.
Evening_Grosbeak, Females/immatures are grayish overall with a yellow wash on the neck. Note black-and-white wings with a white rectangular patch.
Evening_Grosbeak, Flashy white wing patches help make it conspicuous in foliage. Also note hefty pale bill and yellow eyebrow.
Evening_Grosbeak, Uses its hefty bill to crush sunflower seeds at bird feeders.
Evening_Grosbeak, Makes very erratic movements south into the continental United States in some winters, when they can become common at backyard feeders.
Evening_Grosbeak, Often found in flocks, particularly in winter in evergreen and deciduous forests.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Usually found alone or in pairs in open-country where they often perch on power poles.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Flies on broad wings with narrow tips. From above note white streaks in primaries, pale tail, chestnut back, and big-headed look.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Flies with stiff, shallow wingbeats. Light morphs are very pale below with chestnut back and pale head.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Soars on broad wings often held in a slight dihedral with its head held down.
Ferruginous_Hawk, The rarer dark morph has a chestnut belly and inner wing linings. The tail and flight feathers are white.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Young stay in the nest for 38–50 days before fledging.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.
Ferruginous_Hawk, A small percent of the population is dark brown to chestnut above and below with a white tail. In flight, primaries and secondaries are also white. Note feathered legs.
Ferruginous_Hawk, Light morph birds are very pale below.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Often seen on the ground where it hunts gophers, ground squirrels, and rabbits in grassland, prairie, sagebrush steppe, scrubland, and pinyon-juniper woodland edges in western North America.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.

Ferruginous_Hawk, Large buteo with broad wings that are pointed at the tips. In flight the head appears rather large. Light morph birds have white belly with rusty feathered legs that form a V above the white tail.

Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Body color ranges from grayish-brown to cinnamon. Wings have large white spots. Whitish underparts have thick streaks that often merge on the sides, creating a pattern with three prominent vertical white lines.

Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Small owl with round head lacking ear tufts. Body color ranges from cinnamon to grayish-brown. Crown has fine whitish streaks. Whitish underparts have thick streaks that often merge on the sides and top of the breast.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Song is a series of monotonous tooting notes, easily imitated by whistling.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Dark facial disc is streaked with white. Whitish eyebrows vary in size. Iris is lemon yellow. Bill is greenish yellow.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Found in many habitats across its range, including Sonoran desert scrub in Arizona.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Active during the daytime and at night; most active at dawn and dusk.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Typical pygmy-owl shape—round head (without ear tufts), plump body, and long tail.
Ferruginous_Pygmy-Owl, Upperparts can vary from cinnamon to grayish-brown. Birds with cinnamon upperparts have cinnamon-and-brown barring on the tail.
Field_Sparrow, Small, slender sparrow with a pink conical bill and a rounded head. Gray-faced with a distinct white eyering and a rusty crown and eyeline.
Field_Sparrow, The pink conical bill, white eyering, and rusty crown and eyeline are distinctive field marks. Some individuals like this one have rusty-colored chests.
Field_Sparrow, Sings a loud, accelerating song from exposed perches that sounds like a bouncing ball.
Field_Sparrow, Juveniles lack the bright rusty crown and eyeline of adults, but note white eyering and pinkish bill. Juveniles also have streaking on the chest and sides.
Field_Sparrow, Gray overall with a pink conical bill, a rusty cap and eyeline, and a white eyering.
Field_Sparrow, Eats small seeds especially during the colder months when fewer insects are available.
Field_Sparrow, Round-headed sparrow with a rusty cap, pink bill, and white eyering. Note rusty streaking down the back and an unstreaked grayish belly.
Field_Sparrow, Small, slender sparrow with a pink conical bill and a rounded head. Gray-faced with a distinct white eyering and a rusty crown and eyeline.
Field_Sparrow, Juveniles have streaked breasts unlike adults, but still have a pink bill and a faint eyering.
Field_Sparrow, Small, slender sparrow with a pink conical bill and a rounded head. Gray-faced with a distinct white eyering and a rusty crown and eyeline.

Field_Sparrow, Found in areas of tall grass and brush that are growing up into small trees and shrubs, particularly thorny shrubs such as roses and briars. Sings a loud, accelerating song from exposed perches.
Fish_Crow, Entirely black bird with a heavy bill and sturdy legs. Very slightly smaller than an American Crow.
Fish_Crow, Often seen walking or skip-hopping along the ground while foraging.
Fish_Crow, When calling from the ground, it often leans forward and fluffs up its neck feathers.
Fish_Crow, Entirely black bird with a heavy bill and sturdy legs. Very slightly smaller than an American Crow.
Fish_Crow, In addition to eating fish and other plant and animal foods, they frequently raid nests, eating eggs and nestlings of colonial nesting waterbirds, terns, and gulls.
Fish_Crow, Often walks along the ground. A unique wing tag and leg bands mark this individual, which allows researchers to track and monitor its behavior.
Fish_Crow, Found along the coast and inland along major freshwater rivers and lakes. They use a wide variety of habitats often near water, including towns and cities near parks, docks, and landfills.
Fish_Crow, Often found eating food scraps at garbage or compost piles. This individual has a wing tag and leg bands to help researchers monitor its behavior.
Fish_Crow, Similar to American Crows, it flies with rowing wingbeats, but note longer tail.

Five-striped_Sparrow, A large sparrow with five alternating white and black stripes below a thick bill, and an additional white stripe over the eye. Underparts are mostly gray and white, with a large black central breast spot. Upperparts are reddish brown.

Five-striped_Sparrow, A boldly marked sparrow with a white stripe over the eye, a thin white crescent below the eye, and five white/black stripes below the bill. A white belly contrasts with gray flanks and a large black spot on the breast.

Five-striped_Sparrow, A large sparrow with five white and black stripes spanning the throat. Upperparts are rich reddish-brown and flanks are dark gray. A black breast spot and white belly are just partially visible in this video.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Rich reddish-brown upperparts contrast with dark gray flanks.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Long, heavy bill is blackish above and silvery below.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Male sings a variety of short, simple songs from perches as well as the ground.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Occurs almost entirely in northwestern Mexico, but breeds annually in very small numbers in southeastern Arizona.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Both sexes give a chatter call while foraging on or near the ground.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Typically stays close to, or on the ground, where it forages for caterpillars and other insects.
Five-striped_Sparrow, In Arizona, nesting begins with the start of summer rains.
Five-striped_Sparrow, Breeds on steep, dry hillsides with thick vegetation.

Flame-colored_Tanager, A medium-sized songbird with two strong white wingbars, a heavily streaked back, large white spots on the tips of the tertials (innermost flight feathers), a blackish ear patch, and a heavy bill. Male head and underpart color ranges from orange to red.

Flame-colored_Tanager, Female shares many field marks with adult male (white wingbars, white tertial tips, streaked back, and blackish ear patch), but is yellowish overall, with a hint of orange on the crown.

Flame-colored_Tanager, A medium-sized songbird with a heavy bill, blackish ear patch behind the eye, and two large white wingbars on dark wings. Male head and underpart color ranges from orange to bright red.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Adult males in western Mexico are consistently orange on the face and belly, while males elsewhere vary from red to orange-red.

Flame-colored_Tanager, Female and immature male are similar in appearance, with yellow underparts and head and a dark ear patch. Immature male often has some orange-red splotches on the head and underparts.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Female has yellow underparts and head, two white wingbars, and a dark ear patch behind the eye.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Visits feeding stations with fresh fruit. In natural settings, feeds mostly on insects and berries.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Adult males from eastern Mexico to Panama range in color from bright red to orange-red.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Song is a series of 2–6 burry, vireolike notes with long pauses between songs.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Typically found high in trees in mountain forests, coffee plantations, gardens, or shady pastures.
Flame-colored_Tanager, Typically occurs high in trees in mountain forest. Common call is a strong, rolled series of three notes.

Flammulated_Owl, Small owl with short, feathered ear tufts and a short tail. Ear tufts often held flat. Dark vertical stripes or dashes down belly with varying amounts of rusty feathers. Note dark eyes.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl that gives single-noted hoots that can often be difficult to locate.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl that gives single-noted hoots that can often be difficult to locate.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl that gives single-noted hoots that can often be difficult to locate.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl with short ear tufts that are often held flat. Red morph individuals have more extensive rusty plumage.

Flammulated_Owl, Small owl with a short tail, dark eyes, and small ear tufts that are often held flat. Dark vertical stripes or dashes down belly with varying amounts of rusty colored feathers. Note dark eyes.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl that gives single-noted hoots that can often be difficult to locate.
Flammulated_Owl, Small owl that gives single-noted hoots that can often be difficult to locate.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Large, long-tailed songbird with a sturdy bill. Adults have a blue head, wings, and tail and a pale gray back and belly. Note whitish forehead.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Juveniles are grayer overall than adults, lacking the adult's blue head.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, A medium-sized songbird with a heavy bill and long tail. Dull blue overall with a whitish forehead and a pale gray back and belly.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, An uncrested Jay restricted to Florida. Note whitish forehead and gray back.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Often perches in a nearly vertical position, giving it a very elongated look. Note blue necklace.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Florida Scrub-Jays form family groups that consist of a breeding pair and up to 6 nonbreeding birds.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Florida Scrub-Jays eat peanuts and can become quite tame.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, Restricted to Florida oak scrub and scrubby flatwoods found on prehistoric and current sand dunes. Found in scrub with patches of open sand and an open tree canopy.
Florida_Scrub-Jay, One individual from the family group often serves as a sentinel to keep an eye out for approaching predators.

Florida_Scrub-Jay, Florida Scrub-Jays are restricted to low-growing scrub oak in central Florida, where they are intensively studied. This individual has color bands on its legs to help researchers monitor individuals in the population.

Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Medium-sized bluish-gray storm-petrel with a forked tail (fork not always visible) and a steep forehead. Underparts are paler with darker contrasting underwings. Patters on the surface of the water to feed.
Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Medium-sized bluish-gray storm-petrel with a forked tail (fork not always visible). Note small bill, darker gray forehead, and dark ear patch.
Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Medium-sized bluish-gray storm-petrel with a forked tail (fork not always visible) and a steep forehead. Note dark ear patch and pale upper wing band.

Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Medium-sized bluish-gray storm-petrel with a forked tail (fork not always visible) and a steep forehead. Underparts are paler with darker contrasting underwings. Patters on the surface of the water to feed.

Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Medium-sized bluish-gray storm-petrel with a forked tail (fork not always visible) and a steep forehead. Underparts are paler with darker contrasting underwings. Patters on the surface of the water to feed.
Fork-tailed_Storm-Petrel, Hovers above the surface of the water while pattering its feet to feed.
Forsters_Tern, Medium-sized tern with pointed wings and a long, forked tail. Breeding adults have a black cap and a black-tipped orange bill. Note white underparts and pale primaries.
Forsters_Tern, Medium-sized tern with pointed wings and a long, forked tail. Breeding adults have a black cap and a black-tipped orange bill. Note white underparts and pale primaries.
Forsters_Tern, Short-legged tern with a thin black bill. Spends the winter in marshes, coastal beaches, lakes, and rivers.
Forsters_Tern, Nonbreeding adults have a black eyepatch, an unmarked nape, and a slender black bill.
Forsters_Tern, Immature birds are pale gray above and do not have shoulder markings. They have a black eyepatch, pale gray primaries, and a black bill.
Forsters_Tern, Juveniles are mottled rusty brown, white, and gray with a black eye patch.
Forsters_Tern, Nonbreeding adults have a black mask and entirely white underparts. The wings are silvery from below with black tips on the primaries.
Forsters_Tern, Short-legged tern with a long, forked tail that extends beyond the wings when resting. Breeding adults have a full black cap and a slender, black-tipped orange bill.
Forsters_Tern, In flight, note gray tail and pale gray primaries with black tips on nonbreeding adults.
Forsters_Tern, Medium-sized tern with pointed wings and a long, forked tail. Breeding adults have a black cap and a black-tipped orange bill. Note white underparts and pale primaries.
Forsters_Tern, Medium-sized tern with pointed wings and a long, forked tail. Breeding adults have a black cap and a black-tipped orange bill. Note white underparts and pale primaries.
Forsters_Tern, Breeds in marshes with open water and large stands of islandlike vegetation. Spends the winters in marshes, coastal beaches, lakes, and rivers.
Fox_Sparrow, Large, chunky sparrow with a rounded head and heavy bill. Plumage varies significantly across range. The "Red" subspecies group is rich reddish brown with coarse, blurry streaks below.
Fox_Sparrow, Large, chunky sparrow with rounded head. The "Sooty" subspecies group lives along the Pacific Coast. Upperparts are dark brown; face is grayish; bill is gray and yellow.
Fox_Sparrow, A large, round-bodied sparrow with a stout bill. "Red" Fox Sparrow is rusty above with some pale gray on the head and rufous splotches on the underparts.

Fox_Sparrow, Large sparrow with very thick bill. The "Thick-billed" subspecies group lives mainly in the Sierra Nevada and Cascade mountains of California and Oregon. Slate gray head and back with brown wings and tail; heavily spotted underparts.

Fox_Sparrow, Large, chunky sparrow. Head and back are gray; wings and tail are bright rufous. The "Slate-colored" subspecies group breeds in interior western North America and winters mainly along the Pacific Coast.
Fox_Sparrow, Males sing a sequence of about a dozen rich, whistled notes lasting 2–3 seconds in all. During summer they sing vigorously at any time from before dawn until after dark.
Fox_Sparrow, Juveniles are similar in plumage to adults, but generally duller overall. Large size and heavy bill are helpful in distinguishing from other sparrows.
Fox_Sparrow, Most Fox Sparrows have yellowish bills with gray tinges to the upper mandible. The "Red" subspecies group has a mostly gray face with variable reddish brown on the cheek.
Fox_Sparrow, Forages on leaf litter and bare ground, using sturdy legs to kick away leaves in search of insects and seeds.
Fox_Sparrow, Found on or near the ground in thickets, overgrown fields, spruce-tamarack bogs, woodland edges, willow and alder tangles, chaparral, manzanita, and other dense brushy areas.
Fox_Sparrow, Some "Sooty" Fox Sparrows are a more flat gray brown without the reddish tones. The heavy spots (often chevron shaped) coalesce into larger patches on the breast.
Fox_Sparrow, The "Slate-colored" subspecies group has a gray head, reddish wings and tail, and black spotting on white underparts.
Fox_Sparrow, The "Thick-billed" subspecies group has a massive bill, grayish head and back, reddish-brown wings and tail, and heavy dark spotting on white underparts.
Fox_Sparrow, Males often sing from high perches. Songs and calls vary geographically.
Franklins_Gull, Smallish gull with a black head, a red bill, and white eye crescents. Note white spots on the tips of the primaries.
Franklins_Gull, Smallish gull with a black head, a red bill, and white eye crescents. Note white spots on the tips of the primaries.
Franklins_Gull, Compared to the Laughing Gulls around it, note the Franklin's smaller size, smaller bill, and more black around the eye and over the crown.
Franklins_Gull, Smallish gull with a black head, a red bill, and white eye crescents. Note white spots on the tips of the primaries.

Franklins_Gull, First-winter birds have a partial grayish black hood and thick white eye crescents. The gray on the back contrasts with brownish upperwings and dark primaries. Note rather slender bill.
Franklins_Gull, Nonbreeding adults have a partial black hood and thick white eye crescents. The wingtips show limited black. Note slender bill and clean white collar.
Franklins_Gull, Black-hooded gull with white eye crescents and a limited amount of black on the wingtips.

Franklins_Gull, First-winter birds have a black tail band, but it doesn't extend across the entire tail. The primaries are mostly dark while the upperwings are brownish gray. Note smudgy grayish hood.
Franklins_Gull, Breeds in colonies in prairie wetlands. Fairly small gull with a slender bill. Note black head, white eye crescents, and limited black on wingtips.
Franklins_Gull, Often forages in dense flocks.

Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, The stout bill, slim neck, and huge legs and feet identify this as a whistling-duck. The blue-gray bill, legs, and feet combine with the dark back and buff-orange head and underparts to separate it from similar species.

Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, An oddly proportioned duck with a long neck, boxy head, and short tail. Cinnamon head and underparts contrast with the dark back and upperwings, with accents created by the white flank streaks and cinnamon tips on the back feathers.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Forages for seeds and aquatic invertebrates while wadding in shallow water or swimming.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, The long neck projection and large legs and feet make this recognizable as a whistling-duck. Note the entirely dark wings—above and below—and the cinnamon head and underparts.

Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, In flight, the long legs and large feet are conspicuous. The dark upperwing and pale "U" on the rump distinguish this species at great distance from other species of whistling-ducks.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Flies with neck held low. Note dark wings and white U on the tail.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Young chicks show a high contrast black-and-white pattern with an isolated dark "T" that wraps around the back of the neck onto the cheeks.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Note the cinnamon head and underparts contrasting with the dark back and upperwings. Occurs in freshwater wetlands and flooded fields.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Tips up to find seeds and other aquatic invertebrates like other dabbling ducks.

Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Long-legged, gooselike duck with a plump body and long neck. Cinnamon head and underparts marked with white lines on the flanks and grayish streaking on the neck. Note dark blue-gray bill.
Fulvous_Whistling-Duck, Forages for seeds and aquatic invertebrates in flooded areas with emergent vegetation. This video has no audio.
Gadwall, Males are intricately patterned with gray, brown, and black. Note the black rump patch.
Gadwall, Often looks square-headed with a steep forehead. Females resemble female Mallards, but with a thinner, darker bill.
Gadwall, Males are intricately patterned with gray, brown, and black. Note the black rump patch.
Gadwall, Male in flight shows a small white patch in the secondaries of the wing, reduced in the female.
Gadwall, White underwings are visible in flight.
Gadwall, Males are intricately patterned with gray, brown, and black. Note the black rump patch.
Gadwall, At close range in flight, note male's white, black, and chestnut markings on the inner wing.
Gadwall, The female is much browner than the male, with an orange rather than black bill.
Gadwall, Males are intricately patterned with gray, brown, and black. Note the black rump patch.
Gadwall, Males assume a female-like eclipse plumage in late summer and are flightless for about 3–4 weeks as they replace their flight feathers.
Gadwall, Young juveniles are fluffy, with a mostly dark body and yellowish face with dark cap and eyeline.
Gadwall, Males are intricately patterned with gray, brown, and black. Note the black rump patch.
Gadwall, Occurs in a wide variety of wetland habitats.
Gambels_Quail, Plump game bird with comma-shaped, forward-facing crest. Useful markings include creamy buff belly with black central patch, chestnut sides, and bright cinnamon-brown crown.

Gambels_Quail, Plump, short-legged game bird with short, forward-facing crest. Buffy belly and chestnut sides. Females are fairly plain gray on the head and neck, and lack the male's black belly patch.
Gambels_Quail, Adult male has gray upperparts, a rufous crown, a black face and throat, and a black topknot sticking up from the front of the head.
Gambels_Quail, Combination of cinnamon crown, buffy belly with black central patch, and chestnut sides make this species distinctive.
Gambels_Quail, Plump game bird with gray-brown head and neck, chestnut sides, and buffy belly. Usually forages on the ground, but sometimes moves into low shrubs or cacti.
Gambels_Quail, Walks along the ground, jutting its head forward, and picking at seeds and plant material on the ground. This video has no audio.
Gambels_Quail, A classic bird of the deserts of southwestern U.S. and northwestern Mexico. Usually forages on the ground, but sometimes moves into low shrubs or cacti.
Gambels_Quail, In summer, flocks or coveys usually consist of a male and female plus up to 16 offspring. Juveniles have buffy-brown heads and mottled brown and black bodies.
Gambels_Quail, Gambel's Quails walk or run along the ground in groups called coveys that can include a dozen or more birds.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan head and belly. Males have a red crown patch.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan head and belly. Females lack the red crown patch seen on males.
Gila_Woodpecker, A desert woodpecker commonly found on saguaro cactus.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan head and belly. Males have a red crown patch.
Gila_Woodpecker, Found in deserts of southwestern U.S. and western Mexico. Often eats saguaro cactus fruits. Males have a red crown patch.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan head and belly. Males have a red crown patch.
Gila_Woodpecker, Found in deserts of southwestern U.S. and western Mexico including urban areas, where it often visits feeders.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan belly and head. Males have a red crown patch that females lack. Nests in holes in cacti and desert trees.
Gila_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan head and belly. Males have a red crown patch.
Gila_Woodpecker, Nests in holes in saguaro cacti and desert trees.
Gilded_Flicker, Larger woodpecker with a tan crown, a gray face, a black oval-shaped bib, and black spots on the belly. Males have a red mustache stripe.
Gilded_Flicker, Barred black and tan above and spotted below. Females have a tan crown and gray cheek and throat.
Gilded_Flicker, Large woodpecker with a tan crown, gray face, spotted underparts, and barred upperparts. Male has a red malar stripe.
Gilded_Flicker, Larger woodpecker with an oval-shaped black bib that is often larger than the bib on Northern Flickers.
Gilded_Flicker, Yellow underwings and white rump patch are visible in flight. Note gray cheeks and throat and tan crown. Only males have a red mustache stripe.
Gilded_Flicker, Found in the Sonoran Desert in areas with dense stands of saguaro cacti. Often seen perched atop saguaro cacti.
Gilded_Flicker, Found in the Sonoran Desert in areas with dense stands of saguaro cacti where it often builds its nest.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Large white-headed gull with pale gray wingtips and pink legs. Breeding adult has entirely white head and underparts, and a red spot on the lower bill.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Large pale gray gull with gray wingtips and a heavy bill. Nonbreeding adults have variable amounts of tan smudging on the head and neck.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Large gull with heavy bill, pink legs, and pale gray wings without black in the wingtips.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Large pale gray gull with gray wingtips. Note the wide band of white across the folded wings.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, First-winter birds have a heavy black bill and pale brown wingtips that are the same color as the back and wings.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, First-winter birds are heavily mottled pale brown and white. Unlike other gulls the wingtips are pale brown. Note dark bill.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Second-winter birds are smudgy brown overall. Some like this individual have less smudging on the head. Note the pale tan wingtips.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, In flight, note the wide white trailing edge on the wings and the entirely gray wings (no black in the wingtips).
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Large white-headed gull with pale gray wingtips and pink legs. Breeding adult has entirely white head and underparts, and a red spot on the lower bill.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, First-winter birds are pale overall with uniform pale brown wings.
Glaucous-winged_Gull, Breeds on rocky islands and coastal cliffs. Forages at sea, in intertidal areas, along beaches, and at dumps.
Glaucous_Gull, Large gull with white wingtips and a hefty bill. Adults have a clean white head and pale gray back and wings.
Glaucous_Gull, Large and hefty gull with white wingtips. Nonbreeding birds have varying amounts of brown streaking on the head and neck.
Glaucous_Gull, Breeds near the coast in the Arctic, typically placing the nest in a shallow depression on a mound of grassy vegetation, or on a cliff ledge.
Glaucous_Gull, First-winter birds have a hefty bicolored bill and are heavily mottled tan and white.
Glaucous_Gull, First-winter birds have a hefty bicolored bill. Mottled in varying amounts of tan and white, paler than juveniles. Note white or mostly white wingtips.
Glaucous_Gull, Large gull with white wingtips and a hefty bill. Adults have a clean white head and pale gray back and wings.
Glaucous_Gull, First-summer birds are whitish above with white wingtips. Note bicolored bill.
Glaucous_Gull, Large gull with white wingtips and a hefty bill. Adults have a clean white head and pale gray back and wings.
Glaucous_Gull, Large gull with white wingtips and a hefty bill. Adults have a clean white head and pale gray back and wings.
Glaucous_Gull, Large gull with white wingtips and a hefty bill. Adults have a clean white head and pale gray back and wings.
Glaucous_Gull, Young gulls can be heavily mottled tan and white or appear mostly white. White wingtips and hefty bicolored bill are the key field marks.
Glaucous_Gull, This individual has extensive tan and white mottling below, but it still has white wingtips and a hefty bicolored bill.
Glossy_Ibis, Forages in shallow marshes by probing into the mud with its curved bill to catch aquatic invertebrates.
Glossy_Ibis, Juveniles are duller brown overall with some white streaking on the neck. Note dark underparts.

Glossy_Ibis, Flies with neck outstretched and legs trailing behind. Wings, lower back, and tail are metallic shades of green, rust, and purple, but it often appears all dark, especially at a distance.
Glossy_Ibis, Flies with neck outstretched, sometimes drooping slightly. Juveniles are all dark below.

Glossy_Ibis, Large, long-legged wading bird with a football-shaped body and a long curved bill. Adults are rich chestnut with metallic green wings. Breeding birds have dark facial skin with pale lines extending from the bill to the eye, but not around the eye.

Glossy_Ibis, Large wading bird with a rich chestnut-colored body. The other 3 birds are White-faced Ibis—note they have white going all the way around the eye, bare pink facial skin, and reddish legs.
Glossy_Ibis, Found in freshwater marshes, saltmarshes, mudflats, mangroves, and flooded fields.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Males have a bright yellow face with a black eyeline and a black throat. Underparts, including the tail are white.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Females look similar to males, but are often paler with only a few black feathers on the throat. Note 2 white wingbars and black streaking on the flanks.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Males have a bright yellow face with a black eyeline and a black throat. Underparts, including the tail are white.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, The yellow face, black eyeline, and black throat on males is distinctive.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, From above females are grayish olive with faint streaking down the back. The 2 white wingbars contrast with the gray wings.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Males have a bright yellow face with a black eyeline and a black throat. Underparts, including the tail are white.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Breeds in juniper-oak woodlands of central Texas.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Males have a bright yellow face with a black eyeline and a black throat. Underparts, including the tail are white.
Golden-cheeked_Warbler, Males have a bright yellow face with a black eyeline and a black throat. Underparts, including the tail are white.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny songbird with a rounded body, short wings, and a skinny tail. Adult males have a black-and-white striped face and bright yellow and orange crown patch.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Adult females have an all-yellow crown patch, lacking the orange found in males.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny songbird with nervous, twitchy foraging style, given to hanging acrobatically from thin branches and twigs.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny songbird with a small bill. Adult males flash their orange crown when excited; otherwise it is usually concealed.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Juveniles look like messy adults without the head stripes and crown colors.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Call is a very high, thin series of whistles, usually given three at a time.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny with a small bill and skinny tail. Olive above with yellow edges on the wings and tail. Adult males usually conceal their orange crown.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny with a round belly. Grayish white below and olive above with a black-and-white striped face and yellow crown. Note black legs and yellow feet.
Golden-crowned_Kinglet, Found primarily in evergreen forests, often in the canopy.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and fairly small, grayish bill. Distinctive gray face with black cap and yellow crown patch.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with long tail and grayish bill. In nonbreeding plumage, breast is mottled gray-brown, and yellow crown stripe is smaller and duller.

Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Song consists of several clear whistles that slide downward in a melancholy-sounding phrase that's sometimes described as "I'm so tired" or "oh, dear me." Sometimes adds a trill to the end.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with long tail. Immatures have broad rusty stripes on the cap with a yellowish stripe in the middle of the crown.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with grayish bill. Back is brown streaked with blackish. Bold black stripes on the side of the crown, with yellow stripe confined to the top of the head.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and fairly small, grayish bill. Distinctive gray face with black cap and yellow crown patch.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and fairly small, grayish bill. Distinctive gray face with black cap and yellow crown patch.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and fairly small, grayish bill. Distinctive gray face with black cap and yellow crown patch.
Golden-crowned_Sparrow, Breeds among dense shrubs at edge of tundra and forest, or at treeline. Winters in shrubby thickets, chaparral, parks, gardens, and other open areas.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan breast. Males have a yellow spot in front of the eyes, a red crown, and a yellow-orange nape.

Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Barred black-and-white woodpecker with a tan breast. The lower belly is yellow on northern birds, including the ones that occur in the United States. Females have a yellow patch in front of the eye and a yellow nape.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Both sexes care for the young. Here, the female brings a moth and waits for the male to leave before entering the nest hole.

Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Nape color varies across its range from yellow-orange in the north, to red in Yucatán, to orange from Chiapas, Mexico, to Honduras. The lower belly color varies across the range; birds in the Yucatán have red lower bellies.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Individuals in the Yucatán have red napes and red lower bellies.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Eats cactus fruits as well as fruit at bird feeders.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Shows white rump, pale back, and white spots in wings.
Golden-fronted_Woodpecker, Found in open to semiopen woodlands, second-growth forests, and brushlands.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Golden-winged Warblers are slim, silvery gray birds with golden flashes on the head and wings. Males have a black throat and mask with 2 white facial stripes.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Slim warbler with thin, sharply pointed bill. Females have a greenish yellow crown, a dusky gray throat and cheek, and golden wing patch.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Typical song starts with a long, buzzy note followed by 3–6 shorter, lower notes.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Small warbler. Males have a yellow crown, a black throat, and ear patch, 2 white facial stripes, and golden wing patch. Outer tail feathers flash white in flight.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Females lack the male's black mask and bib.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Golden-winged Warblers are slim, silvery gray birds with golden flashes on the head and wings. Males have a black throat and mask with 2 white facial stripes.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Females have a grayish throat and mask and a yellow crown.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Golden-winged Warblers are slim, silvery gray birds with golden flashes on the head and wings. Males have a black throat and mask with 2 white facial stripes.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Golden-winged Warblers are slim, silvery gray birds with golden flashes on the head and wings. Males have a black throat and mask with 2 white facial stripes.
Golden-winged_Warbler, Golden-winged Warblers are slim, silvery gray birds with golden flashes on the head and wings. Males have a black throat and mask with 2 white facial stripes.
Golden_Eagle, Very large with long wings. All dark brown, with slightly paler flight feathers. Golden nape can be seen from some angles.
Golden_Eagle, Very large with long wings. All dark brown, with white patches at the base of the primaries in the wing, and at the base of the tail. Golden nape can be seen from some angles.
Golden_Eagle, Builds large stick nests, often on cliff faces. Note golden feathers on nape (back of the neck)—usually present on immatures through adults.
