Golden_Eagle, Juvenile is dark brown overall, with a golden head and nape, white base to the tail, and white wing patches (but these patches are often absent from the upperwing and sometimes missing from the underwing).
Golden_Eagle, Very large with strongly hooked bill. All dark brown, with contrasting golden-brown nape.

Golden_Eagle, Large, bulky eagle with strongly hooked bill. In addition to hunting, often eats roadkill or other carrion, and may be found near road edges. Immatures have white patches at the bases of the primaries.
Golden_Eagle, Very large with strongly hooked bill. All dark brown, with contrasting golden-brown nape. Immatures have a white base to the tail, visible from some angles.
Golden_Eagle, Shows a golden nape in all plumages.

Golden_Eagle, Soars with wings slightly raised in a V, or dihedral. In silhouette, typically shows a small head and long tail. The broad wings narrow in sharply at the body. Golden nape feathers are often surprisingly visible from distance.
Golden_Eagle, Often occurs in open habitats with mountains or rolling hills.
Golden_Eagle, Juvenile has a golden head and nape and a dark brown body.
Golden_Eagle, Young chicks are white and downy until they grow their first brown body and flight feathers. The large stick nests are often placed on cliff ledges and used year after year.

Golden_Eagle, Very large with long wings. All dark brown, with white patches at the base of the primaries in the wing, and at the base of the tail. Golden nape can be seen from some angles. (Golden Eagle at right; Bald Eagle at left.)
Golden_Eagle, Constructs large stick nests, usually in large trees.
Golden_Eagle, Occurs in a wide variety of habitats, usually in fairly open areas and/or near large cliffs.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Small warbler with gray upperparts, a yellow throat, and a yellow eyebrow. Note white wing bars and white outer tail feathers visible in flight.
Graces_Warbler, Females are paler overall than males, but share the same features: gray back, 2 white wingbars, yellow eyebrow, and yellow throat.
Graces_Warbler, Breeds in pine forests in the West. Gray above with a yellow eyebrow and throat. Tail flashes white in flight.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a deep bill. Unstreaked and buffy below with rusty spotting or streaking on the back. Note orange-yellow stripe in front of the eye.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Flat-headed, short-tailed sparrow. Note unstreaked buffy belly and orange-yellow spot in front of the eye. Yellow feather edges at the shoulder are not often visible
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Song is two short notes followed by a high, thin, insectlike trill.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a deep bill. Unstreaked and buffy below with rusty spotting or streaking on the back. Note orange-yellow stripe in front of the eye.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Note distinctive shape, with large bill, flat head, and thick neck.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a deep bill, unstreaked buffy breast, white eyering, and an orange-yellow mark in front of the eye.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a pale central crown stripe bordered by 2 dark stripes.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Usually shows orange-yellow on the lores—the area between the bill and the eye.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with rusty streaks or spots on the back, a thin white eyering and an orange-yellow spot in front of the eye.
Grasshopper_Sparrow, Main call is a very high, thin seep.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Medium-sized plump thrush without a prominent eyering. The face is grayish and lacks any buffy color. The underparts are whitish with grayer flanks.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Round-headed thrush that lacks an eyering. The face is grayish and lacks any hint of buff color, although the breast is often washed in buff.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Forages quietly on forest floor or low in understory. Breeds in far northern North America; typically seen by  most birders only in migration.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush. Intensity of spotting on the breast varies among individuals. Note grayish face without any buffy color or eyering.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Medium-sized plump thrush without a prominent eyering. The face is grayish and lacks any buffy color. The underparts are whitish with grayer flanks.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Medium-sized plump thrush without a prominent eyering. The face is grayish and lacks any buffy color. The underparts are whitish with grayer flanks.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Plump thrush with a cold gray face that often appears slightly streaky. No eyering.
Gray-cheeked_Thrush, Medium-sized plump thrush without a prominent eyering. The face is grayish and lacks any buffy color. The underparts are whitish with grayer flanks.

Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized, chunky finch. The "Hepburn's" form breeds along the Pacific Northwest coast and has gray cheeks, a blackish throat, and a rich brown body with rosy highlights on the wings and belly.

Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, A chunky brownish finch with pink highlights and a gray crown. The "Gray-crowned" form of interior North America has brown cheeks. The bill is yellow during the winter and black during the breeding season.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Breeds in alpine environments near snowline. Nest is made of moss, lichen, plant fibers, and animal hair and hidden in a rocky crevice.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Individuals on the Pribilof Islands are larger than other forms and they have a darker throat and chest.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Juveniles are brown overall, lacking the gray crown and pink highlights.

Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Medium-sized, chunky finch. The "Hepburn's" form breeds along the Pacific Northwest coast and has gray cheeks, a blackish throat, and a rich brown body with rosy highlights on the wings and belly.

Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Chunky brown finch with pink highlights on the wings and belly. Birds of interior North America have brown cheeks. The bill is yellow during the nonbreeding season and black during the breeding season.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Size and plumage varies regionally. Individuals breeding along the coasts of Alaska, Canada, and the Pacific Northwest have gray cheeks and a richer brown belly.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Forms large nomadic flocks during the nonbreeding season in open areas, including mountain meadows, shrublands, roadsides, cultivated areas, and rocky hillsides.
Gray-crowned_Rosy-Finch, Breeds in alpine areas, usually near snowfields, glaciers, talus, rockpiles, and cliffs.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, A medium-sized chickadee with a brown cap, extensive white cheeks, light brown back, black throat bib, and, in winter, rich rusty brown flanks.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, A fluffy chickadee, well-suited for northern environments. The black throat bib flares outward at the lower end, with a ragged edge.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, A large-headed, long-tailed chickadee with a brown head, lighter brown back, white cheeks, and rusty flanks.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, Frequently resides in spruce, pine, and larch forests.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, Also occurs in deciduous and mixed forests and woodlands.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, Feeds on insects and seeds. Opens seeds by holding under one foot and hammering with its bill.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, A fluffy, large-headed chickadee with a long tail.
Gray-headed_Chickadee, May visit bird feeders during the winter.
Gray-headed_Swamphen, Large, colorful rail with heavy red bill. Note orange-red legs and red forehead shield.
Gray-headed_Swamphen, Large, colorful rail with long, orange-red legs and heavy red bill and forehead shield.
Gray-headed_Swamphen, Juveniles are darker overall with a thick dark bill and dull legs.
Gray-headed_Swamphen, The brilliant blue and purple colors can appear dull or dark in some lighting conditions or at distance. Note the large size, red forehead shield and red-orange legs.

Gray-headed_Swamphen, Large rail native to southern Asia, introduced to Florida. Lives in freshwater marshes, sawgrass, and ponds and puddles in developed areas such as golf courses, ditches, and water conservation areas.
Gray_Catbird, Medium-sized thrushlike songbird with a long tail. Gray overall with a darker cap and cinnamon undertail coverts.
Gray_Catbird, Often perches holding its tail down giving it a hunchbacked look. Mimics the songs of other birds and sings at all hours of the day.
Gray_Catbird, Sings a collection of gurgles, whistles, and parts of other birds songs from the tops of trees and bushes. Often holds its tail down while perched, giving it a humpbacked look.
Gray_Catbird, A distinctive species and the only member of its genus ( Dumetella ).
Gray_Catbird, Long-tailed thrushlike bird. Gray overall with a darker cap and cinnamon under the tail.
Gray_Catbird, Forages on the ground as well as trees and shrubs where it searches for a variety of insects and fruits.
Gray_Catbird, Often secretive, but can be bold at times.
Gray_Catbird, Found in dense shrubs, vine tangles, and thickets of young trees in both summer and winter.
Gray_Catbird, Uses its bill to move leaves and twigs out of the way to uncover insects. Forages on the ground or in trees and shrubs, often in dense cover.
Gray_Catbird, Catbirds build a bulky cup nest with grasses, twigs, and bark often hidden at the center of dense shrubs, small trees, or vines.
Gray_Flycatcher, Slim pale flycatcher. Drab gray overall with a thin eyering, a pale mark in front of the eye, and pale wingbars. The bill is long and thin.
Gray_Flycatcher, Small gray flycatcher with a thin bill, a thin white eyering, and paler gray wingbars.

Gray_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with a fairly long bill (compared to other Empidonax ), a thin eyering, and darker wings with two grayish wingbars. The bill is mostly pinkish or yellowish below, usually with a blackish tip. Habitually dips its tail downward.
Gray_Flycatcher, Slim pale flycatcher. Drab gray overall with a thin eyering, a pale mark in front of the eye, and pale wingbars. The bill is long and thin.
Gray_Flycatcher, Slim pale flycatcher. Drab gray overall with a thin eyering, a pale mark in front of the eye, and pale wingbars. The bill is long and thin.
Gray_Flycatcher, Characteristically twitches its tail up and down while perched.
Gray_Flycatcher, Breeds in dry woodlands and shrublands in western North America, including sagebrush and pinyon pine woodlands.
Gray_Flycatcher, Generally grayer than other Empidonax flycatchers, but best recognized by habit of twitching its tail downward while perched.
Gray_Hawk, A medium-sized hawk with short, rounded wings and a fairly long black-and-white banded tail. Adults are pale gray below with a finely barred chest.
Gray_Hawk, Often fans tail in flight. Juveniles are pale below with finely barred tail and darker blotches on the belly.
Gray_Hawk, A fairly long-legged and long-tailed hawk that usually hunts from a perch in the understory, looking for reptiles and other small animals to pounce on.
Gray_Hawk, Adults have a light gray head, a darker gray back, barred underparts, and a barred black-and-white tail.
Gray_Hawk, Often perch in trees to scan for reptiles, which they catch with sudden, short flights to the ground or nearby tree trunks.
Gray_Hawk, Builds stick nests in upper half of trees including cottonwood, willow, and oak, usually along streams.
Gray_Hawk, Juveniles are brown above and spotted in brown below. They have a long tail banded in black and brown and a white cheek bordered by 2 brown streaks.
Gray_Hawk, Occur in thorn-scrub woodlands, savannas, and forest edges in their limited U.S. range.

Gray_Heron, A large, gray heron with a heavy, daggerlike bill. Adult has a broad black stripe above and behind each eye, a white central crown stripe and white face, black shoulder patches, dark gray upperparts (with lighter gray plumes in breeding season), and a grayish-white neck with black streaks down the middle. The bill is orange in full breeding plumage.

Gray_Heron, Juvenile is duller overall, with a muted head pattern that lacks the crisp black-and-white stripes of an adult. The neck is the same  light gray as the back and wings. Juvenile lacks plumes and has duller bill and legs than adult.

Gray_Heron, A large, long-necked heron found in lakes, ponds, and other wetlands. Adult in breeding plumage has gray upperparts (with lighter gray plumes), a grayish-white neck with black streaks down the front, a white face and crown stripe, a broad black stripe above and behind each eye, and a long black plume extending from the back of the head.

Gray_Heron, Gray Herons fly with the neck tucked in, creating a bulge below the back of the head. In flight, note the two-toned upperwing pattern: black flight feathers and gray inner coverts, with a small white patch at the bend of the wing.
Gray_Heron, Underwings appear more uniformly dark gray. During peak breeding season, both the bill and legs can become bright orange-red.

Gray_Heron, Immature is duller overall and lacks the crisp white-and-black facial patterning of an adult. This heron eats mostly fish, which it catches by standing motionless—or in this case, walking slowly in shallow water—before quickly striking.
Gray_Heron, The rare "Mauritanian" Gray Heron is much paler than the common, widespread "Gray" Gray Heron.
Gray_Heron, The "Madagascar" Gray Heron is typically larger than "Gray" Gray Heron, with a larger bill and longer legs.
Gray_Heron, Performs treetop courtship displays that include elaborate stretches, erected plumes, calls, and bill snaps.
Gray_Heron, Forages in a wide variety of shallow wetlands, including lake shores, marshes, ricefields, and fishponds.
Gray_Heron, Female builds stick nest from materials delivered by male. Nests are high up in treetops and often reused from year to year.
Gray_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with heavy bill. Gray above, white below, with brown wings and tail. Often shows dark mask through eye and onto cheek.
Gray_Kingbird, Large gray-brown flycatcher with big head and heavy bill, giving a bull-headed look. Tail often appears notched and does not show white at the tip.
Gray_Kingbird, Sits on exposed perches in open and semiopen habitats, often around humans. With small movements of the head, scans for flying insects and then flies out after them in pursuit.

Gray_Kingbird, Color pattern is distinctive: uniform gray upperparts, with dark mask through eye, and white underparts. Note heavy bill, even compared with other kingbirds. Tail lacks white edges and tip.
Gray_Kingbird, Juveniles often have cinnamon to brownish margins on the wing coverts and uppertail coverts.
Gray_Kingbird, Juveniles have cinnamon to brownish margins on the wing coverts and uppertail coverts. Note also the yellowish gape at the base of the bill on this recently fledged individual.

Gray_Kingbird, Pursues flying insects on long aerial chases. In flight, note white underparts, gray upperparts, and relatively short tail lacking both white outer tail feathers and white terminal band.
Gray_Kingbird, Eats mostly flying insects, often caught on long aerial chases. Fairly conspicuous in open and semiopen coastal areas, mangroves, and towns.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with a tan to orange face and rusty stripes down its sides. Note the darker rusty patch on the breast (larger on males).

Gray_Partridge, A plump chickenlike bird with a rotund body, small head, and short tail. Adult has an orange face, gray breast, rusty stripes on the sides, and a white belly with a chestnut brown patch (smaller or absent on female).
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides. Males tend to have a larger rusty patch on the belly.
Gray_Partridge, Plump chickenlike game bird. Gray above with an orange face and rusty stripes down its sides.
Gray_Partridge, Found in fields and grasslands.
Gray_Vireo, Small, stocky songbird with a round head. Plain gray overall with a paler belly. Note thin white eyering and small white line in front of the eye.
Gray_Vireo, Round-headed, drab gray vireo with a thin white eyering. Often flicks its tail side to side and is more active than other vireos.
Gray_Vireo, Song is a halting series of 2- and 3-note phrases with a burry quality.
Gray_Vireo, Small, stocky songbird with a round head. Plain gray overall with a paler belly. Note thin white eyering and small white line in front of the eye.
Gray_Vireo, Juveniles are washed brown with a more distinct wingbar than adults. Note white eyering.
Gray_Vireo, Small, stocky songbird with a round head. Plain gray overall with a paler belly. Note thin white eyering and small white line in front of the eye.
Gray_Vireo, Small, stocky songbird with a round head. Plain gray overall with a paler belly. Note thin white eyering and small white line in front of the eye.

Graylag_Goose, A large goose with a light grayish-brown head, neck, breast, and belly; dark brown upperparts; a white tail with a dark band; and pinkish legs. Birds breeding in western Europe (Graylag Goose (European)) have an orangish bill.
Graylag_Goose, Birds breeding from eastern Europe to East Asia (Graylag Goose (Siberian)) are slightly larger and lighter and have pink bills.
Graylag_Goose, In flight, note the strongly contrasting light-dark pattern of the underwings. Some birds show black speckling on the belly, but not as much as in Greater White-fronted Goose.
Graylag_Goose, In flight, note the extensive pale gray patches on the wings, gray rump, and white tail with broad dark band.
Graylag_Goose, The Graylag Goose's combination of very pale upperwing patches plus strongly contrasting underwing pattern is distinctive among the six species of European "gray geese."
Graylag_Goose, Breeds in lakes and wetlands.
Graylag_Goose, Forms large flocks and grazes in grasslands and agricultural fields.
Graylag_Goose, Forages on aquatic vegetation in large wetlands.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Long-legged, slender blackbird with a long V-shaped tail, a flat-headed profile, and a stout bill. Males are iridescent black with piercing yellow eyes.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Long-legged, slender blackbird, with a flat-headed profile. Females are dark brown above, paler below, with a buff-colored throat and stripe above the eye.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Long-legged, slender blackbird with a long V-shaped tail, a flat-headed profile, and a stout bill. Males are iridescent black with piercing yellow eyes.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Adult males have a long V-shaped tail with an iridescent bluish purple body.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Females are dark brown above, paler below, with a buff-colored throat and stripe above the eye.

Great-tailed_Grackle, Loud and social bird. Males defend their territories and threaten rival males by ruffling up their feathers, spreading their tail, and pointing their bill skyward while shrieking.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Loud, social birds that can form flocks numbering in the tens of thousands. Males often display with bills pointed skyward.
Great-tailed_Grackle, Found in agricultural fields, feedlots, suburbs, golf courses, cemeteries, parks, and neighborhood lawns.

Great_Black-backed_Gull, Large stout-bodied gull, with broad wings, a thick neck, and a heavy, slightly bulbous bill. Breeding adults are dark gray, nearly black above with a white head and underparts. Note pink legs.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Hefty gull with a thick bill and a dark back. Breeding adults have a red spot on the lower bill and a red ring around the eye.

Great_Black-backed_Gull, Very large gull with thick, heavy bill. Adults have dark blackish back and wings; juveniles have a frosty tone and are larger than other gulls, such as the immature American Herring Gull at right.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, First-winter birds have a checkered back and diffuse streaking on the neck and breast. Note their large size, stout bicolored bill, and pink legs.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Large, heavy-bodied gull with a stout bill and pink legs. The back and wings on first-winter birds are checkered in tans, grays, and white.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Second-summer gulls have a checkered back and diffuse streaking on the neck and breast. Note the stout bill that is pink at the base with a tiny bit of pink on the tip.

Great_Black-backed_Gull, Some second-winter birds start to acquire the dark gray color, but still have checkered backs. Note the stout bill that is pink at the base with a tiny bit of pink on the tip.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Their large size and stout bill help separate them from other gulls; note also the bill that is pink at the base and tip.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Large, dark gray gull. In flight note the larger white spot at the tip of the primaries.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, In flight, note checkered back and wings and white rump with a black tail band.
Great_Black-backed_Gull, Found mainly around saltwater, but also in some freshwater locales, usually in groups with other gulls.
Great_Blue_Heron, Very large and tall, with a long neck. Grayish-blue overall with long orangish-yellow bill and black crown and head plumes.
Great_Blue_Heron, Very large and tall, with a long neck. Grayish-blue overall with pale belly, dark streaking on the neck, and brownish feathers mixed throughout. Bill long and dusky colored.
Great_Blue_Heron, Often nests in colonies with other species of wading birds. Within colonies, territorial display includes ruffling the long breeding plumes and pointing the head and bill skyward.
Great_Blue_Heron, In flight shows black flight feathers contrasting with powdery-blue plumage. Usually flights with neck in, but sometimes outstretched.
Great_Blue_Heron, Very large and tall, with a long neck. White form is all white with long yellow bill and dull yellowish legs.
Great_Blue_Heron, Stalks prey by wading in shallow water, using daggerlike bill to spear or seize fish and other small animals.
Great_Blue_Heron, Very large and tall, with a long neck. Body powdery-blue with white head, and orangish-yellow bill and legs.
Great_Blue_Heron, When breeding has dense, shaggy plumes on the back and neck.
Great_Blue_Heron, Heavy flight with very slow beats of the very broad wings. Usually flies with neck pulled back and head tucked into shoulders.
Great_Blue_Heron, Hunts in a variety of shallow wetland habitats.
Great_Blue_Heron, Nests in colonies of large stick nests high in trees, sometimes not near water.
Great_Blue_Heron, Typically eats aquatic animals but also forages on land, catching mammals.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Like other cormorants, sits low in the water making its body look small compared to the long neck and head. Dives for fish.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Juveniles have a pale neck and a white belly.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Breeding birds have white flank patches that are most easily seen in flight.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a big head, hefty bill, and long tail. Juveniles are dark above with a small white throat patch.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Cormorant, Large, chunky waterbird with a long tail and neck. Breeding birds are dark overall with white patches on the flanks and the throat.
Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Large flycatcher with a broad shouldered and big headed look. Note rusty primaries and tail feathers. Juveniles have more white edging on feathers than adults.

Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Large flycatcher with a peaked crown. The underside of the tail has a very broad rusty stripe down the middle. Note bright yellow belly that goes farther up the breast than similar flycatchers.
Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Sits still on exposed perches, often in treetops, and scans the nearby airspace for flying insects.
Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Large flycatcher with a thick bill, a big head, and a peaked crown. Head and chest are dark gray and belly is bright yellow.
Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Nests in holes in trees or other artificial structures that provide a protected place to nest.
Great_Crested_Flycatcher, Breeds in woodlots and open woodland, particularly among deciduous trees.
Great_Egret, Long-legged wading bird with a long, S-curved neck and a daggerlike bill.

Great_Egret, "American" Great Egrets occur across much of North America and South America. Breeding adults have an orange-yellow bill and develop showy plumes (known as aigrettes) that they use in courtship displays.
Great_Egret, Slowly walks through freshwater or estuarine habitats hunting foraging with stand-and-wait techniques.
Great_Egret, "African" Great Egrets are found in sub-Saharan Africa and Madagascar. Breeding adults have a black bill and blue-green lores between the bill and the eyes.

Great_Egret, Great Egrets breeding from central Europe to central Asia belong to the alba subspecies group. Breeding adults in this group have a blackish bill, greenish lores, and yellowish to reddish legs.
Great_Egret, Great Egrets are opportunistic foragers. They primarily consume fish, but also eat crustaceans, amphibians, and small mammals.

Great_Egret, Great Egrets breeding from South Asia and East Asia to Australia belong to the modesta subspecies group. Breeding adults in this group have a black bill, green lores, and dark legs with a pink or purplish wash.
Great_Egret, Flies with its long neck tucked in and its long legs trailing behind.
Great_Egret, Males perform elegant courtship displays by raising long plumes on their backs. Displays also include head bowing or neck stretching.
Great_Egret, Wades through water slowly stalking fish, amphibians, and other aquatic invertebrates.
Great_Egret, "American" Great Egret is larger than a Snowy Egret, with a yellow bill and entirely black legs and feet.
Great_Egret, Great Egrets while solitary foragers, roost and nest in mixed-species colonies in trees and shrubs.
Great_Egret, Found in both freshwater and saltwater wetlands.
Great_Gray_Owl, Occurs in boreal forest across northern Eurasia and northern North America.
Great_Gray_Owl, Large, big-headed owl with yellow eyes and a tiny bill. Perches quietly on the edges of meadows or forest openings.
Great_Gray_Owl, Large owl with broad, rounded wings. Quietly floats on broad wings across meadows and openings in evergreen forests.
Great_Gray_Owl, Juvenile has yellow eyes, barred upperparts, and large-headed appearance of adult.
Great_Gray_Owl, Hunts by hovering above the snow, and plunging talons first into the snow to grab small mammals. Note large head, yellow eyes, and black-and-white bowtie.
Great_Gray_Owl, Nests in old raptor or Common Raven nests; or in the broken tops of dead trees, human-made platforms, or in clumps of mistletoe.
Great_Gray_Owl, Large, big-headed owl with yellow eyes and a black-and-white bowtie across the neck.
Great_Horned_Owl, Large owl with large ear tufts and yellow eyes. The color of the facial disc varies regionally from gray to cinnamon.
Great_Horned_Owl, A hefty bird that flies silently on broad wings.
Great_Horned_Owl, Owls can't move their eyes side to side; instead they can swivel their heads more than 180 degrees to look in any direction.
Great_Horned_Owl, Juveniles are covered in fluffy down. The head is often downy white and contrasts with the darker facial disc and yellow eyes.
Great_Horned_Owl, Hefty, upright perching owl with noticeable ear tufts. Plumage coloration varies regionally. Eastern birds tend to have more cinnamon tones.
Great_Horned_Owl, Preens feathers by pulling them through its bill.
Great_Horned_Owl, Uses nests built by other species, sometimes adding lining material of their own.
Great_Horned_Owl, Juveniles are covered in fluffy down. White down often retained on the head longer, which contrasts with the darker facial disc.
Great_Horned_Owl, Male and females perform a duet of alternating calls, with the female's voice recognizably higher in pitch than the male's.
Great_Horned_Owl, Mottled brown above with bright yellow eyes, a cinnamon facial disc, and a white throat.
Great_Horned_Owl, Found in woodlands, orchards, and agricultural areas. Sometimes nest in abandoned buildings.

Great_Horned_Owl, Nests in trees such as cottonwood, juniper, beech, pine, and others. They usually adopt a nest that was built by another species, but they also use cavities in live trees, dead snags, deserted buildings, cliff ledges, and human-made platforms.
Great_Kiskadee, Large, blocky flycatcher with a thick neck and a stout bill. Bright yellow below and reddish brown above. Head is boldly striped black and white. Sexes similar.
Great_Kiskadee, Large, bulky flycatcher with a thick bill and a black-and-white striped head. Reddish brown above and yellow below with a white throat.
Great_Kiskadee, Primarily a bird of the subtropics and tropics. Frequents fruit feeding stations.
Great_Kiskadee, Large and noisy flycatcher found in thorn-scrub, in south Texas and tropical deciduous forest elsewhere. They are also found in suburban areas and plantations.
Great_Kiskadee, Builds conspicuous and bulky oblong nests with a side entrance.
Great_Kiskadee, Large, blocky flycatcher with a thick neck and a stout bill. Bright yellow below and reddish brown above. Head is boldly striped black and white. Sexes similar.

Great_Shearwater, Large shearwater with a prominent white collar and a well-defined dark cap. At close range, also note the bird's scaly dark upperwings and back, and the narrow white band at the base of the tail.

Great_Shearwater, Immature birds and adults in late fall and winter lack a white collar, but otherwise show the same color pattern as other Great Shearwaters on the water—dark head, upperparts, and undertail contrasting with a white chin, throat, and breast. All ages have a long, black bill with a hooked tip.
Great_Shearwater, In flight, the underwings and underparts are mostly white, with irregular brown marks on the wings and belly.
Great_Shearwater, On the underwing, the wingtips and trailing edges are dark; the white "armpits" show a variable amount of brown.
Great_Shearwater, Often rests on water in groups. Birds on the water show a strong black-and-white contrast.

Great_Tit, A small songbird with a white cheek; black cap, throat, and collar; single white wingbar; and small, black bill. Birds across Europe and parts of Asia are yellowish below, with a greenish back and blue-gray wings and tail.
Great_Tit, Feeds on insects, seeds, and berries.

Great_Tit, A small songbird with white cheeks, a black cap and throat, and, in Europe, bright yellow underparts divided by a black central line. Upperparts are greenish, with blue-gray wings and tail. Male is brighter yellow than female, with a wider central line and a black patch on the belly.
Great_Tit, Juvenile has light yellowish cheeks, a dull blackish cap, and paler underparts than adult.
Great_Tit, "Turkestan" Great Tit of Central Asia has silver-gray upperparts and is whitish below.
Great_Tit, Female is paler yellow than male, with a thinner black central line below.
Great_Tit, "Turkestan" Great Tit has silver-gray upperparts and wings; long tail is darker gray with white in the outer tail feathers.
Great_Tit, Great Tit populations in Asia have paler yellow underparts than the bright yellow birds in Europe.
Great_Tit, Probes under tree bark throughout the year in search of insect eggs and larvae.
Great_Tit, Thick black line extends from black throat and divides yellow underparts.
Great_Tit, The largest tit in Europe, nearly as large as Eurasian Tree Sparrow.
Great_Tit, Frequently visits bird feeders and quick to take advantage of new food sources.
Greater_Pewee, Large flycatcher with slight crest. Gray overall with pale wing bars, a pale gray belly, and a bicolored bill.
Greater_Pewee, Large upright perching flycatcher. Gray overall with a yellow wash to the lower belly. The bill is long and slender and dark above and orangish below.
Greater_Pewee, Large flycatcher with slight crest. Gray overall with pale wing bars, a pale gray belly, and a bicolored bill.
Greater_Pewee, Large flycatcher with a slight crest. Gray above and pale yellow washed below. Note orangish lower bill.
Greater_Pewee, Upright perching flycatcher with a wide bill. Lower belly is washed in pale yellow. Often perches on dead branches.
Greater_Pewee, Large flycatcher with slight crest. Gray overall with pale wing bars, a pale gray belly, and a bicolored bill.
Greater_Pewee, Found in pine and pine-oak woodlands. Often perches conspicuously.

Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chickenlike grouse. During courtship displays, males raise the feathers on the side of their neck exposing the orange air sacs below, which they inflate to create a booming sound.
Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chickenlike grouse with a small head. Females have a dark eyeline and a pale throat.

Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Males gather and display for females at sites called leks. Males stomp their feet, raise their tail feathers, and inflate the air sacks to make a deep booming sound. This video has no audio.

Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chickenlike grouse. During courtship displays, males raise the feathers on the side of their neck exposing the orange air sacs below, which they inflate to create a booming sound.
Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Males gather in prairie openings where they display for females.
Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chicklenlike grouse with a small head, rounded wings, and short tail.
Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Found in native prairies with scattered oaks.

Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chickenlike grouse. During courtship displays, males raise the feathers on the side of their neck exposing the orange air sacs below, which they inflate to create a booming sound.

Greater_Prairie-Chicken, Barred brown-and-white chickenlike grouse. During courtship displays, males raise the feathers on the side of their neck exposing the orange air sacs below, which they inflate to create a booming sound.

Greater_Roadrunner, Distinctive shape, with long neck and legs, and a very long tail. Mostly brown with bold streaks over most of the body, and a lighter buffy belly. Distinct crest and long, heavy bill.
Greater_Roadrunner, During the breeding season can show bright blue and red facial skin.
Greater_Roadrunner, Typically forages in open areas for insects, arachnids, centipedes, millipedes, lizards, snakes, and carrion. Also takes adult birds, young, and eggs.
Greater_Roadrunner, Prefers to run on the ground rather than flying. Calls with a nasal "meep meep" when running away from danger.
Greater_Roadrunner, Large with a very long tail and a slightly crested head. Back and underparts are heavily streaked.
Greater_Roadrunner, When flying shows broad, rounded wings with glossy dark feathers, and usually spreads the long tail.
Greater_Roadrunner, Eats a variety of prey, including lizards and snakes.
Greater_Roadrunner, In cold weather will sometimes expose black feathers and skin on the lower back.
Greater_Roadrunner, Will sing or scan for danger from exposed perches.
Greater_Roadrunner, Typically occurs in dry, fairly open to scrubby habitats.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and long tail. Speckled brown and gray above. Males have a white breast, a black belly, and a black throat.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head. Females are speckled brown and gray above with brown speckling on the throat and a black belly.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, One of the characteristic birds of sagebrush country of western North America. Males gather on display grounds, known as leks, to vie for the attention of females in the area.

Greater_Sage-Grouse, Males spread their tail into a starburst and inflate yellow air sacs in the chest when displaying, giving them a bizarre appearance. Females are much more subdued in appearance; they gather to closely inspect displaying males before mating.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large grouse that fans its tail into a starburst when displaying and inflates 2 yellow air sacs in the chest.

Greater_Sage-Grouse, Displaying males lunge forward to push air in and out of the yellow air sacs in their chest, making a quiet gurgling or popping sound. They vigorously defend the small display territories on their leks. They often display even when there are no females around.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and long tail that is fanned into a starburst when displaying. Males also inflate 2 yellow air sacs like round balloons while displaying.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Displays begin in late winter or early spring, often when there is still snow on the ground.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and fairly long tail. Note the large black belly patch.
Greater_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and long tail. Speckled brown and gray above. Males have a white breast, a black belly, and a black throat.

Greater_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with an evenly rounded head and a yellow eye. Dark head, chest, and rear contrasts with white sides and gray back. Greenish iridescence on head only visible with ideal lighting.
Greater_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with rounded head and fairly heavy, broad bill. Warm brownish overall, with white facial patch next to bill and a yellow eye.
Greater_Scaup, Found on large bodies of water around the Great Lakes and coastal areas in the United States. Note the round-headed look with the head peaking closer to the rear.

Greater_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with an evenly rounded head and a yellow eye. Dark head, chest, and rear contrasts with white sides and gray back. Greenish iridescence on head only visible with ideal lighting.
Greater_Scaup, In flight, all plumages have a white wing stripe that extends into the primaries, nearly to the tip of the wing.
Greater_Scaup, Large diving duck with a rounded head and a yellow eye. Nonbreeding males have brownish gray back and flanks.
Greater_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a rounded head. Rich brown overall, with white patch next to bill and, in summer, often a pale "ear" patch toward the back of the head.
Greater_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a broad, black-tipped bill. At close range, gray back is finely marked with black lines. Greenish iridescence on head is only visible in ideal lighting.
Greater_Scaup, Often flocks with other diving ducks, especially in winter and migration. Pale gray back and white sides are distinctive from a distance.
Greater_Scaup, Flocks winter mainly on saltwater bays and estuaries; also on Great Lakes and other large freshwater lakes that stay ice free in winter.

Greater_White-fronted_Goose, A brownish goose with black splotches on the belly, white side stripe, white vent, and white face patch. Greenland-breeding adults (subspecies flavirostris ) show bright orange bill and legs.

Greater_White-fronted_Goose, Fresh juveniles lack the black bars below and white feathering around base of the bill. The tips of the upperparts feathers are rounded rather than squared as in adults. Bill and legs are duller in color than adults.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, During the winter congregates in wetlands and ponds.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, Juveniles in autumn lack white feathering around base of the bill. Note the dull-colored bare parts and rounded back feathers typical of juvenile geese.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, In flight, shows a white "U" on the rump. Large gray upperwing panels contrast with the dark flight feathers.

Greater_White-fronted_Goose, A stout, brown goose with a white face patch and a pink-orange bill. Lighting conditions may make it challenging to distinguish the precise bill color in this variable species.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, The amount of black on the bellies of adults is variable and has led to colloquial use of the nickname "Speckle belly" or even just "Speck."

Greater_White-fronted_Goose, Adults in western North America typically show pinkish bills that contrast with the orange legs. Also note the brown head and neck and pale gray belly marked with black splotches.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, Travels in large flocks and forages in grassy estuaries and wetlands during migration.
Greater_White-fronted_Goose, Often flocks with other goose species like these Cackling Geese. The brown neck color, pink-orange bill, and orange legs help this distinctive goose stand out in a crowd.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Slender, long-necked, and small-headed shorebird with bright yellow legs. Breeding birds have heavy barring on the flanks, sometimes extending across the belly.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Slender shorebird with a small head and bright yellow legs. The bill is long and slightly upturned. Juveniles are browner above with crisp markings.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Call is a string of three or four sharp, high-pitched notes. Note slightly upturned bill more than 1.5x as long as the head.
Greater_Yellowlegs, In flight, note white rump and plain wings.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Juveniles are browner above with crisp markings. Note bright yellow legs and long bill. Stands upright.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Tall and gangly shorebird with bright yellow legs and a long bill. Breeding birds often have heavily streaked underparts. Stands upright.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Breeds in wet bogs with small wooded islands, and forests with wet clearings covered with mosses and lichens.
Greater_Yellowlegs, Winters in wide variety of shallow fresh and saltwater habitats.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow typically found on or near the ground. Breeds in dry, scrubby mountain habitats and brushy forest edges.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Males sing a jumbled series of clear whistles and trills lasting about 2.5 seconds.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow, typically found on or near the ground. Grayish overall with bright reddish cap and distinctive greenish yellow wings and tail.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Juveniles are streaky and brownish, but typically show distinctive greenish yellow tinge to wings and tail.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.
Green-tailed_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill and long tail. Unusual color pattern: green-yellow upperparts with clean gray head and breast, white throat, and reddish cap.

Green-tailed_Towhee, Winters in dry, brushy habitats including mesquite, hackberry, acacia, cactus, and creosote bush. Breeds on sagebrush plains and shrubby mountain slopes up to about 10,000 feet elevation.
Green-winged_Teal, A small dabbling duck. Breeding male has a chestnut head with a green streak behind the eye, and in the "American" subspecies, a vertical white stripe on the side.
Green-winged_Teal, Breeding male of the "Eurasian" subspecies has a horizontal white stripe on the side as opposed to the vertical stripe on the "American" subspecies.
Green-winged_Teal, Small, compact duck. At distance, the white vertical stripe at the shoulder (on males) and the creamy diagonal mark at the tail (on both sexes) are useful marks.
Green-winged_Teal, Small duck with a blocky body. Female and nonbreeding male have a cream-colored stripe at the rear.
Green-winged_Teal, In flight both male and female have a green "speculum" patch in the wing.

Green-winged_Teal, Small duck with a blocky body. Breeding male has a chestnut head with a green stripe behind the eye, and in the "American" subspecies, a vertical white stripe on the side. The undertail coverts are cream colored.
Green-winged_Teal, Green speculum often hidden on resting birds, but is visible in flight.
Green-winged_Teal, Feeds in shallow bodies of water and in flooded fields. Breeds in dense vegetation along river deltas.
Green-winged_Teal, Often gathers in large flocks during the nonbreeding season.
Green-winged_Teal, Wintering birds typically flock to shallow wetlands, including coastal marshes and bayous, estuaries, riparian sloughs, and agricultural areas such as rice fields.
Green_Heron, Small and stocky with a daggerlike bill and a thick neck that is often drawn into their body. Adults have a deep green back and crown, and a chestnut neck and breast.
Green_Heron, Small, compact heron. Juveniles are browner overall, with pale streaking on the neck and spots on the wings. Note dark cap.
Green_Heron, Male gives a show-ch or ow-ch song during breeding season.
Green_Heron, Look rather ungainly in flight, often partially uncrooking their necks to giving them a front-heavy appearance.

Green_Heron, The center of their neck is streaked, but the streaking can be hard to see as they frequently have their necks tucked in or they are crouched over making it difficult to see the center of the neck.
Green_Heron, Usually hunts from shore rather than by wading like other herons. Juveniles have buffy spots and feather edging on the wings.
Green_Heron, Generally appears all dark, except in good light when the feathers shine with an almost iridescent green color.
Green_Heron, Juveniles are browner overall with more streaking on the neck than adults.
Green_Heron, Crouches on sticks, branches, or the waters edge patiently stalking small fish or amphibians.
Green_Heron, Found along swamps, marshes, lakes, ponds, impoundments, and other wet habitats with dense vegetation to provide cover.
Green_Jay, Large and unmistakable. Bright green above with a blue head and black throat.
Green_Jay, Large bright green, blue, and yellow jay. The tail is yellow below and it flashes yellow outer tail feathers in flight.
Green_Jay, A bold and colorful jay that sometimes takes sugar water from hummingbird feeders.
Green_Jay, Individuals farther south tend to be brighter yellow below.
Green_Jay, Large and unmistakable. Bright green above with a blue head and black throat.
Green_Jay, Brightly colored and unmistakeable. This video has no audio.
Green_Jay, Large and unmistakable. Bright green above with a blue head and black throat.
Green_Jay, Large and unmistakable. Bright green above with a blue head and black throat.
Green_Jay, Eats mainly insects, but also eats seeds and visits bird feeders. This video has no audio.
Green_Jay, Large and unmistakable. Bright green above with a blue head and black throat.
Green_Kingfisher, Small kingfisher with large bill. Upperparts are metallic green with white spots on wings. Males have a rufous or chestnut wash on the breast.
Green_Kingfisher, Small kingfisher with heavy bill and often rounded rather than crested head. Note white in the outer tail in flight. Females have double breast band.

Green_Kingfisher, Small kingfisher with large, heavy bill, often showing rounded rather than crested head. While perched, often jerks the head and tail upward. Males have rufous to chestnut wash on breast.
Green_Kingfisher, Immatures resemble females but may have a buffy wash on the breast and buffy spots on the crown.
Green_Kingfisher, Immatures may have a buffy or rufous wash on the breast and buffy spots on the crown. Note extensive white on the outer tail feathers (all ages and sexes).
Green_Kingfisher, Small kingfisher with large, heavy bill. Females have a double breast band and lack rufous on the chest. Note extensive white on the outer tail feathers (all ages and sexes).
Green_Kingfisher, Perches low over water along wooded creeks, streams, ponds, and ditches, then makes quick dives to capture prey. Rarely hovers.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Long-tailed with a thick, curved bill and a hunched posture. Entirely black and lacks feathers around the eye.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Groove-billed_Ani, Slender black bird with a long tail and a thick, curved bill. Feathers around head are often fluffed up. With close views grooves on bill are visible.
Gull-billed_Tern, Rather stocky, medium-sized tern with long wings and a thick black bill. Breeding bird has an entirely black crown.
Gull-billed_Tern, Stocky tern with a thick black bill and black legs. Nonbreeding adult has a dark smudge behind the eye.
Gull-billed_Tern, Breeding adult has a full black cap, thick black bill, and long black legs. At rest, the long wingtips extend well beyond the tip of the short tail.
Gull-billed_Tern, In flight note slightly forked tail and dark gray tips to outermost flight feathers.
Gull-billed_Tern, Juvenile has a smudgy gray patch behind the eye and a thick bill that is often pale at the base.
Gull-billed_Tern, Nonbreeding adult has an overall white-headed look with limited smudging around the eye. Heavy black bill is distinctive in all plumages.
Gull-billed_Tern, Note notched tail in flight and dusky tips to the primaries.
Gull-billed_Tern, Nests on saltmarsh islands as well as sandy barrier beaches. Catches a variety of prey, relying less on fish than other terns.
Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and a long tail. Juveniles are mottled brown and black.
Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Large, chubby grouse with a small head and a long tail that is fanned into a starburst when displaying. Males also inflate 2 bare yellow air sacs when displaying.

Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Males perform unique courtship displays on defined mating territories, or leks. Males produce distinctive "plopping" sounds by inflating their specialized neck pouches and quickly jerking their head and wings.
Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Spends most of the time walking on the ground, only flying when startled or threatened.

Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Large grouse with a small head and long tail. Females are mottled in browns and blacks with a dark belly. Females are more cryptically colored than males and easily blend into their surroundings.
Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Large chubby grouse with a small head and a long tail. Juveniles are mottled brown and black.
Gunnison_Sage-Grouse, Found in areas with sagebrush and native grasses.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Large falcon with a long tail. Juveniles are browner overall than adults and show a weak mustache mark. Underparts have vertical streaks.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, White morph birds are speckled black and white above with dark wingtips and a white tail. Some birds have dark banding on the tail.
Gyrfalcon, Large falcon with a long tail (tail extends beyond wingtips). Highly variable plumage. Some gray juveniles look gray like this one; others look more brown. Note weak mustache.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Large falcon with highly variable coloration. Note long, banded tail and mustache stripe. In North America, gray birds are more numerous than the other morphs.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Can be nearly all white below or show some dark spotting on the breast.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with a long tail and pointed wings. Some individuals are heavily marked below.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Gyrfalcon, Large, stocky falcon with variable plumage coloration. Gray morph birds are banded gray and white above or can be mostly gray without obvious banding.
Hairy_Woodpecker, A medium-sized woodpecker with a long bill. Male has red on the back of the head. "Eastern" Hairy Woodpecker has extensive white spotting on the wings.

Hairy_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a white patch down its back. Female lacks male's red on the head. "Rocky Mts." Hairy Woodpecker, found across much of the western U.S. (and into British Columbia), has mostly black wings.
Hairy_Woodpecker, Hollows out a nest in a live or dead tree. Both males and females feed young soft-bodied insects.
Hairy_Woodpecker, Typically hitches up tree trunks or along large branches, leaning back against stiff tail feathers and springing upward with both feet at once.
Hairy_Woodpecker, "Pacific" Hairy Woodpecker is darker than "Rocky Mts." and "Eastern" groups, with light brownish underparts and mostly black wings.
Hairy_Woodpecker, Juvenile male (in all subspecies groups) has a red crown patch.
Hairy_Woodpecker, "Costa Rican" Hairy Woodpecker from the highlands of eastern Costa Rica and western Panama has cinnamon underparts.
Hairy_Woodpecker, In flight, "Eastern" Hairy Woodpecker has extensive white spotting on the black upperwings.
Hairy_Woodpecker, Hairy Woodpecker is larger than Downy Woodpecker, with a proportionally longer bill and unmarked white outer tail feathers.
Hairy_Woodpecker, Found in in woodlots, suburbs, parks, and cemeteries, as well as forest edges, open pine-oak woodlands, recently burned forests, and stands infested by bark beetles.

Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with an obvious white eyering and small bill. On perched birds note the primary feathers, which are longer than in other Empidonax species. Look for a large step between the secondaries and primaries.
Hammonds_Flycatcher, Found in evergreen forests on the breeding grounds and in scrub and pine-oak woodlands during migration.
Hammonds_Flycatcher, Song consists of a dry, abrupt 2-syllable phrase, followed by a low burry note and another rough two-syllable phrase.

Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with an obvious white eyering and small bill. On perched birds note the primary feathers, which are longer than in other Empidonax species. Look for a large step between the secondaries and primaries.
Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with a distinct eyering and 2 wingbars. Primary feathers are long for an Empidonax , creating a stepped look from the secondaries to the primaries.

Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with an obvious white eyering and small bill. On perched birds note the primary feathers, which are longer than in other Empidonax species. Look for a large step between the secondaries and primaries.
Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a slightly peaked head and a white eyering. Breast is gray with a pale yellowish lower belly.

Hammonds_Flycatcher, Small grayish flycatcher with an obvious white eyering and small bill. On perched birds note the primary feathers, which are longer than in other Empidonax species. Look for a large step between the secondaries and primaries.
Harlequin_Duck, Small sea duck with short bill. Extravagantly marked with slate blue body, white facial crescent and spot, chestnut crown patch and flanks, and bold white body stripes.
Harlequin_Duck, Small brown sea duck with short bill and round head. Telltale facial markings recall male pattern with white patch behind bill and white spot behind eye.
Harlequin_Duck, Gathers in loose flocks in winter along rocky coastlines. Short bill, steep forehead, and rounded crown create a distinctive shape.
Harlequin_Duck, Rounded head and short bill. Body color brownish with hints of slate blue breeding colors. White facial markings as in adult birds, especially cheek spot.
Harlequin_Duck, Winters along rocky seacoasts. Males are slate blue with bold white stripes and chestnut flanks. Females are brownish with distinctive white face markings.
Harlequin_Duck, Small sea duck with short bill. Extravagantly marked with slate blue body, white facial crescent and spot, chestnut crown patch and flanks, and bold white body stripes.
Harlequin_Duck, Winters along rocky seacoasts, often in small flocks.
Harlequin_Duck, Small sea duck with short bill. Extravagantly marked with slate blue body, white facial crescent and spot, chestnut crown patch and flanks, and bold white body stripes.
Harlequin_Duck, Small sea duck with short bill. Extravagantly marked with slate blue body, white facial crescent and spot, chestnut crown patch and flanks, and bold white body stripes.
Harlequin_Duck, Breeds along seacoasts as shown, but also inland. Male's white face markings and body stripes are distinctive from long distances.
Harlequin_Duck, Plump, fairly small sea ducks with rounded heads and short bills. Males and females share distinctive face pattern, especially spot behind eye.
Harlequin_Duck, Gregarious sea duck often seen in flocks. Summers fairly far north and sometimes rests on floating ice.

Harriss_Hawk, Large hawk with broad, rounded wings and fairly long tail. Underparts are dark, with reddish brown patches on the shoulder that can be seen at close range. Tail has a broad dark band, with white at the base and at the tip.
Harriss_Hawk, Large, mostly dark hawk with reddish-brown shoulder patches. Fairly long tail has white undertail coverts and white band at the tip. Legs are long.
Harriss_Hawk, Soars on broad, rounded wings with long tail fanned. Note prominent white at base of tail and on rump.
Harriss_Hawk, Typically perches with an erect posture. Dark overall; reddish brown shoulder patches can blend in with dark plumage. White band at tip of tail.

Harriss_Hawk, Large hawk with broad, rounded wings and fairly long tail. Underparts are dark, with reddish brown patches on the shoulder that can be seen at close range. Tail has a broad dark band, with white at the base and at the tip.
Harriss_Hawk, Occurs in open habitats where it perches vertically on posts, dead trees, and other perches. Reddish shoulder patches can blend in with brown upperparts in some views.
Harriss_Hawk, Large hawk with broad, rounded wings and fairly long tail. Immatures have patchy white near the wingtips and on the belly.
Harriss_Hawk, Immatures have variable amounts of white in the underwings and on the belly; some are nearly as dark as adults. White band at tip of tail is narrower than in adults.
Harriss_Hawk, Eats mainly small mammals and lizards. "Bay-winged" subspecies occurs in tropical forests and scrub of eastern South America.

Harriss_Hawk, Large hawk with broad, rounded wings and fairly long tail. Underparts are dark, with reddish brown patches on the shoulder that can be seen at close range. Tail has a broad dark band, with white at the base and at the tip.
Harriss_Hawk, "Bay-winged" subspecies occurs in eastern South America. It is slightly smaller, with a slightly longer tail than the "Harris's" subspecies.
Harriss_Hawk, Reddish shoulder patches can be indistinct, depending on light. White tip to tail is visible from behind. This video has no audio.

Harriss_Hawk, Large hawk with broad, rounded wings and fairly long tail. Underparts are dark, with reddish brown patches on the shoulder that can be seen at close range. Tail has a broad dark band, with white at the base and at the tip.
Harriss_Hawk, A social species often seen in groups and sometimes hunting together. Groups of up to 7 birds cooperate to raise young.
Harriss_Hawk, Occurs in open habitats including woodland, desert scrub, savannas, and grasslands. Often uses telephone poles and other structures for perches.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with pink bill. Nonbreeding adults are brown on the face and washed brown on the flanks. Black bib is variable in size and may contain white in winter.
Harriss_Sparrow, Foraging at a feeding station with House Sparrow, White-winged Dove, Gambel's Quail, House Finch and White-crowned Sparrow.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with pink bill and long tail. Immatures have buffy-brown heads and a white throat outlined by dark "mustache" stripes and the streaky beginnings of a bib.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with pink bill and long tail. Immature has brown head and white throat outlined by dark "mustache" stripes.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.
Harriss_Sparrow, Breeds in patchy forest and tundra of northern Canada. Winters in grasslands and shrubby areas including agricultural fields, prairie, old fields, and thickets along streams.
Harriss_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and pink bill. Gray head with extensive black face and bib. Streaky brown upperparts; white belly with streaked flanks.

Hawaiian_Goose, A medium-sized goose with a small head, short bill, and long legs. Upperparts are dark brown, with extensive white feather edging. Underparts are light brown with some dark barring. The head is mostly black, with a large cream-colored cheek patch; and the neck is whitish with deeply furrowed feathers.
Hawaiian_Goose, Young goslings are downy, but attain adult plumage in five months, faster than other goose species.
Hawaiian_Goose, A medium-sized goose with a distinctive cream-colored cheek patch leading to a whitish neck with deep grooves.
Hawaiian_Goose, Uses freshwater when available but does not require aquatic habitats like most other waterfowl do.
Hawaiian_Goose, Highly terrestrial, with several adaptations (erect posture, long legs and toes, reduced webbing) for life on islands with limited freshwater.
Hawaiian_Goose, Forages on lava flows with limited vegetation, as well as grassy shrublands, pastures, and golf courses.
Hawaiian_Goose, Pairs remain together year-round.
Hawaiian_Goose, Remains close together in family groups, but generally does not form large flocks like many other goose species.
Heermanns_Gull, Medium-sized bulky gull. Breeding birds are uniquely marked with a dark gray body, a white head, and a red black-tipped bill.
Heermanns_Gull, Nonbreeding adults are gray overall with a darker gray back and a red bill with a black tip.
Heermanns_Gull, During the nonbreeding season, Heerman's Gulls typically hunt offshore for schooling fish or loaf on beaches, rocky shorelines, or estuaries.
Heermanns_Gull, Medium-sized gray gull unlike any other gull. Nonbreeding birds have a red bill with a black tip.
Heermanns_Gull, Second winter gulls are smooth brown overall with a bicolored bill.
Heermanns_Gull, Juveniles have a sooty-brown head and a scalloped looking back. Note heavy bicolored bill.
Heermanns_Gull, Smooth gray overall with a white head, gray rump, and black tail.
Heermanns_Gull, First winter birds are dark brown overall.
Heermanns_Gull, Found along beaches, coastal estuaries, harbors, and lagoons. Migrates north, spending the winters along the West coast.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a relatively large bill. The face has an olive wash to it with a dark spot behind the eye. The breast is ringed in thin streaks.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Henslows_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with an olive wash to the face, a dark spot behind the eye, and dark stripes on the side of the crown. Wing feathers are rusty tipped.
Hepatic_Tanager, Large and chunky with a thick silver bill. Males are red overall, with a grayish red back and a gray cheek patch.
Hepatic_Tanager, Females and immature males are yellowish overall with a dark eyeline and a grayish cheek.
Hepatic_Tanager, Sings slurred notes that rise and fall with short pauses interspersed. Often sings from the tops of pine trees.
Hepatic_Tanager, Large and chunky with a thick silver bill. Males are red overall, with a grayish red back and a gray cheek patch.
Hepatic_Tanager, Large and chunky with a thick silver bill. Males are red overall, with a grayish red back and a gray cheek patch.
Hepatic_Tanager, Eats insects and fruits, often visiting fruit feeding stations.
Hepatic_Tanager, Large and chunky with a thick silver bill. Males are red overall, with a grayish red back and a gray cheek patch.
Hepatic_Tanager, Males are bright red with a gray cheek patch and a grayish back washed in red. Found in open pine and pine-oak forests.
Hepatic_Tanager, Females/immature males are yellowish overall, but note gray cast to back and cheek. This video has no audio.
Hepatic_Tanager, Individuals in Arizona often more orangish yellow on the throat and crown with a grayish cheek patch and back.
Hepatic_Tanager, Hefty tanager with a thick, dark bill. Females and immature males are yellowish overall with a characteristic gray cheek.
Hepatic_Tanager, Moves slowly and deliberately through foliage.

Hermit_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a round head and a full-bodied look. Brown above, with a distinctly reddish tail. The underparts are pale with spots on the throat and smudged spots on the breast.
Hermit_Thrush, Brown above with a strongly contrasting reddish tail. Note thin white eyering.
Hermit_Thrush, A medium-sized thrush with a thin white eyering and distinct blackish spots on the upper breast. Flicks wings and raises and slowly lowers tail.

Hermit_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a rich brown upper body and smudged spots on the breast, with a reddish tail that sets it apart from similar species. Sometimes cocks its tail up, while flicking its wings.
Hermit_Thrush, Hops and scrapes in leaf litter while foraging for insects.
Hermit_Thrush, Can be conspicuous on migration, even foraging out in the open on the ground. Note the reddish tail contrasting with the brownish upperparts.
Hermit_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with dark brown spots on the breast and paler smudgier spots on the flanks.
Hermit_Thrush, Juveniles are brownish gray above with spotting on the back and wings.

Hermit_Thrush, Song—often considered one of the world's most beautiful—is rich, haunting, and melodious. Typically starts with a short whistled phrase, followed by a short pause, and then a second phrase, often higher in pitch.
Hermit_Thrush, Found in the understory of deciduous and evergreen forests, especially around edges or openings.
Hermit_Thrush, Typically found on forest floor, where it hops while foraging in the leaf litter. Note erect posture with head tilted and bill slightly raised.
Hermit_Warbler, Small warbler with a yellow face and beady black eye. Adult males have a brighter yellow face and a black chin. Note clean white underparts.
Hermit_Warbler, Small warbler with a yellow face and beady black eye. Adult females have a paler yellow face and a yellow chin. Note clean white underparts.
Hermit_Warbler, Small warbler with a yellow face and beady black eye. Adult males have a brighter yellow face and a black chin. Note clean white underparts.
Hermit_Warbler, Immatures have a pale yellow face with a dusky cheek and a yellow eyering. Breeds in tall evergreen forests.
Hermit_Warbler, Small warbler with a yellow face and beady black eye. Adult males have a brighter yellow face and a black chin. Note clean white underparts.
Hermit_Warbler, Females and immatures have a pale yellow face with a dusky cheek and a yellow eyering. Note yellow chin and clean white underparts.
Hermit_Warbler, Winters in high-elevation pine and pine-oak forests in Mexico and Central America. Breeds in evergreen mountain forests of California, Oregon, and Washington.
Hooded_Merganser, Small duck with slender bill and flamboyant oversized head. Hood (crest) can be raised as shown or lowered, changing the shape of the head and the white head patch.
Hooded_Merganser, Small brownish duck with warm cinnamon crest and gray-brown body. Long tail is not always visible.
Hooded_Merganser, Courtship typically occurs in groups with several males and a few females. Males raise their crest, pump their head, flap their wings, and give a froglike croak.
Hooded_Merganser, Small, brownish duck with fairly long, straight, slender bill. Ragged crest is cinnamon brown, warmer than the rest of the body.
Hooded_Merganser, In flight, both sexes have limited white markings on the inner upperwings.
Hooded_Merganser, Hooded Merganser clutch size ranges from 5–13 eggs. Ducklings need little parental care—they can dive and collect their own food within hours of hatching.
Hooded_Merganser, Small, brownish duck with slender, straight bill. Movable crest can give head varied shapes; it's usually warmer brown than the rest of the bird, especially toward the tip.
Hooded_Merganser, Male's crest when lowered lies against the back of the neck, the white patch minimized to a stripe behind the eye.
Hooded_Merganser, A slender, serrated bill helps Hooded Mergansers capture aquatic insects, fish, and crayfish. Prey is usually swallowed whole.
Hooded_Merganser, Flamboyant small duck with oversized head when crest is extended. White chest/sides are crossed by one black stripe and bordered by a second; flanks are chestnut.
Hooded_Merganser, Immature male shows a mix of female and adult male features.
Hooded_Merganser, Hooded Mergansers preen while swimming or standing on land.
Hooded_Merganser, Small brownish duck with straight, slender bill and warm brown crest. In summer may be seen with many ducklings in tow.
Hooded_Merganser, May form small flocks; males perform several types of displays that emphasize the black-and-white crest, especially when females are present.
Hooded_Merganser, Nests in holes in trees and in nest boxes.

Hooded_Oriole, Long and slender with more delicate bodies than other orioles. Adult males vary from brilliant yellow to flame orange with a black throat that extends up around the eye. Note large white wingbar.
Hooded_Oriole, Long and slender songbird with a slightly curved bill. Females are olive-yellow overall with grayer backs and thin white wingbars. Note unstreaked grayish back.
Hooded_Oriole, Often forages rather sluggishly. Found in open woodlands with scattered trees, including cottonwoods, willows, sycamores, and especially palm trees.
Hooded_Oriole, Immature males look similar to females are are olive-yellow overall, but have black throats like adult males.

Hooded_Oriole, Large and slender with a long tail and sharply pointed bill. Plumage of adult males varies from yellow in northwestern Mexico and the southwestern U.S. to brilliant orange in south Texas and eastern Mexico.
Hooded_Oriole, Males in northwestern Mexico and the southwestern U.S. tend to be more yellow, while males in south Texas and eastern Mexico are more orange. Note large white wingbar.
Hooded_Oriole, Slender oriole with a slightly curved bill. Adult males in eastern Mexico are more orange than birds to the north.
Hooded_Oriole, Females are olive-yellow overall including the belly.
Hooded_Oriole, Plumage color varies across their range from yellow-orange to bright orange.

Hooded_Oriole, Found in open woodlands with scattered trees, including cottonwoods, willows, sycamores, and especially palm trees. In areas where ornamental palms have increased, Hooded Orioles are expanding and moving farther north.
Hooded_Warbler, Adult males have a bright yellow face surrounded by a black hood and throat. They are olive above and yellow below. Often fans tail to show white outer tail feathers.

Hooded_Warbler, Some adult females show a partial black crown spotted with yellow. Entirely yellow below except for white undertail feathers. Adult females vary considerably in the extent of black on the head and neck, from little or no black to a complete male-like hood. In all plumages, entirely yellow below.
Hooded_Warbler, Males sing an emphatic ringing weeta-weeta-weet-tee-o.

Hooded_Warbler, Immature females during their first year either lack black on the head and neck or have only traces of black framing the yellow face; entirely yellow below. The underside of the tail feathers are white; the outer corners flash white when fanned.
Hooded_Warbler, Many adult females have a near-complete hood, but it is usually neither as black nor as extensive as it is in males.
Hooded_Warbler, Hops quickly on the ground and through the shrub layer often flicking its tail.
Hooded_Warbler, Often found in the understory of forests with shrubby understory. Adult males have a bright yellow face and a beady black eye surrounded by a black hood and throat.
Hooded_Warbler, Adult males have a bright yellow face surrounded by black hood and throat. Olive above and yellow below. Often fans tail to show white outer tail feathers.
Hooded_Warbler, Males sing throughout the day, but tend to sing more both early and late in the day.
Hooded_Warbler, Breeds in hardwood forests with a shrubby understory in the eastern United States and a small area in southern Canada.
