Hooded_Warbler, Spends much of its time in the understory flitting between shrubs and flicking its tail to reveal white outer tail feathers.
Hook-billed_Kite, Medium-sized raptor with very broad, rounded wings. Note checkered pattern on flight feathers and broad bands in the tail. Males have gray underparts.
Hook-billed_Kite, Note very broad, rounded "paddle-shaped" wings and long tail with prominent, broad bands. Females are reddish brown on the neck continuing into barring on the breast and belly.
Hook-billed_Kite, Medium-sized raptor with broad wings and long, banded tail. Note heavy bill with pronounced hook. Immatures are creamy white below with blackish barring.
Hook-billed_Kite, Medium-sized raptor with heavy, strongly hooked bill and banded tail. Adults have yellow eyes. Males are gray below with thin white bars.
Hook-billed_Kite, Rare dark morphs are deep brown-black all over with yellow patch before the eye and broad bands in the tail.
Hook-billed_Kite, Note pale eye (adults) and heavy, strongly hooked bill. Females are reddish brown on the neck, continuing into barring on the breast and belly.
Hook-billed_Kite, Often seen in lowlands along wooded streams and rivers (including rarely in South Texas), but in Andes can occur in cloud forest above 10,000 feet elevation.
Hook-billed_Kite, Medium-sized raptor with long, strongly banded tail, pale eye (adults) and strongly hooked bill. Females have an orange-brown collar.
Hook-billed_Kite, Immature has dark eye and creamy white underparts barred with blackish. Note heavy, hooked bill and banded tail.
Hook-billed_Kite, The form that lives on Grenada is slightly smaller, with a smaller bill and greenish eyes. Females have rufous-brown barring and collar.
Horned_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with short, straight bill. Breeding adults have black head with rich golden tufts, black back, and cinnamon neck, breast, and sides.

Horned_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with small head and short, straight bill. Nonbreeding birds have black head sharply contrasting with white cheek, gray-black upperparts, and grayish white underparts. Note white-tipped bill.
Horned_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with head that appears large in breeding plumage thanks to puffy feathers. Note linear golden head tufts ("horns") and cinnamon neck and breast.
Horned_Grebe, When molting into breeding plumage, can show mix of gold or chestnut breeding coloration with grayish nonbreeding plumage.
Horned_Grebe, Small-bodied grebe with long neck and short, straight bill. Immatures resemble nonbreeding adults, with black cap and clean white cheek, but with grayish wash to neck.
Horned_Grebe, In flight shows clean border of black cap with white neck. Leading edge of wing is dark in nonbreeding plumage. Feet are lobed, not webbed.
Horned_Grebe, Courtship often happens during spring migration; pairs have several displays involving rearing up out of the water and coordinating their movements in "dances."
Horned_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with short, straight bill. Breeding adults have black head with rich golden tufts, black back, and cinnamon neck, breast, and sides.
Horned_Grebe, Fairly small grebe with short, straight bill. Breeding adults have black head with rich golden tufts, black back, and cinnamon neck, breast, and sides.
Horned_Grebe, Often occurs in flocks and winters on large bodies of water, particularly saltwater but also freshwater to a lesser extent.
Horned_Grebe, Breeds in small ponds and marshes, mainly north of 50 degrees North latitude; builds nest out of floating mass of vegetation.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.
Horned_Lark, Females lack the male's black mask and are generally paler, with only a slight yellow wash on the throat and a brown breast band.
Horned_Lark, Small, sparrow-sized bird with thin, straight bill. Tiny black "horns" on the sides of the crown can be raised or lowered. Note sandy brown back contrasting with blackish tail.
Horned_Lark, Small songbird with a small head and bill. Females have a pale yellow wash on the throat and a dusky breast band. They lack the male's black eye patch.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.
Horned_Lark, Males have tiny hornlike feathers on top of the head that can be raised and lowered.

Horned_Lark, Sandy to rusty brown above with a black tail that is especially noticeable in flight. Back and throat color vary across the range from rusty to sandy and from pale yellow to bright yellow.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.

Horned_Lark, Small, sparrowlike bird with a long body and a small bill. Brownish above and pale below with a black chest band. Males have a black mask and variable amounts of yellow on the head and throat. Also note tiny hornlike feathers that sometimes stick straight up on the head.

Horned_Lark, Found in open country with very short or no vegetation, including bare agricultural fields. Often difficult to spot on bare ground thanks to their small size and brown and sandy-colored backs.
Horned_Puffin, Stocky seabird with large red and yellow bill. Breeding birds have black "horns" above their eyes.
Horned_Puffin, Stocky seabird with large red and yellow bill. Breeding birds have black "horns" above their eyes.
Horned_Puffin, Stocky seabird with large red and yellow bill. Breeding birds have black "horns" above their eyes.
Horned_Puffin, Stocky seabird with large red and yellow bill. Breeding birds have black "horns" above their eyes.
Horned_Puffin, Nonbreeding birds have a gray face and the bill is gray and red instead of yellow and red.
Horned_Puffin, Stocky seabird with large triangular-shaped bill. Nonbreeding birds have a gray face.
Horned_Puffin, Immatures have a gray face and a smaller gray and yellow bill. Separated from Atlantic Puffins by range.

House_Finch, Small finch with a conical seed-eating bill. Like other finches, it has a notched tail. Adult males are rosy red around the face and upper breast, with a streaky brown back, belly, and tail.
House_Finch, Small finch with a conical bill and notched tail. Females/immature males are brown overall with blurry streaks down the belly.
House_Finch, Note very thick bill with curved rather than straight-edged profile. Red on head is largely on the eyebrow and throat, with brownish cheeks. Flanks are boldly streaked.
House_Finch, Adult males are rosy red around the face and upper breast, with streaks down the belly and on the flanks.
House_Finch, Females/immature males are brown overall with heavily streaked underparts.
House_Finch, Often numerous at feeders, especially where black oil sunflower is offered. Tends to sit at feeder and crack seeds in its stout bill instead of flying away.
House_Finch, Plumage color varies with diet. The more carotenoid rich foods they eat, the redder they become.
House_Finch, Plumage coloration ranges from yellow to bright red depending on the amount of carotenoid rich foods they eat; the more carotenoids in food the brighter red they become.
House_Finch, Note plain mostly brown face pattern without pale stripes; also the notched tail. May be found in small flocks.
House_Finch, Breeding pair bonds usually form in winter flocks.
House_Finch, Small finch with a conical bill that it uses to crack open seeds.

House_Finch, Susceptible to House Finch eye disease, an illness that gives them swollen eyes and leaves them lethargic. If sick birds are seen around feeders, remove feeders and clean with diluted bleach solution to reduce spread.
House_Finch, Females/immature males are brown overall with blurry streaking on the back and belly.

House_Finch, Small finch with a conical seed-eating bill. Like other finches, it has a notched tail. Adult males are rosy red around the face and upper breast, with a streaky brown back, belly, and tail.
House_Finch, Note blurry brown streaks on the flanks.

House_Finch, In the western U.S., you'll find House Finches in their native habitats of deserts, grassland, chaparral, and open woods as well as city parks, backyards, urban centers, farms, and forest edges across the continent.
House_Sparrow, A chunky full-breasted bird with a round head and a stout bill. Breeding males have gray crowns, white cheeks, a black bib, and a chestnut neck.

House_Sparrow, Full-bodied bird of urban environments with a stout bill. Females are a plain buffy-brown overall with dingy gray-brown underparts. Their backs are noticeably striped with buff, black, and brown.

House_Sparrow, Song is a series of two-parted cheep or chirrup notes, given throughout much of the year. Females sometimes sing as well. Breeding males have a broad black bib, whitish cheek, and chestnut head with gray crown.

House_Sparrow, Nonbreeding males are streaked brown, black, and buffy above and dingy below. They lack the bright chestnut neck and extensive black bib of breeding males. Note yellowish bill on nonbreeding birds.
House_Sparrow, Breeding males' upperparts are richly patterned in chestnut and black.
House_Sparrow, Often comes to feeders or eats fallen seeds. Females are stocky and buffy-brown with gray-brown underparts. Note the stout bill, striped back, and broad, pale eyebrow stripe.
House_Sparrow, Juveniles look similar to females. This individual shows a yellow gape typical of a recently fledged bird.
House_Sparrow, Stocky Old World sparrow with a stout bill. The male's bib becomes darker black as the breeding season approaches.
House_Sparrow, Eats mainly seeds but may eat berries as well. Nonbreeding males have a yellowish bill and reduced black on the breast.

House_Sparrow, Females have light brownish underparts and darker upperparts with a mix of brown, black, and tan. Note also the white wingbar. The thick bill is mostly pale, but darker on top. Females are a plain buffy-brown overall with dingy gray-brown underparts. Their backs are noticeably striped with buff, black, and brown.
House_Sparrow, Compared to breeding males, nonbreeding and immature males have less black on the throat and breast and a yellowish (not black) bill.
House_Sparrow, Nests in tree cavities and birdhouses, including Purple Martin houses. House Sparrows are aggressive and may evict other species to take over their nest sites.
House_Sparrow, Feeds mostly on grains and seeds using thick bill. Readily eats millet, milo, sunflower, and other seeds at birdfeeders.

House_Sparrow, Nest in holes of buildings and other structures such as streetlights, gas-station roofs, signs, and the overhanging fixtures that hold traffic lights. Also nests in nest boxes and competes with other species for them.
House_Sparrow, Associated with human development. Found in cities, parks, zoos, suburban areas, and around farm buildings.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds have a rusty belly and a dark brown mottled back.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long upswept bill. Juveniles have a white eyebrow and a plain buffy gray belly.

Hudsonian_Godwit, A large shorebird with a very long, slightly upturned bill. Juvenile is grayish-brown above and paler brown-buff below. This species uses its long bill—orange or pinkish at the base and dark on the tip—to probe mud for invertebrates. All plumages show a pale whitish stripe above the eye.
Hudsonian_Godwit, In flight the white rump patch and dark underwings are visible.
Hudsonian_Godwit, In flight, note dark underwings and white rump patch.

Hudsonian_Godwit, Although Hudsonian Godwits nest on the ground and typically forage on the ground, they often perch in trees on the breeding grounds where wet sedge meadows intermix with spruce forests.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds have a rusty belly and a dark brown mottled back.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds have a rusty belly and a dark brown mottled back.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds have a rusty belly and a dark brown mottled back.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Most frequently seen singly or in small groups often feeding with other shorebirds during migration. Juveniles have an unmarked dusky belly.
Hudsonian_Godwit, Large shorebird with a long slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds have a rusty belly and a dark brown mottled back.
Huttons_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Broad white eyering on olive-gray head; wings and tail with yellowish edging. Two bold whitish wingbars.
Huttons_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Broad white eyering on olive-gray head; wings and tail with yellowish edging. Two bold whitish wingbars.
Huttons_Vireo, Song is a series of hoarse or burry whistled notes, sometimes with a 2-parted, rising quality.
Huttons_Vireo, Small chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Strong white eyering and two bold whitish wingbars. Prominent yellow edges to wing and tail feathers.
Huttons_Vireo, Underparts can range from mostly olive (as shown) to whitish. Wingbars are usually bold.

Huttons_Vireo, Both sexes help build the nest, which hangs from a horizontal fork in a slender branch and is made of grasses and plant fibers held together with spiderweb and camouflaged with moss, plant down, and lichen.
Huttons_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Broad white eyering on olive-gray head; wings and tail with yellowish edging. Two bold whitish wingbars.
Huttons_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Broad white eyering on olive-gray head; wings and tail with yellowish edging. Two bold whitish wingbars.
Huttons_Vireo, Breeding habitat includes conifer forests and woodlands, as well as other mostly evergreen habitats including live oak, chaparral, madrone, and pine-oak-juniper.
Huttons_Vireo, Small, chunky songbird with short neck and fairly thick bill. Broad white eyering on olive-gray head; wings and tail with yellowish edging. Two bold whitish wingbars.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.

Iceland_Gull, Highly variable gull, but in general it has a pale gray back and a slimmer bill than similar gulls. Nonbreeding Thayer's subspecies have darker gray wingtips and variable amounts of tan streaking on the head and neck.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.
Iceland_Gull, Highly variable gull. Pale first winter birds have tan streaking or spotting throughout. Note whitish wingtips that extend beyond tail when resting.
Iceland_Gull, Color of first-winter birds varies from milk chocolate to pale brown with spotting on the back and wings. Note dark wing tips that extend beyond the tail when resting.
Iceland_Gull, Most often seen in the lower 48 during the winter where they can be found along seacoasts foraging close to shore, on beaches, and sometimes on lawns, and agricultural fields.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.
Iceland_Gull, Nonbreeding adults are pale gray above with a small amount of brownish streaking on the head and neck. Note the pale wingtips on this Iceland subspecies.
Iceland_Gull, On nonbreeding adults in flight, note that the primaries have a limited amount of white on them especially at the tips.
Iceland_Gull, Some first winter birds are pale with tan streaking. Note that the outer primaries are tan and white as opposed to a solid color.
Iceland_Gull, First winter birds are highly variable ranging from dark brown to pale brown. Smaller size and slender bill are useful features to separate from similar gulls.

Iceland_Gull, Medium-sized, pale-gray gull. The color of the wingtips is highly variable, ranging from white (this individual) to dark gray. Breeding birds a red ring around the eye. Note somewhat slender bill.
Iceland_Gull, Compared to the American Herring Gulls behind, note smaller size and slimmer bill.
Iiwi, A spectacular songbird endemic to the Hawaiian Islands. Adult is brilliant vermilion with a heavy, strongly downcurved bill.
Iiwi, Immature shares adult's sickle-shaped bill and black wings and tail, but is mostly yellowish overall, with black spotting and some vermilion splotches.
Iiwi, A small, stunning songbird with a vermilion body, black wings and tail, and a salmon-colored, sickle-shaped bill.
Iiwi, Inhabits mountain forest, mostly between 1,300 and 1,900 meters (4,300 to 6,200 feet)—above the range of malaria-carrying mosquitos.
Iiwi, A vocal species, with both sexes singing and calling frequently.
Iiwi, Feeds primarily on the nectar of native plants, typically visiting a flower for only a few seconds before moving onto the next.
Iiwi, Feeds mainly on nectar from the flowers of ohia, mamane, and other native plants.

Iiwi, Feeds mainly on nectar, using its long, curved bill to reach into flowers. Immature has a patchy appearance—mostly yellow (with black feather tips that fade over time) and varying amounts of vermilion splotches.
Iiwi, A noisy species, with both sexes singing and calling frequently.
Inca_Dove, Small, slender dove with a small head and a long tail. Pale sandy gray overall with dark feather tips creating a scaled appearance.
Inca_Dove, Small, slender dove with a long, narrow tail. Gray upperparts with extensive dark scaling pattern. Outer tail feathers are white (prominent in flight).
Inca_Dove, During courtship males often stick their tail straight up in the air while fanning it.
Inca_Dove, Feeds mainly on open ground often near cover. In flight, shows bright chestnut patches in the wings and white outer tail feathers.
Inca_Dove, Occurs in dry open areas with scattered trees and shrubs. Nests in trees and takes refuge in trees when disturbed, but does not occur in forests.
Inca_Dove, Walks along the ground picking at seeds from grasses, flowers, and shrubs as well as from bird feeders.
Inca_Dove, Small, slender dove with a small head and a long tail. Pale sandy gray overall with dark feather tips creating a scaled appearance.
Inca_Dove, Small, slender dove with a small head and a long tail. Pale sandy gray overall with dark feather tips creating a scaled appearance.
Inca_Dove, Walks along the ground pushing the head forward with each step. Forages on the ground singly or in groups gently picking at the ground for seeds and grains.
Inca_Dove, Often forages in groups, typically on bare ground in grassy areas where they pick at grains and seeds.
Indigo_Bunting, Sparrow-sized, stocky bird with a short tail and a conical bill. Breeding males are bright blue overall, with slightly richer blue on the head.

Indigo_Bunting, Sparrow-sized but finchlike in appearance with a conical bill. Females/immatures are brownish, with faint streaking on the breast and sometimes a touch of blue on the wings, tail, or rump. Note white throat.
Indigo_Bunting, Sings a bright, lively song of sharp, clear, high-pitched notes, with most of the notes doubled. (First song heard from off-camera is an Ovenbird, not an Indigo Bunting.)
Indigo_Bunting, Finchlike with a short tail and conical bill. Nonbreeding males are covered in irregular patches of blue and brown.
Indigo_Bunting, Indigo Buntings migrate at night, using the stars to navigate.
Indigo_Bunting, Note tinges of blue at shoulder and in tail; otherwise, plumage is brown with faint streaks on the breast and a whitish throat.
Indigo_Bunting, Stocky with a conical bill. Females/immatures are brownish overall (darker above and paler below) with blue highlights in the wings and tail. Note tan wingbars.
Indigo_Bunting, Found in weedy and brushy areas, especially where fields meet forests.

Indigo_Bunting, Can look blotchy during molt, with patches of blue breeding plumage mixing with brownish nonbreeding plumage. Note normal bill (not grosbeak sized) and compact proportions with short tail.
Indigo_Bunting, Often feeds in flocks in weedy fields, clinging to stems and eating small seeds.

Island_Scrub-Jay, A large, dark scrub-jay found only on Santa Cruz Island off the Southern California coast. Adult has rich ultramarine upperparts with a dark gray back. Throat and central breast are grayish-white, and lower underparts are light gray.
Island_Scrub-Jay, A blue necklace partially extends onto the pale, lightly streaked breast. Note the light blue tinge to the undertail coverts at the base of the tail.
Island_Scrub-Jay, A large jay with dark blue upperparts and white-and-gray underparts. The face has a broad black mask bordered above by a thin whitish line.
Island_Scrub-Jay, Larger than California Scrub-Jays found on the nearby mainland, with deeper blue upperparts, a darker black facial mask and brown back patch, and a larger bill.
Island_Scrub-Jay, Juvenile is duller than adult, with extensive brown upperparts extending to the head.
Island_Scrub-Jay, Inhabits chaparral and oak woodlands on Santa Cruz Island. Often perches atop shrubs and trees.
Island_Scrub-Jay, An opportunistic forager that feeds on insects and small vertebrates in addition to its primary food source, acorns.
Island_Scrub-Jay, A bold, inquisitive species, unafraid of humans.
Island_Scrub-Jay, Inhabits primarily chaparral and oak woodlands.
Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Very large woodpecker with heavy, straight, pale bill. White lines down black back, with large white panels showing in the folded wings. Males had a red crest.
Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Very large woodpecker with heavy, straight, pale bill. White lines down black back, with large white panels showing in the folded wings. Females had a black crest.
Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Pairs worked together to excavate nest holes, and typically used a different nest hole each year.
Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Very large woodpecker with heavy, straight, pale bill. White lines down black back, with large white panels showing in the folded wings. Males had a red crest.
Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Occurred in extensive stands of large trees, particularly in and around swamps. Fed on beetle larvae in recently dead trees and excavated large, oval holes for nesting.

Ivory-billed_Woodpecker, Very large woodpecker with heavy bill; moved quickly and forcefully by hitching along trunks. This video (which has no sound) was recorded from the species' last stronghold, in Lousiana, in the 1930s.
Ivory_Gull, Plump gull with a thin bill. Adults are entirely white with a yellow-tipped bill and a dark eye.
Ivory_Gull, Full-bellied gull with a small head and thin bill. Immatures have a dark mask around the face and black speckling on the wings and tail.
Ivory_Gull, Ivory Gulls are highly opportunistic foragers, foraging on small fish, invertebrates, and small mammals, as well as carcasses and human trash.
Ivory_Gull, The amount of black markings on immature birds varies; some have a slight smudge on the face and light speckling on the wings and tail, while others have a dark mask and heavy speckling.
Ivory_Gull, The only all white gull. Note thin yellow-tipped bill and black eyes and legs.
Ivory_Gull, Immature has sooty speckling on the face, a dusky gray bill, and dark gray spots on the tips of wing and tail feathers.
Ivory_Gull, The amount of black speckling on the wings and tail of immatures is variable, but they usually have black-tipped flight feathers and wing coverts.
Ivory_Gull, Breeds on rocky islands and cliffs near pack ice in the high Arctic. In the winter found near pack and drift ice.
Juniper_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stout round bill. Its long body and medium-long tail makes it appear bigger than it is. Drab gray above and paler below.
Juniper_Titmouse, Plain gray bird with a prominent black eye and a feisty tuft of feathers on its head.
Juniper_Titmouse, Often calls and sings from elevated perches—a rapid and rolling series of 5 to 15 syllables that sounds almost like a video game.
Juniper_Titmouse, Small chickadee like songbird with a crest. Drab gray overall with a beady black eye that stands out on its plain face.
Juniper_Titmouse, Found in pinyon pine and juniper woodlands. Forages acrobatically with their strong feet, clinging to twigs and branches while they reach for seeds or insects.
Juniper_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees created naturally or excavated by woodpeckers. Also uses nest boxes.
Juniper_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a stout round bill. Its long body and medium-long tail makes it appear bigger than it is. Drab gray above and paler below.
Kentucky_Warbler, Medium-sized, long-legged warbler. Entirely yellow below and olive-green above. Males have black sideburns and crown.

Kentucky_Warbler, Long-legged warbler of the understory. Entirely yellow below and olive-green above. Females also have dark sideburns, but they are often grayer and the cap is often smaller and mottled black or gray.

Kentucky_Warbler, A sturdy warbler with a heavier bill, longer legs, and shorter tail than many other warbler species. Male is olive above and yellow below, with a blackish crown and face broken by a yellow eyebrow that wraps around behind the eye.
Kentucky_Warbler, Medium-sized warbler of the understory. Yellow below with a black crown and sideburns.
Kentucky_Warbler, Males and females are entirely yellow below.
Kentucky_Warbler, Song is a rapid series of two-parted notes, all on the same pitch.
Kentucky_Warbler, Breeds in bottomland hardwood forests and forests near streams with dense understory. From a distance, note yellow underparts, long legs, and black sideburns.
Killdeer, Slender shorebird with long wings and tail. Adults have 2 black breast bands.
Killdeer, Adults perform broken-wing displays to distract predators from their nests and young. Note rusty tail in flight.
Killdeer, Both adults and juveniles habitually pause while walking to bob their heads up and back down. Call note is a thin, piercing "dee" note.
Killdeer, Chicks can leave the nest as soon as their downy feathers dry out. Downy juveniles have a single breast band.
Killdeer, Nests on the ground in open areas.
Killdeer, Slender shorebird with long wings and tail. Brownish above and white below with 2 black breast bands.
Killdeer, Found in open areas such as sandbars, mudflats, grazed fields, lawns, driveways, athletic fields, parking lots, airports, and golf courses.
Killdeer, Found in dry, flat landscapes, running and halting on the ground in search of insects and earthworms.
King_Eider, Large sea duck with an oblong head and a smaller bill. Males have an ornately colored blue, green, and orange head and a black-and-white body. Note orange-red bill.
King_Eider, Large sea duck. Females have a black bill and are mottled in brown and black.
King_Eider, A spectacular sea duck of the Far North. Adult male is ornately adorned with soft blue and green on the head, a large orange plate above a bright red bill, and a black-and-white body.
King_Eider, Large sea duck. Immature males have a pale orange bill, a white chest, and a brown back.
King_Eider, In flight, note adult male's white wing and flank patches.
King_Eider, A large sea duck. Female is rich rusty brown with intricate black patterning.
King_Eider, Immature males have an orange bill but lack adult male's large knob and vibrant head coloring.
King_Eider, Adult females are rich rusty brown with paler brown cheeks and neck. Note the graceful sloping transition between the forehead and black bill.
King_Eider, Males display for females by pushing their head forward while swimming around them.
King_Eider, Breeds in the high Arctic, either along the coast or on interior lakes.
King_Eider, Large sea duck with an oblong head and a smaller bill. Males have an ornately colored blue, green, and orange head and a black-and-white body. Often gathers with other sea ducks.
King_Rail, Large, slender rail with a short tail and long bill. Upperparts are mottled brown and rusty. Flanks are barred white. Neck and breast are rusty.
King_Rail, Large and slender with a long neck and bill. Neck and chest are rusty. Flanks are barred dark and white.

King_Rail, King Rail chicks follow their parents for several weeks learning how to forage. By the time they are 4-6 weeks old they obtain about half of their food and by about 7-9 weeks find all of their own food.
King_Rail, Large, slender rail with a short tail and long bill. Upperparts are mottled brown and rusty. Flanks are barred white. Neck and breast are rusty.
King_Rail, Note white barring on flanks and overall warm rusty tones.
King_Rail, Call is a staccato series of harsh, throaty notes, more crisply delivered than Clapper Rail.
King_Rail, Occurs in tidal brackish and nontidal freshwater marshes including rice fields. Tail often held up.
King_Rail, Typically forages in densely vegetated freshwater wetlands where it can be difficult to see. Forages more frequently at dawn and dusk.
King_Rail, Forages for small aquatic crustaceans, fish, amphibians, insects, and seeds by probing bill into the water and mud.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Females are grayish above with black streaks. They are pale yellow below with dark spotting. Note thin white eye crescents.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Females can look brownish gray above. From below, females have streaking or spotting on a pale yellow belly.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Breeds in young stands of jack pine. Males are bright yellow below and steel gray above. White wing bars are present, but often not visible.
Kirtlands_Warbler, Large steel gray-and-yellow warbler with white eye crescents. Gray above with black streaks. Throat and belly is yellow. Males have a dark mark in front of the eyes.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white woodpecker. A ladder of stripes goes all the way up the back. Males have a red crown that extends from the eye to the back of the head.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white barred woodpecker with streaky sides. Females have a buffy patch in front of the eye and do not have any red markings.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white woodpecker. A ladder of stripes goes all the way up the back. Males have a red crown that extends from the eye to the back of the head.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with a red crown and whitish face. The flanks are streaked and often washed in buff.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Some females have a darker buffy wash on the belly and in front of the eye than others.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white woodpecker. A ladder of stripes goes all the way up the back. Males have a red crown that extends from the eye to the back of the head.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Agile woodpecker often found foraging on thinner trees and saplings. Males have a red crown that females lack.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Found in desert and desert scrub.
Ladder-backed_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white woodpecker. A ladder of stripes goes all the way up the back. Males have a red crown that extends from the eye to the back of the head.
Lapland_Longspur, Chunky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black crown, face, and bib and a rusty nape.

Lapland_Longspur, Chunky sparrowlike bird. Nonbreeding birds have a heavily streaked back and crown with a clean nape. A dark line outlines the ear and the flanks are streaked. Note rusty patch in the wings.
Lapland_Longspur, Breeds in Arctic tundra in wet meadows, grassy tussocks, and scrub. Sings a series of loud, squeaky, jingling notes from low perches near the ground or during flight.
Lapland_Longspur, Chunky bird with a stout bill. Nonbreeding birds are streaked above with a black border around the ear, streaked flanks, and a dark often smudgy breast band.
Lapland_Longspur, Chunky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black crown, face, and bib and a rusty nape.
Lapland_Longspur, In winter, often found in mixed flocks with Horned Larks and Snow Buntings.
Lapland_Longspur, Breeds in wet tundra meadows. Breeding males have a black hood, rusty nape, and yellow bill.
Lapland_Longspur, Chunky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black crown, face, and bib and a rusty nape.
Lapland_Longspur, Chunky grassland bird with a stout bill. Breeding males have a black crown, face, and bib and a rusty nape.
Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with very thick, bluish gray bill. Breeding males are mostly black with a large white patch in the wing and white corners to the tail.

Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with very thick, bluish gray bill. Females and young birds have thick brown streaking on the breast. They have a pale stripe over the eye and a dark "mustache" stripe with a white throat patch.
Lark_Bunting, To separate from other brown, streaky songbirds, note very thick, bluish gray bill and long white patch along the folded wing.
Lark_Bunting, Large, chunky sparrow with thick bill. Nonbreeding males are dark brown and streaky, with the same large white patch in the wing that breeding males have.

Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with thick bill and relatively short tail. Females and immatures are heavily streaked with brown, with white edges to the wing coverts that form a streaky white patch, especially visible in flight.
Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with very thick, bluish gray bill. Breeding males are mostly black with a large white patch in the wing and white corners to the tail.
Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with very thick, bluish gray bill. Breeding males are mostly black with a large white patch in the wing and white corners to the tail.
Lark_Bunting, Large sparrow with very thick, bluish gray bill. Breeding males are mostly black with a large white patch in the wing and white corners to the tail.
Lark_Bunting, Occurs in grasslands, prairies, sagebrush and other shrublands, desert grasslands, and stands of mesquite, hackberry, and willow.

Lark_Sparrow, Large, pale sparrow with a thick bill. Adults have very striking head pattern with a chestnut crown and cheek patch, a pale stripe over the eye, and a strong black malar or mustache stripe.  Note the black spot in center of the white breast.
Lark_Sparrow, The long, rounded tail has white corners that flash in flight. The chestnut crown and cheek with a pale eyebrow and a dark mustache stripe are distinctive.
Lark_Sparrow, Large sparrow with bold, complex head pattern of dark, light, and reddish stripes. Call note is a thin chip.

Lark_Sparrow, Large, pale sparrow with a thick bill. Adults have very striking head pattern with a chestnut crown and cheek patch, a pale stripe over the eye, and a strong black malar or mustache stripe.  Note the black spot in center of the white breast.
Lark_Sparrow, Adults have a colorful head pattern and black streaks on the back. Juveniles have brown-on-white head pattern and streaks on the breast.

Lark_Sparrow, Large, pale sparrow with a thick bill. Adults have very striking head pattern with a chestnut crown and cheek patch, a pale stripe over the eye, and a strong black malar or mustache stripe.  Note the black spot in center of the white breast.

Lark_Sparrow, Large, pale sparrow with a thick bill. Adults have very striking head pattern with a chestnut crown and cheek patch, a pale stripe over the eye, and a strong black malar or mustache stripe.  Note the black spot in center of the white breast.
Lark_Sparrow, Large sparrow with long tail and rounded tail. Immatures have similar face pattern to adults but lack the chestnut coloration to the crown and cheek.

Lark_Sparrow, Large, pale sparrow with a thick bill. Adults have very striking head pattern with a chestnut crown and cheek patch, a pale stripe over the eye, and a strong black malar or mustache stripe.  Note the black spot in center of the white breast.
Lark_Sparrow, Occurs in prairie, grassland, agricultural areas, desert scrub, sagebrush, and other open areas.
Laughing_Gull, Medium-sized gull with a thin and slightly drooping bill. Breeding adults have a black head, thin white eye crescents, and a red bill.
Laughing_Gull, Nonbreeding adults have a bit of black smudging behind the eye, but are otherwise white with a medium gray back. Note the small white spots on the primaries.
Laughing_Gull, Medium-sized gull with dark hood and dark gray back. Commonly forages with other species of gulls, terns, and shorebirds.
Laughing_Gull, Medium-sized gull with a thin, slightly drooping bill. Juveniles are brownish, paler on the head and neck, with white eye crescents.
Laughing_Gull, First winter gulls are starting to acquire gray feathers on their back and wings. The head and neck remains gray and smudgy. Note slightly drooping bill and dark primaries.
Laughing_Gull, Nests on sand, typically near or under vegetation, where eggs can be very difficult to see. In hot sun, gulls and other birds open their bills and pant to cool off.
Laughing_Gull, Second winter gulls have a gray wash on their neck and chest with darker gray smudging on the head.
Laughing_Gull, In flight, note the dark underside of the primaries on breeding adults
Laughing_Gull, This bird's crouching posture while running with partially spread wings is a display intended to signal aggression or to claim ownership of a space.
Laughing_Gull, First winter gulls in flight show dark primaries and a wide dark tail band.

Laughing_Gull, Nonbreeding adults are mostly white and gray with a bit of gray smudging on the head above and behind the eye. Note the dark primaries with little to no white spots on the folding wings.
Laughing_Gull, Gathers in large groups when food is abundant, such as eggs from horseshoe crabs. Gives frequent loud, shrill cries.
Laughing_Gull, Found in groups in beaches, salt marshes, mangroves, or on agricultural fields or landfills near the coast.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Females are grayish brown with a faint yellow wash on the belly.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, A small songbird with a conical bill and slight forked tail. Male is mostly gray, with a black face and yellow on the breast, upper belly, and wings.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Males are gray with a black face, yellow belly patch, and yellow wing patches. Tends to be nomadic outside of the breeding season.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Found in open woodlands, chaparral, and brushy areas.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Females are grayish overall with yellow wing bars. Note typical forked tail and pointed bill of finches.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Note yellow wing edging on both the male and female. This video has no audio.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Small finch with a pointed bill and forked tail. Males have a black face and a bright yellow belly patch.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, From the side, males appear gray overall with yellow wing patches and a black face.
Lawrences_Goldfinch, Makes erratic movements during the nonbreeding season.
Laysan_Albatross, Very large seabird with narrow, pointed wings. Long, thick, hooked bill is pale. Head and rump white, with dark tail and dark shading on the face.

Laysan_Albatross, Very large seabird with narrow, pointed wings and distinctive looping flight style; rarely flaps wings. Underwings are patchy white with variable amounts of dark. Grayish smudge on face.
Laysan_Albatross, Nests on the ground on islands in the Hawaiian island chain and off Mexico; flies to the Gulf of Alaska to forage. Chicks take about 6 months to fledge.
Laysan_Albatross, Forages at sea, either by landing and dabbling, or by picking food items from the surface in flight. Note all-brown back and grayish wash on face.

Laysan_Albatross, Chicks are wispy brown with pale or blond highlights and a dark bill. Laysan Albatrosses nest among short vegetation, mainly in the remote Northwest Hawaiian Islands; also small colonies on Kauai and Oahu and on a few Mexican Islands.
Laysan_Albatross, Feeds at sea on squid and fish as well as flying-fish eggs and other items attached to floating debris.
Laysan_Albatross, Older chicks tend to retain fuzzy brown head and neck down while molting into flight feathers before fledging.
Laysan_Albatross, Spends most of the year at sea, sometimes in flocks especially around fishing boats. More likely to sit on the sea surface during calm winds when dynamic soaring is more difficult.
Laysan_Albatross, Spends most of the year on the open ocean. Characteristic looping flight style takes advantage of prevailing winds to fly while rarely flapping wings.

Lazuli_Bunting, Small, stocky songbird with a cone-shaped bill and a gently sloping forehead. Breeding males are brilliant blue above with a pumpkin-colored breast and a white belly. Note white shoulder patch.
Lazuli_Bunting, Females/immature males are warm brown above with blue tints on the wings and tail and an unstreaked pale cinnamon breast. Note buffy wingbars.
Lazuli_Bunting, Perches upright and sings from exposed perches in low trees, shrubs, or wires. Males sing a complex series of jumbling and squeaky notes and give a sharp, metallic pik.
Lazuli_Bunting, Nonbreeding males have a pumpkin-colored breast, but their backs and heads are mottled blue and tan.

Lazuli_Bunting, Small, stocky songbird with a cone-shaped bill and a gently sloping forehead. Breeding males are brilliant blue above with a pumpkin-colored breast and a white belly. Note white shoulder patch.
Lazuli_Bunting, Sings a complex series of jumbled notes.
Lazuli_Bunting, Small, finchlike, stocky songbird with a cone-shaped bill. Females/immature males are warm grayish brown above, with an unstreaked pale cinnamon or tan breast.
Lazuli_Bunting, Male Lazuli Buntings perch upright and sing from exposed perches in low trees, shrubs, or wires. Brilliant blue head and pumpkin breast are distinctive.
Lazuli_Bunting, Frequents bird feeders, especially ones that offer white proso millet, sunflower seeds, or nyjer/thistle seeds.
Lazuli_Bunting, Breeds in brushy hillsides, areas near streams, wooded valleys, thickets and hedges along agricultural fields, recently burned areas, and residential gardens of western North America.
Lazuli_Bunting, Females/immatures are warm grayish brown above, with an unstreaked pale cinnamon or tan breast.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.
LeContes_Sparrow, Song is a fine, hissing grasshopper-like buzz, starting and ending with a faint "tik."
LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill. Overall rather buffy with a gray cheek patch and a dark eyeline that gets wider toward the back of the head.
LeContes_Sparrow, Juveniles have similar features as adults, but with less distinct markings.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.

LeContes_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a small bill and a buffy wash on the face and breast. The eyeline is dark and wider toward the back of the head. The eyebrow is brighter than the rest of the face.
LeContes_Thrasher, Pale sandy gray overall with unmarked wings, a dark eye, and a curved bill. Often holds its long tail up.
LeContes_Thrasher, Often walks or runs on the ground with its tail held up in sparsely vegetated desert flats.
LeContes_Thrasher, Long-tailed sandy gray songbird with a long curved bill. About the size of a Northern Mockingbird. Note pale cinnamon undertail coverts and plain wings.
LeContes_Thrasher, Pale sandy gray overall with pale cinnamon undertail tail coverts. Found in sparsely vegetated desert areas often with saltbush.

Leachs_Storm-Petrel, A small seabird with long, angular wings, a strongly notched tail, and a broad pale "carpal bar" making a diagonal line across the wing and contrasting with brownish upperparts. Most populations have a white rump with a dark line running through the middle, though this line can be difficult to notice at distance.
Leachs_Storm-Petrel, In flight, note long, angled wings with a pale carpal bar running diagonally from the leading edge to the trailing edge.

Leachs_Storm-Petrel, A medium-sized storm-petrel with a distinctive bouncy, erratic flight. Note also the pale carpal bar, white rump (with dark dividing line just visible at times in this video), and notched tail.

Leachs_Storm-Petrel, The dark-rumped "Chapman's" subspecies group breeds only on a few islands off the coast of Baja California and ranges north to waters off the California coast. Note the long, angled wings, pale carpal bar, and notched tail.
Leachs_Storm-Petrel, Normally occurs over deep ocean waters far from land. Forages by hovering and then picking individual prey items (fish and crustaceans) from the water surface.
Leachs_Storm-Petrel, Often best detected and identified at sea by erratic, bounding flight style, which is reminiscent of a Common Nighthawk.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Females have a dark brown back and crown.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Bittern, Flies with neck tucked and feet trailing behind. Flight feathers are dark.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Bittern, Juveniles look like females, but with a paler and browner crown and back and bolder stripes on the neck.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Bittern, Small heron with a long, pointed yellow bill and hunchbacked appearance. Males have a dark green, almost black crown and back. Neck is striped chestnut and white.
Least_Flycatcher, Small, compact flycatcher with a bold white eyering and 2 white wingbars.
Least_Flycatcher, Small and compact flycatcher with a round head. Grayish olive above with a dusky breast and a bold white eyering.
Least_Flycatcher, Sings incessantly throughout the summer, tossing its head back with each "chebec" note.
Least_Flycatcher, Small and compact flycatcher with a round head. Grayish olive above with a dusky breast and a bold white eyering.
Least_Flycatcher, Congregates in clusters in deciduous forests during the breeding season and sings incessantly throughout the summer. Note bold white eyering.
Least_Flycatcher, On the breeding grounds, nests in clusters, creating a flycatcher neighborhood with anywhere from 2 to 30 territories per cluster.
Least_Flycatcher, Breeds in deciduous and mixed forests of all ages including second-growth and mature forests.
Least_Flycatcher, Small and compact flycatcher with a white eyering found in deciduous and mixed forests of all ages.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Often sunbathes by fluffing up its rear feathers to expose the black skin beneath to absorb the solar radiation.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small waterbird with a yellow eye and fluffy backside. Nonbreeding birds are grayish brown.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Small dark gray waterbird with a yellow eye and a small thin bill.
Least_Grebe, Found in temporary or permanent wetlands, including ponds, lakes, ditches, and slow-moving rivers.
Least_Sandpiper, Small sandpiper with yellow legs and a thin slightly curved bill. Breeding birds have rusty speckling on the back.
Least_Sandpiper, Small sandpiper with yellow legs. Nonbreeding birds are brownish with a smudgy brown breast.
Least_Sandpiper, Very small sandpiper with yellowish legs and thin, slightly drooped bill. Favors muddy habitats.
Least_Sandpiper, Juveniles have brighter rusty-colored speckling on the back than breeding adults.
Least_Sandpiper, Breeding birds have a heavily streaked throat and breast. Note yellow legs and small size.
Least_Sandpiper, Juveniles have yellow legs, like adults—but note that mud can obscure leg color. Juveniles have brighter rusty-colored speckling on the back than breeding adults.
Least_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding birds have a smudgy throat unlike similar sandpipers. Tends to have a more crouched posture when foraging.
Least_Sandpiper, In flight, note short, dark wings and small overall size.
Least_Sandpiper, Forages on mudflats and the edges of water bodies. Tends to favor muddier shores and estuaries than other sandpipers.
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Smallest tern in North America. Thin yellow bill and yellow legs during the breeding season help separate it from similar species.
Least_Tern, Very small, neatly marked tern with white forehead and yellow bill (often with black tip).
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Small with narrow, pointed wings. Breeding birds have a black crown and a white forehead. In flight, note black edge on outer flight feathers.
Least_Tern, Immature birds have a small smudgy black patch behind the eye and a dark bill unlike adults, but they still have yellow legs.
Least_Tern, Very small tern. Juveniles have a barred or scaly looking back and yellow legs. The crown patch on this bird is small and smudgy brown; others can have a darker black partial crown.
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Smallest North American tern, with a yellow bill and white forehead. In flight, note pointed wings and black outer edge on the primaries.
Least_Tern, Found along seacoasts, beaches, bays, estuaries, lagoons, lakes, and rivers. Breeds on sandy or gravelly beaches and banks of rivers or lakes.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A large, dark-backed gull with long wings and yellow legs. Adults show a large red spot on the bill and moderate contrast between the dark gray back and black primaries. In late summer and fall, adults molt their wing feathers—the worn tips to the old, unreplaced outer primaries are visible here.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A large, high-contrast gull with long wings, yellow legs, and a dark gray back; adults show a large red spot on the yellow bill. Subspecies identification is very complicated away from the breeding grounds. The European subspecies intermedius shows dark gray upperparts that are intermediate in shade between the paler birds of northwestern Europe ( graellsii ) and the black-backed birds from the Baltic Sea and northeastern Europe ( fuscus ).

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, Long wings, yellow legs, and dark upperparts combine to distinguish this adult. Breeding birds from the Baltic Sea and northeastern Europe (fuscus) are truly blackish above rather than slate gray. This is the darkest-backed of all subspecies.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A long-winged, dark gray-backed gull with yellowish legs. The subspecies found breeding in western Siberia between the Kola and Taimyr peninsula (subspecies heuglini ) apparently interbreeds with "Taimyr" Lesser Black-backed Gull ( taimyrensis ) at the eastern edge of its range. Subspecies identification of Lesser Black-backed Gulls away from each subspecies' breeding range can be difficult or impossible.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A large but slim, long-winged gull. Young immatures like this 1st-winter bird are pale-headed, crisply checkered dark and white, and usually show a fully black bill through the first winter. The brown, black, and white plumage is relatively cold-toned.
Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, Large gull with long wings and a slim black bill; juveniles are cold-toned and show dark feathers crisply edged in white on the back and upperwing.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A long-winged, yellow-legged gull showing moderate contrast between the slate gray upperwing and black wingtip. Adults show a restricted amount of white near the wingtip and a red spot on the bill, but may also show immature-like black bill markings.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, As juveniles, these slim, long-winged gulls show cold plumage tones and feature an all dark bill, blackish primaries and secondaries, and a dark tail band that contrasts with a whitish rump and tail base. They appear crisply marked with neat, even feather edgings.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, The wings of first cycle birds are dark below and contrast strongly with the pale body. Birds of this age show black bills and whitish bodies marked with dark splotches. Note the leg color—young immatures show pink legs that gradually become yellow after 2–3 years.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A dark-backed gull with yellow legs and a slim white crescent near the tail formed by the tertial tips. Winter adults show dusky streaks on the head. Wing molt often carries into mid-winter, and late-molting adults like this often appear short-winged because of the new, growing outer primary feathers.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, As far as large gulls go, this species appears slim due to its both long wings and long legs. Most subspecies (including heuglini , shown here) show moderate contrast between the dark gray upperparts and the black primary tips.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, Perhaps because of their long distance migrations, these gulls wander widely and can be expected to appear nearly anywhere on the globe. This pale-backed, dark-eyed individual with long fleshy-yellow legs was seen in Nova Scotia and fits the description of Taimyr Gull (subspecies taimyrensis ), though identification of large gull taxa so far out of range is usually either speculative or impossible.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, As they repeatedly molt over the course of 3-4 years, these gulls progress from the checkered juvenile plumage to gray-backed, white-bodied adults. This presumed second winter gull shows replaced, gray-toned upperparts and round-tipped primaries. Note the mostly white head and the mostly black bill, which help to distinguish immatures from other immature large gulls.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, A long-winged, dark-gray backed gull with pale eyes and yellowish legs. Older immatures show a mix of immature and adult plumage and soft parts characteristics. By focusing on the degree of contrast between the plain, adult-like back feathers and the black primary tips, you can judge the relative darkness of the upperparts, and this can help sort through various local large gull options.

Lesser_Black-backed_Gull, Because of their long distance migrations and extended exposure to sun and abrasion, it's very important for large gulls to replace their flight feathers each year. In gulls, molt generally starts near the middle of the wing and progresses outward through the primaries. This older immature bird is midway through replacing its primaries - the dark, ragged outer primaries are old, unreplaced feathers, and the four gray feathers with white tips near the middle of the wing are newly replaced inner primaries. With older immature large gulls, the exact gray tone of the plain adult-like back feathers can be very helpful for identification—compare them to the black wingtips to judge the contrast between these feather tracts.

Lesser_Goldfinch, Small finch with a conical bill. Adult males are yellow below with a glossy black cap and white patches in the wings. Their backs can be solid glossy black or dull green, particularly west of the Rockies.

Lesser_Goldfinch, Small finch with a short, conical bill and notched tail. Adult males are yellow below with a glossy black cap and white patches in the wings. Back color varies from dull green to black depending on region.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Feeds in small groups, moving through low weeds, shrubs, and trees to take mainly small seeds, as well as buds, flowers, or fruits. Often visits feeders.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Females/immatures have olive backs, dull yellow underparts, and black wings marked by two whitish wingbars and a white rectangle on the edge of the wing.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Adult males in the western U.S. have green backs.
Lesser_Goldfinch, The conspicuous white wing patch helps differentiate female/immature Lesser Goldfinch from the similar American Goldfinch.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Individuals east of the Rockies and south into Central America have solid black backs and bright yellow underparts.

Lesser_Goldfinch, Females/immatures are drabber and lack the male's black crown. They are olive above and yellow below, sometimes with faint dusky streaks on the crown. Note white rectangle on the wing.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Forages in low vegetation in search of seeds, buds, flowers, and fruits.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Adult male has a large white wing patch.
Lesser_Goldfinch, Feeds in large groups in weedy fields, budding treetops, and the brush of open areas and edges.

Lesser_Nighthawk, A long-winged and long-tailed nighthawk with rounded wings. Males have white bar across the wingtips (farther out on the wings that the similar Common Nighthawk) and a white band across the tail.

Lesser_Nighthawk, A long-winged and long-tailed nighthawk with rounded wings. Males have white bar across the wingtips (farther out on the wings that the similar Common Nighthawk) and a white band across the tail.
Lesser_Nighthawk, Lesser Nighthawks roost motionless on the ground or in trees and shrubs during the day.
Lesser_Nighthawk, Lesser Nighthawks are cryptically-colored in browns and grays and easily blend in with their surroundings.
Lesser_Nighthawk, Females have a smaller cream-colored band across the wingtips and lack the male's band across the tail.

Lesser_Nighthawk, A long-winged and long-tailed nighthawk with rounded wings. Males have white bar across the wingtips (farther out on the wings that the similar Common Nighthawk) and a white band across the tail.

Lesser_Nighthawk, A long-winged and long-tailed nighthawk with rounded wings. Males have white bar across the wingtips (farther out on the wings that the similar Common Nighthawk) and a white band across the tail.

Lesser_Nighthawk, A long-winged and long-tailed nighthawk with rounded wings. Males have white bar across the wingtips (farther out on the wings that the similar Common Nighthawk) and a white band across the tail.

Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Barred grayish brown-and-white chickenlike grouse with a short tail. Males raise the feathers on the side of their neck to expose bare patches of reddish skin, which they inflate to produce booming sounds.
Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Barred grayish brown-and-white chickenlike grouse with a short tail and small head. Females have a pale throat and eyeline.
Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Males gather on display grounds, where they compete for females by performing spectacular displays.
Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Barred grayish brown-and-white chickenlike grouse. Juveniles look like females with a pale throat and eyeline.

Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Barred grayish brown-and-white chickenlike grouse with a short tail. Males raise the feathers on the side of their neck to expose bare patches of reddish skin, which they inflate to produce booming sounds.
Lesser_Prairie-Chicken, Found in native prairies.

Lesser_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a tall, peaked head. Glossy black head, front, and rear with a gray back and white sides. Head is purplish-iridescent, but is only visible with ideal lighting.

Lesser_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a tall, peaked head and a fairly straight bill. Females are rich brown overall, with a darker head and white patch next to the bill. Note that the back of the head is flat.
Lesser_Scaup, Found on lakes and ponds during migration and winter. Note the peaked head and that the back of the head is flat.
Lesser_Scaup, All plumages have a white wing stripe that extends halfway along the wing (through the secondaries), but usually does not reach the primary feathers.
Lesser_Scaup, Nonbreeding males have a dark head with a yellow eye. The body is mottled brown-gray.

Lesser_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a peaked head and a smallish straight bill. Females can show only small amounts of white on the face like this individual. They acquire yellow eyes with age.
Lesser_Scaup, Medium-sized diving duck with a peak to the back of the head (inconspicuous in some postures), and head that is often darker than body. Can be very difficult to tell from Greater Scaup.
Lesser_Scaup, Often uses shallow freshwater lakes and ponds on migration. In winter also occurs in bays, estuaries, and lagoons.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Dainty shorebird with bright yellow legs and a thin bill. Breeding birds have variable amounts of streaking on the breast with only a bit of barring on the flanks.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Small-headed and dainty shorebird with bright yellow legs and a thin bill. Nonbreeding birds have sparse streaking on the neck that often looks smudgy.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Slender shorebird with long legs and a fairly long bill, although typically shorter and more slender than Greater Yellowlegs' bill. This video has no audio.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Medium-sized, dainty shorebird with a thin bill and bright yellow legs. Juveniles have less distinct markings on the breast, which tends to make the breast look smudgy.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Slender shorebird with a thin bill. Juveniles often have fine spotting on the back and a cap-headed look.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, In flight, note white rump and plain wings.
Lesser_Yellowlegs, Breeds in open boreal forest with scattered shallow wetlands. Winters in a wide variety of shallow fresh and saltwater habitats.

Lewiss_Woodpecker, The Lewis's Woodpecker is a bulky pink and green woodpecker with a red face that often appears dark depending on lighting. It looks like a woodpecker, but forages like a flycatcher.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, A large, dark woodpecker with a pink belly and red face. Occasionally visits feeders.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, Often perches on posts or wires from which it flycatches for insects.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, A green-backed woodpecker with a pink belly, a gray collar, and a red face patch.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, Can appear black, especially at a distance and in poor light. Unlike other woodpeckers, often catches insects on the wing. In flight often looks and flies like a crow.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, Hitches up trees like a woodpecker, but also perches perpendicular on branches or on wires similar to a songbird.

Lewiss_Woodpecker, The Lewis's Woodpecker is a bulky pink and green woodpecker with a red face that often appears dark depending on lighting. It looks like a woodpecker, but forages like a flycatcher.
Lewiss_Woodpecker, Nests in cavities in dead and decaying trees in oak woodlands, open ponderosa pine forests, and woodlands near streams.
Limpkin, Tall, long-legged bird of marshes and swampy forests with a long neck and a long and heavy yellowish bill. Brown overall with white spotting on the back and sides.
Limpkin, Tall, long-legged bird of marshes and swampy forests with a long neck and a long and heavy yellowish bill. Brown overall with white spotting on the back and sides.

Limpkin, An Apple Snail specialist, Limpkins use their strong decurved bills to pry open these snails before eating them. Other food items taken include frogs, lizards, crustaceans, worms, and aquatic insects.
Limpkin, Uses the long and heavy bill to break apart the shells of apple snails, its primary food source.
Limpkin, Long and heavy yellowish bill used to open apple snails. Long neck is streaked in white giving it an overall pale appearance.
Limpkin, Typically inhabits freshwater marshes, swamp forests, and pond or lake shores.
Limpkin, Large. Brown overall with a long, pale neck and a long, heavy bill. Walks on top of floating mats of vegetation as well as up branches leaning over water.
Limpkin, Juvenile is similar to adult, but with narrower spots, which makes them look more streaked than spotted.
Limpkin, By two weeks of age, young birds begin to show foraging behavior, but are not able to feed themselves efficiently until five weeks of age.
Limpkin, Tall, long-legged bird of marshes and swampy forests with a long neck and a long and heavy yellowish bill. Brown overall with white spotting on the back and sides.
Limpkin, Limpkins have shallow wingbeats when flying—the upward strokes are quick and "snappy," while the downstrokes are slower. Flies with head and neck extended with legs trailing behind.
Lincolns_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with fairly small bill. Neat appearance with fine, crisp streaks, gray face with pale eyering, and buffy wash across breast.

Lincolns_Sparrow, Males sing a rich wrenlike song of trills, gurgles, and buzzes. Each song starts off with 2 or 3 bell-like notes before bursting into bubbly trills and gurgles that rapidly change pitch.

Lincolns_Sparrow, Males sing a rich wrenlike song of trills, gurgles, and buzzes. Each song starts off with 2 or 3 bell-like notes before bursting into bubbly trills and gurgles that rapidly change pitch.
Lincolns_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with fairly small bill. Crisp dark streaks on buffy breast transition to unmarked white belly.
Lincolns_Sparrow, Gray face, pale eyering, and very fine streaks on buffy breast are distinctive.
Lincolns_Sparrow, Gray face, pale eyering, and very fine streaks on buffy breast are distinctive.
Lincolns_Sparrow, Breeds in wet meadows among dense shrubs, particularly willows. Also found in wetlands with aspen and cottonwood, and in black spruce–tamarack bogs.
Little_Blue_Heron, Smaller, long-legged heron with a daggerlike bill. Adults have a purple-maroon head and neck and a dark slaty-blue body. Bill is two-toned, with blue-gray at the base.
Little_Blue_Heron, Juveniles are entirely white, except for vague dusky tips to the outer primaries. Note two-toned bill.
Little_Blue_Heron, Wades in shallow wetlands or stands patiently as it stalks fish, amphibians, crustaceans, and insects.
Little_Blue_Heron, Immature birds that are molting into adult plumage are a patchwork of white and blue.
Little_Blue_Heron, Flies with its neck tucked in and legs trailing behind. Often appears all dark, especially from a distance and in poor light.

Little_Blue_Heron, Flies with slow, steady wingbeats, usually with its neck and head pulled back against the body. The dusky tips on the outer primaries of juveniles are often easier to see in flight.

Little_Blue_Heron, Little Blue Herons are stand-and-wait foragers, patiently watching the water with their necks extended and bills pointed downward for small fish, amphibians, or aquatic invertebrates.
Little_Blue_Heron, When not foraging often stands with its neck tucked, in a hunchbacked posture.
Little_Blue_Heron, Found in swamps, marshes, ponds, streams, lagoons, tidal flats, canals, ditches, fish hatcheries, and flooded fields.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, During migration Little Gulls forage along large lakes or coastal waters for small fish.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, Note slender black bill and small size. The crown and ear patch on some juveniles is brownish black.
Little_Gull, Little Gulls regularly associate with Bonaparte's Gulls and other gull species at roosting sites — usually on beaches or mudflats.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, Small, black-headed gull with red legs, a black bill, and dark underwings.
Little_Gull, First-summer birds have a thin black "M" pattern on the back and a black band on the tail.
Little_Gull, Nonbreeding birds are pale gray above with a white tail. In flight, shows dark underwings. Note dark ear patch and smudgy crown.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with a thick, hooked bill. It has a gray head with a black mask that wraps across the top of the bill.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Chunky songbird with a thick, hooked bill and a long tail. White wing patch often visible at rest. Sometimes shows faint barring on the whitish undersides.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Often perches on exposed twigs or powerlines. Song is variable and often weak, sometimes sounds like a hiccup.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Frequently sits on low, exposed perches to scan for rodents, lizards, birds, and insects.
Loggerhead_Shrike, In flight, white wing flashes are prominent. Outer tail feathers also flash white.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Chunky songbird with a thick, hooked bill. Young birds are more brownish than adults, with stronger brownish barring on the chest.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Often hunts from exposed perches such as telephone wires and fencelines.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Eats small animals including insects, birds, and reptiles; impales prey on thorns and barbed wire to save for later.
Loggerhead_Shrike, Lives in open, brushy habitats including grasslands, desert scrub, prairies, savannas, and agricultural areas.
Long-billed_Curlew, Large, long-legged shorebird with a very long curved bill. Underparts are washed with a pale cinnamon color.
Long-billed_Curlew, In flight, note rusty wing patches.
Long-billed_Curlew, A large, long-legged shorebird with a very long, thin curved bill. Pale cinnamon below, with brown speckling and barring above.
Long-billed_Curlew, Very long curved bill is distinctive. Note heavy football-shaped body, plain crown, and pale cinnamon wash on the belly.
Long-billed_Curlew, Large, long-billed shorebird with cinnamon underwings.
Long-billed_Curlew, During migration and breeding season, often occurs in areas with sparse, short grasses, including shortgrass and mixed-grass prairies and agricultural fields.
Long-billed_Curlew, Uses its long bill to probe into underground burrows for crabs and shrimp.
Long-billed_Curlew, Breeds in areas with sparse, short grasses, including shortgrass and mixed-grass prairies as well as agricultural fields.
Long-billed_Curlew, Uses its long, curved bill to probe into burrows or between rocks for crabs and shrimp, which it swallows whole.

Long-billed_Dowitcher, Front heavy, chunky shorebird with a long bill (twice as long as its head). Breeding birds are bright cinnamon below and darker brown above. Has a distinctive sewing-machine-like feeding behavior.

Long-billed_Dowitcher, Front heavy, chunky shorebird with a long bill (twice as long as its head). Breeding birds are bright cinnamon below and darker brown above. Has a distinctive sewing-machine-like feeding behavior.
Long-billed_Dowitcher, Note rather hunchbacked profile while foraging. Breeding birds are rich cinnamon below barred with black.
Long-billed_Dowitcher, Juveniles are grayish overall with rusty edging on feathers. Note rather front heavy look.
Long-billed_Dowitcher, In flight, white upper rump patch distinguishes it from many other shorebirds except Short-billed Dowitchers.
Long-billed_Dowitcher, Front heavy, chunky shorebird with a round underbelly. Juveniles have a grayish breast and are mottled brown and cinnamon above.

Long-billed_Dowitcher, Nonbreeding birds are grayish overall. When foraging the back looks humped, unlike the flat-backed Short-billed Dowitcher. Note chunky, front-heavy posture and sewing-machine-like head motion while feeding.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Forages primarily on the ground. Brown overall with dark streaks on belly. Yellow eye stands out on gray cheek.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-billed_Thrasher, About the size of a robin. Sings from conspicuous perches, otherwise stays closer to the ground. Note long tail and bill.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Found in woodlands near streams and dense thickets.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-billed_Thrasher, Hefty with a long tail and bill. Other stand out features include gray face, yellow eye, and heavily streaked belly. More brown than rusty like the similar Brown Thrasher.
Long-eared_Owl, Long and slender owl with prominent ear tufts, an orangish facial disc, and yellow eyes.
Long-eared_Owl, Spends the day roosting in dense parts of pines and other trees.
Long-eared_Owl, Roosts in the dense parts of pines and other trees, often near the trunk of the tree.
Long-eared_Owl, In flight, note large rounded wings and streaked underparts. Hunts above open grasslands and shrublands.
Long-eared_Owl, Juveniles are fluffy with downy feathers and a prominent V between their eyes.
Long-eared_Owl, Long ear tufts, orangish face, and yellow eyes stand out on this owl. Roosts in trees during the day.
Long-tailed_Duck, Small sea duck with a small bill and very long, slender tail feathers. White head outlines dark face and neck; white plumes cover brown back.
Long-tailed_Duck, Small sea duck with a small bill. Back, wings and breast are brown, contrasting with white head and smudgy brown cheek.
Long-tailed_Duck, Often found in groups on coastal marine waters and large freshwater lakes during the winter.
