Long-tailed_Duck, Small sea duck with a small bill and very long tail feathers. Dark head and neck outlines white face patch (reverse of nonbreeding male's pattern).
Long-tailed_Duck, In flight, note long tail. White collar, dark breast, and white belly are distinctive.
Long-tailed_Duck, Small sea duck with a small bill, all dark wings, and white sides on the rump.
Long-tailed_Duck, Female lacks the male's long tail. Mostly white face with dark cheek and fairly small, straight bill.
Long-tailed_Duck, Immature males lack the long tail and white back feathers, but have yellow-orange tip to bill like adult males.
Long-tailed_Duck, Females lack the long tail. Brownish overall with white patch around and behind eye, and a white collar.
Long-tailed_Duck, Small sea duck with a small, straight bill. Adult male has long tail; female lacks it.
Long-tailed_Duck, In winter usually found in salt water, especially sandy coastlines. Often occurs in flocks.

Long-tailed_Jaeger, Slender seabird with thin, pointed wings. Neat black cap with creamy wash on throat and nape. Underside of wings show little to no white flash. Breeding adults have very long tail streamers.

Long-tailed_Jaeger, Slender seabird with thin, pointed wings. Neat black cap with creamy wash on throat and nape. Underside of wings show little to no white flash. Breeding adults have very long tail streamers.
Long-tailed_Jaeger, First summer light-morphs tend to be more grayish and less brownish than other first summer jaegers. Note long, slender, pointed wings and relatively small body.

Long-tailed_Jaeger, Slender but powerful seabird with long, pointed wings, neat black cap, and relatively short, thick bill. Compared with other jaegers, the white flash in the wings is smaller and confined to 2-3 outermost primary feathers. Outside the breeding season, few adults show the long tail streamers.
Long-tailed_Jaeger, Juvenile jaegers are very difficult to identify. Shape and proportions are the best features, including long, slender wings, slim body, and short, thick bill.
Long-tailed_Jaeger, The smallest and most ternlike of all jaegers: note the long, slender wings with white in the outer primaries. Only breeding adults have the very long tail streamers.

Long-tailed_Jaeger, Slender seabird with thin, pointed wings. Neat black cap with creamy wash on throat and nape. Underside of wings show little to no white flash. Breeding adults have very long tail streamers.

Long-tailed_Jaeger, Slender seabird with thin, pointed wings. Neat black cap with creamy wash on throat and nape. Underside of wings show little to no white flash. Breeding adults have very long tail streamers.

Long-tailed_Tit, A small black-and-white songbird with a tiny bill and an extremely long tail. Adults in northern Europe and across much of Asia have a bright white head, clean white underparts, and pink on the scapulars.
Long-tailed_Tit, Adults in much of Europe (and also in East Asia) have a broad black band over each eye, a black nape and mantle, and a pinkish wash on the scapulars and lower underparts.
Long-tailed_Tit, A small, active, black-and-white songbird with pinkish highlights and an extremely long tail.
Long-tailed_Tit, Adults in Mediterranean Europe and western Asia have grayish upperparts with little or no pink, a broad black band over each eye, and a shorter tail than other groups.
Long-tailed_Tit, Plumage soft and fluffy. The long, graduated tail—which makes up more than half the overall length of the bird—has white outer feathers and black inner feathers.
Long-tailed_Tit, Both sexes build a large, domed nest covered with lichen. Many breeding pairs are assisted by one or more helpers—a third adult related to the male.
Long-tailed_Tit, An active and acrobatic forager, at times hanging upside down in search of insects.
Long-tailed_Tit, Birds in the alpinus group have grayish upperparts (with little or no pink) and some populations have a black throat patch.
Long-tailed_Tit, Frequently feeds on caterpillars.
Long-tailed_Tit, Juvenile across range has a blackish mask covering much of the head, a thin pink eyering, a shorter tail than adults, and overall more subdued plumage with little or no pink.
Long-tailed_Tit, A highly social species. Recent fledglings huddle together, and in winter, flocks roost side-by-side.
Long-tailed_Tit, Forages high in the canopy of trees or atop shrubs. Explores twigs and leaves for insects and hangs upside when needed to seize prey.
Long-tailed_Tit, Occurs in scrubby areas, woodlands with a shrubby understory, gardens, parks, and other habitats with bushes or hedgerows.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, A warbler that looks like a thrush with its long legs and long body. Brown above with a white eyebrow stripe that is wider at the rear.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Found along streams constantly bobbing its tail up and down as it walks. Note white eyebrow that is wider at the back of the head.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Song is a loud, sweet series of clear introductory notes followed by a slurred phrase that rises and falls.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Brown above and streaked below, but has fewer streaks on the breast (and particularly the throat) than similar Northern Waterthrush.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Loud ringing song carries well over rushing streams.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Forages along rocky streams in forests, and habitually bobs its tail as it goes.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Long-legged warbler with an elongated body. Throat is usually unmarked.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Found in forests near streams. Sings from elevated perches.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Call note of adults and juveniles is a very sharp, metallic chip.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Forages primarily on the ground alongside forested streams, or on rocks or downed logs in the middle of the stream.
Louisiana_Waterthrush, Forages along rocky forested streams, often venturing out to rocks in the middle of the stream.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.

Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with curved bill. Females are iridescent green above with cinnamon patch on the upper tail feathers. Underparts are whitish with cinnamon flanks. Note short tail on females.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, The curved bill and purple gorget stand out on this male. This video has no audio.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill, green forehead, and a purple gorget that flares out on the sides.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Note the curved bill and buffy underparts on this female. This video has no audio.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Visits feeders, but often chased away by more aggressive species.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a curved bill. Males have a purple gorget that flares out on the sides. Iridescent green above. Tail on perched birds is long and narrow.
Lucifer_Hummingbird, Females have cinnamon-washed flanks and a smudgy line behind the eye. Note curved bill and short tail.
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small, pale gray warbler. Females have a plain face and a faint buffy wash on the flanks.
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small grayish warbler. Males have a rusty cap and rump (not visible on perched birds).
Lucys_Warbler, Small, pale gray warbler with a paler belly. Nests in cavities in mesquite woodlands near streams.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Females and immatures are paler than males and lack the darker patches around the eye and chest. Note gray hood, white eye crescents, and yellow underparts.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Song is a series of churring syllables, sometimes ending with a sweet-toned warble.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.

MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Feathers in front of the eye and on the chest are darker than the rest of the hood. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Breeds in areas with dense understories, including regenerating clearcuts, regrowing burned forests, thickets, riparian areas, and deciduous forests.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.
MacGillivrays_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood and white eye crescents. Olive above and yellow below. Lacks wingbars.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, An all dark, long-winged, fork-tailed bird of tropical oceans. Note also the long bill with hooked tip.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Soars effortlessly on its long wings using its deeply forked tail to steer. Females have a dark head and white breast patch.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Soars across tropical oceans with the occasional slow beat of its wings.

Magnificent_Frigatebird, An all dark fork-tailed bird of tropical oceans. Soars effortlessly on its long wings, which have a pronounced bend. Males have a bare patch of red skin on the throat (gular sac), barely visible outside the breeding season.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Spends most of its time in the air, gliding for hours with little to no wing movements. Immature females have a white head and belly.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Flies on large angular wings with long tail trialing behind. The tail is deeply forked, but is often held closed.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Juveniles have a white head and belly.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Juveniles have a white head and belly.

Magnificent_Frigatebird, Unlike other seabirds, they lack waterproof feathers and cannot easily take flight from the ground. They typically take flight from an elevated perch that faces into the wind.

Magnificent_Frigatebird, Male's gular sac becomes bright red and is inflated like a large balloon during courtship displays and early incubation period, but becomes pale orange and shrinks to become barely visible at other times of the year.

Magnificent_Frigatebird, Males gather in groups to court females, perching in low trees and shrubs with their red throat sac inflated like a balloon. Male Magnificent Frigatebirds gather in groups to court females. They perch in low trees and shrubs with their red throat sac inflated like a balloon and clatter their bills, waving their heads back and forth, and calling at females flying overhead.
Magnificent_Frigatebird, Flaps with deep wing beats when needed, otherwise soars effortlessly across tropical oceans. Note immatures and females with white heads and breasts.

Magnolia_Warbler, Small-billed, long-tailed warbler. Adult males have distinctive black streaking that radiates from a black neck band creating a necklaced look. White undertail coverts and black-tipped tail are diagnostic at all ages.
Magnolia_Warbler, Small-billed, long-tailed warbler. Females/immatures have a gray head, a faint gray band across the neck, and 2 narrow white wingbars.
Magnolia_Warbler, The combination of white undertail coverts and black tip to the tail create a distinctive pattern useful for identifying all plumages of Magnolia Warblers.

Magnolia_Warbler, Adult females do not have as strong of a black mask and lack the black back seen on adult males, though some females show darker necklace stripes like a male. Adult females are often paler overall with thinner wingbars.
Magnolia_Warbler, Females/immatures have less black on the back and fainter streaking on the flanks and chest.
Magnolia_Warbler, Forages primarily in trees and shrubs, but sometimes forages for insects on the ground.
Magnolia_Warbler, Adult males have a black patch on the back, a wide white wing patch, and a black mask.
Magnolia_Warbler, White undertail coverts and black-tipped tail are diagnostic at all ages. Females/immatures have a gray head and faint gray band across the neck.
Magnolia_Warbler, Bathes by dipping its bill in the water and tossing water over its back.
Magnolia_Warbler, Adult males are bright yellow below with obvious black streaking on the chest and flanks as well as a black mask and black back.
Magnolia_Warbler, Found in dense stands of all ages during migration. Breeds in areas with young evergreen trees.
Magnolia_Warbler, Adult males have a distinctive black necklace and boldly striped flanks.
Mallard, Breeding male has iridescent green head, yellow bill, white collar around neck, brown breast, and a grayish body.
Mallard, Female is mottled brown, with an orange-and-black bill.
Mallard, Common on ponds, lakes, and streams. Males have glossy green head, white ring on neck, brown chest, and yellow bill.
Mallard, In flight, note male's black-and-white tail and blue wing patch bordered by two white bars.
Mallard, A strong flier that can reach speeds of 55 miles per hour.
Mallard, Feeds in shallow water on aquatic invertebrates and vegetation. Does not dive.
Mallard, Nonbreeding male is browner, like a female, but retains its black-and-white tail and often shows at least a trace of green on the head.

Mallard, Mallards shed all their flight feathers at the end of the breeding season and are flightless for 3–4 weeks. They are secretive during this vulnerable time, and their body feathers molt into a concealing "eclipse" plumage that can make them hard to identify.
Mallard, Courtship involves many displays, including synchronized head-bobbing and the female swimming toward the male with her head held low in the water.
Mallard, Newly hatched ducklings are covered in down and ready to leave the nest within 13–16 hours.
Mallard, At home on the ground as well as in the water.
Mallard, Feeds in shallow water by tipping up to reach submerged vegetation. Does not dive.
Mallard, Most pairs form in the fall or early winter, well before the start of actual breeding.
Mallard, Found in almost any wetland habitat, including marshes, lakes, ponds, roadside ditches, pastures, and rice fields.
Mallard, Frequently hybridizes with American Black Duck. Male hybrid has only partial green head and is darker overall than male Mallard.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Long and slender with a stout bill that is yellow below and black above. Brown above with a peachy wash below. Note dark face mask.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Long and slender with a long tail that has large white spots as seen from below.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Often secretive and difficult to see. Sings a guttural "coo."
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Long and slender with a stout bill that is yellow below and black above. Brown above with a peachy wash below. Note dark face mask.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Long and slender with a stout bill that is yellow below and black above. Brown above with a peachy wash below. Note dark face mask.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Individuals show variation in plumage color. Those in the Lesser Antilles tend to be more cinnamon below.
Mangrove_Cuckoo, Breeds in mangroves and woodland scrub. Perches motionless in thick vegetation where it can be hard to spot. Note yellow lower bill, peachy wash on belly and large white tail spots.
Marbled_Godwit, Large shorebird with a slightly upturned bicolored bill. Breeding birds are barred above and below.
Marbled_Godwit, Long-legged shorebird with very long, slightly upturned, bicolored bill. Nonbreeding birds have unstreaked cinnamon washed underparts.
Marbled_Godwit, Uses its very long bill to probe into wet sand of beaches and mudflats, reaching deeper than other shorebirds can manage.
Marbled_Godwit, In flight, note cinnamon washed underwings.
Marbled_Godwit, Tall shorebird with a long, slightly upturned bicolored bill.
Marbled_Godwit, Smaller than a Long-billed Curlew with a long, slightly upturned bill.
Marbled_Godwit, Breeds in short grassy areas, marshes, and flooded plains. Forages in grasslands and abandoned pastures.
Marbled_Godwit, During migration and winter found in coastal mudflats, wet meadows, estuaries, and sandy beaches.
Marbled_Murrelet, Small, plump seabird with a short bill and tail and narrow wings. Breeding birds appear brown overall.
Marbled_Murrelet, Small, plump seabird with a short bill and tail and narrow wings. Breeding birds appear brown overall.
Marbled_Murrelet, Nonbreeding birds are dark blackish gray above and white below with a white collar around the neck. When resting on the water, the tail is often held up and out of the water.
Marbled_Murrelet, Often seen in small groups during the nonbreeding season. From a distance note white collar on a dark and white seabird.
Marbled_Murrelet, Plump, short-tailed seabird with a short bill. Note white collar and black eye patch.

Marsh_Wren, Tiny, round-bodied wren with a short tail that is often held up. Rusty-brown above with black-and-white streaks down its back. Underparts are paler and unstreaked. Individuals in eastern North America are often rustier and more brightly colored than those in the West.

Marsh_Wren, Boisterous bird of wetlands. Sings a gurgling rattling trill, usually while hidden in reeds. Brown above with black-and-white streaks down the back. Note pale eyebrow and unstreaked shoulder.
Marsh_Wren, A rusty-brown wren with black-and-white streaks down its back, a white eyebrow, and a short, frequently cocked tail.
Marsh_Wren, Clings to reeds, grasping a different stalk in each foot. Rich brown above with dark barring on the tail; paler below with a white throat and breast. Note pale eyebrow.

Marsh_Wren, Small, plump wren with a thin bill. Individuals in eastern North America are rustier and more brightly colored than birds in the West. Note dark barring on tail, black-and-white stripes down the back, unstreaked shoulder, and pale eyebrow.
Marsh_Wren, Builds a nest out of dead grass and sedge stems, secured to stems of marsh vegetation.
Marsh_Wren, A rusty-brown wren with black-and-white streaks down its back, a white eyebrow, and a short, frequently cocked tail.
Marsh_Wren, A rusty-brown wren with black-and-white streaks down its back, a white eyebrow, and a short, frequently cocked tail.
Marsh_Wren, Found in wetlands with emergent vegetation such as cattails and bulrushes.
Marsh_Wren, Small wren of wetlands, difficult to see but easy to hear. Look for the pale eyebrow, white throat and breast, black-and-white stripes down the back, and unmarked shoulders.
Masked_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a hefty yellow bill. Adults are all white with black primaries and secondaries and a black tail. Note black mask.
Masked_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a hefty yellow (greenish yellow on Juveniles) bill. Juveniles have a brownish head and neck, a dark back, and a white belly.
Masked_Booby, Large, heavy-bodied seabird with a hefty yellow bill. Adults are all white with black primaries and secondaries and a black tail. Note black mask.
Masked_Booby, Flies on long stiff wings. Note black primaries, secondaries, and tail feathers.
Masked_Booby, Immatures have a mottled brown and white neck and back. Note mostly white underwings in flight.
Masked_Booby, Immatures have brownish mottling on the head and back with a distinct white collar.
Masked_Booby, The amount of brown color on the neck and back of immatures varies depending on age, some are solid brown whereas others have extensive mottling.
Masked_Booby, Nests on small tropical islands, especially ones that are flat and without forests. Spends rest of time at sea.

Merlin, Small, stocky falcon with a blocky head. Males are generally dark overall, but their color varies geographically. Adult male "Taiga" Merlin is medium gray above with a pale mustache stripe and a thin white eyebrow.
Merlin, Stocky and powerful falcon. Adult male "Prairie" Merlin from the central U.S. and Canada is pale gray above with a thin white eyebrow and no noticeable mustache stripe.
Merlin, Small but powerfully built falcon with compact body and long tail. Note heavy dark streaking on underparts and lack of a strong "mustache" mark on the face.
Merlin, "Black" Merlin, which breeds from Alaska to Washington, is very dark overall—almost black—with a pronounced mustache.

Merlin, Females/immatures are brown overall, but color varies geographically. "Taiga" Merlin breeding in the northern U.S. and Canada is medium brown above with a thin eyebrow and thick brown streaks below.
Merlin, Mainly hunts birds, often shorebirds. Flight is fast and powerful. Note compact proportions with broad chest and broad-based, sharply pointed wings.
Merlin, Small, square-headed falcon. Female/immature "Prairie" Merlin from the central U.S. and Canada is pale brown with a thin eyebrow and pale brown streaks below.
Merlin, Stocky, compact falcon. Adults are heavily streaked below. Note square-tipped tail on perched birds.
Merlin, Flies with stiff, powerful, and fast wingbeats. Note pointed wings and heavy streaking below.
Merlin, Eats mostly birds, typically catching them in midair during high-speed attacks.
Merlin, "Black" Merlin breeding from Alaska to Washington is dark overall with dark heavy streaking below.

Merlin, "Pallid" Merlin breeds on the steppes of Central Asia and winters from eastern Turkey to northwestern India. Adult male is similar to the North American "Prairie" Merlin, with pale gray upperparts and buffy highlights on the head and breast.
Merlin, Female/immature "Pallid" Merlin is heavily barred above, with a mix of orange, brown, and buff. The tail is whitish with faint dark barring.
Merlin, "Eurasian" Merlin breeds from Iceland to the Russian Far East. Adult male has gray upperparts and buffy, streaked underparts.

Merlin, Breeds in forested openings, edges, and along rivers across northern North America. During migration and winter, found in open forests, grasslands, and especially coastal areas with flocks of small songbirds or shorebirds.

Mexican_Chickadee, A small songbird with a black cap, white cheek, black bib, gray upperparts, and a small black bill. The gray flanks and extensive black bib make this the darkest North American chickadee.
Mexican_Chickadee, Extensive black bib and gray underparts distinguish Mexican Chickadee from similar species, and no other chickadees occur within its range.
Mexican_Chickadee, A gray-backed chickadee with a black cap and white cheeks. Note the extensive black bib and gray flanks as the bird turns and flies.
Mexican_Chickadee, Active and alert, often serving as a sentinel against predators in large mixed species flocks.
Mexican_Chickadee, Gleans caterpillars and other small insects from branches and leaves.
Mexican_Chickadee, Found in coniferous, mixed, and deciduous forests and woodlands.
Mexican_Chickadee, Occurs in coniferous, deciduous, and mixed forests and woodlands in Mexico.
Mexican_Duck, A large dabbling duck. Male has a dark reddish-brown body, a lighter neck and head, and an olive-green to yellow bill.
Mexican_Duck, Female is similar to male, but typically has a dusky orange bill and is not as richly reddish-brown.
Mexican_Duck, A large dabbling duck, slightly smaller than a Mallard. Male (seen here courting a female Mallard) is a rich reddish-brown with a lighter head and neck and yellow bill.
Mexican_Duck, Speculum is blue, bordered by a white trailing edge and usually a white leading edge.
Mexican_Duck, Often found together in pairs, with bill color—orangeish in female, yellowish in male—the best way to tell the sexes apart.
Mexican_Duck, Inhabits a variety of human-made and natural waterbodies.
Mexican_Duck, Female bill color is variable, ranging from orange (with some dark marks) to drab olive.

Mexican_Duck, In flight, white underwing linings contrast with darker upperwings. The speculum is blue, bordered by a white trailing edge and narrow white leading edge (sometimes absent). Tail is dark.
Mexican_Duck, Occurs in virtually all areas with water, ranging from seasonal and permanent wetlands to reservoirs, irrigation canals, and other human-made water features.

Mexican_Jay, Large songbird with long tail and heavy bill. Adults are blue with a gray patch on the back and dingy gray underparts. The intensity of blue varies across their range; birds in Arizona tend to be paler blue.

Mexican_Jay, Large songbird with long tail and heavy bill. Adults are blue with a gray patch on the back and dingy gray underparts. The intensity of blue varies across their range; birds in Arizona tend to be paler blue.
Mexican_Jay, Lacks a crest, has an all-blue back, and no necklace across the chest.
Mexican_Jay, Medium-sized crestless jay with dingy gray underparts. Often seen hopping on the ground while foraging for insects and stored acorns.
Mexican_Jay, Juveniles look like adults but have a pale bill. Juveniles in Arizona have a pale bill for 2 years before they acquire the dark bill of adults.

Mexican_Jay, Large songbird with long tail and heavy bill. Adults are blue with a gray patch on the back and dingy gray underparts. The intensity of blue varies across their range; birds in Arizona tend to be paler blue.
Mexican_Jay, Found in pine, oak, and juniper woodlands.

Mexican_Whip-poor-will, Highly camouflaged, with an intricate mix of black, brown, gray, buffy, and rufous feathers. Note the faint buffy-white collar contrasting with black throat and breast feathers. Females show limited buffy tips to the outer tail feathers.
Mexican_Whip-poor-will, Nightjar coloration can vary based on age, individual variation, and lighting conditions.
Mexican_Whip-poor-will, Adult males have bold white tips on their outer tail feathers.

Mexican_Whip-poor-will, Highly camouflaged, with an intricate mix of black, brown, gray, buffy, and rufous feathers. Note the thin buffy-white collar contrasting with black throat and breast feathers. Adult males have extensive white in their outer tail feathers.
Mexican_Whip-poor-will, Mexican Whip-poor-wills have small bills bordered by long rictal bristles (modified, whisker-like feathers).
Mexican_Whip-poor-will, During the day, roosts on or near the ground.
Mississippi_Kite, Small, slender raptor with narrow and pointed wings and a long tail. Note dark tail in flight.
Mississippi_Kite, Small raptor with pointed wings and a long tail. Immatures have a banded tail and mottled looking wings. Younger juveniles have brown streaking on the belly.
Mississippi_Kite, Slim, graceful raptor with pale head, dark eye patch, and dark gray wings.
Mississippi_Kite, In flight, juvenile shows mottled underwing coverts, a banded tail, and streaked breast and belly. Note the pointed wings and flared tail.
Mississippi_Kite, In flight, note adult's whitish secondaries on upper wing and, at close range, reddish tinge to primaries.
Mississippi_Kite, Slim raptor with pointed wings and long tail that can show a shallow fork. At close range, note striking pattern gray-black-white pattern in wings.
Mississippi_Kite, Pale gray overall with darker gray wings and a black tail. At close range note the red eye and dark eye patch.
Mississippi_Kite, Adults are pale gray below and darker gray above with a long black tail. Note dark eye patch.
Mississippi_Kite, Forms large flocks during migration. Flight style is light and buoyant.
Mississippi_Kite, Juveniles have heavily streaked bellies. Note long wings and tail.
Mississippi_Kite, Graceful and buoyant fliers that catch insects on the wing.
Mississippi_Kite, Eats mainly insects, typically caught and eaten on the wing. Often sits on exposed perches and scans for prey.
Mississippi_Kite, Found in bottomland hardwood forests and in tree-lined areas including windbreaks, shelterbelts, parks, and urban areas.
Mississippi_Kite, Forms large flocks during migration.
Monk_Parakeet, Fairly small parakeet with a long, pointed tail, a large head, and a hooked bill. Green overall with a gray face and breast. Note the pale pink bill.
Monk_Parakeet, Monk Parakeets are recognizable by their gray head and breast and the lack of other prominent patches of color on the head.
Monk_Parakeet, Builds large nests out of sticks, often containing multiple pairs each with separate nesting chambers. In North America, often builds nests on structures in urban environments.
Monk_Parakeet, Long-tailed and big headed. In flight, note the blue underwings, which can appear pale blue depending on lighting.
Monk_Parakeet, Noisy and social bird almost always seen in groups. Note pale gray breast and face and pink bill.
Monk_Parakeet, Forages mainly on seeds. Uses foot to hold food while eating; may use bill to grasp stems and twigs while climbing or moving.
Monk_Parakeet, In its native range in South America, found in dry savannas with scattered trees.
Monk_Parakeet, In the U.S. found in urban and suburban settings, where they feed on ornamental fruit trees and often build stick nests on human structures such as power transformers.
Monk_Parakeet, In North America, often seen around human structures.
Montezuma_Quail, Small-headed, round-bodied quail with a very short tail. Males have a harlequin facial pattern, a deep chestnut breast, and white spots on their sides.
Montezuma_Quail, Small-headed, round-bodied quail that can be difficult to see well. Males have a harlequin pattern on the face and white dots on the side of its body.
Montezuma_Quail, Forages by scratching the ground for seeds, grass roots, acorns, and insects. Typically uses surrounding dense vegetation or large rocks for cover while foraging.
Montezuma_Quail, Small-headed, round-bodied quail with a very short tail. Females are cryptically marked in browns with whitish lines and a ghosting of the male's facial pattern.
Montezuma_Quail, Small-headed, round-bodied quail with a very short tail. Females are cryptically marked in browns with whitish dots and lines. They have a ghosting of the male's facial pattern.
Montezuma_Quail, Small-headed, round-bodied quail with a very short tail. Males have a harlequin facial pattern, a deep chestnut breast, and white spots on their sides.

Morelets_Seedeater, A small finchlike songbird with a short, thick, curved bill. Breeding males from southern Mexico to Panama often look largely black and white, with a black head, white throat and collar, black back, black wings with two white wingbars, black breast band, and white to buffy underparts.
Morelets_Seedeater, Male breeding plumage is variable. Some males from southern Mexico to Panama are black and white, while others have varying amounts of buff below.

Morelets_Seedeater, A small finchlike songbird with a short, thick, curved bill. Breeding males are variable, but individuals from southern Mexico to Panama have a black head, broad white crescent under the eye, thick black breast band, and often white (sometimes buffy) underparts.
Morelets_Seedeater, Female is buffy below and brownish olive above, with two white wingbars on dark gray wings, and a pale bill.
Morelets_Seedeater, Nonbreeding male is similar to female, but with blackish wings and a prominent white spot at the base of the primaries.
Morelets_Seedeater, Female is brownish overall, darker above than below. Note the small body size, thick curved bill, and buffy wingbars.
Morelets_Seedeater, Rarely found on the ground, instead staying in trees, shrubs, or the tops of grass seedheads.
Morelets_Seedeater, Some breeding males are a crisp black and white, with the black head and breast band contrasting with the white throat and white underparts.
Morelets_Seedeater, Feeds mainly on seeds and insects. Typically perches on a grass stalk and then extracts seeds.
Morelets_Seedeater, Female is buffy below, with a pale, thick, curved bill.
Morelets_Seedeater, Typically perches on grass stems to feed on seedheads.
Mottled_Duck, Warm dark-brown body contrasting with pale buffy head, dark brown cap, and eyeline. Female's bill is black with orange-yellow tip.
Mottled_Duck, Forages for seeds, vegetation, and insects by dabbling in shallow marshes and flooded fields.
Mottled_Duck, In flight shows contrasting white underwings and dark blue secondaries with little or no white borders in the wing.
Mottled_Duck, Male has a bright yellow bill; female has a mostly blackish bill with yellow tip.
Mottled_Duck, Strong contrast between dark brown body and pale buffy head, with few or no markings on the throat.
Mottled_Duck, Warm dark-brown body contrasting with pale buffy head and dark brown cap. Bright yellow bill with small black spot at the gape.
Mottled_Duck, In flight, note pale head and underwings contrasting with dark body.
Mottled_Duck, Ducklings are fluffy and dark brown with pale yellowish faces and a dark eyeline.
Mottled_Duck, Occurs in shallow marshes, wet prairies, flooded fields and ditches, and other wetlands of the southeastern U.S. and Mexico.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small, stocky thrush with a round head and a thin bill. Adult males are sky-blue overall, darker above than below.
Mountain_Bluebird, Round-bellied thrush with a thin bill. Females/immatures are mostly gray-brown with tinges of pale blue in the wings and tail. Belly color varies from pale rusty to grayish.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small, stocky thrush with a round head and a thin bill. Adult males are sky-blue overall, darker above than below.
Mountain_Bluebird, Juveniles look similar to females, but have sparse spotting on the back and belly.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small thrush. Females/immatures can have pale rusty wash on the breast or a grayish wash. Note thin white eyering.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small, stocky thrush with a round head and a thin bill. Adult males are sky-blue overall, darker above than below.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small sky-blue thrush. Adult males are unmistakable.
Mountain_Bluebird, The sky-blue color tends to be brighter on the tail and wings.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small, stocky thrush with a round head and a thin bill. Adult males are sky-blue overall, darker above than below.
Mountain_Bluebird, Adult males in winter tend to be paler overall with a grayer belly.

Mountain_Bluebird, Found in open spaces such as prairie, sagebrush steppe, and even alpine tundra; anywhere with open country with at least a few trees that have holes in them or nest boxes for nesting.
Mountain_Bluebird, Small, stocky thrush with a round head and a thin bill. Adult males are sky-blue overall, darker above than below.
Mountain_Bluebird, In winter, often occurs in large flocks wandering the landscape feasting on berries, particularly those of junipers.
Mountain_Chickadee, Tiny, large-headed but small-billed, with a long, narrow tail and a round belly. Grayish overall with white cheeks, a black cap and throat, and a white eyebrow.
Mountain_Chickadee, Small and inquisitive. Looks similar to other chickadees, but white eyebrow stripe separates them from other chickadees.
Mountain_Chickadee, Small, active bird with black bib, white cheeks, and white eyebrow stripe.
Mountain_Chickadee, Nests in holes in trees created by woodpeckers or excavates its own in trees with soft wood. Also uses nest boxes.
Mountain_Chickadee, Visits bird feeders year-round to eat suet, black oil sunflower seeds, and nyjer seeds.
Mountain_Chickadee, Active and acrobatic, clinging to small limbs and twigs or hanging upside down from pine cones. Found in evergreen forests in mountains of western North America.
Mountain_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird of inland shortgrass prairies. Stands with an upright posture. Pale brown above with a white face, a black forehead mark, and a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird of inland shortgrass prairies. Stands with an upright posture. Pale brown above with a white face, a black forehead mark, and a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Has classic plover habit of taking several quick steps and then stopping short. Pale brown back, lack of bands on breast, and upland habitat set it apart from other plovers.
Mountain_Plover, Juveniles are brownish above with a buffy breast and face.
Mountain_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird of inland shortgrass prairies. Stands with an upright posture. Pale brown above with a white face, a black forehead mark, and a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird of inland shortgrass prairies. Stands with an upright posture. Pale brown above with a white face, a black forehead mark, and a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird of inland shortgrass prairies. Stands with an upright posture. Pale brown above with a white face, a black forehead mark, and a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Upright shorebird with a peachy wash on the neck and shoulders. During the breeding season has a black line in front of the eye.
Mountain_Plover, Winters on fields of harvested grain, grazed grasslands, and tilled fields.
Mountain_Quail, Large, round-bodied quail with 2 straight plumes, that often appear as one on top of its head. Note chestnut throat, bold white bars on its side, and a short tail.
Mountain_Quail, Large, round-bodied quail with 2 straight plumes, that often appear as one on top of its head. Note chestnut throat, bold white bars on its side, and a short tail.
Mountain_Quail, Rapidly walks or runs along the ground, usually sticking close to cover.
Mountain_Quail, Large, round-bodied quail with 2 straight plumes, that often appear as one on top of its head. Note chestnut throat, bold white bars on its side, and rusty undertail coverts.
Mountain_Quail, Forages primarily on the ground. Rapidly kicks its feet back and forth in leaf litter to uncover seeds and insects.
Mourning_Dove, Gray above with large black spots on the wing coverts and pale peach-colored below, with a long, thin tail. Note the thin, black bill and pinkish legs.
Mourning_Dove, In flight shows a long, fan-shaped tail with large white tips. Its wings make a distinctive high-pitched whistle in flight.
Mourning_Dove, Characteristic "mourning" call is made by puffing up the throat but without opening the bill.
Mourning_Dove, Juveniles look similar to adults, but with small white tips to most of the upperparts feathers, and white markings in the face.
Mourning_Dove, Shows a black mark on the side of the neck that can be hidden, depending on the angle.
Mourning_Dove, Note small, round head, straight, thin bill, and long, pointed tail with white edge. Often found in backyards and neighborhoods.
Mourning_Dove, Constructs small, flimsy nests in a variety of trees and bushes.
Mourning_Dove, Often occurs in flocks, sometimes quite large, and perches prominently in a variety of habitats.
Mourning_Dove, Nest is a flimsy pile of twigs or needles arranged on a flat surface such as a tree branch, gutter, railing—or cactus.
Mourning_Dove, Typically feeds on the ground, in the open, and usually in small groups. Often comes to platform feeders and to seed scattered on the ground.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Adult females/immature males are paler overall than adult males and lack the black chest.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Immature females have less of a hooded look and show less contrast between the head and the back.
Mourning_Warbler, Immature males have a paler gray hood and a partial eyering. Note yellow underparts.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Mourning_Warbler, Hops along the ground and from branch to branch often staying concealed in vegetation.
Mourning_Warbler, Breeds in disturbed second-growth forested areas, with moderately closed canopy and thick understory.
Mourning_Warbler, Chunky warbler with a gray hood, black chest, and yellow underparts. Lacks wingbars and eyerings.
Muscovy_Duck, Large heavy-bodied duck. Mostly dark above and below with a white wing patch. The face is marked with red warty-looking bumps.
Muscovy_Duck, In flight, adult male shows large white wing patches on broad black wings.
Muscovy_Duck, Large heavy-bodied duck with warty red spots on face. Feral birds have varying amounts of white to brown patches on their bodies.
Muscovy_Duck, Feral birds have varying amounts of white to brown patches on their bodies and varying amounts of red wartlike bumps on the face.
Muscovy_Duck, In flight, female/immature has less white in the wing than male.
Muscovy_Duck, Male is significantly larger than female, which has a duller, less glossy plumage.
Muscovy_Duck, In flight, note female's significantly smaller body size and limited white wing patch.
Muscovy_Duck, Forages in shallow ponds and wetlands. From a distance looks all dark. Note long neck and sloping forehead.
Mute_Swan, Very large and entirely white with a long neck, bright orange bill, black skin around the face, and black legs.
Mute_Swan, Immatures have paler, dusky-pinkish bills.
Mute_Swan, Skims plants from the surface or submerges head to reach vegetation in deeper water.
Mute_Swan, In display or when threatened will partly raise its wings while swimming.
Mute_Swan, Flies with neck outstretched. Entirely white with black legs and bright orange bill.
Mute_Swan, Eats aquatic vegetation in city-park ponds, as well as rivers, lakes, and estuaries.
Mute_Swan, Older juveniles can have extensive dusky-brownish highlights on the body.
Mute_Swan, Young juveniles are fluffy and entirely pale gray with black bills and legs.
Mute_Swan, Flies with its head and neck extended with shallow wingbeats.
Mute_Swan, Can be extremely aggressive toward other swans and waterfowl.
Mute_Swan, Found on a variety of water bodies, including small ponds and large reservoirs.
Mute_Swan, Swims with its long neck curved into an S and often holds its wings raised slightly above its back.

Nashville_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a short tail. Yellow below with an olive-green back and no wingbars. Its white eyering stands out on the gray head. Chestnut crown patch usually not visible. Birds in the western U.S. have a brighter yellow rump and grayer back than those in the eastern U.S.
Nashville_Warbler, Compact warbler with a round head. Females/immatures are paler than males. Note eyering, yellow underparts, and lack of wingbars.

Nashville_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a short tail. Yellow below with an olive-green back and no wingbars. Its white eyering stands out on the gray head. Chestnut crown patch usually not visible. Birds in the western U.S. have a brighter yellow rump and grayer back than those in the eastern U.S.
Nashville_Warbler, Immature birds are paler than adults. Note eyering, yellow underparts, and lack of wingbars.
Nashville_Warbler, Compact warbler with a round head. Females/immatures are paler than males. Note eyering, yellow underparts, and lack of wingbars.

Nashville_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a short tail. Yellow below with an olive-green back and no wingbars. Its white eyering stands out on the gray head. Chestnut crown patch usually not visible. Birds in the western U.S. have a brighter yellow rump and grayer back than those in the eastern U.S.

Nashville_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a short tail. Yellow below with an olive-green back and no wingbars. Its white eyering stands out on the gray head. Chestnut crown patch usually not visible. Birds in the western U.S. have a brighter yellow rump and grayer back than those in the eastern U.S.
Nashville_Warbler, Birds in the eastern U.S. are slightly duller yellow than birds in the western U.S. Note eyering, yellow underparts, and lack of wingbars.

Nashville_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a short tail. Yellow below with an olive-green back and no wingbars. Its white eyering stands out on the gray head. Chestnut crown patch usually not visible. Birds in the western U.S. have a brighter yellow rump and grayer back than those in the eastern U.S.

Nashville_Warbler, Birds in the eastern U.S. have a greener back and less white on the lower belly (between the feet) than birds in the western U.S.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a short bill and round belly. The face and breast have a pale orangish wash. The nape and cheek are gray. The breast is streaked.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Interior populations are brighter and have well-defined cinnamon streaks on the flanks.

Nelsons_Sparrow, A colorful sparrow with an inconspicuous, raspy song. Adult has orange on the face and streaked breast, a gray central crown stripe bordered by black, and a gray patch behind the eye.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a short bill and round belly. The face and breast have a pale orangish wash. The nape and cheek are gray. The breast is streaked.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small sparrow with a round belly and short bill. Washed in pale orange-buff with a gray cheek and nape.
Nelsons_Sparrow, The song starts with a harsh introductory chip followed by a short, rasping trill.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Atlantic populations are paler with blurry streaks on the flanks.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a short bill and round belly. The face and breast have a pale orangish wash. The nape and cheek are gray. The breast is streaked.

Nelsons_Sparrow, During the breeding season, habitats used varies widely among geographically isolated populations. However, all populations inhabit tidal marshes in the southeastern United States during the nonbreeding season.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a short bill and round belly. The face and breast have a pale orangish wash. The nape and cheek are gray. The breast is streaked.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a short bill and round belly. The face and breast have a pale orangish wash. The nape and cheek are gray. The breast is streaked.
Nelsons_Sparrow, Breeds in wet meadows, marshes, and saltmarshes. Note "pot-bellied" look and orangish wash to the face and gray cheek patch.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Large waterbird with a long tail and neck, but small for a cormorant. Breeding birds have thin white plumes on the head and a yellow chin outlined in white, forming a V shape.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Large waterbird, although smaller than other cormorants. Juveniles have a brown head, neck, and breast.
Neotropic_Cormorant, A small cormorant with a short, hooked bill. Note the small patch of orange bordered by a thin white line.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Long-tailed waterbird with a long neck and slender body. Juveniles have a brown head, neck, and breast with a small yellow chin patch.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Large waterbird with a long tail and neck, but small for a cormorant. Breeding birds have thin white plumes on the head and a yellow chin outlined in white, forming a V shape.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Fairly small for a cormorant with a relatively small bill, small head, and long tail.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Found in wetlands, including fresh, brackish, and saltwater habitats. Nests and roosts mostly in trees, but also on cliffs and human-made structures.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Small for a cormorant with a short bill. Juveniles have a brown head, neck, and breast.
Neotropic_Cormorant, Nests in small trees and large shrubs. Usually silent except at nest site, where it gives a low-pitched croaking sound.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, A tiny grayish olive flycatcher with 2 buffy wingbars and a peaked crown. Note the stubby bill with an orange base.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, A slender grayish olive flycatcher with a stubby bill. Some individuals have inconspicuous wingbars.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, Female Northern Beardless-Tyrannulets build globular nests with an entrance near the top or the side in epiphytic plants or amongst tent caterpillar webbing.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, A tiny grayish olive flycatcher with 2 buffy wingbars and a peaked crown. Note the stubby bill with an orange base.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, Tends to perch in an upright position and often erects head feathers when agitated.
Northern_Beardless-Tyrannulet, Found in woodlands near streams and dry washes.

Northern_Bobwhite, Distinctive small quail with short crest or peak to the head. Strong black-and-white striped face with brown crown and white throat. Rich chestnut upperparts with brown-and-white-scaled underparts.
Northern_Bobwhite, Small, plump quail striped and speckled overall with black, brown, and white. Females have buffy throat and stripe over the eye.
Northern_Bobwhite, Eats mostly seeds and leaves, which they pick off the ground or from low plants.
Northern_Bobwhite, In "Masked" subspecies group, male has black head with solid rufous or chestnut underparts.
Northern_Bobwhite, In "pectoralis" subspecies group, male has rich chestnut underparts, an extensive black bib, a white throat, and a black-and-white head.
Northern_Bobwhite, Sings a clear bob-white often from an elevated perch.
Northern_Bobwhite, Males in the "graysoni/nigripectus" subspecies group are similar to the "pectoralis" groups, but lack an extensive black bib.

Northern_Bobwhite, Small quail usually found on the ground in dense grassy or brushy areas; can be easier to find when they venture onto or cross roads. Females have buffy stripe over eye and throat; may show a short raised crest as males do.
Northern_Bobwhite, Found in agricultural fields, grasslands, open pine or pine-hardwood forests, and grass-brush rangelands.
Northern_Bobwhite, Typically occurs on the ground in grassy or shrubby areas.
Northern_Bobwhite, Small quail with striking black-and-white face pattern. Usually found in groups on the ground.
Northern_Bobwhite, Walks or runs along the ground pushing its head and neck forward. This video has no audio.
Northern_Bobwhite, Usually found on the ground in dense grassy or shrubby areas.
Northern_Bobwhite, Small quail with short crest and striking black-and-white face pattern.
Northern_Bobwhite, Usually seen in groups known as coveys that include males, females, and young birds.
Northern_Cardinal, Large, long-tailed songbird with a short, very thick bill and a prominent crest. Males are brilliant red with a black mask and throat.
Northern_Cardinal, Large, crested songbird with a short, thick bill. Females are pale brown overall with warm reddish tinges in the wings, tail, and crest.

Northern_Cardinal, Juveniles are similar to females, but have a gray to black bill.
Northern_Cardinal, Some birds lose all the feathers from their head at the same time, remaining bald until the feathers grow back.
Northern_Cardinal, Both females and males sing a loud series of clear whistles that can sound like the bird is singing cheer, cheer, cheer or birdie, birdie, birdie .
Northern_Cardinal, Common in yards and suburban areas.
Northern_Cardinal, Often sits with a hunched-over posture and with the tail pointed straight down.
Northern_Cardinal, Female sings alone and also in duet with male (as heard here).
Northern_Cardinal, Year-round resident that adds color to winter landscapes in the East.
Northern_Cardinal, Found in backyards, parks, woodlots, and shrubby forest edges.
Northern_Cardinal, Year-round resident throughout its range. Often sits upright with its tail pointed downwards giving it a hunchbacked look.
Northern_Flicker, Large woodpecker with a black bib and spotted belly. Males in the East have a red nape, a black whisker, and yellow shafts on the flight and tail feathers.

Northern_Flicker, A large woodpecker with black barring on the back, a spotted belly, and a black band across the breast. Male "Red-shafted" Northern Flicker has a gray face with a red whisker. Frequently seen on the ground.
Northern_Flicker, In flight note the white rump patch. Birds in the East flash yellow shafts on the flight feathers and tail.
Northern_Flicker, In flight, its white rump contrasts with the rest of the plumage. Individuals in the West have red shafts to the flight feathers and tail that are usually obvious in flight.

Northern_Flicker, In spring and summer, rivals may face off with bills pointed upward in a display sometimes called a "fencing duel." The "Yellow-shafted" Northern Flicker has a tan face with a gray crown. Both "Yellow-shafted" and "Red-shafted" females lack males' facial whiskers.
Northern_Flicker, Shows a bold white rump in flight.

Northern_Flicker, Male "Yellow-shafted" Northern Flicker has black facial whiskers (as opposed to the red whiskers of male "Red-shafted"). In addition to their terrestrial foraging habits, Northern Flickers also dust bathe and "ant"—intentionally smear ants over their feathers—on the ground.
Northern_Flicker, Regularly forages on the ground.
Northern_Flicker, Found in a wide variety of both open and wooded habitats.
Northern_Flicker, Common calls include a loud "clear." Note the red underwings and white rump as the bird takes flight.

Northern_Fulmar, Stocky gull-like seabird with a thick neck and a bull-headed appearance. Flies like a tank with stiff wingbeats. Varies in color from dark gray to nearly white. Note gray rump and tail on light morph birds.
Northern_Fulmar, Stocky gull-like seabird that flies on outstretched stiff wings. This bird is darker gray than other light morph birds in the Atlantic.

Northern_Fulmar, Like many seabird species of the high arctic, Northern Fulmars are highly opportunistic feeders. They often consume discarded fish from commercial fishing vessels, squid, crustaceans, and carrion.

Northern_Fulmar, Stocky gull-like seabird with a thick neck and a bull-headed appearance. Flies like a tank with stiff wingbeats. Varies in color from dark gray to nearly white. Note gray rump and tail on light morph birds.
Northern_Fulmar, Stocky gull-like seabird with a thick neck, bull-headed appearance, and a pale stubby bill. Varies in color from dark gray to nearly white.
Northern_Fulmar, This light morph bird is white overall with gray wings and darker gray wingtips. Often rests on the water with other Northern Fulmars.
Northern_Fulmar, Breeds on steep sea cliffs. Spends the winters at sea from ice-covered northern waters to temperate zones.
Northern_Gannet, Large heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Adults are mostly white with a yellowish wash on the head and neck and black flight feathers.
Northern_Gannet, Large seabird. Juveniles are brown overall with white spotting.

Northern_Gannet, Large white seabird with black wingtips. Though they spend most of their lives at sea, they often come close enough to shore to be seen when scanning with binoculars or a spotting scope.
Northern_Gannet, Bullet-shaped seabird with long pointed wings and long tail. In flight note white body and black flight feathers.
Northern_Gannet, Juveniles in flight are brown overall with a white patch on the tail.
Northern_Gannet, Immatures have patchy brown and white feathers. They attain adult plumage after 4–5 years. Note long pointed tail and wings.
Northern_Gannet, Note wedge-shaped tail that is often held closed in a point. Juveniles have a dingy belly and a dark tail.
Northern_Gannet, Nests in colonies on cliff ledges and steep slopes.
Northern_Gannet, Immature birds attain adult plumage after 4–5 years. Note daggerlike bill, narrow black mask, and pale yellow-washed head.
Northern_Gannet, Breeds in dense colonies and spends the rest of its time at sea.
Northern_Harrier, Medium-sized raptor with long, broad wings, a long tail, and a characteristic white rump patch. Adult males are grayish above with a dark trailing edge on the wings.
Northern_Harrier, Often flies with its broad wings held in a "V". Note long tail. Females are pale below withe brown streaking.
Northern_Harrier, Note languid wingbeats with wings raised in a dihedral when gliding. Hunts low to the ground, teetering from side-to-side.
Northern_Harrier, Immature birds have an unstreaked cinnamon wash on their belly and a darker brown head. Their flight feathers and tail are banded.
Northern_Harrier, From below adult males are pale with black wingtips and black-tipped secondaries. Often hovers above prey before pouncing.
Northern_Harrier, Hunts for small rodents by gliding low over wetlands or open fields. Northern Harriers often flap intermittently and make sharp turns when flying.
Northern_Harrier, Northern Harriers have an owl-like face that helps them detect prey by ear.
Northern_Harrier, Found in open areas such as grasslands, marshes, and fields soaring low over the ground.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a long, tapered tail. The face is white with a dark border. Horizontal brown stripes mark the belly.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, The wings are short and pointed (much more so than on other owls). Note white face bordered by dark lines.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Hunts from prominent tree tops day and night looking for small mammals and birds.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a long tail. Juveniles are a bit paler than adults and look fluffier.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Medium-sized owl with fully feathered legs and feet. Note horizontal barring on belly and white face bordered in black.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Nests in cavities, including old woodpecker nests, and hollow tops of broken tree trunks.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a long, tapered tail. The face is white with a dark border. Horizontal brown stripes mark the belly.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Found in evergreen or mixed forests near marshes and open areas where it perches on top of tall trees.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Perches on prominent trees and shrubs where it hunts primarily for small mammals. This video has no audio.
Northern_Hawk_Owl, Its long tapered tail and dark marks on the side of the face are distinctive.
Northern_House_Wren, Small, nondescript brown bird with a short tail, thin bill, and dark barring on wings and tail with a paler throat.
Northern_House_Wren, The "Brown-throated" subspecies group, found in Southeastern Arizona and the mountains of Mexico, is warm brown, especially below.
Northern_House_Wren, Small, fairly plain brown wren with indistinct eyebrow stripe and strongly barred tail and wings. Bubbly song is given frequently in spring and early summer.
Northern_House_Wren, The distinctive loud bubbling song is often heard before the bird is seen.
Northern_House_Wren, Dark barring on the wings and tail contrast with the more uniform brown plumage elsewhere.
Northern_House_Wren, Forages fairly low in tree branches and shrubs, eating mainly insects and spiders. This video has no audio.
Northern_House_Wren, The "Northern" subspecies group breeds across southern Canada and most of the United States.
Northern_House_Wren, Nests in nest boxes, old woodpecker nests, natural crevices, and other cavities.
Northern_House_Wren, Song is a long, bubbly jumble of trills and scolds given by both males and females. Often pushes tail downward while singing, unlike other wrens.
Northern_House_Wren, Found in scrubby habitats, often close to homes and buildings.
Northern_House_Wren, Nests in tree cavities and birdhouses, where it is a strong competitor for nest sites and may evict larger birds to claim the spot for its own.
Northern_Mockingbird, Medium-sized slender songbird with a long tail. Adults are grayish above and whitish below with two white wingbars.
Northern_Mockingbird, Medium-sized slender songbird with a long tail. Adults are grayish above and whitish below. Mimics songs of other songbirds.
Northern_Mockingbird, Very vocal: song is a long series of phrases, with each phrase repeated 2–6 times before shifting to a new sound. Many sounds are mimicked. Both males and females sing.
Northern_Mockingbird, Juveniles have spotted breasts.
Northern_Mockingbird, Flashes white wing patches in flight.
Northern_Mockingbird, Note distinctive slender shape with long tail. The large white wing patches visible in flight fold up into a small white mark when the bird is perched.
Northern_Mockingbird, White wing patches are distinctive.
Northern_Mockingbird, Often runs and hops along the ground. Found alone or in pairs year-round.

Northern_Mockingbird, When defending territory boundaries, rival birds fly toward each other, land near the boundary, and face off, silently hopping from one side to another. Eventually, one bird retreats and the other chases it a short ways.
Northern_Mockingbird, Usually sits conspicuously on high vegetation, fences, eaves, or telephone wires. Found in in towns, suburbs, backyards, parks, forest edges, and open land at low elevations.

Northern_Mockingbird, Both sexes help build the nest, with the male starting several nests and the female choosing one and then finishing it, lining it with grasses, rootlets and other soft vegetation. This video has no audio.

Northern_Parula, Small wood-warbler with a short tail and a thin bill. Adults have a blue-gray back with a yellow-olive patch in the center. Adult males have a bright yellow throat and breast with a black and chestnut band. Note white eye crescents.
Northern_Parula, Immature males are paler overall and lack the chestnut breast band. Immatures also have have yellow-green edged primaries and secondaries .
Northern_Parula, Northern Parulas hop through branches often in the canopy of eastern forests.
Northern_Parula, Immature females have more of a green wash on their back and head and have green edged primaries and secondaries. Immatures lack the chestnut breast band seen on adult males.
Northern_Parula, Small, short-tailed warbler. Note yellow throat, chestnut breast band, and white belly and undertail coverts. Also note yellow lower bill, a distinct feature in parulas.
Northern_Parula, Northern Parulas sing a buzzy insectlike trill that pinches off at the end.
Northern_Parula, Immature females have more of a green wash on their back and head and have green-edged primaries and secondaries. They also lack the chestnut breast band.
Northern_Parula, Adult males have a distinctive breast pattern—yellow with a black and chestnut band.
Northern_Parula, Northern Parulas nest in hanging clumps of epiphytes like Spanish moss, beard moss, or lace lichen.
Northern_Parula, Breeds in mixed woodlands and mature forests along streams and swamps. Nests in beard or Spanish mosses.
Northern_Parula, Northern Parulas occasionally take nectar from flowers on the wintering grounds.
Northern_Pintail, A long-necked duck. Breeding males have a very long tail, a white breast, and a white neck stripe.
Northern_Pintail, Females are slender ducks with a long tail and neck. Females have rather plain tan heads compared to other female ducks.
Northern_Pintail, An elegant, long-necked duck with a slender profile. Breeding male has a gleaming white breast, grayish sides, and a thin white line extending up a chocolate brown head.
Northern_Pintail, A slender duck with a long neck and tail. In flight, breeding males have a green speculum.
Northern_Pintail, Females are slender with a plain tan face. In flight, the speculum is brownish bronze.
Northern_Pintail, Tips up and submerges head underwater to eat aquatic seeds and insects, filtering out the water with its bill.
Northern_Pintail, Slender duck with a long tail and neck. Nonbreeding males in eclipse plumage are pale overall with a plain face.
Northern_Pintail, Slimmer than a Mallard with a long tail.

Northern_Pintail, Courting males stretch their necks up, bob their heads, and tip their bill down while giving a whistle call to attract a female. Interested females follow with head bobbing, preening, and clucking.
Northern_Pintail, Breeding males have very long black tails and a white stripe up the side of their neck.
Northern_Pintail, Slender duck with a long neck and tail. Shape helps separate from other ducks.
Northern_Pintail, Flies on long and slender wings and almost hovers before gently landing on the ground.
Northern_Pintail, In flight, note slender, long-necked profile and long, pointed tail (longer in breeding males).
Northern_Pintail, Uses shallow wetlands and flooded fields during the winter.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small and compact, with a large, circular head without ear tufts. Brown overall with fine white speckles on the head and white spots on the back. Note yellow eyes and bill.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Individuals along the wet Pacific slope are darker brown overall and give slower single toots.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small and compact, with a large, circular head without ear tufts. Brown overall with fine white speckles on the head and white spots on the back. Note yellow eyes and bill.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Reddish color morphs are rusty-colored throughout with a spotted crown.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small, compact owl with a round head and no ear tufts. Plumage varies from gray brown to brown to reddish, with darker individuals along the wet Pacific slope.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small and compact, with a large, circular head without ear tufts. Brown overall with fine white speckles on the head and white spots on the back. Note yellow eyes and bill.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Individuals in the interior tend to be more gray brown and often gives toots in pairs. Note tiny white spots on crown and narrowly striped tail.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small owl with a round head. Brown overall with white spots on the back and two spots on the back of the head that look like eyes.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small and compact, with a large, circular head without ear tufts. Brown overall with fine white speckles on the head and white spots on the back. Note yellow eyes and bill.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Small and compact, with a large, circular head without ear tufts. Brown overall with fine white speckles on the head and white spots on the back. Note yellow eyes and bill.
Northern_Pygmy-Owl, Found in montane forests of western North America. Look for them in towns, especially during winter when they move to lower elevations.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Small, long-bodied bird with a small head and bill. Entirely brown above with a dingy throat and chest that fades to white.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Flies with smooth deliberate wingbeats on long, pointed wings. Brown above and paler below with a dingy wash on the throat, chest, and sides. Note square tail.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Often found near water where it flies low over the surface taking insects in midair.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Small, long-bodied bird with a small head and bill. Entirely brown above with a dingy throat and chest that fades to white.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Long-bodied with a small head and bill. Adults are brown above and whitish below with a dingy wash on the throat and chest.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Entirely brown above with a dingy throat and chest that fades to a dirty white belly.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Plain brown swallow with few markings. Note small head and square tail.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Juveniles look like adults, but have cinnamon wingbars.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Like other swallows, it has long, somewhat sickle-shaped wings. Note the dingy brown chest.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Small, long-bodied bird with a small head and bill. Entirely brown above with a dingy throat and chest that fades to white.

Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Residents in the Yucatán Peninsula, northern Guatemala, and the southern parts of Oaxaca, Chiapas, and Veracruz, Mexico, have a white spot in front of the eyes and a forked tail.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Females collect grasses, twigs, and plant fibers from the ground to build a cup nest inside a burrow or crevice.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, From below, note mostly white underparts with a dingy wash on the throat and chest.
Northern_Rough-winged_Swallow, Found in open areas and open woodlands where it nests in crevices in rocks or in burrows.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Small, round-headed owl without ear tuffs. Mottled brown and white with fine white streaks on the head and a white "V" between the eyes.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Juveniles have a cinnamon belly, an unspotted brown back, and a white "V" between the eyes.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, During the day Northern Saw-whet Owls roost in dense vegetation, typically just above eye level and near the trunk in evergreen trees.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Adult on Haida Gwaii (formerly Queen Charlotte Islands) is darker than widespread acadicus group, with light cinnamon underparts and face.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Small owl with a larger round head. Note yellow eyes and pale facial disc. Active only at night.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, A nocturnal owl that can be difficult to see during daylight hours. Its whitish facial disk and eyebrows are distinctive.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Roosts in dense vegetation during the day. Found in a variety of forested areas.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes in evergreen and deciduous forests.
Northern_Saw-whet_Owl, Juveniles have a cinnamon belly and though they have the white eyebrows of adults they don't have streaking on the head or spotting on the back.
Northern_Shoveler, Reddish-brown flanks contrast with white chest and black back. Note the male's green head, long, oversized black bill, and yellow eye.
Northern_Shoveler, Females have a coarsely marked brown head and body. Their powdery-blue shoulder patch is sometimes visible at rest. Note the long, oversized orange bill and orange legs.
Northern_Shoveler, Very long and wide bill is distinctive on both males and females, even at considerable distance.
Northern_Shoveler, Subdued shadow of breeding plumage visible under coarse brown markings. Long, oversized black bill.
Northern_Shoveler, Wings in flight show green secondaries and powdery-blue shoulder patch. Large, wide bill is often noticeable even in flight.
Northern_Shoveler, When molting into breeding plumage, males can still have some coarse brown markings on the chest and flanks.
Northern_Shoveler, Bill has a distinctive long and lobed shape.
Northern_Shoveler, Nonbreeding males are darker overall than breeding birds, but still easily identifiable by bill shape, yellow eye, and striking wing pattern.
Northern_Shoveler, In flight, female has a subdued speculum edged in white. Large, orange bill is conspicuous even in flight.
Northern_Shoveler, Chicks are covered in down and able to walk and swim as soon as they hatch.
Northern_Shoveler, Large flocks sometimes feed by swimming in circles to stir up food.
Northern_Shoveler, Occurs in wetlands, particularly shallow ponds where it dabbles for food.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.
Northern_Shrike, Chunky songbird with thick, hooked bill. More brownish than adult, with fine brownish bars on the underside. Narrow black mask.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.
Northern_Shrike, Adults often have underparts finely barred with gray. Mask is narrow and usually does not extend over eye or bill.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.
Northern_Shrike, Immatures have finely barred underparts and indistinct or incomplete masks. Shrikes often sit on exposed perches and swoop down to catch prey on the ground.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.
Northern_Shrike, In flight shows prominent white flashes in the wings and outer tail.
Northern_Shrike, Predatory songbird; catches insects, birds, and small mammals. Breeds in far northern North America; for most birders, typically seen in winter.

Northern_Shrike, Chunky, big-headed songbird with thick, hooked bill. Gray head with black mask that narrows as it meets the bill and usually does not cover the top of the bill. White flashes in wings and tail.
Northern_Shrike, Lives in open, brushy or grassy landscapes with exposed perches such as shrubs and fencerows.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with long legs and a long body. Brown above with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow, though some individuals have a white eyebrow. Heavily streaked below.
Northern_Waterthrush, Long-legged warbler with a heavily streaked belly. Some individuals have extensive yellow wash on the belly. Note narrow buffy or white eyebrow.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with long legs and a long body. Brown above with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow, though some individuals have a white eyebrow. Heavily streaked below.
Northern_Waterthrush, The throat is often spotted and the belly heavily streaked. Some individuals are whiter below than others and have more of a white eyebrow.
Northern_Waterthrush, Sings a loud ringing song from elevated perches.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with long legs and a long body. Brown above with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow, though some individuals have a white eyebrow. Heavily streaked below.
Northern_Waterthrush, Found in wooded swamps, ponds, bogs, and slow moving streams. Bobs its tail while walking.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with long legs and a long body. Brown above with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow, though some individuals have a white eyebrow. Heavily streaked below.
Northern_Waterthrush, Thrushlike warbler with long legs and a long body. Brown above with a narrow, often buffy eyebrow, though some individuals have a white eyebrow. Heavily streaked below.
Northern_Wheatear, Adult male in breeding plumage has a black mask, grayish upperparts, black wings and tail, and a buffy throat.
Northern_Wheatear, "Greenland" adult male in breeding plumage has a darker buff throat and more extensive buff underparts than "Eurasian" adult male.

Northern_Wheatear, A small, rather full-bodied songbird. When alert, stands in an upright position, bobs body, and wags tail. Song is a variable mix of whistles, buzzes, crackling sounds, chack and weet calls, and imitations of the alarm calls of other bird species.
Northern_Wheatear, Adult female in breeding plumage has a faint charcoal mask bordered by a white eyestripe, brownish-gray upperparts, blackish wings and tail, and mostly whitish underparts.
Northern_Wheatear, Some immature birds are a rich cinnamon overall.

Northern_Wheatear, Adult male in breeding plumage has a black mask, gray upperparts, black wings, a black tail, a buffy throat, and white underparts with a variable amount of buff coloring. Frequently found in rocky areas.
Northern_Wheatear, Even in unfamiliar juvenile plumage, this species has a distinctive long-legged, short-tailed appearance.
Northern_Wheatear, Shows namesake white rump and white-and-black tail in all plumages. The black band at the tip of the tail extends to form an inverted "T" on the central tail feathers.

Northern_Wheatear, Adult breeding female lacks the male's black mask and has more subdued colors—brownish-gray upperparts and brownish-black wings. Both sexes frequently give chack and weet calls, often in combination.
Northern_Wheatear, Typically found on the ground, often perched on rocks.
Northern_Wheatear, Nonbreeding male has a reduced black mask, grayish upperparts, and black wings with buffy feather edging.
Northern_Wheatear, Nests in rocky crevices, animal burrows, and human-made cavities (in building crevices, under roof tiles, in pipes, etc.). Feeds primarily on insects.
Northern_Wheatear, Female and immature in the autumn have black lore (between eye and bill), faint blackish mask behind the eye, whitish stripe over the eye, and brownish-gray upperparts.
Northern_Wheatear, A bird of open-country habitats with short vegetation and scattered rocks and boulders.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.
Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Females look like males, but lack the red crown patch. Note thin facial stripes and white underparts.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.
Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white barred woodpecker. Males have red patch at the rear of the head. Note solid black patch on the upper back and thin facial stripes.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.
