Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Found in oak woodlands, wooded suburban areas, and woodlands near streams with cottonwoods, willows, and sycamores.

Nuttalls_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white barring up its back. Note that the barring on the back does not go all the way up the back, leaving a solid black patch below the neck. Males have a red patch at the rear of the head.
Oak_Titmouse, Small songbird with a short, stubby bill, a short crest, and a medium-long tail. Plain gray-brown overall, but paler below. Its beady black eye stands out on its plain face.
Oak_Titmouse, Small crested songbird with a short, round bill. Rather nondescript gray-brown above and paler below. Frequently sings a scratchy and rapid song.
Oak_Titmouse, Rather plain gray-brown bird with a crest that can be raised or lowered. In most cases the crest is at least partially visible, as in this individual.
Oak_Titmouse, Flits between branches and trees, flying with a shallow undulating motion. Tends to feed among the woody twigs in the lower canopies of oaks and other trees.
Oak_Titmouse, Plain gray-brown overall with paler underparts. Sometimes holds its crest down.
Oak_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees created naturally or excavated by woodpeckers. Sometimes they partially excavate a cavity in softer wood.
Oak_Titmouse, Found in warm, open, dry oak or oak-pine woodlands.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, Large, upright-perching flycatcher. From the front it looks like it is wearing a vest. Sexes similar.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, Head feathers are sometimes raised giving the head a peaked look.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, Perches upright often on the top of dead branches and trees.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, Large, elongated, upright-perching flycatcher with a "vested" look—gray sides contrast with white stripe down the belly. Head sometimes looks peaked at the rear.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, White tufts on the sides of the rump can be helpful in distinguishing this species from pewees, but these tufts are not always visible.
Olive-sided_Flycatcher, Perches prominently often on dead branches, especially snags in recently burned forests.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, Adults are brownish gray overall and have an unmarked belly. Note the whiter throat.
Olive_Sparrow, Sings an accelerating series of chips that sounds similar to a ping-pong ball.
Olive_Sparrow, Along the Pacific and Atlantic slope, some individuals farther south have darker head stripes and are a darker olive above than individuals farther north.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, Often holds its tail up or gently flicks it while hopping along the ground.
Olive_Sparrow, Individuals along the Pacific slope have darker and more chestnut-colored crown stripes than individuals in Texas and those along the Atlantic slope.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, Tends to stay in dense cover on or near the ground.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Sparrow, A towhee-like sparrow with a long tail and heavy bill. Adults are grayish below and olive above with brown crown stripes.
Olive_Warbler, A warbler-shaped songbird with a long bill and a notched tail. Males have an orange hood and black "ear" patch. Males and females are grayish overall with 2 bold white wingbars.
Olive_Warbler, Females have a yellowish hood and a dark gray "ear" patch. Note the forked tail.
Olive_Warbler, Forages on the outer branches in the canopy of open pine forests, typically above 6,000 feet.
Olive_Warbler, A warbler-shaped songbird with a long bill and a notched tail. Males have an orange hood and black "ear" patch. Males and females are grayish overall with 2 bold white wingbars.
Olive_Warbler, Immature birds have faint yellowish patches on the chest and face. The light gray "ear" patch is usually conspicuous. Also note the yellow-green edging on the flight feathers.

Olive_Warbler, The Olive Warbler behaves similarly to other New World warblers despite not being in the same family. Usually forages for insects among branches and twigs of tall pine trees. Foraging style is similar to Pine Warbler—using a "creeping or hopping" method.
Olive_Warbler, A warbler-shaped songbird with a long bill and a notched tail. Males have an orange hood and black "ear" patch. Males and females are grayish overall with 2 bold white wingbars.
Olive_Warbler, A warbler-shaped songbird with a long bill and a notched tail. Males have an orange hood and black "ear" patch. Males and females are grayish overall with 2 bold white wingbars.
Olive_Warbler, Immature birds have an unstreaked grayish belly and a faint yellow wash on the chest and face.
Olive_Warbler, A warbler-shaped songbird with a long bill and a notched tail. Males have an orange hood and black "ear" patch. Males and females are grayish overall with 2 bold white wingbars.
Olive_Warbler, Found in the canopy of open coniferous forests.

Orange-crowned_Warbler, Small warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Generally yellow-olive overall with a faint eyeline. Birds in the West are brighter than birds in the East, but the undertail coverts are always yellow.

Orange-crowned_Warbler, Immature birds often grayer than adults. Head color varies regionally from gray in the East to yellow-green in the West, but they all have yellow undertail coverts (not visible in this photo). Note broken eyering and faint eyeline.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Forages for insects on the ground and in trees. Pokes through leaf litter, and probes bark and moss with the sharp, fine-tipped bill.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Western birds are brighter yellow-green with faint blurry streaking on the breast. Note thin, pointy bill and yellow undertail coverts.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Generally yellow-olive overall, but head color varies regionally from gray in the East to yellow-green in the West. Note broken eyering bisected by a faint eyeline.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Flits rapidly through shrubs, trees, vine tangles, and other vegetation as it glean insects from leaves and buds.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Adults have an orangish crown patch that is usually concealed and difficult to see.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Gray-headed subspecies has a grayer head, but note faint eyeline, thin, pointy bill, and yellow undertail coverts.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Orange-crowned Warblers supplement their diet with fruit and nectar during the winter. Sometimes visits fruit, suet, and hummingbird feeders.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Dull yellow-olive overall with a thin, pointy bill. Head color varies regionally from gray in the East to yellow-green in the West, but they all have yellow undertail coverts.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Populations on the Channel Islands and nearby mainland tend to have streaky breasts and undertail coverts. Note thin, pointy bill.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Sometimes visits suet feeders, especially during the winter.
Orange-crowned_Warbler, Often found foraging in dense shrubbery and low trees. Note thin, pointy bill and yellow undertail coverts.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbirds with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males are mostly black above with chestnut underparts and a chestnut patch in the wings.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbird with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Females are greenish yellow with two white wing bars and no black on the head or back.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbirds with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males are mostly black above with chestnut underparts and a chestnut patch in the wings.
Orchard_Oriole, Immature males are greenish yellow overall like females, but have a black throat.
Orchard_Oriole, The subspecies (Fuertes's) that breeds in northeast Mexico and winters in southwest Mexico has golden yellow underparts instead of chestnut.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbirds with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males are mostly black above with chestnut underparts and a chestnut patch in the wings.
Orchard_Oriole, As immature males molt into adult plumage patches of chestnut and black feathers begin to replace the greenish yellow feathers.
Orchard_Oriole, Small for an oriole with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males have a black hood and upper back and a chestnut rump and underparts.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbirds with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males are mostly black above with chestnut underparts and a chestnut patch in the wings.
Orchard_Oriole, The smallest breeding oriole in the U.S. and Canada. Adult male has a black hood and distinctive chestnut underparts.
Orchard_Oriole, Females are yellowish below and greenish above, with two narrow white wingbars.
Orchard_Oriole, Slim songbirds with a straight, sharply pointed bill. Adult males are mostly black above with chestnut underparts and a chestnut patch in the wings.
Orchard_Oriole, Spend summers in open woodlands and areas of scattered trees. Look for them along river edges, in pastures with scattered trees, and in parks and orchards.
Osprey, Large. Brown back and wings contrast with the white underparts. Head white with a broad brown line through the eye, beak black and strongly hooked.
Osprey, Breeds widely in the Northern Hemisphere, with the "haliaetus" group found in Eurasia and the "carolinensis" group nesting across much of the United States and Canada.
Osprey, Call is a high-pitched series of short whistles. The calls are often slow and paced far apart—when the speed increases, it's often a response to a threat or an unfamiliar Osprey approaching.
Osprey, "Australasian" Osprey is smaller than birds that breed across Eurasia.
Osprey, Has large feet with a unique structure for holding onto slippery fish prey.
Osprey, Flies on slightly bowed wings with a kink at the wrists, creating an M-shape when seen from below.
Osprey, Feeds exclusively on fish.
Osprey, Osprey breeding in the Caribbean (part of the "ridgwayi" group) are pale, appearing almost white-headed.
Osprey, Large raptor that eats fish exclusively. Note mostly white head with brown line behind eye.
Osprey, In flight shows white belly and underwings contrasting with brown "wrists" and strongly barred flight feathers.
Osprey, Juvenile has brown upperparts with extensive white edging, a buffy wash on the nape and breast, and orange eyes.
Osprey, Builds big stick nests in trees and on open-topped platforms. Juveniles have white edging to the back and wing feathers, creating a scaly appearance.
Osprey, Juvenile has brown upperparts with extensive white edging.
Osprey, Can show a distinct crest, depending on wind direction and mood.
Osprey, "Australasian" Osprey has a distinctive combination of pale head and dark breast band that separates it from other subspecies.
Osprey, Constructs prominent large stick nests on platforms or large trees.
Ovenbird, Rather chunky for a warbler with bold black spots on the chest, a white eyering, and a black and orange striped crown.
Ovenbird, Note bold black spots on the chest and black and orange striped crown, although crown color can be difficult to see.
Ovenbird, Song is a loud "teacher, teacher, teacher" that increases in volume as it goes on.
Ovenbird, Chunky, wide-eyed warbler with bold spotting on the chest, olive-brown upperparts and striped crown.
Ovenbird, Territorial males are very vocal, singing a loud "teacher, teacher, teacher" from tree branches, occasionally quite high up in the canopy.
Ovenbird, Typically forages on the ground in forest understory and leaf litter, walking with a hesitating gait.
Ovenbird, Breeds in closed-canopy forests, particularly deciduous and mixed deciduous-evergreen woods. Forages on the ground, often walking with a herky-jerky, wandering stroll.
Ovenbird, Note white eyering in otherwise unmarked face.
Ovenbird, Forages mainly by walking slowly through the leaf litter looking for concealed insects.

Pacific_Golden-Plover, Medium-sized shorebird with an upright posture and a short bill. Black face and underparts bordered by white stripe, extending from forehead to flanks. Upperparts are mottled in gold, black, and white.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, Breeding females have a more mottled white and brown face with a thicker white stripe down the flanks.  Note spotted undertail coverts.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, Call is a high, rising whistle. Nests on tundra in western Alaska and Eurasia; males help incubate and care for the young.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, A shorebird with an upright posture and a short, somewhat thick bill. Nonbreeding birds have a pale eyebrow stripe with gold-spotted backs and grayish smudgy breasts.

Pacific_Golden-Plover, A shorebird with an upright posture and a short, somewhat thick bill. The wing feathers barely extend beyond the tail. Nonbreeding birds have a pale face with a paler eyebrow and golden spots on the back.

Pacific_Golden-Plover, Winters across Pacific including the Hawaiian Islands, Australia, and New Zealand. This individual shows a few black belly feathers beginning to molt in as breeding season approaches.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, During the nonbreeding season found in fields, grassy areas, beaches, and mudflats. Nonbreeding birds have a pale face with with a paler eyebrow and golden spots on the back.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, In flight, note dark rump, long, pointed wings, and heavy chest.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, Molting adults have the spotted back and pale eyebrow of a nonbreeding bird combined with the black belly of a breeding bird.
Pacific_Golden-Plover, Slightly smaller, more slender, with a thinner bill than Black-bellied Plovers (background).
Pacific_Loon, Long-bodied waterbird with thin bill and round head. Breeding birds have pale gray head and nape with vertical black-and-white stripes on the neck and thick white stripes on the back.
Pacific_Loon, Nonbreeding birds often show less white on their back that other loons. Most nonbreeding birds have a dusky chinstrap, but this can be difficult to see.
Pacific_Loon, Bill is less heavy than Common Loon's but heavier than Red-throated Loon's. Catches fish by diving, using feet for propulsion.
Pacific_Loon, In flight, often holds head level with the body. Head and neck are gray.
Pacific_Loon, Has a shorter neck than other loons. Nonbreeding/immature birds often have a dusky chinstrap.
Pacific_Loon, Daggerlike bill typically held horizontally. Some birds in summer don't molt into breeding plumage; these have whiter necks with dusky vertical stripes.
Pacific_Loon, Long-bodied waterbird with thin bill and round head. Breeding birds have pale gray head and nape with vertical black-and-white stripes on the neck and thick white stripes on the back.
Pacific_Loon, Nonbreeding birds often show less white on the back that other loons. Most nonbreeding birds have a dusky chinstrap, but this can be difficult to see.
Pacific_Loon, Long-bodied waterbird with thin bill and round head. Breeding birds have pale gray head and nape with vertical black-and-white stripes on the neck and thick white stripes on the back.
Pacific_Loon, During migration, often found in large flocks.
Pacific_Loon, Breeds in freshwater ponds and wetlands in the Arctic.
Pacific_Wren, Small, plump ball with a thin tail, often held up. Brown overall with barring on the wings and tail. Note pale eyebrow.
Pacific_Wren, Small, round wren with a short and thin tail. Brown overall with barring on the wings, tail, and belly.
Pacific_Wren, Small, plump ball with a thin tail, often held up. Brown overall with barring on the wings and tail. Note pale eyebrow.
Pacific_Wren, Holds tail upright when singing a series of tumbling, trilling notes with a staccato quality.
Pacific_Wren, Residents on the Pribilof Islands, Alaska, are larger than other Pacific Wrens and tend to be paler without the rusty tones.
Pacific_Wren, Small, plump ball with a thin tail, often held up. Brown overall with barring on the wings and tail. Note pale eyebrow.
Pacific_Wren, Most common in old-growth evergreen forests, but also found in deciduous forests, treeless islands in Alaska, and in mixed-species forests near streams.
Pacific_Wren, Small, plump ball with a thin tail, often held up. Brown overall with barring on the wings and tail. Note pale eyebrow.
Painted_Bunting, Stocky, finchlike bird with a stubby, thick, seed-eating bill. Adult males are unmistakable with their brilliant blue head, green back, red rump and red belly.
Painted_Bunting, Females and immatures are a uniform, bright yellow-green overall, with a pale eyering.
Painted_Bunting, Males sing a sweet musical jumble when attracting mates or defending territories.
Painted_Bunting, Immature male shows a highly muted version of adult male's color pattern, with hints of blue on the head and wing.

Painted_Bunting, Stocky bird with a finchlike conical bill. Females/immatures are yellow-green overall, with a pale eyering. Oftentimes appears dull overall, but in general appears greener than similar species.
Painted_Bunting, Feeds on seeds for the majority of the year, but eats more insects during the breeding season.
Painted_Bunting, Males are stunningly colored with blue heads, red underparts, and green backs. Forages on the ground most often in dense cover, among grasses, or at seed feeders.
Painted_Bunting, Breeds in dense brush, often adjacent to thick, grassy areas or woodland edges.
Painted_Bunting, Both local and vagrant Painted Buntings often seek out bird feeders as an easy source of food.
Painted_Bunting, Usually occupies riparian thickets, shrubby areas, and open woodlands throughout the year.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Juveniles are grayish overall with white wing patches and white crescent below the eye.
Painted_Redstart, The undertail is white, which they regularly flash while foraging.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.
Painted_Redstart, Larger warbler with a bright red belly, white wing patches, and a white crescent below the eye. Sexes similar year-round.

Palm_Warbler, On the larger side for a warbler with a round belly and a rusty cap. Warblers breeding east of Hudson Bay ("Yellow" Palm Warblers) have entirely yellow underparts with stronger rusty streaks on the breast and yellow eyebrows.
Palm_Warbler, Large, stocky warbler with a rusty cap. Individuals breeding west of Hudson Bay ("Western" Palm Warblers) have whitish bellies, yellow undertails, and pale eyebrows.
Palm_Warbler, Wags tail nearly constantly. Note yellow undertail coverts, which are distinctive in all plumages and populations.

Palm_Warbler, Nonbreeding/immatures have paler yellow undertails, a dull brown crown, and faint streaking on the breast. Most individuals in eastern North America (Yellow) have yellower bellies and a yellow eyebrow.

Palm_Warbler, Nonbreeders and immatures have paler yellow undertails, a dull brown crown, and faint streaking on the breast. Individuals in western North America (Western) have whitish bellies and a pale eyebrow.

Palm_Warbler, On the larger side for a warbler with a round belly and a rusty cap. Warblers breeding east of Hudson Bay ("Yellow" Palm Warblers) have entirely yellow underparts with stronger rusty streaks on the breast and yellow eyebrows.
Palm_Warbler, Nonbreeders and immatures have paler yellow undertails, a dull brown crown, and faint streaking on the breast. Note yellow undertail coverts.
Palm_Warbler, Nonbreeders and immatures have paler yellow undertails, a dull brown crown, and faint streaking on the breast. Note yellow undertail coverts.
Palm_Warbler, Often forages on the ground and in open areas. Wags tail nearly constantly.
Palm_Warbler, Often found foraging on the ground. Wags its tail nearly constantly.
Palm_Warbler, Breeds in the boreal forest in bogs with scattered evergreen trees and thick ground cover. Eastern birds have entirely yellow underparts.
Palm_Warbler, Eats insects in summer and seeds and berries in winter. Typically forages in open areas including bogs, weedy fields, and forest edges.
Parakeet_Auklet, Small auk with round head and very thick, short bill. In breeding plumage, note dark throat. Pale eye, orange bill, and single white streak behind eye visible all year.
Parakeet_Auklet, Small auk with very thick, short, orange bill. Nonbreeding birds (right) have white extending up onto the throat; breeding birds have dark throats.

Parakeet_Auklet, Typically selects nesting sites along high cliffs with rocky crevices or within steep grassy slopes where burrowing is possible. Occasionally chooses to use abandoned burrows from previous auklet pairs.
Parakeet_Auklet, Small auk with round head and very thick, short bill. All-dark upperparts with pale streak behind eye.
Parakeet_Auklet, In flight, note all-dark upperparts contrasting with white underparts.
Parakeet_Auklet, Pairs perform displays including coordinated calling and "billing" or rubbing the bills together, near nesting sites during breeding season.
Parakeet_Auklet, Breeds on rocky cliffs and slopes on islands of the Bering Sea; forages and winters at sea.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Powerful, gull-like seabird with angular wings and full-chested look. Breeding adults have central tail feathers roughly double the length of the tail. Light morph has sharply defined dark cap with white arc near the bill, a creamy neck, and pale underparts.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Gull-like seabird with powerful, acrobatic flight style. Dark morphs are uniform dark brown with bright flashes in the outer wings. Parasitic Jaegers have more white in the wing than Long-tailed, but less white than Pomarine.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Nests on arctic tundra and hunts mainly birds and their eggs. Jaegers can occur in light, intermediate, and dark morphs. Dark morphs are all chocolate brown with pale patches in the outer wing.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Juvenile jaegers can be very difficult to identify to species. They always lack the distinctive tail feathers of breeding adults. Parasitic Jaegers have a smallish bill, a full-chested look, and moderate white flashes in the wing.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Immature jaegers can be very difficult to identify. Parasitic Jaegers tend to be pale brown, particularly on the head, with little contrast on the rump. The white wing flashes appear on both the upperside and underside of the wing.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Juvenile jaegers can be very difficult to identify. Parasitic Jaegers usually have a single white flash in each wing, whereas Long-tailed has a thin white edge to the wing and young Pomarines have a double flash in each wing.
Parasitic_Jaeger, Adult light morphs have a dark cap with a pale spot or arc just before the bill.
Parasitic_Jaeger, Breeds on tundra of the high Arctic.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Powerful, gull-like seabird with angular wings and full-chested look. Breeding adults have central tail feathers roughly double the length of the tail. Light morph has sharply defined dark cap with white arc near the bill, a creamy neck, and pale underparts.

Parasitic_Jaeger, Powerful, gull-like seabird with angular wings and full-chested look. Breeding adults have central tail feathers roughly double the length of the tail. Light morph has sharply defined dark cap with white arc near the bill, a creamy neck, and pale underparts.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a heavily streaked breast and a bright white belly that forms a sharp border.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Overall a medium-sized shorebird. Juvenile has a finely streaked breast that forms a sharp border with its white belly. Feathers on the back have rufous edging.

Pectoral_Sandpiper, Male's courtship display involves flying over the female, then following her on the ground, bobbing head, puffing out his chest, raising his tail, and eventually stretching his wings toward the sky. After mating, males do not help raise young.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a heavily streaked breast and a bright white belly that forms a sharp border.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Streaked chest forms a sharp border with the white belly.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Sharp border between streaked neck and white belly. Found in wet grassy areas and saltmarshes during migration.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, In flight bright white belly contrasts with darker breast. In flight, shows only a very faint wingstripe.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a heavily streaked breast and a bright white belly that forms a sharp border.
Pectoral_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a heavily streaked breast and a bright white belly that forms a sharp border.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird—but smaller than most other cormorants, with a slender neck and thin bill. Black overall with a green sheen on the body.
Pelagic_Cormorant, In flight, breeding birds show white patches on the lower flanks.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird—but smaller than most other cormorants, with a slender neck and thin bill. Black overall with a green sheen on the body.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird with a thin neck and small bill. Nonbreeding birds are blackish overall.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Breeding adults have white patches on the flanks, a greenish sheen on the body, a purplish sheen on the head, and a red chin patch.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird—but smaller than most other cormorants, with a slender neck and thin bill. Black overall with a green sheen on the body.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Breeding birds look dark overall but in the right light the body has a green sheen and the head a purplish sheen.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Slender waterbird with a small head, thin neck, and thin bill. Immature and nonbreeding birds are dark overall.
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird—but smaller than most other cormorants, with a slender neck and thin bill. Black overall with a green sheen on the body.

Pelagic_Cormorant, Breeds and roosts along rocky coasts and forages in coastal waters, never far from land. Smaller with a more slender neck and thinner bill than Double-crested Cormorant (center right, with light brown chest).
Pelagic_Cormorant, Large, slender waterbird—but smaller than most other cormorants, with a slender neck and thin bill. Black overall with a green sheen on the body.

Peregrine_Falcon, A medium-to-large falcon that occurs on every continent but Antarctica. "North American" adults have a grayish-black helmet, white breast, barred belly and flanks, and dark gray upperparts.
Peregrine_Falcon, Juveniles have buffy underparts that are densely streaked with dark brown. Note brown mask and whisker, and paler eyebrow imparting a distinctive face pattern.
Peregrine_Falcon, Large falcon with bold black "sideburns" and strongly barred underparts. Often hunts shorebirds along coastlines.
Peregrine_Falcon, Long, pointed wings. In flight shows strongly checkered whitish and black underwings and flanks.
Peregrine_Falcon, Long, pointed wings. In flight juveniles show boldly checked brown and whitish underwings, dense brown streaking on the underparts, and fine barring in the flight feathers and tail.
Peregrine_Falcon, Call is a long series of harsh "kak" notes, usually given as an alarm.
Peregrine_Falcon, Long, pointed wings. In flight immatures show boldly checked brown and whitish underwings, dense brown streaking on the underparts, and fine barring in the flight feathers and tail.
Peregrine_Falcon, Primarily hunts other birds, but will take a variety of prey.

Peregrine_Falcon, Powerful but relaxed flight style with fluid beats of the long, sharply pointed wings. Hefty body and fairly long tail. Sometimes mobbed by other species trying to drive away the danger.
Peregrine_Falcon, "Barbary" Peregrine Falcons, found on the Canary Islands and from Morocco to western Iran, have buffy markings on the back of the head and nape.

Peregrine_Falcon, "Peale's" Peregrine Falcons occur along the Pacific Coast from Washington to Alaska. Juveniles are extremely dark, with nearly blackish upperparts and heavy dark streaking on the underparts.
Peregrine_Falcon, Large falcon with dark upperparts and sharply pointed wings.

Peregrine_Falcon, "Tundra" Peregrines nest on the tundra of North America and Eurasia. Compared to adults, juveniles are brownish (rather than gray) and fairly pale, with creamy white on the head and underparts and upperparts heavily marked with buffy feather edging.
Peregrine_Falcon, Dark gray above with a blackish helmet and a yellow eyering and cere. Bill small and strongly hooked. Underparts pale whitish, with fine dark barring on the flanks.
Peregrine_Falcon, "Mediterranean" Peregrine Falcons occur from the Mediterranean to the Caucasus and northern Iran.
Peregrine_Falcon, Adult "Red-capped" Peregrine Falcons have light gray upperparts and reddish-brown marks on the head and nape.
Peregrine_Falcon, Adult "Shaheen" Peregrine Falcons of South Asia and East Asia have nearly blackish upperparts and a reddish-orange wash below.
Peregrine_Falcon, Immature "Shaheen" Peregrine Falcons have a blackish helmet and off-white underparts with a buffy wash and fine streaking.
Peregrine_Falcon, Feeds mainly on birds, with over 425 North American bird species alone documented as prey.
Peregrine_Falcon, Sometimes nests and roosts on tall buildings.
Peregrine_Falcon, Sometimes nests and roosts on tall cliffs.
Phainopepla, Slender medium-sized songbird with a long tail and shaggy crest. Females are dark gray overall with white edging on the wing feathers. Note red eye.
Phainopepla, Consumes a large amount of fruit, which it swallows whole.
Phainopepla, Long and slender songbird with a red eye and shaggy crest. Males are entirely glossy black.
Phainopepla, Long and slender crested bird of dry woodlands and deserts. Males are glossy black overall, but have visible white wing patches in flight.
Phainopepla, Sometimes drinks from temporary pools of water.
Phainopepla, Females are dark gray overall with a red eye and a shaggy crest. Note long tail and slender appearance.
Phainopepla, Found in the Sonoran and Mojave Deserts. Often seen perched on the tops of trees and shrubs.
Phainopepla, Juveniles look like females, but often have a yellowish bill.
Phainopepla, Found in dry woodlands and deserts. Often perches on top of tall trees and shrubs giving a rising "wurp."

Philadelphia_Vireo, Somewhat stocky songbird with a thick, hooked bill. Adults in fresh plumage are bright yellow below with a yellow throat. The dark gray crown contrasts with the white eyebrow, though this can be indistinct on some birds.

Philadelphia_Vireo, Small and stocky songbird. Rather plain and unmarked overall with a yellowish belly, gray crown, and grayish brown back. Note unmarked wings. Some individuals are brighter than others.

Philadelphia_Vireo, A small, compact vireo with a gray crown, white stripe above the eye, and light yellow throat. Male sings a song that is very similar to the song of Red-eyed Vireo, with short, variable phrases given with a pause of 1–2 seconds in between phrases.
Philadelphia_Vireo, Small songbird. Pale yellow below with a gray crown and white eyebrow. Easily confused with Warbling and Red-eyed Vireos.
Philadelphia_Vireo, Often perches horizontally. Upperparts are brownish gray with unmarked wings. Underparts are washed in pale yellow; some individuals are brighter. Note white eyebrow and dark eye.
Philadelphia_Vireo, Hops between small twigs in trees and shrubs. This video has no audio.

Philadelphia_Vireo, A small, compact vireo with a gray crown, white stripe above the eye, and light yellow throat. Male sings a song that is very similar to the song of Red-eyed Vireo, with short, variable phrases given with a pause of 1–2 seconds in between phrases.

Philadelphia_Vireo, A small, compact vireo with a gray crown, white stripe above the eye, and light yellow throat. Male sings a song that is very similar to the song of Red-eyed Vireo, with short, variable phrases given with a pause of 1–2 seconds in between phrases.
Philadelphia_Vireo, Jumps up to pick insects off leaves or grabs insects while perched. This video has no audio.

Philadelphia_Vireo, A small, compact vireo with a gray crown, white stripe above the eye, and light yellow throat. Male sings a song that is very similar to the song of Red-eyed Vireo, with short, variable phrases given with a pause of 1–2 seconds in between phrases.
Philadelphia_Vireo, Note the yellow underparts and plainer face; two features that help separate it from the similar looking Red-eyed Vireo. This video has no audio.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Small, chunky waterbird with a blocky head, short, thick bill, and almost no tail. Breeding birds have a vertical black stripe on the bill.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Small waterbird with a short, thick bill and almost no tail. Nonbreeding birds have a brownish neck and lack the black bill stripe.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Propels itself rather quickly with its lobed feet across flat or sluggish water bodies.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Can adjust their buoyancy to float with just the upper half of the head above the water.
Pied-billed_Grebe, They have lobed feet to help propel them underwater.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Some nonbreeding birds have more cinnamon coloring on the neck.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Small, chunky waterbird with a blocky head, short, thick bill, and almost no tail. Breeding birds have a vertical black stripe on the bill.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Breeds in quiet ponds and marshes with wetland vegetation.
Pied-billed_Grebe, Forages in slow moving waters with aquatic vegetation. Juveniles accompany adults for several weeks.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Nonbreeding birds have smudgy black-and-white bodies with variable amounts of white on the head and underparts.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Breeding adults are entirely black with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Breeding adults are entirely black with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Breeding adults are entirely black with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Breeding adults are entirely black with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Black overall with white wing patches bisected by a black bar.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Black seabird of rocky coastlines with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Medium-sized seabird with a thin bill. Breeding adults are entirely black with white wing patches.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Breeding birds have bright red legs and feet.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Nonbreeding birds have smudgy black-and-white bodies with variable amounts of white on the head and underparts. Found more often in sheltered inshore waters in winter.
Pigeon_Guillemot, Found along rocky coastlines between Alaska and California. Nests on the ground in crevices or burrows in rocky cliffs. Forages in near-shore waters.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Large woodpecker with white stripes on the face continuing down the neck and a red crest. Males have a bright red crest and a red stripe on the cheek.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Large woodpecker with a heavy bill. Females have a red crest like the males but don't have the red cheek stripe.

Pileated_Woodpecker, Very large woodpecker with mostly black body. Female has gray-black forecrown and red crest; she lacks the red mustache mark of the male. Often feeds in one spot for long periods as it works to get insect larvae from under bark or inside wood.
Pileated_Woodpecker, In flight shows white underwings and a white stripe in the upperwings. Flies with a distinctive, vaguely crowlike style.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Sometimes raises wings in display or aggression, showing white underwings.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Often forages on fallen logs, using heavy bill to dig into rotten wood for carpenter ants and other insects. Males have fully red crown and red mustache stripe.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Excavates holes in holes in large trees for nesting.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Excavates large holes, usually oblong in shape.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Digs deeply into soft wood, leaving distinctive rectangular excavations. Powerful blows of the bill can be audible from far away.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Typically found in wooded areas with at least some large trees.
Pileated_Woodpecker, Nestlings beg loudly from nest entrances. Both sexes feed the young. Adult female has gray-black forecrown and lacks red mustache stripe of male.
Pine_Grosbeak, Large and plump, heavy-chested finch with a round head. Its conical finchlike bill is thick and stubby. Adult males are rosy red and gray with two white wingbars on dark gray wings.
Pine_Grosbeak, A large, plump finch with a short, stubby bill. Females are mostly gray, with orange or yellow on the head and rump. Note the long tail and two white wingbars.
Pine_Grosbeak, A large, plump, heavy-chested finch with a short, stubby bill. Male is reddish-pink and gray, with two white wingbars on dark wings.
Pine_Grosbeak, Immature males are grayish with tints of reddish orange or yellow on the head, chest, and rump.

Pine_Grosbeak, North America's largest finch. Adult males are distinguished from other reddish finches by combination of large size; stubby, slightly hooked bill; bold white wingbars; and long, forked tail.
Pine_Grosbeak, Female/immature is grayish with tints of reddish orange or yellow on the head and rump. Note also dark gray wings with two white wingbars.
Pine_Grosbeak, Plump, heavy-chested finch with a thick, stubby bill. Adult females have golden yellow heads and chests with a gray lower belly and dark gray wings with two white wingbars.
Pine_Grosbeak, Plumage coloration varies regionally, but not consistently. Immature males on the coast tend to be darker red on the head and chest.
Pine_Grosbeak, Plumage varies regionally, but not always consistently. Some adult males in the interior of North America have more grayish mottling on their backs with grayer flanks.
Pine_Grosbeak, The amount of yellow on the head, chest, and rump on females is variable. This female has limited yellow on the head and no yellow on the chest. Note stocky size and thick stubby bill.
Pine_Grosbeak, In flight, size and shape are reminiscent of American Robin. Note Pine Grosbeak's undulating flight, with a series of slow wingbeats followed by a long glide.
Pine_Grosbeak, Breeds in open spruce, fir, and pine forests as well as subalpine forests. In winter, tends to use mountain ash, maple, and ash forests with abundant seeds.
Pine_Siskin, Small finch with a sharp, pointed bill and a short, notched tail. Adults are brown and streaky overall with subtle yellow edgings on the wings and tail.
Pine_Siskin, Small, streaky finch with a sharply pointed bill and notched tail.
Pine_Siskin, Small, heavily streaked finch with yellow tones in the wings and tail. Note the sharply pointed bill that is thinner than in other finches.
Pine_Siskin, Immatures look similar to adults.
Pine_Siskin, The rarely encountered "green morph" has more intense yellow and green plumage tones and often reduced streaking below.
Pine_Siskin, Adult males resident in the highlands of s. Chiapas and w. Guatemala have a black cap, gray lightly streaked underparts and brighter yellow edging in the wings and tail.
Pine_Siskin, Female "Chiapas" Pine Siskin is similar to "Northern" Pine Siskin, but note the grayish eyeline and more diffusely streaked underparts.
Pine_Siskin, Juveniles look similar to adults, but have buffy edging on their wing feathers.
Pine_Siskin, Brown and streaky finch with a sharply pointed bill. Cannot be reliably sexed based on the amount of yellow in the wings.
Pine_Siskin, Feeds mostly on seeds—both coniferous and deciduous—and also eats some plant buds, stems, and leaves.

Pine_Siskin, Rare "green morph" birds, which appear to be exclusively male, have darker and more greenish upperparts, paler and less extensively streaked underparts, and more extensive yellow at the base of the wings and tail.
Pine_Siskin, A social species, often found in noisy flocks.
Pine_Siskin, Found in evergreen or mixed forests with open canopies, weedy fields, scrubby thickets, or backyards and gardens.

Pine_Warbler, A large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.
Pine_Warbler, Large (for a warbler) with a stout bill. Adult females are pale yellow with a broken yellow eyering and 2 white wingbars.

Pine_Warbler, A large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.
Pine_Warbler, Some immature females are gray overall lacking any yellow coloration, with a broken white eyering and 2 white wingbars.
Pine_Warbler, Immature birds vary from gray to pale yellow, but they all have a white eyering.

Pine_Warbler, A large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.

Pine_Warbler, Large (for a warbler) with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.
Pine_Warbler, Large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat and a yellow-olive back. Note broken yellow eyering.

Pine_Warbler, A large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.
Pine_Warbler, Large warbler with a stout bill. Adult females are pale yellow with a broken yellow eyering and 2 white wingbars.
Pine_Warbler, Unlike most warblers sometimes visits feeders.

Pine_Warbler, A large warbler with a stout bill. Adult males have a yellow throat, a yellow-olive back, and blurry streaking on the sides. Note broken yellow eyering and white lower belly and undertail coverts.
Pine_Warbler, Found in pine forests often foraging high in the canopy.

Pink-footed_Goose, A medium-sized goose with a dark brown head, a lighter brown neck and breast, dark flanks, and light blue-gray to brownish upperparts. The short, stubby bill is mostly dark with a variable pink mark. The legs and feet are pink.
Pink-footed_Goose, In flight, note the mainly light gray upperwings and darker underwings. The white tail has a dark grayish band and a broad white tip.
Pink-footed_Goose, Grazes on grasses and agricultural crops during the winter.
Pink-footed_Goose, Rare in the United States and Canada, but when found here, usually in the company of larger Canada Geese.
Pink-footed_Goose, Nests on arctic tundra or on rocky cliffs, outcrops, or pinnacles.
Pink-footed_Goose, Gathers in large flocks on wintering grounds.
Pinyon_Jay, Smaller, crestless jay with a long sharply pointed bill and shorter tail. Entirely dull blue, except for whitish chin.
Pinyon_Jay, The bill is longer and the tail shorter than other jays. Dull bluish gray overall.
Pinyon_Jay, Eats seeds, plants, insects, acorns, and visits bird feeders.
Pinyon_Jay, Crestless dull blue jay with a long, pointed bill and short tail.
Pinyon_Jay, From below often looks grayish. Uses its long, pointed bill to access pine seeds.
Pinyon_Jay, Eats seeds, plants, insects, acorns, and visits bird feeders.
Pinyon_Jay, Highly social. Breeds in colonies and forages in large flocks.
Pinyon_Jay, Found in groups in pinyon-juniper woodland, sagebrush, scrub oak, and chaparral.
Pinyon_Jay, Forms large, often noisy flocks.
Piping_Plover, Round and stocky little plover that frequently stands in a horizontal position. Breeding adult has a short, orange bill with a black tip, a black crown stripe and black neck band.
Piping_Plover, Nonbreeding adults and immature birds have an all-black bill but lack the black neck band and black crown mark of breeding adults.
Piping_Plover, A stocky little plover with sandy upperparts, white underparts, and yellowish-orange legs in all seasons. Nonbreeding adult has a black bill and a partial brown collar.
Piping_Plover, Note the extremely pale, sand-colored upperparts in all plumages.
Piping_Plover, Juvenile has a plain face, a stubby black bill, and yellow legs.
Piping_Plover, Forages on shorelines and mudflats; uses stout bill to probe mainly for marine worms.
Piping_Plover, In flight, note pale rump and white wingstripe.
Piping_Plover, Chick is capable of walking several hours after hatching.
Piping_Plover, Forages alone or in small groups sticking to the higher parts of the shoreline relative to other shorebirds.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large, often arboreal chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail tipped in white. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, Call is a very loud, raucous, repeated "chac-a-lak."
Plain_Chachalaca, Often climbs trees. Large, chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail tipped in white. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, When displaying, a patch of red bare skin under the throat is visible.
Plain_Chachalaca, Largely arboreal chickenlike bird that walks or runs along larger tree limbs.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large, often arboreal chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail tipped in white. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large, often arboreal chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail tipped in white. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, Forages in shrubs and trees as well as on the ground for seeds, plant material, and fruits.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large, often arboreal chickenlike bird with a small head and a long tail tipped in white. Brownish gray above with a buffy belly.
Plain_Chachalaca, Large chickenlike bird with a long tail tipped in white. Often found in small groups.
Plain_Chachalaca, Often shy in areas where they are hunted, but in other areas they readily accept food and water from humans. This video has no audio.
Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill, large head, and short neck. Upperparts grayish overall with little to no contrast between head and back. Note bold white "spectacles."

Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill and slow, deliberate foraging style. Fairly uniform grayish upperparts with white underparts; flanks sometimes washed with grayish or yellowish. Two white wingbars.
Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill, large head, and short neck. Upperparts grayish overall with little to no contrast between head and back. Note bold white "spectacles."
Plumbeous_Vireo, Like other vireos, bill is thicker than a warbler's with a slight hook at the tip. Uniform grayish above with white "spectacles" and wingbars; white below.
Plumbeous_Vireo, Typically forages in small twigs with slow and deliberate pace.
Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill, large head, and short neck. Upperparts grayish overall with little to no contrast between head and back. Note bold white "spectacles."
Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill, large head, and short neck. Upperparts grayish overall with little to no contrast between head and back. Note bold white "spectacles."

Plumbeous_Vireo, Typically breeds in mountain forests above 3,500 feet elevation, particularly in ponderosa pine and pinyon-juniper. Also uses woodlands along streams including cottonwoods, box elder, and willows, as well as pine-oak forests and oak scrub.
Plumbeous_Vireo, Small songbird with thick bill, large head, and short neck. Upperparts grayish overall with little to no contrast between head and back. Note bold white "spectacles."
Pomarine_Jaeger, Large, powerful seabird with sharply pointed wings. Of all the jaeger species, Pomarine has the largest white flashes in the wings.
Pomarine_Jaeger, Heavy-bodied, barrel-chested seabird. Pomarine Jaegers often show a "double flash" in the wings with a white bar near the wrist in addition to the white flash in the primaries.

Prairie_Falcon, Sandy brown falcon with white cheek, white line over eye, and thin dark mustache stripe. Immatures have heavier dark streaking on the underparts. The cere (skin around base of bill) is bluish gray.
Prairie_Falcon, Large falcon with long, pointed wings, white line over eye. In adults tail is often paler than wings. Adults have yellow skin around the bill (cere) and yellow legs and feet.
Prairie_Falcon, Large falcon with sandy brown upperparts and strong "mustache" mark on face. Juveniles have bold streaks on the breast.

Prairie_Falcon, Large falcon with sharply pointed wings and fairly long tail. Uniform sandy brown upperparts. Note whitish line over the eye, pale cheek, and narrow malar or "mustache" stripe. Tail is often lighter than wings.
Prairie_Falcon, Large falcon with sharply pointed wings. Prominent dark "armpits" and wing linings are distinctive when seen. Note thin mustache stripe.

Prairie_Falcon, Large falcon with sharply pointed wings and a long, slightly tapering tail. Flies with shallow wingbeats and may glide for short periods on flat or slightly bowed wings. Mostly pale below but with distinctive black axillaries or "armpits."
Prairie_Falcon, Sandy brown falcon with white cheek, white line over eye, and thin dark mustache stripe. Adults have neat brownish spotting on the underparts.

Prairie_Falcon, Sandy brown falcon with white cheek, white line over eye, and thin dark mustache stripe. Immatures have heavier dark streaking on the underparts. The cere (skin around base of bill) is bluish gray.

Prairie_Falcon, Sandy brown falcon with white cheek, white line over eye, and thin dark mustache stripe. Immatures have heavier dark streaking on the underparts. The cere (skin around base of bill) is bluish gray.

Prairie_Falcon, Sandy brown falcon with white cheek, white line over eye, and thin dark mustache stripe. Immatures have heavier dark streaking on the underparts. The cere (skin around base of bill) is bluish gray.
Prairie_Falcon, Hunts ground squirrels and other small mammals and birds across open country of western North America, including plains, prairies, agricultural land, deserts, and sagebrush.
Prairie_Warbler, Small warbler. Adult males are bright yellow below with black streaking on the flanks. Note black eyeline, black semicircle under the eye, and chestnut back patch.

Prairie_Warbler, Females/immatures are paler yellow with blurry streaks on the sides. The head can be yellowish or grayish with darker semicircle under the eye, giving them a thick broken eyering look.
Prairie_Warbler, Song is a rising series of buzzy notes.

Prairie_Warbler, Females/immatures are paler yellow than males with blurry streaks on the sides. The head can be yellowish or grayish with darker semicircle under the eye, in an echo of the male's face pattern.
Prairie_Warbler, Adult males are bright yellow below with black streaking on the flanks. Note black eyeline and semicircle under the eye.
Prairie_Warbler, Small warbler. Adult males are bright yellow below with black streaking on the flanks. Note black eyeline, black semicircle under the eye, and chestnut back patch.
Prairie_Warbler, Often sings from exposed perches throughout the day.
Prairie_Warbler, Found in scrubby fields and forests throughout the eastern and south-central United States.
Prairie_Warbler, Small warbler. Adult males are bright yellow below with black streaking on the flanks. Note black eyeline, black semicircle under the eye, and chestnut back patch.
Prairie_Warbler, Small warbler. Adult males are bright yellow below with black streaking on the flanks. Note black eyeline, black semicircle under the eye, and chestnut back patch.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, heavy-bodied warbler with a big head and bill. Bright yellow overall with an olive back and grayish wings. Undertail coverts are white.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large warbler with a thicker black bill and a big head. Females are slightly paler than males with a crown and nape washed with green.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, heavy-bodied warbler with a big head and bill. Bright yellow overall with an olive back and grayish wings. Undertail coverts are white.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Forages in the understory, slowly hopping along branches, twigs, and on the ground.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, big-headed warbler with a thicker bill than most warblers. Golden yellow overall with an olive back and gray wings.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, heavy-bodied warbler with a big head and bill. Bright yellow overall with an olive back and grayish wings. Undertail coverts are white.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes in wooded swamps and forested wetlands.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Heavy-bodied warbler that is yellow overall with a beady black eye.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, heavy-bodied warbler with a big head and bill. Bright yellow overall with an olive back and grayish wings. Undertail coverts are white.
Prothonotary_Warbler, Large, heavy-bodied warbler with a big head and bill. Bright yellow overall with an olive back and grayish wings. Undertail coverts are white.
Purple_Finch, Small finch with a conical seed-eating bill. Adult males have a raspberry red head, breast, and back.
Purple_Finch, Females are coarsely streaked below, with strong facial markings including a whitish eyebrow and a dark line down the side of the throat.
Purple_Finch, Often forages in the upper parts of trees eating mainly seeds and soft buds of evergreen trees and elms, tulip poplars, maples, and others.

Purple_Finch, "Western" Purple Finches occur along the Pacific Coast from British Columbia to Baja California. Compared to "Eastern" males, "Western" males have more olive-green coloration and generally have brown markings on the sides and flanks.
Purple_Finch, Individuals from the western states tend to be more olive colored on the back with less well-defined streaks on the belly. Their head pattern is also less distinct.
Purple_Finch, Small, somewhat stocky finch. Like other finches, it has a notched tail. Adult males have a raspberry red head, breast, and back.
Purple_Finch, Females/immatures are brown overall with crisp brown streaking on the breast and flanks. Also note white eyebrow.

Purple_Finch, Purple Finches are erratic migrants that follow cone crops. Typically they leave Canadian breeding grounds to winter widely across the central and southeastern U.S, returning to specific regions roughly every other year.
Purple_Finch, In winter, found in a wider variety of habitats, including shrublands, old fields, forest edges, and backyards.
Purple_Finch, Breeds mainly in evergreen forests or mixed woodlands.
Purple_Gallinule, Medium-sized marsh bird with long yellow legs. Adults are an brilliant purple with a bright red-and-yellow bill.
Purple_Gallinule, Juveniles are pale brown with tints of bronze-green on the wings and back. Note white undertail coverts and long toes.

Purple_Gallinule, Despite having incredibly long toes that help distribute their weight as they walk on floating vegetation, these birds also manage to cling to plant stems and fairly often move through marshes this way.
Purple_Gallinule, Immature birds are bronze above with purple feathers coming in on the chest. The bill and forehead shield are pale.
Purple_Gallinule, Flies with legs hanging down when going short distances. Note iridescent bronze, green, and blue back and red-and-yellow bill.

Purple_Gallinule, Adults have a blue shield on the forehead and a bright red-and-yellow bill. In good light their backs shine with green and turquoise colors. Can swim like a duck and walk on vegetation.
Purple_Gallinule, Their long toes help them grab onto stems of marsh plants and walk on top of floating vegetation.
Purple_Gallinule, Brilliant purple marsh bird with a red-and-yellow bill and long yellow legs. Walks on top of floating marsh vegetation, often pushing its head forward with each step.
Purple_Gallinule, Found in freshwater marshes with dense stands of floating vegetation.
Purple_Martin, Large, broad-chested swallow with a slightly hooked bill and long, tapered wings. Adult males are iridescent, dark blue-purple overall with brown-black wings and tail.
Purple_Martin, Large and chunky swallow. Females/immatures are duller, with variable amounts of gray on the head and chest and a dingy lower belly. Note gray collar around the neck.
Purple_Martin, Purple Martins commonly utilize artificial nest box colonies when raising their young.

Purple_Martin, Martins pair up with one male and one female per nest, but sometimes two females may settle into different compartments of one male's territory, and both sexes frequently mate outside of their pair bond.
Purple_Martin, In flight, note long, tapered wings and forked tail. Adult males are dark purplish overall, but often appear black.
Purple_Martin, Adult males are iridescent, dark blue-purple overall, but often look black.
Purple_Martin, Females/immatures in flight look brownish below with a paler speckled belly.

Purple_Martin, Large and long-bodied with a small head and bill. Females/immatures are duller, with variable amounts of gray on the head and chest and a dingy lower belly with variable amounts of speckling.
Purple_Martin, A Purple Martin's dark body, long wings, and notched tail are all easily visible in flight.
Purple_Martin, In the East, nests with other Purple Martins in birdhouses and artificial gourds clustered together in groups.
Purple_Martin, Females and immatures show a mix of gray, blue, and white. Note the gray collar and forehead.
Purple_Martin, Often perches on wires and other manmade structures to rest, preen, or sunbathe.
Purple_Martin, Purple Martins in eastern North America nest almost exclusively in birdhouses and artificial gourds.
Purple_Martin, In the West, nests in holes in trees with dozens of martins nesting nearby.
Purple_Martin, Purple Martins in the southwestern U.S. and northwestern Mexico nest mainly in saguaro cactus.
Purple_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a dropping bill that is yellow at the base. Slate gray above with grayish spotting on the breast.
Purple_Sandpiper, Its short legs and round belly often make it look like it's squatting.  Purplish sheen only visible at close range.
Purple_Sandpiper, Forages in the rocky intertidal zone, quickly picking up aquatic invertebrates at low tides before the rocks get covered as the tide comes back in.
Purple_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a dropping bill that is yellow at the base. Slate gray above with grayish spotting on the breast.
Purple_Sandpiper, Breeding birds are heavily spotted below with whitish edging on the wings. The bill is yellowish at the base and slightly curved.
Purple_Sandpiper, Plump shorebird with short, yellow legs found foraging along rocky shorelines.
Purple_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a dropping bill that is yellow at the base. Slate gray above with grayish spotting on the breast.
Purple_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a dropping bill that is yellow at the base. Slate gray above with grayish spotting on the breast.
Purple_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a dropping bill that is yellow at the base. Slate gray above with grayish spotting on the breast.

Pygmy_Nuthatch, Tiny songbird with a short, square tail, a large head, and a straight, sharp bill. Slate gray wings and back; rich brown cap ending in a sharp line through the eye. Underparts are whitish to pale buff.

Pygmy_Nuthatch, Tiny songbird with a short, square tail, a large head, and a straight, sharp bill. Slate gray wings and back; rich brown cap ending in a sharp line through the eye. Underparts are whitish to pale buff.
Pygmy_Nuthatch, Often travels and breeds in extended family groups. Call is a squeaky, nasal note like the sound of a rubber ducky.
Pygmy_Nuthatch, The smallest nuthatch. It has a brown crown, blue-gray back, and buffy to grayish underparts. Although not visible in this photo, they also have a pale spot on the back of the neck.

Pygmy_Nuthatch, Tiny songbird with a short, square tail, a large head, and a straight, sharp bill. Slate gray wings and back; rich brown cap ending in a sharp line through the eye. Underparts are whitish to pale buff.

Pygmy_Nuthatch, Tiny songbird with a short, square tail, a large head, and a straight, sharp bill. Slate gray wings and back; rich brown cap ending in a sharp line through the eye. Underparts are whitish to pale buff.

Pygmy_Nuthatch, Tiny songbird with a short, square tail, a large head, and a straight, sharp bill. Slate gray wings and back; rich brown cap ending in a sharp line through the eye. Underparts are whitish to pale buff.
Pygmy_Nuthatch, Juveniles are paler overall with a yellowish bill and grayish crown.
Pygmy_Nuthatch, Found in pine forests in western North America, especially mature ponderosa pine forests.

Pyrrhuloxia, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a tall crest and a long tail. It has a heavy but short seed-cracking yellow bill. Adult males are grayish overall with red highlights on the wings, crest, and tail as well as a red mask and belly stripe.
Pyrrhuloxia, Stocky, long-tailed bird with a short and heavy bill. Adult females are grayish with red highlights on the crest, wings, and tail. Note yellow bill.

Pyrrhuloxia, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a tall crest and a long tail. It has a heavy but short seed-cracking yellow bill. Adult males are grayish overall with red highlights on the wings, crest, and tail as well as a red mask and belly stripe.
Pyrrhuloxia, Immatures look like females, but have a darker bill and have fewer red highlights.
Pyrrhuloxia, Long-tailed and crested songbird. Adult males are gray with a red mask and belly as well as red highlights on the crest, wings, and tail. Note thick yellow seed-eating bill.

Pyrrhuloxia, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a tall crest and a long tail. It has a heavy but short seed-cracking yellow bill. Adult males are grayish overall with red highlights on the wings, crest, and tail as well as a red mask and belly stripe.
Pyrrhuloxia, Yellow parrotlike bill is distinctive. Males are grayish overall with red highlights on the crest, wings, and tail.
Pyrrhuloxia, Found in desert scrub, dry grasslands, and open mesquite forest.

Pyrrhuloxia, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a tall crest and a long tail. It has a heavy but short seed-cracking yellow bill. Adult males are grayish overall with red highlights on the wings, crest, and tail as well as a red mask and belly stripe.
Razorbill, Robust crow-sized seabird that is black above and white below. A thin white line marks its face and thick black bill during the breeding season.
Razorbill, Nonbreeding birds have a white throat and cheek that extends up behind the eye.
Razorbill, Robust crow-sized seabird that rapidly flaps its narrow and pointed wings. Often seen flying in small groups.
Razorbill, Breeds in colonies on rocky coastlines.
Razorbill, Breeding birds have a thin white line on their thick black bill and another thin line extending from the bill to the eye.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Medium-sized black-and-white barred woodpecker with a pale belly. Males have a red crown and nape.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Medium-sized black-and-white barred woodpecker with a pale belly. Females have a red nape, lacking the red crown.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Clings to tree bark and uses stiff tail feathers for support. Probes into bark for insects. Note white flashes in wings as this bird takes flight.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Most often the red belly is obscured by surrounding feathers and is difficult to see.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Found in eastern woodlands and suburban areas. Nests in holes in trees.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Often comes to backyard feeders, including suet feeders.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Immature is grayer overall than adults and lacks red on the head.
Red-bellied_Woodpecker, Hitches up trees in search of insects. Found in woodlands and suburban areas.
Red-billed_Pigeon, A large pigeon with a mauve head and neck, grayish upperparts, and grayish wings with broad pinkish-purplish markings. The bill is two-toned—mostly pale yellow with a red base.
Red-billed_Pigeon, Pinkish throat and breast fade to light gray belly. Legs and feet are dark red.

Red-billed_Pigeon, A large, tree-dwelling pigeon found in tropical deciduous forest. Head and neck are pinkish, upperparts are mostly grayish, and tail is slate gray. Bill is mostly pale yellow, with a red base.
Red-billed_Pigeon, Upperparts are dark gray to bluish gray. Tail is a uniform slate gray.
Red-billed_Pigeon, Typically forages high in trees or shrubs, feeding mainly on berries, small fruits, acorns, and tree buds.
Red-billed_Pigeon, An arboreal species that comes to the ground largely to drink. Like other pigeons, this species is able to drink by sucking water, without raising its head.
Red-billed_Pigeon, At northern edge of range in southern Texas, found almost exclusively along the Rio Grande.
Red-billed_Pigeon, Found in tropical deciduous forest, including gallery forest, forest patches and edges, and semiopen areas with scattered trees.
Red-billed_Pigeon, A tree-dwelling species; often perches in the crowns of trees and shrubs.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Slim-profiled and long-bodied diving duck with a long, thin bill. Breeding males have a cinnamon chest, a white neck band, and a shaggy green head.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Slim, long-bodied diving duck with a long, thin bill. Female/nonbreeding males are brownish gray overall with brownish chin and dingy breast.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Note slender body, ragged crest, and narrow, straight bill.
Red-breasted_Merganser, In flight, note thin neck, dark breast, and dark back. Tends to fly at an angle, with the head higher than the feet.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Slender diving duck with a thin neck and a long, thin bill. Female/nonbreeding males have a brownish head and neck and a dingy breast.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Immature males look like messy breeding males.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Female/nonbreeding males have a brownish head with a shaggy crest. The color on the neck blends gradually into the chest without distinct white patches.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Males dunk their chests and raise their heads and rears in a "curtsey" display for females.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Slim-profiled and long-bodied diving duck with a long, thin bill. Breeding males have a cinnamon chest, a white neck band, and a shaggy green head.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Large, slim, long-bodied duck with long, slender bill and ragged crest. Breast is smudged with reddish brown; back is dark.
Red-breasted_Merganser, Occurs in large flocks; in winter, more common in salt (or brackish) water than freshwater.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Compact bird with a very short tail, almost no neck, and a sharp bill. Sharply marked with a black crown, white eyebrow, and black eyeline. Blue-gray above and rusty below.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Barrel-chested and compact, these active birds move up, down, and around tree branches and trunks. Females have grayer caps and paler rusty underparts.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Often makes its own nest holes rather than using pre-existing cavities. Both males and females help in excavation. Rarely uses nest boxes.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, A frequent visitor at seed and suet feeders.

Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Compact bird with a short tail. Blue-gray above with a sharply marked black-and-white face. Clings to trees with its feet, moving up, down, and around tree trunks, often heading downward in a zigzag pattern.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Stout, no-necked bird with a long, sharply pointed bill. Adult males have a dark black cap and rusty underparts.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Juveniles are patterned like adults, but with a duller cap and paler underparts.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Typically makes short flights between trees. Note short tail.
Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Moves up, down, and around tree trunks and branches pulling out insects from bark or seeds from cones.

Red-breasted_Nuthatch, Found primarily in evergreen forests of spruce, fir, pine, hemlock, larch, and western red cedar. Eastern populations use more deciduous woods, including aspen, birch, poplar, oak, maple, and basswood.

Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a red head and breast and a white spot in front of the eye. A large vertical white patch is usually visible on the folded wing. Lacks black on the breast. Sexes alike.
Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Juveniles are washed in brown with a darker back and a vertical white wing patch.

Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a red head and breast and a white spot in front of the eye. A large vertical white patch is usually visible on the folded wing. Lacks black on the breast. Sexes alike.
Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Breeds in evergreen and deciduous forests.
Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Drills a series of parallel rows to access tree sap. Note red head and breast and vertical white wing patch.

Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a red head and breast and a white spot in front of the eye. A large vertical white patch is usually visible on the folded wing. Lacks black on the breast. Sexes alike.
Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Nests in holes in trees. Males and females look alike.
Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Drills series of parallel rows to access sap, which it laps up with it tongue.

Red-breasted_Sapsucker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a red head and breast and a white spot in front of the eye. A large vertical white patch is usually visible on the folded wing. Lacks black on the breast. Sexes alike.
Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white ladder striped back and a white cheek. Males have a tiny, nearly invisible red streak ("cockade") at the upper border of the cheek.
Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white ladder striped back and a white cheek. Males have a tiny, nearly invisible red streak ("cockade") at the upper border of the cheek.

Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, Hitches up trees using its feet to grip the bark and its stiff tail feathers for balance. Picks at live trees for insects and to make the sticky pine resin flow from the tree where the nest is located.
Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, Small woodpecker with black-and-white ladder striped back and a white cheek. Males have a tiny, nearly invisible red streak ("cockade") at the upper border of the cheek.
Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, Small black-and-white woodpecker with a ladder of stripes up the back and distinctive white cheeks.
Red-cockaded_Woodpecker, A habitat specialist of the Southeast's once-vast longleaf pine stands with little understory.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with blocky head, thick neck, and short tail. Escaped birds have set up breeding populations in some U.S. cities outside the native range.

Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with flat head and short tail. Leaf green with prominent red patch on forecrown and yellowish tip to tail. Red patch in secondaries of wing are prominent in flight.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with red forecrown and bluish nape. Often uses bill in addition to feet to grasp tree branches when moving around.

Red-crowned_Amazon, Leaf-green parrot that can be very difficult to pick out amid tree foliage. Red forecrown transitions into bluish hindcrown and nape. Note red patch in secondaries of the wing, visible at rest.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with blocky head, thick neck, and short tail. Escaped birds have set up breeding populations in some U.S. cities outside the native range.

Red-crowned_Amazon, Groups travel from roosting to feeding areas in the morning and evening, often forming small flocks and flying with shallow wingbeats. Note red patch in secondaries on trailing edge of wing, and yellowish tail tip.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large, leaf green parrots with red on the forecrown. Social and vocal, often feeding in groups on fruits in trees.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with blocky head, thick neck, and short tail. Escaped birds have set up breeding populations in some U.S. cities outside the native range.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with blocky head, thick neck, and short tail. Escaped birds have set up breeding populations in some U.S. cities outside the native range.
Red-crowned_Amazon, Fairly large parrot with blocky head, thick neck, and short tail. Escaped birds have set up breeding populations in some U.S. cities outside the native range.
Red-eyed_Vireo, A small songbird with olive-green upperparts, white underparts, and a strong head pattern: a gray crown and white eyebrow stripe bordered above and below by blackish lines.
Red-eyed_Vireo, Adult has red eyes that appear dark from a distance; immature has dark eyes.
Red-eyed_Vireo, Sings a series of slurred notes. Phrases usually end in either a downslur or an upswing and then a pause, as if the bird asks a question, then answers it, over and over.
Red-eyed_Vireo, A large, chunky vireo with a thick neck and a strong, long bill with a small but noticeable hook at the tip.
Red-eyed_Vireo, Males sing incessantly during the day and throughout the entire breeding season.
Red-eyed_Vireo, One of the most common summer residents of Eastern forests, but can be difficult to see as they remain high in lush forest greenery.
Red-eyed_Vireo, Breeds in deciduous and mixed forests with shrubby understories.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Small cormorant with slender bill and red facial skin. Breeding adults have two short crests and square white patches on the flanks.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Small cormorant with pale bill, blue at base. Breeding adults are glossy purple-green, with short crests on the forecrown and hindcrown.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Nests on cliffs, typically alone or in small groups rather than in large colonies. Note extensive red facial skin and pale bill.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Small cormorant of the North Pacific with small, light-colored bill, red facial skin, and fairly thick neck. Breeding adults have white flank patches.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Breeding adults have vivid red facial skin, glossy sheen to head, neck, and body, light yellow bill with bluish base, and two short crests.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Small cormorant of the North Pacific. Immatures have slender, light-colored bill and lack the bright facial skin and glossy plumage of adults.
Red-faced_Cormorant, Red-faced Cormorant (second from left) is slightly larger and more thick-set than Pelagic Cormorants, with brighter facial skin and pale bill.
Red-faced_Warbler, Male has an unmistakable red face and throat and a black bonnet. Gray above and whitish below.
Red-faced_Warbler, From below, Males have a red throat and a white belly. The tail is grayish from below. In flight white rump also visible.
Red-faced_Warbler, Male has an unmistakable red face and throat and a black bonnet. Gray above and whitish below.
Red-faced_Warbler, Females look similar to males, but are more orangish red. The intensity of color varies among individuals and could be related to age.
Red-faced_Warbler, Male has an unmistakable red face and throat and a black bonnet. Gray above and whitish below.
Red-faced_Warbler, Males have a bright red face and throat and look like they are wearing a black bonnet. Breeds in high elevation fir, pine, and oak forests.
Red-footed_Booby, Large heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Light morph adults are mostly white with black wings. Note red feet.
Red-footed_Booby, Large seabird with a daggerlike bill. Dark morph birds have a tan head and belly. Nests in trees and shrubs.
Red-footed_Booby, Large heavy-bodied seabird with a daggerlike bill. Light morph adults are mostly white with black wings. Note red feet.
Red-footed_Booby, Bullet-shaped seabird with long pointed wings. Dark morph birds in flight have dark underwings and a tan belly.
Red-footed_Booby, Large seabird with long pointed wings. Wingbeats are deep and somewhat bouncy with interspersed glides. Light morph birds are white with black flight feathers.
Red-footed_Booby, Dark morph birds have dark underwings and tan, dingy-looking bellies.
Red-footed_Booby, Smallest of the boobies. Stands with body in a more horizontal position than other boobies.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a large red head and a big chisel-like bill. The back is black with white wing patches. The belly is white and unstreaked. Sexes alike.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Juveniles have a brown head, a dingy belly, and a blackish brown back.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Sometimes stores extra food, like this acorn, in caches by jamming the food item into the bark or wood of a tree.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Adults have large red heads and a black-and-white body. Like other woodpeckers forages on tree trunks, but also catches insects in air.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, In flight, adult has large white patches on the inner wings, contrasting with the black outer wings.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, As immatures molt into adult plumage they can have mixed brown and red on the head and show black bars in the white wing patches.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, In flight, juvenile also shows large white wing patches, but with two black bars across them.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Juveniles have a brown head, but start acquiring adult coloration in February.

Red-headed_Woodpecker, Clings to fence posts either to probe for food or as a perch from which to sally out after flying insects. Young birds are mostly brownish with black bars on the white wing patches.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Found in pine savannas and other open forests with clear understories. Nests in holes in trees.
Red-headed_Woodpecker, Doesn't always forage in tree bark. Often catches flying insects in midair, flycatcher style, and returns to the same or a nearby perch.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, A small, cliff-nesting gull that breeds only in the Bering Sea. Adult has dark gray upperparts, a short yellow bill, and bright red legs.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, At rest, note the short legs, short bill, large eye, rounded head, and long wingtips extending well beyond the short tail.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, A small, short-legged gull. Nests on steep cliffs on a handful of remote islands in the Bering Sea.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Immature has orange-red legs, a greenish-yellow bill, and a blackish ear spot.
