Red-legged_Kittiwake, In flight, note all-black wingtips bordered on the underwing by gray outer primaries.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Adult has a stubby yellow bill, short red legs, and dark gray upperparts.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Immature has an all-white tail, unlike other immature gulls, and a large white triangle on the upperwings.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, First-year immature has a black bill, black neck collar, white tail, grayish underwings, and broad white trailing edge to the wing.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Flies strongly on rapid wingbeats. As these birds land, note the all-black wingtips and gray primaries on the underwings.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Smaller than Black-legged Kittiwake, with shorter legs, a shorter bill, and darker gray upperparts.
Red-legged_Kittiwake, Breeds in mixed-species colonies with Black-legged Kittiwake and other seabirds.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Small woodpecker with vertical white patch on the folded wing. Males have a red throat, crown, and small nape patch.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Females have a small white chin patch under the bill, while males have a fully red chin and throat. The nape on females can be red or white.

Red-naped_Sapsucker, Note the red sides of the throat without a black border (Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers have a full black border to throat). Males have a fully red chin and throat; females have a white chin patch.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Small woodpecker with vertical white patch on the folded wing. Males have a red throat, crown, and small nape patch.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Juveniles are washed in brown with a brown crown.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Small woodpecker with vertical white patch on the folded wing. Males have a red throat, crown, and small nape patch.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Drills rows of parallel circular holes known as sap wells in tree bark to access tree sap.
Red-naped_Sapsucker, Breeds in mixed forests of willow, aspen, birch, ponderosa pine, juniper, or Douglas-fir.
Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with long neck and fairly stout, straight bill. Breeding adults have a black cap ending sharply at gray-white cheeks and a chestnut-red neck. Note eye is not red.

Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with long neck and fairly large bill. Solid black cap with clean gray-white cheeks contrasting with darker gray "ear" patch. Often holds bill pointing downward. Eye is not red.
Red-necked_Grebe, Breeds in shallow freshwater lakes and marshes. Like other grebes, places nest on floating mass of vegetation.
Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with fairly stout, straight, yellowish bill. In flight, neck is long; white patch on leading edge of wings near shoulder. Immatures are washed grayish with darker crown.
Red-necked_Grebe, Fairly large grebe with yellowish bill. Juveniles have striped faces and reddish chestnut necks.
Red-necked_Grebe, Breeds on shallow freshwater lakes and marshes. Like other grebes, pairs perform several types of displays, beginning on the wintering grounds and continuing through migration.
Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with long neck and fairly stout, straight bill. Breeding adults have a black cap ending sharply at gray-white cheeks and a chestnut-red neck. Note eye is not red.
Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with long neck and fairly stout, straight bill. Breeding adults have a black cap ending sharply at gray-white cheeks and a chestnut-red neck. Note eye is not red.
Red-necked_Grebe, Large grebe with long neck and fairly stout, straight bill. Breeding adults have a black cap ending sharply at gray-white cheeks and a chestnut-red neck. Note eye is not red.
Red-necked_Grebe, At distance, partially submerged body can appear small. Bill is yellowish with black cap and white cheeks. Winters along seacoasts.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Small, dainty shorebird that sits high on the water, with a slender neck and very thin, sharp bill. Breeding birds are dark gray above with a rusty neck and a dark gray cap.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Breeding males are less bright than females and tend to be more brownish gray above than dark gray.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Picks at the water's surface for zooplankton. Often feeds by spinning frantically in circles, drawing invertebrates up to the surface to eat.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Small shorebird with a long, thin bill. Nonbreeders are white below with a gray back. Note the black ear patch.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Small, dainty shorebird that sits high on the water, with a slender neck and very thin, sharp bill. Breeding birds are dark gray above with a rusty neck and a dark gray cap.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Juvenile look similar to nonbreeding birds, but have buffy stripes on the back.
Red-necked_Phalarope, Small, dainty shorebird that sits high on the water, with a slender neck and very thin, sharp bill. Breeding birds are dark gray above with a rusty neck and a dark gray cap.

Red-shouldered_Hawk, Medium-sized hawk with slim body and fairly long tail. Wings are broad and somewhat square at the tips when soaring. Adults have extensively reddish brown underparts. Tail and flight feathers are banded black and white.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Medium-sized hawk with slim shape, small head, and fairly long tail. Adults are rich reddish-brown on the chest.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Medium-sized hawk with fine reddish barring on breast and black-and-white checkered wings. The Florida form (extimus) has a paler head and breast than other forms.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Eastern adults have richly marked upperparts, with a mix of black, rufous, and white. Long black tail has narrow white bands.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Juveniles are more flat brown than adults, with variable dark streaking on the underparts. They lack the adult's strong black-and-white patterning on the flight feathers.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Note broad wings, short tail, and translucent crescents near the tips of the wings. Typically soars holding wings slightly forward of perpendicular.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Juveniles are brownish above with brown streaking on whitish underparts.

Red-shouldered_Hawk, Note fairly long tail, slim body, and squared-off wings with translucent crescents at the tips. Immatures of the eastern subspecies have narrow brown-on-white bands on the tail and flight feathers.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, A hawk of woodland habitats. Adults have reddish barred chest, broad bars on the tail, and black-and-white checkered wings.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, In flight, note fairly long tail, square-tipped wings, and bright, translucent crescents in the outer wing.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, In Florida, adults have pale gray heads and light orange-brown barring on the underparts.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Breeds in wooded areas, where pairs build stick nests usually in a crotch in the main trunk of a deciduous tree. This video has no audio.

Red-shouldered_Hawk, Immatures from Florida have heavier brown streaking on the breast than on the belly. The flight feathers and the tail have narrow bands of brown and white, more subtle than the black-and-white patterning of adults.

Red-shouldered_Hawk, Slim, medium-sized hawk. The California subspecies is rich reddish-orange on the breast, head, and shoulders. The wings are strongly patterned black-and-white, and the tail has strong bands.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Adults in the "elegans" group, found from Oregon to Baja California, have a solid orange breast, lacking the breast barring of Eastern adults.

Red-shouldered_Hawk, Note fairly long tail, slim body, and squared-off wings with translucent crescents at the tips. Immatures of the California subspecies have dark patterning on the wings and strongly banded tails, in addition to brown streaks on the breast.
Red-shouldered_Hawk, Lives in forests, particularly bottomland forests and swamps, but also open upland forests and wooded suburbs.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Large with a red tail. Mostly pale below, with a darker belly band, wing tips, and edges of the flight feathers. Head brown with a white throat.

Red-tailed_Hawk, Large with a red tail. Mostly brownish above with variable white in the wing coverts and lower back forming a pale 'V' on the upperwings. Eastern subspecies (borealis) tends to have plain red tail with neat black band near the tip.
Red-tailed_Hawk, When they detect prey on the ground, they glide or flap-and-glide downward, pushing their legs forward when nearing the prey and impaling it with their talons.

Red-tailed_Hawk, Western subspecies (calurus) differs in being more richly colored below on average, and more heavily-marked. The body plumage is polymorphic in the western subspecies, occurring in light (as here), intermediate, and dark morphs.
Red-tailed_Hawk, The red tail is more obvious when viewed from above. Otherwise all dark brown with light barring in the flight feathers.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Soars with wings held in a shallow V and "fingers" spread. Stoops to the ground by tucking its wings into its body.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Some dark morphs are strongly reddish-brown below, especially on the chest.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Dark chocolatey-brown body and wing linings, with paler flight feathers lightly barred and contrasting with dark wing tips and edges to the flight feathers.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Often perches motionless in trees along roadsides or slowly scans for prey from its perch.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Large with a red tail. Mostly pale below, with a heavy darker belly band. Dark wing tips and edges to flight feathers contrast with paler wings.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Chocolatey-brown below, with lightly barred whitish flight feathers, dark wing tips and edges to the flight feathers, and a mostly whitish tail with a dark tip.
Red-tailed_Hawk, When hunting, often hangs in the air scanning for prey below; a behavior known as kiting.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Mostly pale below with a heavy dark belly band, dark wing tips and edges to the flight feathers, and dark tips to a white tail.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Adult Harlan's tail pattern highly variable above, characterized by white, gray, and black mottling and longitudinal streaking. Some lack red altogether.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Subspecies characterized by extremely lightly-marked underparts with faint patagial mark (often rufous toned) and faint to absent belly band.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Subspecies typically has rufous-toned upperparts with extensive white spangling, and whitish-based tail with red to pinkish tip.

Red-tailed_Hawk, Birds in Costa Rica and Panama have rufous bellies and wing linings, pale flight feathers contrasting with dark wingtips and flight feather edges, and chocolatey-brown head and shoulders.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Heavily streaked below, with bold barring on the wings, dark wingtips, and a lightly barred pale tail.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Very heavily streaked below, with darkly checkered wing linings, boldly barred wings with dark wingtips, and a finely barred brown and white tail.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Very heavily streaked below, with darkly checkered wing linings, boldly barred wings with barred wingtips, and a finely barred brown and white tail.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Very pale, almost white head. Brown above mixed with white feathering, and finely barred wings and tail.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Pale below with light reddish-brown streaking on the chest and a bold brown belly band. Head brown with some darker markings. Red tail often not visible on perched birds.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Pale below with a broad and bold brown belly band. Head brown mixed with white feathering. Tail barred brown and whitish.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Juvenile Krider's is strikingly pale, with a mostly white head, white underparts with little or no breast streaking, and significant white on the dark upperparts.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Eats a wide variety of prey, including snakes, and occurs in many different habitats.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Often mobbed by smaller birds, especially during the nesting season.
Red-tailed_Hawk, Occurs in a wide variety of habitats, and often nests on or near cliffs.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a long and slender bill often held slightly raised. Breeding adults have a red throat patch and a plain gray head.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a thin bill typically held above horizontal. Nonbreeding birds have more white on the neck and face than other loons.
Red-throated_Loon, Note distinctive posture, sitting low in the water with the fairly slender bill raised slightly above horizontal.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a thin bill typically held raised. Often sits lower in the water than other loons. Immature birds are pale gray with varying amounts of white on the face and neck.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a long and slender bill often held slightly raised. Breeding adults have a red throat patch and a plain gray head.
Red-throated_Loon, In flight appears hunchbacked.
Red-throated_Loon, Holds bill up and often sits lower in the water than other loons. Nonbreeding birds have extensive white on the neck and face.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a long and slender bill often held slightly raised. Breeding adults have a red throat patch and a plain gray head.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a long and slender bill often held slightly raised. Breeding adults have a red throat patch and a plain gray head.
Red-throated_Loon, Small loon with a long and slender bill often held slightly raised. Breeding adults have a red throat patch and a plain gray head.
Red-throated_Loon, Often sits lower in the water than other loons and holds bill upward.
Red-throated_Loon, Breeds in wetlands and bogs on arctic tundra.

Red-throated_Pipit, A small songbird with a thin bill, fairly short tail, and heavily streaked upperparts. Breeding adult is richly colored with pinkish to rusty-red throat, upper breast, and line above the eye. Sexes are similar, but individuals like this with extensive pink on the breast and underpart streaking limited to the flanks are more likely to be males.
Red-throated_Pipit, Immature lacks adult's rusty-red throat and eyeline and has more heavily streaked underparts. All plumages show heavily streaked upperparts. Frequently found on the ground.

Red-throated_Pipit, Adult has a rusty-red throat and eyeline and a variable amount of rufous wash and streaking on the breast. Often found on the ground, but also alights on fences, wires, and other elevated perches.
Red-throated_Pipit, During migration and nonbreeding season, often occurs in wet grassy areas, but also perches on rocks, bushes, fences, and wires.
Red-throated_Pipit, Juvenile has heavy streaking on the throat and breast and lacks adult's rusty-red throat, breast, and eyeline.
Red-throated_Pipit, Breeds on alpine and coastal tundra across northern Eurasia (and in small numbers in western Alaska). Forages and nests on the ground.
Red-throated_Pipit, Breeds in tundra regions, often in wet areas with willow scrub.
Red-throated_Pipit, In flight, note streaked rump and limited white in the outer tail feathers and listen for distinctive flight call—a high-pitched, descending peeez .
Red-throated_Pipit, Forages on the ground for insects, spiders, and other invertebrates. Note heavily streaked upperparts, including two prominent whitish lines running down the back.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Stocky, broad-shouldered blackbird with a slender, conical bill. Males have a red shoulder patch bordered in yellow.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Stocky, broad-shouldered blackbird with a slender, conical bill. Females are brown and heavily streaked overall with a yellowish wash around the bill.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Displaying males sit on cattails and other high perches, spreading their wings and puffing out their shoulder patches while singing and calling.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Males sing frequently from cattails and other conspicuous perches.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Females are dark brownish overall, with crisply streaked underparts.

Red-winged_Blackbird, Often seen on the ground foraging or gathering nesting material. Females look very different from males, but have the same long, pointed bill and stocky stature. This video has no audio.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Nonbreeding males often look scaly and have incomplete red shoulder patches.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Males in California lack the yellow border on the red shoulder patch.
Red-winged_Blackbird, In addition to the male's "conk-la-ree" song, males and females make several calls including a harsh "check" note and a high, thin whistle.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Female birds in California often have more cinnamon tones to their feathers and dark undertail coverts with less streaking.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Birds breeding in Mexico lack the yellow border to the red shoulder patch.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Forms large flocks in winter in marshes and open habitats, sometimes with other blackbird species.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Males spend much of the breeding season sitting on a high perch over their territories and singing their hearts out.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Males display by holding their wings out to show off the red shoulder patches.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Breeds in wetlands.
Red-winged_Blackbird, Flocks in the thousands with other blackbirds, grackles, cowbirds, and starlings.
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Full-bodied finch with a crisscrossed bill. Females are yellowish with dark unmarked wings.
Red_Crossbill, A medium-sized songbird with a unique crossed bill. Crossbills use their specialized bill to pry open conifer cones and then extract the seeds found inside.
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Juveniles are heavily streaked overall with thin buffy wingbars, which can be hard to see depending on position of the bird.
Red_Crossbill, Different Red Crossbill populations, known as "types," have distinctly different flight calls and bill shapes that are adapted for different types of cones.
Red_Crossbill, Immature males are a patchy mix of red and orangish yellow feathers as they molt into adult plumage. Note dark unmarked wings and tail.
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Typical call is a series of short, sharp "jip" notes.
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Uses its crisscrossed bill to extract seeds from pine cones. Females are yellowish overall.
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Medium-sized finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are red overall with darker brownish-red wings (some individuals may show wingbars).
Red_Crossbill, Moves in large nomadic flocks in search of good cone crops.
Red_Crossbill, Found in mature evergreen forests with large cone crops. Feeds on seeds from spruce, Douglas-fir, eastern and western hemlock, or pine trees.
Red_Knot, Bulky sandpiper with a stout bill. Breeding adults are a rich cinnamon below and mottled grayish with cinnamon edgings above.
Red_Knot, Bulky shorebird with a stout bill, thickest at the base. Cinnamon below and mottled gray and cinnamon above.
Red_Knot, Nests in the tundra with low growing lichens and grasses. Lays 3 to 4 eggs in a scrape on the ground. Both males and females incubate.
Red_Knot, Nonbreeding birds are gray above with gray barring on the flanks and faint vertical barring on the chest. Note thick sturdy bill.
Red_Knot, In flight, pale gray rump and tail is visible. A long-winged and strong flier.
Red_Knot, Juveniles have a fine scaly pattern on the back and a white eyebrow stripe. Note plump body, sturdy bill, and dingy yellow legs.
Red_Knot, Bulky shorebird with a stout bill, thickest at the base. Cinnamon below and mottled gray and cinnamon above.
Red_Knot, Bulky sandpiper with a stout bill. Breeding adults are a rich cinnamon below and mottled grayish with cinnamon edgings above.
Red_Knot, Bulky sandpiper with a stout bill. Breeding adults are a rich cinnamon below and mottled grayish with cinnamon edgings above.
Red_Phalarope, Breeding females are brighter than males with entirely rusty underparts, a white ear patch, and a yellow bill.
Red_Phalarope, Nonbreeding Red Phalaropes have a solid gray back and a dark ear patch.
Red_Phalarope, Swims on the surface of the water like other phalaropes, picking at aquatic invertebrates.
Red_Phalarope, Juvenile Red Phalaropes have white edging on the wings and have a less clean gray back than nonbreeding adults.
Red_Phalarope, A small shorebird with a long bill that is thicker at the base. This juvenile has white edging on the wings.
Red_Phalarope, Breeding males are less bright than females, but still have entirely rusty underparts and a white cheek patch.
Red_Phalarope, During molt, mottled with rusty patches on neck and belly. Note yellow bill.
Red_Phalarope, In flight Red Phalaropes have cleaner underwings and a solid gray back, unlike Red-necked Phalaropes that have dark markings on the underwing and a striped gray back.
Reddish_Egret, Medium-sized heron with a shaggy rusty-colored neck, slate-gray body, and heavy, two-toned bill.
Reddish_Egret, Small percentage of the population in Florida and the Gulf Coast are entirely white. Breeding adults have a pink bill with a black tip. Note shaggy-looking neck.
Reddish_Egret, Has a very active foraging style compared to many herons—often runs through shallows to catch prey.
Reddish_Egret, Immature birds are grayish overall with a dark bill.
Reddish_Egret, Medium-sized heron with a shaggy rusty-colored neck, slate-gray body, and heavy, two-toned bill.
Reddish_Egret, Medium-sized shaggy-necked heron. Juvenile white morphs are entirely white with a dark bill.
Reddish_Egret, Performs dancing displays during courtship with wings spread, plumes erect, and heads up. The base of the bill on breeding birds is pink.
Reddish_Egret, Often puts its wings over its head when foraging to create a canopy and a shadow over the water, which may attract fish.
Reddish_Egret, Found foraging in coastal lagoons, ponds, and flats. Rarely found inland.
Redhead, Medium-sized diving duck with a steep forehead that meets the bill at a sharp angle. Cinnamon-red head, black chest and rear, and gray body. Bill is gray with a black tip.
Redhead, Medium-sized diving duck with a steep forehead and an abrupt transition to the bill. Medium brown overall with a pale face and a dark gray bill with a black tip.
Redhead, Forms large flocks during migration and winter. Forages for plant material and invertebrates by taking them from the surface or diving below to reach submerged vegetation.
Redhead, In flight, wingstripe is grayish rather than white. Flies with shallower wingbeats than scaup.
Redhead, Rounded head with an abrupt angle between the forehead and bill. Nonbreeding males are brownish overall, like females, but with a warmer brown head. Dark gray bill with a black tip.
Redhead, Both sexes have a gray bill with a black tip.
Redhead, Medium-sized diving duck with a steep forehead that meets the bill at a sharp angle. Cinnamon-red head, black chest and rear, and gray body. Bill is gray with a black tip.
Redhead, Forms large flocks with other duck species, especially in winter on lakes and coastal waters.

Redpoll, Small finch with a red cap, two white wingbars, notched tail, and short yellow bill surrounded by black. Adult male "Common" form has a rosy-red wash on the breast and upper flanks and brownish streaked upperparts.
Redpoll, Small finch with a short, conical yellow bill. Female/immature "Common" form is brown and streaky with a tiny red patch on the crown. Note streaking on undertail coverts on both sexes.

Redpoll, Small, energetic finch with red cap, yellow bill, streaked upperparts, and two white wingbars. Adult male "Common" form has pinkish-red wash across breast and streaked flanks. Often visits bird feeders when populations irrupt south to the northern U.S. and southern Canada.

Redpoll, Adult male "Hoary" form is mostly white with a red crown patch and a pink washed chest. Some individuals like this one are extremely pale with limited streaking on the sides while others are darker with more streaking.
Redpoll, Female/immature "Hoary" form is white overall with a red crown patch and lightly streaked back and sides. Note unstreaked undertail coverts.
Redpoll, Acrobatic little songbird, often seen hanging upside down in pursuit of seeds. The "Hoary" form (seen here) is typically paler and smaller-billed than the "Common" form.
Redpoll, The "Lesser" group, restricted to Europe, is smaller and darker than other Redpoll subspecies groups.
Redpoll, Nonbreeding female/immature "Lesser" group has a strong brownish wash on the head.
Redpoll, Feeds mainly on seeds, but also eats insects when they are available. Female/immature "Lesser" Redpoll, found only in Europe, has a distinctive brownish wash on the head, throat, and flanks.
Redpoll, Juvenile "Common" is dark brown and heavily streaked overall and lacks adult's yellow bill.
Redpoll, Small-billed finch with heavily streaked sides. Adult males have a red crown and a pink-washed chest.
Redpoll, Often forages in large flocks in weedy fields during the nonbreeding season.
Redpoll, All forms have a small red cap (the "poll" in redpoll) on the forehead.
Redpoll, Feeds largely on birch and willow seeds during the nonbreeding season.
Redpoll, Breeds in arctic tundra and boreal forest across much of the Northern Hemisphere.
Redpoll, The "Hoary" form has an unstreaked white rump and a cold pale appearance overall.
Redpoll, During the nonbreeding season, flocks of several hundred individuals feed on seeds in weedy fields.
Redpoll, Often found at backyard bird feeders in the winter in the northern U.S. and southern Canada.

Rhinoceros_Auklet, Medium-sized stocky seabird. Breeding adults have a characteristic "horn" that protrudes from its orange bill and two white plumes on its face. Dark gray above and paler gray below.
Rhinoceros_Auklet, Nonbreeding birds appear dark overall. Some nonbreeding birds may have reduced white plumes on the face.

Rhinoceros_Auklet, Medium-sized stocky seabird. Breeding adults have a characteristic "horn" that protrudes from its orange bill and two white plumes on its face. Dark gray above and paler gray below.

Rhinoceros_Auklet, Medium-sized stocky seabird. Breeding adults have a characteristic "horn" that protrudes from its orange bill and two white plumes on its face. Dark gray above and paler gray below.
Rhinoceros_Auklet, Stocky seabird with a portly whitish belly. Flight often looks labored.
Rhinoceros_Auklet, Breeding adults have a characteristic "horn" that protrudes from its orange bill. White facial plumes not always visible on breeding birds. Note yellow eye.

Rhinoceros_Auklet, Medium-sized stocky seabird. Breeding adults have a characteristic "horn" that protrudes from its orange bill and two white plumes on its face. Dark gray above and paler gray below.
Rhinoceros_Auklet, Rarely glides when flying, instead continuously flaps its wings, flying low over the water.
Ridgways_Rail, Large rail with a slightly curved bill and a short tail. Gray-brown above with dark streaking down its back. Note pale barring on the flanks and cinnamon chest and neck.
Ridgways_Rail, Heavy-bodied marsh bird with a cinnamon neck and pale barring on the flanks.
Ridgways_Rail, Slowly walks through marsh vegetation. Cinnamon below with paler barring on the flanks and grayish brown above with heavy streaking.
Ridgways_Rail, Chickenlike bird of wetlands where it forages for crustaceans, minnows, and aquatic insects. Note the heavy slightly curved bill.
Ridgways_Rail, Most often stays concealed in marsh vegetation, but occasionally walks across open wetlands with its tail cocked up and its head pushed forward.
Ridgways_Rail, Found in saltwater marshes, freshwater marshes, and mangrove swamps in California, Arizona, Nevada, and coastal western Mexico.
Ring-billed_Gull, Medium-sized gull with a shorter bill. Breeding adults have black band across their yellow bill, yellow legs, a pale eye, and a pale gray back.

Ring-billed_Gull, Nonbreeding adults like this one have only a little bit of tan streaking on the head or neck, but other can have more tan streaking. Otherwise nonbreeding adults look similar to breeding adults with a black band across their yellow bill and a pale eye.
Ring-billed_Gull, Medium-sized gull with fairly small bill. Breeding adults typically have clean white head, pale eye, and yellow legs.
Ring-billed_Gull, Second winter gulls have tan streaking on the neck, head, and chest (like this one), but others have relatively little. Note the black band across the yellow bill.

Ring-billed_Gull, First winter birds start acquiring gray feathers on their back, but still retain some brown feathers on their wings and have variable amounts of brown streaking and spotting on their head, neck, and underparts.
Ring-billed_Gull, Juveniles are a patchwork of brown and white with a dark bill that is most often pink at the base.
Ring-billed_Gull, In flight, note the small white spot on the tips of the outer primaries and relatively little black on the primaries.
Ring-billed_Gull, Juveniles in flight have dark primaries and mottled inner wings with a wide, dark tail band.
Ring-billed_Gull, First winter birds begin to acquire pale gray feathers on their back while retaining a mottled brown look overall. Note short bill that is pink at the base.
Ring-billed_Gull, Found along coastal beaches, inland lakes, garbage dumps, parking lots, and freshly plowed fields.

Ring-necked_Duck, Medium-sized diving duck with a peaked head. Breeding male has glossy black head, front, rear, and back, with gray sides and white wedge at the shoulder. Gray bill has a black tip bordered by a white band.

Ring-necked_Duck, Medium-sized brownish duck with a tall, peaked head. Brown top of head contrasts with gray face, white eyering, and white strip behind bill. Gray bill has white band and a black tip.

Ring-necked_Duck, Paddles across waterbodies like dabbling ducks, but dives to the bottom to eat submerged plants and aquatic invertebrates unlike dabbling ducks. Note the peaked head, white ring around the bill, and white "spur" on its side.
Ring-necked_Duck, In flight, wings are dark with grayish, not white, wingstripe.
Ring-necked_Duck, Pairs tend to form in spring and stay together at least until incubation begins

Ring-necked_Duck, Medium-sized diving duck with a tall, peaked head and a white ring near the tip of the bill. Glossy ring around neck is very difficult to see. Nonbreeding males have gray-brown sides.
Ring-necked_Duck, Fairly common on lakes and ponds, especially small bodies of water. Less common in saltwater.
Ring-necked_Duck, In flight, male's black back and grayish wingstripe help differentiate it from male scaup.
Ring-necked_Duck, The breeding male's namesake chestnut collar, visible here, is usually difficult to see.
Ring-necked_Duck, Breeds in freshwater marshes, often in shallow waters where patches of open water are fringed with vegetation.
Ring-necked_Duck, Forms flocks, especially in winter and migration. Both sexes have distinctive gray bill with white band and black tip.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, Fairly large, long-tailed and long-necked game bird. Females are brown overall marked with black, particularly on the back and wings.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, Native to Asia, this popular game bird has been widely introduced in Europe and North America.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, Fairly large, long-tailed and long-necked game bird. Females are brown overall marked with black, particularly on the back and wings.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, When flushed, bursts vertically into flight with loud wing flapping; typically flies short distance to cover. Long tail, coppery body, and white collar are distinctive.

Ring-necked_Pheasant, Fairly large game bird with long, pointed tail. Usually forages on the ground in agricultural, grassy or brushy areas. Females form flocks of up to 18 birds in summer and 30 or more in winter.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, Females are fairly large, brownish game birds with long, pointed tails. Juveniles are mobile from hatching; up to 15 may be seen with one female.
Ring-necked_Pheasant, Large game bird typically seen on agricultural lands and grassy or brushy areas.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Very large kingfisher with heavy bill and ragged crest. Females have a blue breast band and chestnut belly.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Very large kingfisher with heavy bill and ragged crest. Males are mostly chestnut below from breast through belly.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Hunts for fish from perches over freshwater. Often jerks the tail and head upwards while perched.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Very large, heavy-billed kingfisher. Females usually show a thin white band separating blue breast from chestnut belly.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Immatures usually show some female-like plumage including some blue feathering across breast.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Females have a blue breast band and chestnut or rufous belly, separated by a narrow white border. Often jerks the tail and head upwards while perched.
Ringed_Kingfisher, In flight, females have extensive rufous under the wing and tail.
Ringed_Kingfisher, The subspecies that breeds in southern South America has a shorter bill and darker blue upperparts than the northern subspecies.
Ringed_Kingfisher, Large kingfisher with white collar, white spotting in wings and tail. Note chestnut extends all the way down the belly.
Ringed_Kingfisher, In flight, females show rufous or chestnut underwings and under the tail; in males these areas are white.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.
Rivolis_Hummingbird, Though males have colorful iridescent crowns and throats, they often look dark. The silhouette is distinctive: a large, lanky hummingbird with a long, straight bill.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.
Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird with a long straight bill. Adult males have a green back and most often appear all dark from the front. Note white spot behind the eye.
Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird with a long straight bill. Females are green above and grayish below. They have a small white streak behind the eye.
Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large and lanky hummingbird. In good light, adult males have a purple crown, a yellow-green throat (the color may change with the light), and a black belly.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.

Rivolis_Hummingbird, Large hummingbird. Adult males are dark green above with a purple crown and an iridescent yellow-green throat. They often appear dark overall in poor light. Note white dot behind the eye.
Rivolis_Hummingbird, Found in dry pine-oak forests in the southwestern United States and south to northern Nicaragua.

Roadside_Hawk, A small raptor found at forest edges across much of the tropical Americas. Adult has light iris, yellow cere (facial skin), orange-yellow legs, and rufous-and-white barring on the belly and below; other plumage details vary considerably across range. Some "Northern" adults, like this individual, have a light gray head and breast.

Roadside_Hawk, All adults show large, distinctive rufous wing patches in flight. Adult tail color varies from rufous to gray, with 4–5 broad black bands. The "Northern" subspecies group ranges from Mexico to the southern Amazon.

Roadside_Hawk, A small hawk of forest edges and other open habitats. Adult plumage varies considerably. Some "Northern" adults have brownish-gray upperparts and head, coarse streaking on the breast, and rufous barring below. All adults have a pale eye, yellow cere, bright rufous wing patches (more obvious in flight), and broad black bands on the tail.

Roadside_Hawk, The "Southern" subspecies group occurs south of the Amazon, from northeastern Brazil to northern Argentina. Many "Southern" adults have dark brown upperparts, a nearly black head, and rusty underparts (streaked on the breast, barred below).
Roadside_Hawk, Immature has white or buffy underparts, with coarse brownish streaking on the breast and barring on the belly. Many immatures also have a prominent white line above the eye.
Roadside_Hawk, "Southern" adult often has a dark brown head, brown upperparts, and cinnamon underparts with fine barring on the belly.
Roadside_Hawk, In flight, note short, rounded wings; fairly long tail (usually kept closed); and, in adult, large rufous wing patches.
Roadside_Hawk, Often seen perched on wires, fence posts, and telephone poles alongside roads. Juvenile "Northern" has upper tail pattern similar to adult, but with gray bands alternating with black.
Roadside_Hawk, Juvenile "Southern" has light stripe above the eye, buffy streaking on the neck, and whitish underparts with brownish streaking and barring.
Roadside_Hawk, Juvenile "Southern" has light stripe above the eye, buffy streaking on the neck, and whitish underparts with brownish streaking on the breast and barring below.
Roadside_Hawk, Immature "Northern" can have little or no rufous patch in the wings. Note short, rounded wings and fairly long, barred tail.
Roadside_Hawk, A very vocal hawk. Both sexes give long series of nasal calls, somewhat reminiscent of a woodpecker. Note the large rufous wing patches when the bird opens its wings.
Roadside_Hawk, In some "Southern" populations, adult has a dark head, rich brown upperparts, and a reddish tail with black bands.
Roadside_Hawk, Often perches close to the ground, in search of insects, reptiles, amphibians, small mammals, and other prey.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with small head and straight, thin bill. Plumage is variable, but most common form has gray back, 2 black bars in the wing, and blue-gray head.
Rock_Pigeon, In flight, note black wingbars and broad black band at tip of tail.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with small head and straight, thin bill. Plumage is variable, but most common form has gray back, 2 black bars in the wing, and blue-gray head.
Rock_Pigeon, A common sight in towns and cities around the world.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with short legs and small head. Plumage is variable; some birds are dark gray with green-purple iridescence on the neck. Tail usually shows a dark band at the tip.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with small head and straight, thin bill. Plumage is variable, but most common form has gray back, 2 black bars in the wing, and blue-gray head.
Rock_Pigeon, Walks and runs with head moving back and forth.
Rock_Pigeon, Occasional variants are pale or rusty colored; often found in flocks with pigeons in standard gray plumage.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with small head and straight, thin bill. Plumage is variable, but most common form has gray back, 2 black bars in the wing, and blue-gray head.
Rock_Pigeon, Struts on the ground with head-bobbing motion to pick at seeds and handouts.
Rock_Pigeon, Plumage is variable; some individuals can be nearly all white.
Rock_Pigeon, Plump bird with small head and straight, thin bill. Plumage is variable, but most common form has gray back, 2 black bars in the wing, and blue-gray head.
Rock_Pigeon, A strong flier, capable of sustained high-speed flight.
Rock_Pigeon, Gathers in large flocks in urban areas and on farms. In flight, most individuals have pale underwings and a dark band at the tail tip.
Rock_Ptarmigan, Stocky, chickenlike grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males have a red eyebrow and are mottled brown with a white belly.

Rock_Ptarmigan, Stocky, chickenlike grouse with a short bill and tail. Males and females are white in the winter with black outer tail feathers. Males have a more pronounced red eyebrow and a black stripe in front of the eye.
Rock_Ptarmigan, Found in arctic and alpine tundra even during the nonbreeding season. Males and females molt out of their muted brown plumage in summer into white plumage for the winter.
Rock_Ptarmigan, Breeding females are mottled in brown and black with a small red eyebrow.
Rock_Ptarmigan, Males and females turn white in the winter. They have black outer tail feathers that are usually only visible in flight.
Rock_Ptarmigan, Found in barren rocky tundra.
Rock_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a drooping bill that is yellow at the base. Nonbreeding birds are pale gray above with spotting on the breast.
Rock_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a drooping bill that is yellow at the base. Breeding birds have a pale head, chestnut markings on the back, and a dark belly patch.
Rock_Sandpiper, Males and females may incubate the eggs alone, or both parents may share the responsibility. Clutch sizes are generally between one and four eggs.
Rock_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a drooping bill that is yellow at the base. Nonbreeding birds are pale gray above with spotting on the breast.
Rock_Sandpiper, Stocky, short-legged sandpiper with a drooping bill that is yellow at the base. Nonbreeding birds are pale gray above with spotting on the breast.
Rock_Sandpiper, Plumage brightest varies from darkest in the Aleutian Islands to palest in the Pribilof Islands. Nonbreeding birds are grayish above with gray spotting below.
Rock_Sandpiper, Juveniles have cinnamon edging on their back feathers and brownish spotting on the beast.
Rock_Sandpiper, Adults molting from breeding plumage to winter plumage show a combination of characteristics. Stocky, short-legged stature and drooping bill help with identification.
Rock_Sandpiper, Often seen huddling together on rocky coastlines or along breakwaters. Note stocky, short-legged stature and drooping bill that is yellow at the base.

Rock_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and thin bill. Pale brown above and whitish below with slight buffy or peachy wash on the lower belly. Back and wings are finely speckled. Note pale eyebrow stripe.
Rock_Wren, Underparts are finely streaked, but often look whitish. Lower belly is washed in a pale peachy color. Upperparts are pale brown with speckling. Bounces up and down as it stands.
Rock_Wren, Has a habit of bobbing quickly down and then up again while standing.
Rock_Wren, Found in rocky habitats; frequently bobs body up and down. Pale brown above with finely speckled back and wings. Note pale eyebrow stripe.

Rock_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and thin bill. Pale brown above and whitish below with slight buffy or peachy wash on the lower belly. Back and wings are finely speckled. Note pale eyebrow stripe.

Rock_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and thin bill. Pale brown above and whitish below with slight buffy or peachy wash on the lower belly. Back and wings are finely speckled. Note pale eyebrow stripe.

Rock_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and thin bill. Pale brown above and whitish below with slight buffy or peachy wash on the lower belly. Back and wings are finely speckled. Note pale eyebrow stripe.

Rock_Wren, Medium-sized wren with a long tail and thin bill. Pale brown above and whitish below with slight buffy or peachy wash on the lower belly. Back and wings are finely speckled. Note pale eyebrow stripe.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a very large triangular bill. Males have a distinctive red breast.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Stocky, medium-sized songbird with a very large triangular bill. Females are heavily streaked above and below with a white eyebrow and a pale bill.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Song is a long rising and falling series of notes with a very sweet quality.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Immature males look like a cross between a female and a male with a white eyebrow and a smaller red breast patch.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a hefty triangular bill. From behind males have a white rump patch.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Often comes to feeders, where it uses its very large, triangular bill to crack open seeds.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Females are heavily streaked above and below with a white eyebrow and pale bill.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Stocky songbird with a red breast and white belly.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Usually gleans food from dense foliage and branches, often fairly high in trees. Eats insects, berries, and fresh buds, as well as seed from feeders.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Females are heavily streaked above and below. Note the white eyebrow and white wingbars.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, In flight, males have prominent white wing patches and show pink wing linings below.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Large, stocky bird with very large, thick bill. Note bold face pattern with strong whitish stripe over eye, and warm buffy wash to breast. This video has no audio.
Rose-breasted_Grosbeak, Found in eastern forests and forest edges. Often sings from elevated perches.
Rose-throated_Becard, A small, stocky songbird that often shows a bushy crest. Adult male in drier areas is pale gray below and darker gray above, with a black cap and deep pink throat patch.

Rose-throated_Becard, Female upperparts range from grayish to rufous, and cap color can be black, blackish-gray, or rusty brown. Note also large head; short neck; short, narrow tail; and stout, slightly hooked bill.

Rose-throated_Becard, A small, stocky songbird with a short, thick bill, and a bushy-headed look when crest is raised. This immature male looks similar to an adult male, with light gray underparts, darker gray upperparts and head, and a pink throat patch, but it also shows some rusty coloration typical of a female.
Rose-throated_Becard, Immature male shows a mix of female and adult male coloration.
Rose-throated_Becard, Adult males in humid areas are darker overall, with little or no pink on the throat.
Rose-throated_Becard, This species builds a large, messy domed nest out of dead leaves, dry grasses, stems, and pieces of bark.
Rose-throated_Becard, When foraging, sits upright on a perch for long periods, moving its head slowly in search of insects.
Rose-throated_Becard, Typically occurs singly or in pairs. Often inconspicuous as it perches within the foliage of tree crowns.
Rose-throated_Becard, Feeds on fruits, seeds, and insects.
Rose-throated_Becard, Adult male in humid regions is blackish-gray above, with a slightly darker black cap. Note short, stout bill.
Rose-throated_Becard, Note large head; short neck; capped appearance; short, narrow tail; and stout, slightly hooked bill to help identify this highly variable species.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Large, pink wading bird with a long, spoon-shaped bill. Adults have brighter pink shoulders and a bare yellowish green head.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Juveniles look similar to adults, but are paler pink and have a completely feathered head. Spoon-shaped bill is distinctive.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Roseate Spoonbills forage in shallow waters for aquatic invertebrates sweeping their head side to side with the bill partly opened.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Flies with its neck outstretched. Note pink underwings.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Flies with deep and strong wingbeats.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Roseate Spoonbills roost and nest in colonies with other waterbirds in trees and shrubs at the edges of wetlands and estuaries.
Roseate_Spoonbill, In flight, note adult's bright pink underwing coverts.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Nests and roosts in trees and shrubs including mangrove, sea myrtle, hackberry, and mesquite.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Roseate Spoonbills build bulky stick nests in trees and shrubs that often hang over standing water. They typically raise 3 to 4 chicks every year.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Juveniles are pale pink with a completely feathered head.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Found in freshwater and saltwater wetlands, mangroves, forested swamps, rivers, bays, estuaries, mudflats, and lagoons.
Roseate_Spoonbill, Flies with its neck stretched out with powerful wingbeats.
Roseate_Tern, Flies with stiff, but shallow rowing wingbeats. Note black cap and long forked tail.
Roseate_Tern, Nests and roosts on rocky islands in colonies with other terns.

Roseate_Tern, Medium-sized, very pale gray tern with a long forked tail. Bill color varies from entirely black to having orange at the base depending on time of year. Note black crown and rounded head.
Roseate_Tern, The long, forked tail extends beyond the wingtips when resting. The pale rose color on the belly for which it is named is often not visible.
Roseate_Tern, Juveniles have a scaly looking back and a smudgy crown and forehead.
Rosss_Goose, Small, all white goose with black wingtips and pink legs. Note the stubby pink bill with a blue-gray base.

Rosss_Goose, White and blue morphs both occur, though the blue morph is very rare. It is very dark gray with a high contrast white head and white upperwing patch. Suspected blue morph birds should be carefully scrutinized for signs of hybridization with Snow Goose—most reported blue morph Ross's Geese show hybrid characters like a black grin patch or curved bill base under close inspection.
Rosss_Goose, Flocks with other species of geese during the nonbreeding months in shallow wetlands, ponds, and agricultural fields.

Rosss_Goose, Juvenile are mostly white with some dusky highlights on the head and back. Bill and legs are dusky gray-pink. Juveniles often show slight dark grin patches because their bills continue to grow through the first year of life before assuming adult structure.
Rosss_Goose, In flight, all white with black primaries. The stubby bill and short neck help confirm the identification.
Rosss_Goose, Forms flocks during the nonbreeding season. Strong flier.
Rosss_Goose, A compact, all-white goose with black primaries and gray primary coverts.

Rosss_Goose, The short pink bill is often marked with grayish caruncles at the base. The base of the bill is vertical instead of curved, and the grin patch is quite reduced in comparison to the large black grin patch shown by Snow Goose.
Rosss_Goose, Found on shallow wetlands and ponds often with other goose species.

Rosss_Goose, Often flocks together with larger Snow Geese. Plumage between white morph adults is identical, so size and structure are very important. Note the small size and short-necked, stubby-billed look here in comparison to the lanky Snow Goose at left.
Rosss_Goose, In addition to traveling with Snow Geese, they can be found with other species of dark geese. Usually appears tiny, compact, and toy-like in comparison to other species.
Rosss_Goose, Small, round-headed goose with a small pinkish bill.
Rosss_Gull, A small gull with a short, slender black bill, rounded head, and pale gray wings. Breeding adult has a thin black necklace or collar and pink wash to underparts.
Rosss_Gull, Nonbreeding adult has a dark spot behind the ear, smudge around eyes, and pinkish wash to underparts. Wings are uniform pale gray with gray tips. Legs are red.

Rosss_Gull, A small, almost dovelike gull with a round head and short black bill. Breeding adult has a lovely pink wash to the underparts, a black necklace, light gray upperparts, and vibrant red legs.
Rosss_Gull, First-summer bird has black necklace of adult and prominent black wing patch of juvenile.
Rosss_Gull, Breeding adult is one of the most beautiful and distinctive gulls, with its black necklace, pink underparts, and wedge-shaped tail.
Rosss_Gull, Nests on small, dry rises in marshy tundra in the High Arctic.
Rosss_Gull, In flight, note long, slender wings and tern-like flight.
Rosss_Gull, First-winter bird has bold blackish M on the upperwings, dark spot behind eye, and dark tip to the wedge-shaped tail.
Rosss_Gull, A small, graceful, long-winged gull with a distinctive wedge-shaped tail.
Rosss_Gull, A bird of the remote far north. Seen regularly at Utqiagvik (formerly Barrow), Alaska, but otherwise extremely rare anywhere in North America.

Rough-legged_Hawk, Large hawk with fairly narrow wings. Note the black patches at the wrist and the white tail base with black band at the tip. Males tend to be more mottled on the wings with less of a black belly patch than females.

Rough-legged_Hawk, Large hawk with relatively narrow wings and a long tail. Note black patches at the wrist. Immatures have a lighter head and extensive black belly patch. The tail is white with a dark tip.

Rough-legged_Hawk, Breeds in the Arctic; typically seen wintering in cold, often snowy fields with patchy trees. Perches on slender branches and at the tops of small trees. Flies with easy wingbeats but soars less often than other raptors.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Note light head, mottled brown upperwing, and white tail base with dark band at tip. Juveniles have distinctive white panels in the primaries.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Strongly mottled with buff and reddish-brown above. Males have streaky underparts and barred legs. They usually have less of a distinct black belly band than females.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Bulky hawk of open country and cold climates. Males have darker head and breast than females. Note dark patches at the bend of the wing (wrist) on the underside.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Hunts in open country and often perches on the ground. Note pale head and white base of tail with dark tip.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Dark morph adults have pale flight feathers giving a two-toned appearance to the underwings. They also usually show white bands in the tail.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Often hunts by turning into the wind and flapping to hover in place, while scanning the ground below.

Rough-legged_Hawk, Dark morphs can be fully chocolate-brown except for pale undersides to the flight feathers, which are not visible when perched. The tail often has narrow white bands, but they can be indistinct. Eye darkens with age.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Dark morphs can have variable amounts of mottling on the back, wings, and belly.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Hunts by flying over open country, sometimes hovering into wind. Dark morph is mostly dark brown with contrasting white in the wings and tail.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Males usually have darker heads, a streakier breast, and less of a black belly patch than females. The legs are feathered all the way to the feet, unlike most other hawks.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Large hawk with long wings. Female usually has a light head, pale breast, extensive black belly patch, and a white-based tail with black tip.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Males have streakier, darker breast than females and often have barred flanks.
Rough-legged_Hawk, Feathering extends all the way to the feet, unlike on many other hawks. Males typically have darker chests than females.

Rough-legged_Hawk, Breeds in arctic tundra; usually seen in winter, when it hunts in open country including fields, marshes, prairies, and sagebrush. Perches on telephone poles and on the slender top branches of small trees.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with a daggerlike orange bill. Breeding birds have a shaggy black crown that is sometimes held flat. Note black legs.
Royal_Tern, Plunge dives into shallow water to capture fish and crustaceans such as shrimp.
Royal_Tern, Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Immature birds have darker wingtips and a narrow shaggy crest.
Royal_Tern, Juveniles are spotted with black and gray above with a partial cap. Note gray bar across the wings.
Royal_Tern, Pale gray above with a long forked tail and pointed wings. Flies with strong rowing wingbeats.
Royal_Tern, Social and colonial nesting waterbird found in groups year-round. Breeding adults have a shaggy black cap and a bright orange bill.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Large tern with pointed wings, a long forked tail, and a bright orange bill. Nonbreeding birds have a narrow often shaggy band at the back of the head.
Royal_Tern, Found along coastal warm waters and sandy beaches.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny songbird with an equally tiny tail and bill. Olive-green overall with a prominent white eyering and white wingbar. Note black bar below the wingbar.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny, small featured bird. Adult males flash a brilliant red crown when excited; otherwise it is concealed.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny, thin-billed bird filled with seemingly nervous energy. Forages (often at lower levels but only rarely on the ground) with twitchy motions and often flicks wings.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Olive-green above with a white wingbar and yellow-edged wing and tail feathers. Note black bar below the wingbar.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, The namesake crown is usually concealed, but white eyering and small size are good field marks.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Frequently flicks wings while foraging.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Tiny and acrobatic. Often forages at lower and middle levels flicking its wings as it goes.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Plain face helps to distinguish Ruby-crowned Kinglet from the similar (but more boldly marked) Golden-crowned Kinglet.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Juvenile is browner than adult, with buffy wingbars. Note also the orange gape at the corner of the mouth.
Ruby-crowned_Kinglet, Breeds in tall, dense evergreen forests. In winter and during migration, found in shrubby habitats, deciduous forests, parks, and suburbs.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Tiny, with long wings and bill. Dusky below with a bright red throat, black mask, and green crown.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Female is golden-green above and whitish below, lacking male's ruby throat.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Tiny bird with emerald green back and brilliant red throat. The throat is iridescent and looks black or dark red, then lights up when viewed at the correct angle.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Expert flier that can stop instantly, hover, and adjust its position up, down, or backwards with exquisite control.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, In some light the throat of the adult male can appear black.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Hovers with pinpoint precision, beating wings so fast they're almost invisible. Drinks nectar by probing flowers with long, thin bill.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Feeds on a variety of flowering plants. Tiny, with long wings and bill. Mostly white below, with buffy flanks, a dusky mask, and green upperparts.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Upperparts bright metallic green, and short tail is black and forked.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Eats insects in addition to nectar, often plucking them from spiderwebs or taking them from a sapsucker's sap wells.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Upperparts bright metallic green, and short tail is mostly black with white tips to the outer feathers.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Immature males have some red feathers on the throat.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Nestlings have shorter bills than adults. Nest is thimble-sized, made with spiderweb that stretches as the young birds grow.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Uses long tongue to drink nectar from tubular flowers or sugar water from hummingbird feeders.
Ruby-throated_Hummingbird, Sometimes perches prominently on exposed branches.
Ruddy_Duck, Small, compact duck with a stout, scoop-shaped bill, and a long, stiff tail that is often held up. Breeding males have a blue bill and chestnut bodies.
Ruddy_Duck, Females and immatures are brownish overall, with a black bill, dark cap, and indistinct line across the cheek.
Ruddy_Duck, Courtship display starts with tapping sounds from male's bill beating against his chest and ends with a belch-like call.
Ruddy_Duck, Small, compact duck with a big head and scoop-shaped bill. Nonbreeding males have a dark cap and solid white cheek.
Ruddy_Duck, This duck is part of a small group of waterfowl known as "stiff tails" due to their long, pointed tails, which are often held straight up.
Ruddy_Duck, Small and compact diving duck that sits relatively low in the water. Sometimes it cocks its tail up above the water and other times lays it flat on the water's surface.
Ruddy_Duck, Small, compact duck. Breeding males have a blue bill and a white cheek patch.
Ruddy_Duck, Small, compact ducks with a stout, scoop-shaped bill. Females have a whitish cheek with a black stripe across it.
Ruddy_Duck, Small, compact ducks with a stout, scoop-shaped bill, and a long, stiff tail often held up. Nonbreeding males have a dark cap and a white cheek.
Ruddy_Duck, Males stick their tails straight up while striking their bills against their inflated necks, creating bubbles in the water during courtship displays.
Ruddy_Duck, Ducklings are well developed and receive minimal care from the female (and none from the male).
Ruddy_Duck, Compact shape, raised tail, and white cheek distinctive at a distance. Often congregates in groups on lakes during the winter.
Ruddy_Duck, Breeds in wetlands and reservoirs with dense emergent vegetation.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, A very small dove with a long tail, deep red eyes, and black markings on the wings. Male has rich cinnamon upperparts that give way to a pale pink neck and face and a gray crown.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Female is less colorful than male, with grayish underparts and brownish upperparts with a hint of cinnamon.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, A miniature dove with black wing markings, deep red eyes, and a fairly long tail. Male is cinnamon to rusty above, with pinkish underparts and a gray head.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Sometimes joins mixed-species flocks with other small doves, including Inca Dove.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Male's rusty upperparts are distinctive among Neotropical ground dove species.

Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Resident from northern Mexico to northern Argentina, this species has become a regular visitor to Arizona and has occurred in several other U.S. states. Typically forages on the ground for seeds.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Forages on the ground for seeds.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Often seen in pairs or small flocks.
Ruddy_Ground_Dove, Socially monogamous, with strong pair bonds. Male has pinkish underparts, while female is tan below.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Short, stocky, oval-shaped shorebird with a stout and slightly upturned bill. Breeding birds have a calico patterned back and a black-and-white face. Note orange legs.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Short, stocky, oval-shaped shorebird with a stout and slightly upturned bill. Nonbreeding birds have a brown ghosting of the breeding plumage pattern and orange legs.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Stout body tapers to a slender tail. Walks along shorelines turning over rocks and debris to look for flies and midges hiding underneath.
Ruddy_Turnstone, In flight, note the white stripe down the back, a black tail stripe, a white rump, and white stripes down the wings.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Short, stocky, oval-shaped shorebird with a stout and slightly upturned bill. Breeding birds have a calico patterned back and a black-and-white face. Note orange legs.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Juveniles look like nonbreeding birds, but have rusty edges to the feathers on the upperparts.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Short, stocky, oval-shaped shorebird with a stout and slightly upturned bill. Breeding birds have a calico patterned back and a black-and-white face. Note orange legs.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Flips rocks, pebbles, and seaweed along shorelines in search of food with stout but sharply pointed bill.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Stocky and short-legged shorebird with orange legs. Nonbreeding birds are brownish overall with a rounded brown chest patch.
Ruddy_Turnstone, Breeds in the tundra. Uses freshwater shorelines, mudflats, rocky shorelines, and sandy beaches during migration and winter.
Ruff, A chunky, medium-sized shorebird with long legs and a short, slightly curved bill. Breeding males are adorned with bizarre head tufts, ruffs, facial warts, and boldly marked upperparts.

Ruff, Plumage, bill color, and leg color are all highly variable, so key in on shape for identification. Note relatively small head, large body, long legs, and short bill. Nonbreeding adult has grayish upperparts with pale feather edging. Female typically has a black bill and develops blackish chest barring during the breeding season.

Ruff, A bizarre yet spectacular shorebird. Breeding males gather on courtship grounds known as leks, where they display their colorful facial warts, head tufts, and neck ruffs to females watching from the edge of the lek.
Ruff, Juvenile has a buffy face, neck, and breast. Upperparts are variably colored. Bill is black. Leg color in all plumages varies from orange to greenish.
Ruff, In flight, note the thin white wingbars, white V or U on the uppertail coverts, and feet extending beyond the tail.
Ruff, Males on leks sometimes sit motionless before suddenly springing to life to perform displays and, at times, fight one another.
Ruff, Male's ruff and head tuft can be black, white, dark purple, chestnut, or buff; pattern can be barred, spotted, or solid.
Ruff, Males can be endlessly variable in the exact details of their ruffs, head tufts, and upperpart patterning.

Ruff, Occurs in a variety of wetlands, where it forages for insects and other invertebrates. Nonbreeding female is grayish-brown above, with pale feather edging, and typically has a dark bill. Note the white patch at the base of the bill. Leg color in all plumages varies from bright orange to dull yellow-green.
Ruff, Males with white ruffs are known as "satellite" males and are subordinate to most other males on display grounds.

Ruff, Nonbreeding adult is grayish-brown above, with pale feather edging. Note the white patch at the base of the bill. Legs in all plumages vary from bright orange to dull yellow-green. Nonbreeding female typically has a dark bill.
Ruff, Forages by picking prey from the surface or probing in shallow water or mud. Juvenile has a buffy face, neck, and breast; a white belly; and crisp, scaly upperparts.
Ruff, Juvenile has a buffy face, neck, and breast. Upperparts are variably colored. Bill is black. Leg color in all plumages varies from orange to greenish.
Ruff, Most males grow fancy head tufts and ruffs during a special molt lasting from March to May.
Ruff, Breeding males gather and display on communal courtship sites known as leks.
Ruff, Often found in small groups, but during migration occurs in large flocks of hundreds or thousands of birds.
Ruff, Males, such as the leftmost bird and the white-headed individual on the right, are about 20% larger than females.

Ruffed_Grouse, Medium-sized game bird with short crest. A well-camouflaged bird with intricately barred and spotted plumage. Individuals can be grayish brown overall, reddish brown, or an intermediate tawny brown.
Ruffed_Grouse, Medium-sized game bird with extravagant display, including erecting long neck feathers to create a black "ruff" and fanning the tail, exposing a dark band near the tip.

Ruffed_Grouse, Males typically perform a "drum display" atop a raised surface such as a log or stump. Ruffed Grouse do not produce the drumming sound by hitting their wings against their body, but rather by creating miniature sonic booms while pumping their wings back and forth.
Ruffed_Grouse, When not displaying, sexes are difficult to tell apart. Often forages among tree branches during winter, especially when snow covers the ground.
Ruffed_Grouse, Often bathes in dust or lies on anthills ("anting"), fluffing feathers to clean them.
Ruffed_Grouse, Usually secretive and elusive, but occasional tame individuals actively approach humans.
Ruffed_Grouse, Medium-sized game bird with peaked crest, pale line through the eye, and dark band near tip of tail. Sometimes forages in trees, especially in winter, taking berries and buds.
Ruffed_Grouse, Lives in forest undergrowth where it can be very difficult to see; often most easily seen when crossing roads.

Rufous-capped_Warbler, A small warbler with a rufous cap and cheek patch, white stripes above and below the eye, and a narrow black mask running through the eye. The widespread rufifrons subspecies group has a bright yellow throat and breast that contrasts with a whitish belly.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, The salvini subspecies group, found in southern Mexico, Belize, and northern Guatemala, has entirely yellow underparts.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, A small, boldly marked warbler with a rufous-and-white head, yellow throat and breast, and grayish-olive upperparts. Both sexes sing a rapid, multiparted song.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Upperparts and tail are gray to grayish olive.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Often holds its long, narrow tail nearly vertically.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Builds a dome-shaped nest, placed on the ground, from plant fibers.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Found in brushy habitats, including woodland edges and second growth areas.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Forages for insects in low to midlevel vegetation.
Rufous-capped_Warbler, Forages close to the ground in search of insects. Frequently raises or cocks its long tail.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with rufous cap, white eyering, and strong white-and-black "mustache" or malar stripes.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Overall grayish sparrow with rusty stripes on the back. Strong face pattern with rufous crown, white eyering, and dark stripes at sides of the throat.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Walks or hops, pecking or scratching at the ground for seeds and insects often under the protective cover of shrubs or dense grasses.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Long-tailed, grayish sparrow with rusty stripes on back. Rufous cap and stripe through eye; white eyering.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Found in open, shrubby areas on dry slopes with patchy ground cover. Avoids dense woody habitats.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Males sing a mix of slurs and chatters with a bubbly quality reminiscent of a Northern House Wren in spring and summer from exposed perches or while in flight.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Long-tailed sparrow with rufous cap, white eyering, and strong white-and-black "mustache" or malar stripes.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Found in open, shrubby areas on dry slopes, often with areas of bare rock or patches of sparse grass.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Drinks water from small pools or gathers dew from vegetation. This video has no audio.
Rufous-crowned_Sparrow, Look for Rufous-crowned Sparrows in spring or early summer when males sing in the early morning from exposed perches.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.
Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Rusty or rufous wing patch sometimes visible on its shoulder. Note black throat stripe, pale conical bill, and rusty streaks on a gray head.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, A sparrow with a long, rounded tail and pale, conical bill. Other notable features include unstreaked belly and black throat stripe. Year-round resident in Sonoran desert scrub and Sinaloan thorn scrub.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous-winged_Sparrow, Small bird with a short conical bill and long tail. It has rusty stripes on its head and a rusty line behind its eye. Underparts are grayish and unstreaked. Namesake rufous wing patch is not always visible.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a nearly straight bill, a tail that tapers to a point when folded, and fairly short wings that don't reach the end of the tail when the bird is perched. Males are bright orange on the back and belly, with a vivid iridescent-red throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are greenish above with rusty-washed flanks, rusty patches on their green tail, and often a spot of orange on the throat.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a nearly straight bill, a tail that tapers to a point when folded, and fairly short wings that don't reach the end of the tail when the bird is perched. Males are bright orange on the back and belly, with a vivid iridescent-red throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Immature males have rusty washed sides and a spot of orange coming in on their throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, The majority of adult males have a rusty back and tail. The outer tail feathers are broad and the fourth tail feather from the outside has a notched tip.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a nearly straight bill, a tail that tapers to a point when folded, and fairly short wings that don't reach the end of the tail when the bird is perched. Males are bright orange on the back and belly, with a vivid iridescent-red throat.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Some adult males have green on their backs similar to Allen's Hummingbirds. Separating these green-backed individuals in the field requires careful inspection of the shape of the spread outer tail feathers.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Broad outer tail feathers help to differentiate female/immature Rufous Humminbird from very similar Allen's Hummingbird.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a nearly straight bill, a tail that tapers to a point when folded, and fairly short wings that don't reach the end of the tail when the bird is perched. Males are bright orange on the back and belly, with a vivid iridescent-red throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Females/immatures are greenish above with rusty-washed flanks, rusty patches on their green tail, and often a spot of orange on the throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Aggressive hummingbird that tirelessly chases other hummingbirds away from feeders.

Rufous_Hummingbird, Small hummingbird with a nearly straight bill, a tail that tapers to a point when folded, and fairly short wings that don't reach the end of the tail when the bird is perched. Males are bright orange on the back and belly, with a vivid iridescent-red throat.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Immature males often look messy as their new feathers come in, showing features of both immature and adult plumages.
Rufous_Hummingbird, Breeds in open or shrubby areas, forest openings, yards, and parks, and sometimes in forests, thickets, swamps, and meadows from sea level to about 6,000 feet.
Rusty_Blackbird, Medium-sized blackbird with a slender, slightly curved bill. Breeding males are dark glossy black with a greenish sheen.

Rusty_Blackbird, Medium-sized blackbird with a slender, slightly curved bill. Females are brownish to rusty colored with pale eyes, and a pale eyebrow that contrasts with darker feathers around the eye.
Rusty_Blackbird, Song consists of two or three notes, followed by a higher, rising note, like the creak of rusty hinges.
Rusty_Blackbird, Nonbreeding males are dark brown overall with rusty edging on the feathers, a pale eye, and a pale eyebrow.
Rusty_Blackbird, Some nonbreeding males have more extensive rusty tipped feathers than others.
Rusty_Blackbird, Medium-sized blackbird with a slender, slightly curved bill. Breeding males are dark glossy black with a greenish sheen.
Rusty_Blackbird, Found in wet areas, including flooded woods, swamps, marshes, and the edges of ponds.
Sabines_Gull, Striking black-headed gull on the breeding grounds in the Arctic. Bill is black with a yellow tip.
Sabines_Gull, Juveniles have a brownish back that appears scaly and a brownish neck. The outer primaries are black, narrowly edged in white.
Sabines_Gull, Sabine's Gulls typically nest along pond edges, on islands, or on low-lying marshy tundra near the shore.
Sabines_Gull, Nonbreeding birds have black primaries, white secondaries, and a gray back. A smudgy gray partial hood marks the head. The tail is entirely white.
Sabines_Gull, Breeding birds in flight have black primaries, white secondaries, and a gray back, all of which form triangular patches of color.
Sabines_Gull, Juveniles in flight look similar to breeding adults, but have paler triangular blocks of color and the tail is tipped in black.
Sabines_Gull, Nonbreeding birds have black primaries, white secondaries, and a gray back. A smudgy gray partial hood marks the head. The tail is entirely white.
Sabines_Gull, Resting nonbreeding birds show a smudgy gray partial hood and black wingtips with a touch of white edging. The bill is black with a yellow tip.
Sage_Thrasher, Small thrasher with a short bill—rather thrushlike overall. Heavily streaked below with a grayish brown back and 2 thin white wingbars. Note pale eye.
Sage_Thrasher, Often runs along the ground in areas with dense sagebrush, scattered bunchgrasses, and bare ground.
Sage_Thrasher, Males sing long, complex songs made up of a rambling series of phrases. Notes include clear whistles, burrs, clucking notes, and sometimes mimics other birds.
