Sage_Thrasher, Small thrasher with a short bill—rather thrushlike overall. Heavily streaked below with a grayish brown back and 2 thin white wingbars. Note pale eye.
Sage_Thrasher, Found in expanses of dense sagebrush with scattered bunchgrasses and bare ground.
Sage_Thrasher, Small thrasher with a short bill—rather thrushlike overall. Heavily streaked below with a grayish brown back and 2 thin white wingbars. Note pale eye.
Sage_Thrasher, Small thrasher with a short bill—rather thrushlike overall. Heavily streaked below with a grayish brown back and 2 thin white wingbars. Note pale eye.
Sage_Thrasher, Males have a long and variable song. The rambling series of phrases, often preceded by soft clucking notes, is continuous and interspersed with moments of repetition and mimicry.
Sage_Thrasher, Small thrasher with a short bill—rather thrushlike overall. Heavily streaked below with a grayish brown back and 2 thin white wingbars. Note pale eye.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Fairly large and long-tailed sparrow. Spends much of its time hopping or running on the ground between or beneath shrub cover, often with the tail raised.

Sagebrush_Sparrow, Breeds in sage-dominated landscapes of western North America. Males sing from prominent perches during the breeding season; otherwise spend much of their time on the ground or hidden in shrubs.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Round, gray head contrasts with brown back. The face has a white spot in front of the eye, a white eyering, and a white mustache stripe with a thin black border.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Often twitches or bobs the tail while perched. Call is soft and high pitched.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Sagebrush_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a long tail and round head. The face has a white eyering, a white spot before the eye, and a white mustache bordered by a thin black stripe.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Flat-headed sparrow with a relatively long bill. The eyebrow and mustache stripes are orangish. The flanks are streaked brown.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Found in tidal saltwater marshes with extensive reeds and grasses. Runs or walks along the ground dipping in and out of grasses.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Juveniles are heavily streaked below and have a ghosting of the adult's facial pattern.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Small, flat-headed sparrow with a round belly. Key field marks include orangish eyebrow and mustache, buffy breast with streaking that gently fades towards the belly.
Saltmarsh_Sparrow, Breeds in tidal saltmarshes where it can be difficult to see.
Sanderling, Plump sandpiper with a stout black bill. Breeding birds have rusty mottling on the back, head, and breast. Note unmarked sides and black legs.
Sanderling, Plump sandpiper with a stout black bill. Nonbreeding birds are pale gray above and white below without streaking. Darker shoulder bar sometimes visible.
Sanderling, Forages at the water's edge, typically on sandy beaches during winter; often found inland during migration.
Sanderling, Juveniles have a checkered back and unmarked white underparts.
Sanderling, In flight, note dark leading edge of the wing from above and all white wings from below.
Sanderling, Breeding adults have varying amounts of rusty wash on the upperparts. Note stout black bill and clean white underparts.
Sanderling, Plump shorebird with a stout black bill and black legs. Breeding birds have rusty mottled upperparts.
Sanderling, Juveniles have speckled backs and unmarked white underparts.
Sanderling, Scurries back and forth chasing waves while foraging in loose groups.
Sanderling, Forms large flocks during migration. Found on sandy beaches chasing waves.
Sandhill_Crane, Tall, heavy-bodied bird with a long neck and long legs. Drooping feathers form a "bustle" around its back end. Gray overall with some tan body feathers. Note red crown.
Sandhill_Crane, Large bird with broad wings. Flies with its neck stretched out and feet trailing behind.
Sandhill_Crane, Tall, graceful bird with gray plumage, white throat, and red crown patch.
Sandhill_Crane, Immature birds have a rusty crown and back of the neck. They also have more rusty plumage on their back and wings.
Sandhill_Crane, Young can stand and walk shortly after hatching, but adults care for the chicks for up to 10 months.
Sandhill_Crane, Flies with neck and legs extended. Wings are very broad, with wingtips slightly darker than rest of wing.
Sandhill_Crane, Performs dances to attract mates. Displaying birds stretch their wings, pump their heads, bow, and leap into the air.
Sandhill_Crane, Nests in shallow wetlands where it builds a mounded nest out of reeds, sedges, and grasses on the ground, often above standing water.
Sandhill_Crane, Often occurs in flocks, unlike herons. Displaying birds stretch their wings, pump their heads, bow, and leap into the air.
Sandhill_Crane, Adults have a bright red crown and a large dark bill.
Sandhill_Crane, Forages for seeds, reptiles, amphibians, small mammals, and insects in open grasslands, fields, and wetlands.
Sandhill_Crane, During migration, flocks can be extremely large, gathering along broad river valleys. This video has no audio.
Sandhill_Crane, Migrates and winters in extremely large flocks, numbering into the tens of thousands. Found in open prairies, grasslands, and wetlands.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip, although pale tip can be difficult to see. It is the only shaggy crested tern with a black bill.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Nonbreeding birds are very pale gray above with only a partial black crown. The bill is black with pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Juveniles have a mottled black-and-gray back and a dark rear crown patch. The bill is orangish, but quickly turns dark.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Slender tern with a long black bill with a pale tip.
Sandwich_Tern, Highly social tern that congregates in good feeding areas. Note pale gray back and dark bill.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.

Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with fairly small bill and short tail. The "Belding's" form breeds in saltmarshes of California and Baja California; it is darker, more heavily streaked, and has a thinner crown stripe than other forms.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Eats larvae, spiders, grasshoppers, millipedes, and other insects. This individual is likely carrying food back to the nest to feed its nestlings.
Savannah_Sparrow, Crisp brown streaks on white breast (may converge to form a spot). Strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Typically found in open habitats including grassland, saltmarsh, tundra, roadsides, agricultural areas, and beaches.
Savannah_Sparrow, The "Ipswich" form breeds in coastal Nova Scotia and winters in coastal areas in northeastern North America. They are paler brown than other forms of Savannah Sparrow.
Savannah_Sparrow, The dark, heavily streaked "Belding's" form with a thinner crown stripe occurs in saltmarshes of California and Baja California.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with short tail. "Large-billed" form occurs in northwestern Mexico and Baja California; note large, heavy bill and lack of yellow in the stripe over the eye.
Savannah_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a fairly small bill and short tail. Crisply streaked breast and strong face pattern with yellowish stripe over the eye.
Says_Phoebe, Slender, long-tailed flycatcher with a relatively large head. Brownish gray above with a cinnamon belly and gray breast.
Says_Phoebe, Slender, long-tailed flycatcher with a relatively large head. Brownish gray above with a cinnamon belly and gray breast.
Says_Phoebe, Perches low to the ground in open country, on shrubs, grasses, barbed wire, etc. Often bobs its tail while perched.
Says_Phoebe, Slender, long-tailed flycatcher with a relatively large head that sometimes looks peaked. Brownish gray above with a cinnamon belly and gray breast. Often wags its tail when perched.
Says_Phoebe, Slender, long-tailed flycatcher with a relatively large head. Brownish gray above with a cinnamon belly and gray breast.
Says_Phoebe, Slender, long-tailed flycatcher with a relatively large head. Brownish gray above with a cinnamon belly and gray breast.
Says_Phoebe, Found in open country, sagebrush, badlands, dry barren foothills, canyons, and borders of deserts.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird with peaked crest. Brownish head and wings with neat white-and-black scaling on upper body and belly.
Scaled_Quail, Plump, short-legged game bird with short peaked crest. Intricate white-and-black scaling on the breast and belly.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird with peaked crest. Brownish head and wings with neat white-and-black scaling on upper body and belly.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird with short peaked crest. Tail is fairly short and grayer than back. Brown wings show white barring.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird of dry, open habitats. Usually seen on the ground or standing on a low perch.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird with peaked crest. Brownish head and wings with neat white-and-black scaling on upper body and belly.
Scaled_Quail, Plump, short-legged game bird of dry, open areas. Young are able to walk immediately after hatching.
Scaled_Quail, Social game bird often found in groups or coveys. Sometimes huddles in shade to stay cool and watch for predators.
Scaled_Quail, Plump game bird with peaked crest. Brownish head and wings with neat white-and-black scaling on upper body and belly.
Scaled_Quail, Small plump game bird of desert grasslands and shrublands. Typically occurs in coveys of 10 to 40 birds (flocks are usually largest in winter).
Scaly-breasted_Munia, A small songbird with a large, seedeating bill. Adult is brown above, often with fine white streaking, and white below, with dark scaling.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, The "Checkered" subspecies group, native to South Asia and introduced to parts of the continental U.S., has a chestnut-brown head, distinctive black (not brown) scalloping on the underparts, and orange uppertail coverts.
Scaly-breasted_Munia, A small songbird with a large bill. Adult has brown upperparts, head, and throat, and white underparts with fine dark scalloping.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, Juvenile has plain brown upperparts and buffy, unmarked underparts. Very similar to juveniles of other munia species and best identified by association with adult Scaly-breasted Munia.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, Adults in the "Scaled" subspecies group, found across Southeast Asia, are variable in appearance, but always lack the black scalloping and orange uppertail coverts of the "Checkered" group.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, Uses its heavy bill to eat the seeds of grasses and other plants. Adult in the "Checkered" subspecies group has crisp black scalloping on the underparts and a rich chestnut brown head.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, Adult's scaly breast clearly differentiates this species from other munias, with which it sometimes flocks. This individual's black underpart markings and orange uppertail coverts identify it as part of the "Checkered" subspecies group.
Scaly-breasted_Munia, Introduced to parts of North America, Europe, and Australia, as well as Japan, the Hawaiian Islands, Mauritius, and Reunion. Note pointed tail.

Scaly-breasted_Munia, A social bird that forages in small groups while breeding and in larger flocks at other times of the year. Immature (in background) is buffy-brown above and slightly paler below. This individual is just starting to show some rich brown on the lower throat.
Scaly-breasted_Munia, Frequently forages in small groups, perching atop and feeding on grasses and other seeding plants.
Scaly-breasted_Munia, Builds a large, loose nest of grasses and leaves.
Scarlet_Tanager, Stocky songbird with a thick blunt-tipped bill. Breeding males are unmistakable with bright red bodies and black wings and tails.
Scarlet_Tanager, Medium-sized rather stocky songbird. Females/immatures are olive-yellow with darker wings and tails.
Scarlet_Tanager, Song is a hurried series of rising and falling warbles with a burry tone.
Scarlet_Tanager, Nonbreeding males look like females, but have darker black wings and tail.
Scarlet_Tanager, Chunky songbird with brilliant red plumage. Some males may have more orangish feathers on the back.
Scarlet_Tanager, Some males have orangish feathers in the wing that could be leftover from molting into breeding plumage.
Scarlet_Tanager, Males can have a splotchy appearance as they molt into their yellow-olive nonbreeding plumage.
Scarlet_Tanager, Breeding males are unmistakable with bright red bodies and black wings and tails.
Scarlet_Tanager, Breeds in large tracts of deciduous and mixed deciduous-evergreen forests.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Slender, stout-billed flycatcher with a very long, deeply forked tail. Pale gray with blackish wings and tail and salmon-pink flanks and under belly.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Juveniles have shorter tails than adults and are pale gray overall without the salmon wash on the flanks and under belly.

Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Often perches conspicuously on utility lines, treetops, and fence lines. Tends to wander widely on their way to and from the wintering grounds, showing up much farther north than expected.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Slender, stout-billed flycatcher with a very long, deeply forked tail. Pale gray with blackish wings and tail and salmon-pink flanks and under belly.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, In flight, salmon-colored shoulders and underwings are visible. Note extremely long, forked tail.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Juveniles have a pale gray head and back and a shorter tail than adults.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Slender, stout-billed flycatcher with a very long, deeply forked tail. Pale gray with blackish wings and tail and salmon-pink flanks and under belly.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Slender, stout-billed flycatcher with a very long, deeply forked tail. Pale gray with blackish wings and tail and salmon-pink flanks and under belly.
Scissor-tailed_Flycatcher, Breeds in open habitats in the southern Great Plains and south Texas, especially around scattered trees or utility lines.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Males have a black back, head, and breast and are lemon yellow below. Shows one white wingbar, plus yellow shoulder bordered in white.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Males have a black back, head, and breast and are lemon yellow below. Shows one white wingbar, plus yellow shoulder bordered in white.
Scotts_Oriole, Found on arid slopes, where it forages fairly low on yuccas and small trees seeking insects and also drinking nectar.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Males have a black back, head, and breast and are lemon yellow below. Shows one white wingbar, plus yellow shoulder bordered in white.
Scotts_Oriole, Males have black head and breast and a lemon yellow belly and rump.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Males have a black back, head, and breast and are lemon yellow below. Shows one white wingbar, plus yellow shoulder bordered in white.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Males have a black back, head, and breast and are lemon yellow below. Shows one white wingbar, plus yellow shoulder bordered in white.

Scotts_Oriole, Large and slender with a thin, slightly curved, pointed bill. Females are yellowish olive with dark wings marked with 2 white wingbars. Some females have variable black spotting on head and chest.
Scotts_Oriole, Uses drier areas with scattered trees and shrubs. Breeds in dry mountain foothills where yuccas are common.
Seaside_Sparrow, Found in tidal marshes with dense areas of marsh grass. Sings a soft buzzing song that sounds like a distant Red-winged Blackbird.
Seaside_Sparrow, Gulf of Mexico populations have a yellow stripe in front of the eye and a buffy chest with obvious streaking. Note long bill.
Seaside_Sparrow, Juveniles are buffier than adults, with a pale eyebrow. Juveniles also lack the rufous patch in the wing.
Seaside_Sparrow, Juveniles have only a hint of the yellow stripe in front of the eye. Note long bill.
Seaside_Sparrow, Medium-sized, hefty sparrow with a long bill. Atlantic populations have a bright yellow stripe in front of the eye and are grayer below with faint streaking. Note rusty wing patch.
Seaside_Sparrow, Breeds in tidal marshes.
Sedge_Wren, Small wren with a round belly, a streaked back, and banded wings. Often holds its short tail upright. Sexes similar.
Sedge_Wren, Small wren with a finely streaked crown and peachy flanks. Found in wet meadows, hayfields, and marshes.
Sedge_Wren, Song is an accelerating series of 3 or 4 sharp chips, followed by a trill or chatter.
Sedge_Wren, Small, round wren with banded wings and tail and a streaked back. Flanks and lower belly have a peachy wash.
Sedge_Wren, Found in areas with dense patches of sedges and grasses in wet meadows, hayfields, and marshes.
Sedge_Wren, Occupies wet habitats with dense vegetation such as pond edges, meadows, marshes, or unmaintained hayfields.
Sedge_Wren, Note streaked crown and the brown-and-white streaking on the back.
Sedge_Wren, Small wren of wet grasslands. Note short bill and banded wings.
Sedge_Wren, Males countersing to maintain and defend their territories. They often show off their large song repertoires during these exchanges.
Sedge_Wren, Small wren with buffy or peachy wash to the underparts. Stays low in grassy vegetation; does not tend to use deeper marshes with cattails.
Sedge_Wren, Found in areas with dense patches of sedges and grasses in wet meadows, hayfields, and marshes.
Semipalmated_Plover, Small shorebird with a round head and a stubby bill. Breeding birds have orange at the base of the bill and a black crown, eye patch, and breast band. Note yellow legs.
Semipalmated_Plover, Small shorebird with a round head and a stubby bill. Nonbreeding birds have a brown (instead of black) crown, breast band, and eyepatch.
Semipalmated_Plover, Plump shorebird with a short neck and round head. Note single dark band on chest and fairly small, orange-and-black bill.
Semipalmated_Plover, In flight, note brown tail with a darker tip (a common pattern among plovers) and long wings.
Semipalmated_Plover, Juveniles look like adults but have paler collar and facial markings.
Semipalmated_Plover, Small shorebird with a round head and a stubby bill. Note that the breast band goes all the way around the breast.
Semipalmated_Plover, Small shorebird with a round head and a stubby bill. Breeding birds have orange at the base of the bill and a black crown, eye patch, and breast band. Note yellow legs.
Semipalmated_Plover, Small shorebird with a round head and a stubby bill. Breeding birds have orange at the base of the bill and a black crown, eye patch, and breast band. Note yellow legs.
Semipalmated_Plover, Walks or runs with its head up. Stops and tilts forward to pick invertebrates from the ground. Note yellow legs and solid black breast band.
Semipalmated_Plover, Found on mudflats, estuaries, lagoons, ponds, lakeshores, agricultural ponds, and beaches during migration and the winter months.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Small shorebird with a short neck and small head. Breeding birds can have some rusty mottling on the back or have more of a gray-brown color.

Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Small shorebird with a short neck and small head. The bill is dark and may droop slightly at the tip. Nonbreeding birds have faint streaking on the breast, clean flanks, and dark legs.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Forms large flocks during migration and winter. Note relatively short, straight bill and dark legs.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Juveniles have a scaly looking back without any rusty coloring. Note darker cap and eyebrow stripe.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Juveniles have a scaly looking back caused by white edges to the feathers, and they lack rusty coloring. Note darker cap and eyebrow stripe.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, In flight, note dark stripe down the center of the tail bordered by whitish outer tail feathers.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Winters and migrates along mudflats, sandy beaches, shores of lakes and ponds, and wet meadows.
Semipalmated_Sandpiper, Found in large foraging or roosting flocks of up to several thousand individuals during migration and on the wintering grounds.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Small, long-tailed hawk with a small head. Adult "Northern" Sharp-shinned Hawk, which breeds in Canada and the U.S., has narrow, horizontal red-orange bars on the breast.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Adult "Northern" Sharp-shinned Hawk has blue-gray upperparts and dark bands on the tail.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Note small head and large eye. The very long tail distinguishes this and other accipiters from other types of hawks. Immatures are brown overall with yellow eyes.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Small raptor with thin legs and small feet. Immature "Northern" Sharp-shinned Hawk is brown above with thick brown streaks below.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Small raptor with short, rounded wings, which are often pushed forward. Note the long square-tipped tail.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Distinctive flight style of a few quick wingbeats followed by a short glide. Note fairly small head. Because of their small size, in windy conditions Sharp-shinned Hawks can appear unsteady in flight.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Often flies with its wings pushed forward with quick and snappy wingbeats.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Resident "Madrean" Sharp-shinned Hawk, found along the Sierra Madre del Sur in Guerrero to western Oaxaca, Mexico, is paler below with a pale cheek, a chestnut-washed belly, and chestnut leg feathers.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Short, rounded wings and very long tail are distinctive of accipiters. Although postures can change in flight, the small head nestled in crook of wings, and square-tipped tail, can be useful marks for Sharp-shinned Hawk.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Adult "White-breasted" Sharp-shinned Hawk, resident from Chiapas, Mexico, south to Nicaragua, has unmarked white underparts and a white cheek that contrasts with the gray crown.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Immature "White-breasted" Sharp-shinned Hawk has rusty streaks and spots on the underparts.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, "Plain-breasted" Sharp-shinned Hawk occurs in the Andes from western Venezuela to Bolivia. This group is highly variable, with underpart colors ranging from heavily barred (like this individual) to very pale; a dark morph also occurs.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, "Plain-breasted" Sharp-shinned Hawk occurs in the Andes from western Venezuela to Bolivia. This group is highly variable, with underpart colors ranging from heavily barred to very pale (like this individual); a dark morph also occurs.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, "Plain-breasted" Sharp-shinned Hawk occurs in the Andes from western Venezuela to Bolivia. This group is highly variable, with underpart colors ranging from heavily barred to very pale; a dark morph (like this individual) also occurs.

Sharp-shinned_Hawk, "Rufous-thighed" Sharp-shinned Hawk occurs in eastern Bolivia, southern Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay, and northern Argentina. Adult is nearly black above, with fine barring on the breast and rich chestnut feathers covering the upper legs (although not visible in this photo).
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Immature "Rufous-thighed" Sharp-shinned Hawk has brown upperparts and thick brown streaking below.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Adult "Caribbean" Sharp-shinned Hawk has cinnamon on the sides of the head, light barring on the breast, and a white belly.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Eats primarily songbirds about the size of an American Robin and smaller.
Sharp-shinned_Hawk, Found in forests and forest edge.

Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long and pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Purple skin patches are visible on the male's neck during courtship displays.
Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long and pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Barred in brown, black, and buff. Note V-shaped marks on belly.

Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long and pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Purple skin patches are visible on the male's neck during courtship displays.
Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long, pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Barred in brown, black, and buff.
Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with a small, slightly crested head. Barred in brown, black, and buff.

Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long and pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Purple skin patches are visible on the male's neck during courtship displays.
Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Males gather at specific sites called leks to perform courtship displays for females.
Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Social grouse that sometimes perches in trees.

Sharp-tailed_Grouse, Round and chickenlike with long and pointed central tail feathers and a small, slightly crested head. Purple skin patches are visible on the male's neck during courtship displays.

Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, A medium-sized shorebird with a rufous cap, prominent white eyeline, thin white eyering, and fairly short, dark bill with pale base. Breeding adult has heavy black spots and chevrons on cinnamon-and-white underparts, rich rufous markings above, and yellowish legs.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding adult has mostly plain brown upperparts. Note subdued rufous cap bordered by white eyeline.

Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, A medium-sized shorebird with a rufous cap, white eyeline, and relatively short, mostly dark bill. Juvenile has a buffy wash across the breast and a necklace of fine streaks across the upper breast. Often forages in shallow water with short vegetation.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Juvenile has a buffy-cinnamon breast with fine black streaking, a whitish belly, and dark upperparts with extensive bright orange and white feather edges.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, By late November, young birds can show a mix of juvenile (rufous cap) and nonbreeding adult characters (brownish-gray upperparts).
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding adults have brown upperparts, a grayish-brown wash across the breast, and limited streaking on the breast and flanks. Note the capped appearance and white eyeline.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Adults in late summer are less colorful than spring birds, but still retain some breeding-plumage spots and chevrons below.

Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Typically occurs in areas with shallow water and short vegetation. Nonbreeding adult has a grayish-brown wash across the breast with faint streaking that extends down the flanks. Note the distinct white eyestripe and dark rufous cap.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Nests on the ground in areas of wet tundra in the Russian Far East.
Sharp-tailed_Sandpiper, Breeding adult has a rufous cap, yellow legs, heavy spotting on a buffy-washed breast, and thick chevrons that extend down the flanks to the undertail.
Shiny_Cowbird, Chunky with a conical bill. Males are glossy black overall.
Shiny_Cowbird, Medium-sized bird with a conical, sharply pointed bill. Females are tan overall with a faint paler eyebrow.
Shiny_Cowbird, Note the fairly long, thick-based bill that comes to a sharp point, characteristic of cowbirds.
Shiny_Cowbird, Juveniles are dull brown with a streaky belly.
Shiny_Cowbird, Chunky with a conical bill. Males are glossy black overall.
Shiny_Cowbird, Song is a bubbling purring, followed by an ascending series of short, high notes.
Shiny_Cowbird, Chunky bird with a conical bill. Females are tan overall and have little to no streaking on the belly.
Shiny_Cowbird, Often feeds in mixed flocks of other blackbirds on the ground or in trees and shrubs.
Shiny_Cowbird, Found in open or semiopen habitats, especially agricultural areas with patches of trees and shrubs.

Short-billed_Dowitcher, Medium-sized shorebird with a long, football-shaped body and a long straight bill. Breeding birds have variable amounts of cinnamon coloring on their bodies. Feeds with a vertical, sewing-machine-like movement of the head.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Short-necked shorebird with a long bill. When foraging, looks flat-backed. Nonbreeding birds are brownish gray with barring on the flanks.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Forages by plunging its long bill deep into mud or sand, making a sewing-machine-like motion with its head. When it does this, the back usually appears fairly flat.

Short-billed_Dowitcher, Juveniles have more extensive cinnamon color on the folded wings above the tail. Juveniles molt out of juvenile plumage on the wintering grounds, unlike Long-billed Dowitchers that molt on the breeding grounds.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, In flight, white upper rump patch distinguishes it from many other shorebirds, except Long-billed Dowitchers.

Short-billed_Dowitcher, Medium-sized shorebird with a long, football-shaped body and a long straight bill. Breeding birds have variable amounts of cinnamon coloring on their bodies. Feeds with a vertical, sewing-machine-like movement of the head.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Plumage color is geographically variable. Those migrating through eastern and central North America (hendersoni) have darker and more extensive cinnamon underparts.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Plumage color is geographically variable. Those migrating through eastern North American (griseus) have pale orangish breasts and whitish bellies.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Congregates in groups with other dowitchers during migration and winter.
Short-billed_Dowitcher, Found in saltmarshes, lagoons, flooded agricultural fields, and coastal mudflats during migration and on the wintering grounds.
Short-billed_Gull, Small white-headed gull with a little yellow bill and yellow legs. Head looks very round and petite. Breeding adults have a red ring around the eye.
Short-billed_Gull, Small to medium-sized gull with a little yellow bill and a round head. Nonbreeding adults have smudgy tan marks on the head and neck.
Short-billed_Gull, Note small bill and rounded head. First-winter birds have gray back, brown markings on the wings, and barred undertail coverts.
Short-billed_Gull, First-winter birds start to acquire pale gray back feathers, but are otherwise tan with white fringing. Note small bicolored bill.
Short-billed_Gull, Juveniles are pale brown with white feather edging. Note dark barring on the undertail coverts.
Short-billed_Gull, Nonbreeding adults in flight show large white spots on the primaries.
Short-billed_Gull, First-winter birds have dark flight feathers, a pale rump, and brown tail feathers with lighter brown tips.
Short-billed_Gull, Breeds in marine and freshwater environments including tundra, marshy areas, ponds, lakes, rivers, and streams. Frequently gathers along streams, lakeshores, and coastal mudflats.
Short-eared_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a rounded head and tiny ear tufts that are difficult to see. Heavily streaked overall with dark eye patches and whitish face.
Short-eared_Owl, In flight look for barred wing tips. Hunts during daylight, flying low over short vegetation with a mothlike quality.
Short-eared_Owl, Perches in the open and flies low over open areas with deep and somewhat mothlike wingbeats. This video has no audio.
Short-eared_Owl, Immature is similar to adult, but head and upperparts are darker.
Short-eared_Owl, Widespread owl with variation in plumage color. Heavily streaked and sometimes spotted looking overall with dark eye patches and a whitish face.
Short-eared_Owl, The "South American" subspecies group is widespread in southern South America, with scattered populations in the northern half of the continent.
Short-eared_Owl, An open-country species that is active both day and night, making it more conspicuous than most owl species.
Short-eared_Owl, This species has colonized two of the world's most remote island archipelagos—the Galapagos and the Hawaiian Islands.
Short-eared_Owl, The "Antillean" subspecies group is typically restricted to Cuba, Puerto Rico, and Hispaniola, but individuals occasionally stray to southern Florida.
Short-eared_Owl, Ear tufts are small and difficult to see. Heavily streaked overall with black eye patches, yellow eyes, and a whitish face.
Short-tailed_Hawk, Fairly small hawk with broad wings and long secondaries giving curve to trailing edge of wing. Light morph has neat white underparts including throat and narrow bands in tail.

Short-tailed_Hawk, Dark morph has dark brown-black body and wing coverts. Flight feathers are barred white creating a checkered pattern. Tail has narrow white bands. In Florida, dark morphs individuals are more common than light morph.

Short-tailed_Hawk, Soars high up before diving on perched birds. Note broad, slightly raised wings (can resemble Turkey Vulture flight). Dark morph (more common in Florida) shows white barring/checkering in the flight feathers even at distance.

Short-tailed_Hawk, Fairly small hawk with contrast between dark brown upperparts and clean white underparts, including throat. At close range can show faint brown markings on the sides of the breast. Note narrow bands on tail, darkest at tip.
Short-tailed_Hawk, Fairly small hawk with dark brown upperparts, brown markings on sides of breast, and clean white underparts.
Short-tailed_Hawk, When perched, dark morph appears entirely sooty brown-black.
Short-tailed_Hawk, Fairly small hawk with broad wings and long, "bulging" secondaries. Juvenile dark morph is dark brown but strongly spotted or streaked with white.
Short-tailed_Hawk, Juvenile light morph is buffy white below and often shows buffy streaks on the cheek.
Short-tailed_Hawk, Juvenile light morphs are buffy white below, though the amount of buff is variable. Note buffy feathering on face, unlike adult. Short-tailed Hawks specialize in hunting birds.

Slaty-backed_Gull, A large, stocky, pot-bellied gull with short pink legs, short wings, and a hefty bill. Breeding adult has a white head and underparts, dark gray upperparts, and a yellow bill with a red spot.

Slaty-backed_Gull, Nonbreeding adult has a heavily streaked head and upper breast. In flight, adult shows an all-white tail, a broad white trailing edge on the inner wings, and a diagnostic "string of pearls" pattern near the wingtips: small white arcs separating the dark gray feathers from black wingtips.

Slaty-backed_Gull, A large, full-bodied gull with pink legs in all plumages. Nonbreeding adult has dark gray upperparts, a broad white tertial crescent in front of the black-and-white wingtips, a yellow bill with red mark, and a heavily streaked head with a darker patch around the eye.

Slaty-backed_Gull, Slaty-backed Gulls take four years to transition to full adult plumage. First year birds are quite variable, but note the short pink legs, thick black bill, dark mask around the eye, and brown wingtips and tail.
Slaty-backed_Gull, First-winter birds can look pale and bleached.
Slaty-backed_Gull, An opportunistic, omnivorous feeder, with some individuals specializing in plundering seabird colonies.
Slaty-backed_Gull, Early second-year birds have a slaty mantle contrasting with brown-and-white wing coverts. Second-year birds develop a pinkish base to the bill.
Slaty-backed_Gull, This species is largely restricted to the coast of northeastern Asia, but nonbreeding and wintering birds regularly occur in western Alaska.

Slaty-backed_Gull, In flight, note the strikingly patterned underwing, with white wing linings, mostly gray flight feathers, broad white trailing edge to inner wing, and black wingtips with white spots.

Slaty-backed_Gull, Third-year birds are similar to adults, but have some brown on the wings and some black markings on a horn-colored bill. Note the wide white crescents on the back and in front of the black-and-white wingtips.

Slaty-backed_Gull, In flight, third-year individuals are similar to adults, but note the broad black tail band and brown blotches in the wings. The adult "string of pearls" pattern in the outer flight feathers is often less conspicuous in third-year birds.
Smiths_Longspur, Medium-sized and sparrowlike with a thin bill. Breeding males have an unstreaked orangish belly and a patterned black-and-white face. Note white outer tail feathers.
Smiths_Longspur, Nonbreeding birds are buffy below with fine streaking down the belly.
Smiths_Longspur, A small, somewhat plump songbird with a short, notched tail, and a pointed, conical bill. Breeding male is mostly rich caramel with bold black-and-white stripes on the face.
Smiths_Longspur, Breeding females have a heavily streaked back often flecked with white. The face is rather plain with a white eyering and thin bill.
Smiths_Longspur, Nonbreeding birds have two thin white wingbars, though the wingbars are not always visible. Note buffy underparts with fine streaky.
Smiths_Longspur, Nonbreeding adult and immature have fine brown streaks on buffy underparts and often show a thin white eyering. The tail is black with white outer tail feathers.
Smiths_Longspur, Breeding males are mostly rich caramel with bold black-and-white stripes on the face. The back and wings are streaked brown and buff, with a white mark at the shoulder.
Smiths_Longspur, Chunky sparrowlike bird that is buffy overall with a heavily streaked back and finely streaked belly.
Smiths_Longspur, In flight, note white upper wing patch.
Smiths_Longspur, Nests where the boreal forest gives way to scattered dwarf trees and shrubs amid open tundra.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large and bulky with a long tail and parrotlike bill. Entirely black. The bill is arched with a prominent ridge or bump on the top, but otherwise lacks grooves.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Juveniles look like adults, but do not have the ridge or bump on the upper bill.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large and bulky with a long tail and parrotlike bill. Entirely black. The bill is arched with a prominent ridge or bump on the top, but otherwise lacks grooves.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large and bulky with a long tail and parrotlike bill. Entirely black. The bill is arched with a prominent ridge or bump on the top, but otherwise lacks grooves.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large all black bird with a long tail and hefty bill. Note parrotlike humped bill. Often found in pairs or small groups.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large and bulky with a long tail and parrotlike bill. Entirely black. The bill is arched with a prominent ridge or bump on the top, but otherwise lacks grooves.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Found in open areas with brush or scrub including fields, plantations, gardens, and forest clearings.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Often found in groups and nests in communal groups.
Smooth-billed_Ani, Large and bulky with a long tail and parrotlike bill. Entirely black. The bill is arched with a prominent ridge or bump on the top, but otherwise lacks grooves.
Snail_Kite, In flight note broad wings and triangular-shaped tail with a dark band on a white tail. Adult males have reddish orange legs and a thin hooked reddish orange bill with a black tip.
Snail_Kite, In flight note broad wings and triangular-shaped tail with a dark band on a white tail. Adult males have reddish orange legs and a thin hooked reddish orange bill with a black tip.
Snail_Kite, Found in marshes and other bodies of water with marsh edge where it forages for apple snails. This video has no audio.
Snail_Kite, Dark gray above and below with white under tail coverts. Bill and legs are reddish orange.
Snail_Kite, Females are brown above with streaking below. Most females have a white eyebrow. Note thin, curved bill.
Snail_Kite, Females are brown overall with a distinctive white eyebrow. This video has no audio.
Snail_Kite, Juveniles are dark brown above with a buffy face and dark streaking on a buffy belly. Note entirely dark bill and yellow legs.
Snail_Kite, In flight note broad wings and triangular-shaped tail with a dark band on a white tail. Adult males have reddish orange legs and a thin hooked reddish orange bill with a black tip.
Snail_Kite, Flies with slow and somewhat floppy wingbeats. Note broad wings and white upper tail.
Snail_Kite, In flight note broad wings and triangular-shaped tail with a dark band on a white tail. Adult males have reddish orange legs and a thin hooked reddish orange bill with a black tip.
Snail_Kite, Typical habitat includes freshwater marshes, edges of shallow lakes, and other flat-water courses with marsh edge.
Snow_Bunting, Chunky ground-dwelling bird with a short conical bill. Breeding males are mostly white with a black back.
Snow_Bunting, Medium-sized full-bodied songbird with a small conical bill. Breeding females have a dark and streaky back with a dusky head and white underparts.
Snow_Bunting, Males sing a low, husky warble on the breeding grounds.
Snow_Bunting, Small-billed sparrowlike bird. Nonbreeding males are white below with rusty patches on the head, "ear," and shoulders. Its back is dark and streaky.
Snow_Bunting, Sparrowlike bird with a small conical bill. Nonbreeding females have rusty patches on the head, "ear," and chest. The back is dark with rusty streaks.
Snow_Bunting, Forages for seeds, picking them from vegetation or from the ground.
Snow_Bunting, Juveniles are grayish overall with darker wings and a paler belly.
Snow_Bunting, Distinctive plumage pattern in flight. On males the outer wings are dark while the inner wings are white. The outer tail feathers also flash white in flight.
Snow_Bunting, Breeds in the high arctic in rocky areas.
Snow_Bunting, Forms flocks with other Snow Buntings during winter where they tend to blend in with their surroundings. Forages in fields or along lake shores.
Snow_Bunting, Breeds in rocky areas in the tundra. Nests on the ground in rock crevices.
Snow_Bunting, Tends to crouch low to the ground, blending in with the background.
Snow_Bunting, Chunky ground-dwelling bird with a short conical bill. Breeding males are mostly white with a black back.
Snow_Goose, All white plumage with black wingtips visible at rest. The pink bill shows a curved base and a prominent black grin patch.
Snow_Goose, Blue morph is the same shape and size as the white morph, with a variably dark body and a white head. Note the curved bill base and the black grin patch on the pink bill.
Snow_Goose, Forages in wide-open spaces, such as cultivated fields and shallow wetlands during the nonbreeding season.

Snow_Goose, Dark-plumaged birds are quite variable and may show a white belly contrasting with dark body plumage. The orange color on the head is from iron oxides that stain white plumage while foraging.

Snow_Goose, In flight, all white with black primaries. Distinguishing Snow and Ross's geese in flight is difficult but can be attempted with direct comparisons or good views of the head and bill structure—longer in Snow, more compact in Ross's.
Snow_Goose, Snow Geese typically give numerous nasal honks in flight. Their black wingtips are highly visible in flight even at a distance.
Snow_Goose, White with dusky gray-brown on head, neck, and wings. Bill and legs are dusky pink. The large black grin patch on the bill is a useful character.
Snow_Goose, Entirely dark sooty gray at rest; long bill structure with an arched grin patch is identical to the pattern shown by paler Snow Geese.
Snow_Goose, Snow Geese often form massive flocks during the nonbreeding season, and often make mass exoduses.

Snow_Goose, White and blue morphs commonly flock together, but white almost always outnumber blue. Note the white armpits of the blue morph adult here—this contrast helps to distinguish this color variant from other species of dark geese which have dark underwings.
Snow_Goose, Shorter-necked and more compact at rest than Canada Goose. This dark morph adult shows a mostly dark body with white head and a large pale upperwing patch.
Snow_Goose, This flock in the Midwest contains both white and blue morph individuals. Blue morphs tend to be more common in the Midwest and along the Gulf Coast.
Snow_Goose, Often forages in large flocks during migration and winter. White and blue morphs flock together and interbreed freely, though white morphs are more common.
Snow_Goose, Frequently occurs in shimmering flocks of hundreds of thousands during migration and winter.
Snowy_Egret, Medium-sized snow white heron with a black bill and yellow feet.
Snowy_Egret, Immature birds look similar to adults, but have dull yellowish green legs.

Snowy_Egret, Often eats insects attracted to washed up beach debris. While foraging, sometimes they vibrate their bills, sway their heads, or flick their wings. This video has no audio and was filmed in slow motion.
Snowy_Egret, Adult's yellow feet are visible as legs extend beyond tail in flight.
Snowy_Egret, During the breeding season, adult Snowy Egrets develop long, wispy feathers on their backs, necks, and heads.

Snowy_Egret, Stalks, walks, or runs after fish, frogs, and aquatic invertebrates. Often uses its bright yellow feet to stir up the water or probe in the mud, rounding up prey before striking with its bill.
Snowy_Egret, Medium-sized heron with a long neck and daggerlike bill. Entirely white with a yellow patch of skin in front of the eye.
Snowy_Egret, Snowy Egrets are smaller than Great Egrets and have a black (not yellow) bill and yellow (not black) feet.
Snowy_Egret, Found in mudflats, beaches, and wetlands, but also forages in wet agricultural fields and along the edges of rivers and lakes.
Snowy_Owl, Large white owl with piercing yellow eyes. Adult males range from pure white to white with a few brown spots.
Snowy_Owl, Females/immatures are white with darker barring throughout except on the face, which is always white.
Snowy_Owl, Nests on arctic tundra, often on a slight rise where wind keeps the ground free of snow. In good lemming years, Snowy Owls may raise 10 or more chicks per nest.
Snowy_Owl, Immature females have extensive dark barring throughout and a white face.
Snowy_Owl, Large, hefty owl. In flight note all-white underwings and broad wings.
Snowy_Owl, Winters in treeless areas including shorelines, where prey includes ducks and other waterfowl taken from the water.
Snowy_Owl, Immature females are barred throughout, but note white underwings in flight.
Snowy_Owl, Some adult males are entirely white.
Snowy_Owl, Like other owls, Snowy Owls swallow their prey whole and then regurgitate pellets containing the indigestible parts, such as bones and fur or feathers.
Snowy_Owl, During the winter in some years Snowy Owls show up farther south than normal, to hunt in fields, dunes, and other open areas.
Snowy_Owl, Often found sitting on or near the ground in wide-open areas or perching on rises such as the crests of dunes, fenceposts, telephone poles, or hay bales.
Snowy_Owl, Often perches on the ground, usually in raised areas with a view of the surroundings.

Snowy_Plover, Small shorebird with a horizontal posture and a short neck. Breeding adults have a black crown stripe, a dark ear patch, and a black patch on the side of the neck. Pale sandy gray above and white below. Bill is black in all seasons.
Snowy_Plover, Nonbreeding birds lack the dark crown stripe and have a paler neck stripe. Sandy gray above and white below with a black bill and gray legs.
Snowy_Plover, Rests and forages on the higher parts of the beach with loose sand. Often hunkers down in depressions in the sand to rest.
Snowy_Plover, Small shorebird with a horizontal posture and a short, black bill. The facial marks on nonbreeding birds are paler. Note gray legs.
Snowy_Plover, Some breeding birds show a darker ear patch in addition to the black crown and neck stripe. The bill is dark in all seasons.

Snowy_Plover, Small shorebird with a horizontal posture and a short neck. Breeding adults have a black crown stripe, a dark ear patch, and a black patch on the side of the neck. Pale sandy gray above and white below. Bill is black in all seasons.

Snowy_Plover, Small shorebird with a horizontal posture and a short neck. Breeding adults have a black crown stripe, a dark ear patch, and a black patch on the side of the neck. Pale sandy gray above and white below. Bill is black in all seasons.
Solitary_Sandpiper, Medium-sized slender shorebird with a prominent eyering. Small white spots mark the back.
Solitary_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a prominent white eyering. Nonbreeding birds look similar to breeding birds, but have smaller spots on the back.
Solitary_Sandpiper, Forages along edges of shallow wetlands, muddy fields, and small ponds. Note neat spots on back and strong white eyering.
Solitary_Sandpiper, In flight note dark stripe down the center of the tail and barred outer tail feathers. Also note dark underwings (not visible in photo).
Solitary_Sandpiper, Generally found alone or in small numbers on freshwater ponds and flooded fields. Note prominent eyering and white spotting on back.
Solitary_Sandpiper, Nods head while walking. Note complete white eyering.
Solitary_Sandpiper, When lands often holds its wings straight up before slowly bringing them back down.

Solitary_Sandpiper, During migration and winter found along freshwater ponds, stream edges, temporary pools, flooded ditches, and fields, more commonly in wooded regions, less frequently on mudflats and open marshes.

Song_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with rounded head and long, rounded tail. Coarse streaks on breast converge into a central spot. Russet stripes on crown and through eye. Broad malar or mustache stripe.
Song_Sparrow, Song Sparrows in the southwestern U.S. and northwestern Mexico have rusty streaking and are small and pale.
Song_Sparrow, Songs vary regionally but usually begin with a few loud well-spaced chip notes followed by trills or buzzes.
Song_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with rounded head and long tail. Face is grayish with russet stripes on crown and through eye. Heavy streaks on breast.
Song_Sparrow, Song Sparrows from the Aleutian Islands are larger than other forms, with grayish bodies and heavy dark brown streaking.
Song_Sparrow, Songs vary regionally but usually begin with a few loud well-spaced chip notes followed by trills or buzzes.
Song_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with rounded head and long tail. Individuals on the California coast are darker and grayer overall, with heavy streaking.
Song_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with long, rounded tail. Many individuals in the Pacific Northwest are dark brown and gray with heavy streaking on breast.
Song_Sparrow, Sometimes forages on the ground by hopping forward and scratching the leaf litter with both feet to uncover insects.
Song_Sparrow, Song Sparrows vary across North America. They typically have grayish faces and reddish brown markings that can be warm in color. Note thick, triangular mustache or malar stripe.
Song_Sparrow, Juvenile is generally drabber and buffier than adult, with less distinct stripes on the head.
Song_Sparrow, Diet consists mostly of insects during the summer, and switches to mostly seeds and fruits in the winter.
Song_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with long tail without a notch. Back is grayish streaked with brown; wings and tail are russet brown.
Song_Sparrow, One of the most widespread and common sparrows in North America. Found in brushy edges, often but not always near water.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse. Males expose bare yellow throat patches during courtship displays.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a small head and long tail. Females are speckled in brown and black with a dark tail.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse. Males expose bare yellow throat patches during courtship displays.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a small head. Juveniles look like females.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse. Males expose bare yellow throat patches during courtship displays.
Sooty_Grouse, Individuals in the Sierra Nevada of California are paler gray overall than individuals elsewhere.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse. Males expose bare yellow throat patches during courtship displays.
Sooty_Grouse, Chickenlike bird with a long, dark tail tipped in light gray. Plumage is darker overall than Dusky Grouse. Males expose bare yellow throat patches during courtship displays.
Sooty_Shearwater, Relatively large, all-dark shearwater with silvery flashes under the wing. Note narrow wings, short tail, and slender, strongly hooked, tubenosed bill.
Sooty_Shearwater, Relatively large, all-dark shearwater with straight, narrow wings, heavy body, and small head.
Sooty_Shearwater, Often flies low to the water with stiff wingbeats interspersed with long glides.

Sooty_Shearwater, Relatively large, all-dark shearwater with silvery flashes under the wing. Note slender, sharply hooked, tubenosed bill. Typically seen on the open ocean; only occasionally from shore.
Sooty_Shearwater, Relatively large, all-dark shearwater with small, rounded head.

Sooty_Shearwater, Sometimes occurs in immense flocks such as in fall along the California coast. Breeds in the Southern Hemisphere and travels into most of the world's oceans on long annual migrations.

Sora, Small secretive bird of freshwater marshes. The short tail is often held up showing white underneath. The face is gray with a black mask and a thick and stubby yellow bill, reminiscent of candy corn.
Sora, Small rail of shallow freshwater wetlands with dense emergent vegetation. Uses brackish marshes during migration. Note stubby yellow, bill, black mask, and gray cheek.
Sora, A small chickenlike marshbird with a stubby bill. Frequently holds short tail cocked up.
Sora, Juveniles are pale below and brown above with a buffy face. Found in shallow wetlands with a lot of emergent vegetation.
Sora, Walks through shallow wetlands with a jerking motion flicking and raising its tail.
Sora, In flight, note relatively long wings with a pale trailing edge.

Spectacled_Eider, Spectacular large duck of Alaska and Russia. Males have large, sloping orange bill, white back and black underparts. Distinctive face pattern of white "spectacles" outlined in black, with greenish back of the head.
Spectacled_Eider, Large duck with long, sloping bill and forehead. Females are brown, barred with darker brown, paler on the face with hint of male's "spectacle" pattern.
Spectacled_Eider, Large duck with sloping forehead and bill. Males have green wash on back of head, bright white spectacles, dark forehead, and orange bill.
Spectacled_Eider, Large duck with white patches over the eye and orange bill. In flight, note white back and wing coverts, black flight feathers and underparts with white flank patch.
Spectacled_Eider, Large duck with sloping bill and forehead. Females are densely barred with dark brown. Note brown forehead and paler face hinting at male's "spectacled" pattern.

Spectacled_Eider, Large ducks with sloping bill and forehead. Males are strongly patterned with orange bill, white spectacles, greenish back of head, and white-and-black body. Females are barred brown with black bill and pale brown "spectacles."
Spectacled_Eider, Males are distinctive with orange bill, white "spectacles" on dark head, and white-and-black body. For females, look for dark forehead with pale echo of male's spectacle pattern.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Large and long-bodied songbird with a sharply pointed bill. Adults are black and orange overall, with black spotting on the breast and white edged wing feathers.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Juveniles have a yellow-orange head and underparts, with a dark back, wings, and tail.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Large oriole with black spotting on the breast.

Spot-breasted_Oriole, A native of southern Mexico and Central America, the Spot-breasted Oriole was introduced into the Miami area of southern Florida in the late 1940s. Note black spotting on breast.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Large and long-bodied songbird with a sharply pointed bill. Adults are black and orange overall, with black spotting on the breast and white edged wing feathers.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Found in suburban neighborhoods in Florida. Juveniles are yellow-orange with a dark back, wings, and tail.
Spot-breasted_Oriole, Large and long-bodied songbird with a sharply pointed bill. Adults are black and orange overall, with black spotting on the breast and white edged wing feathers.
Spotted_Owl, Round head lacks ear tufts. Mexican Spotted Owls are the palest and they have more white on the face with larger white spots on the breast and back.
Spotted_Owl, Medium-sized hefty-looking brown owl with white spots on the head, back, and breast.
Spotted_Owl, Sits quietly during the day in trees concealed by vegetation. This video has no audio.
Spotted_Owl, Medium-sized owl with a round head (no ear tufts). Brown overall with white spots on the head, back, and breast.
Spotted_Owl, Juveniles retain some downy feathers and look fluffy overall with some spotting on the breast.
Spotted_Owl, Rests during the day and hunts small mammals at night. This video has no audio.
Spotted_Owl, Primarily uses old-growth forests, but also uses oak stands in California, and pine-oak forests in Mexico. Juveniles look fluffy.
Spotted_Owl, A large owl with a round head and a spotted belly. This video has no audio.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird with a unique bobbing behavior. Breeding adults have dark spots on the belly and an orangish bill.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Often walks in a crouched position. Nonbreeding birds are brownish above with a bit of brown on the breast. Note yellow legs.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Bobs tail up and down nearly constantly while it walks. Gradually loses the spots on its breast and belly as it molts out of breeding plumage.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Flies with stuttering wingbeats (quick, snappy wingbeats interspersed with glides).
Spotted_Sandpiper, Medium-sized shorebird. Breeding birds have a heavily spotted breast and an orangish bill.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding birds and juveniles lack the spotted breast. Brownish above with a brown wash on the breast and a white belly. Often crouches low and bobs its tail up and down.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Most often found on the ground, but sometimes perches on trees or posts, while taking care of young.
Spotted_Sandpiper, Found almost anywhere near water, and often inland along streambanks, rivers, ponds, lakes, and beaches, particularly on rocky shores.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Males have a black head, throat, and upperparts, with a white belly and rufous sides. The back and wings are spotted white.
Spotted_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow. Females along the Pacific Coast are dull blackish on the head, throat, and upperparts, with white spots on the wings and back.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Males have a black head, throat, and upperparts, with a white belly and rufous sides. The back and wings are spotted white.
Spotted_Towhee, Some populations in Mexico have olive-green on the back.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with thick bill. Juveniles are heavily streaked and brownish.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Males have a black head, throat, and upperparts, with a white belly and rufous sides. The back and wings are spotted white.
Spotted_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow of brushy areas, often found on or near the ground. Note prominent white flashes in the tail in flight.
Spotted_Towhee, Large, long-tailed sparrow. Females along the Pacific Coast are dull blackish on the head, throat, and upperparts, with white spots on the wings and back.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Males have a black head, throat, and upperparts, with a white belly and rufous sides. The back and wings are spotted white.
Spotted_Towhee, Lives in dense shrubby habitats. Scratches in leaf litter to forage, but males often perch in the open to call or sing.
Spotted_Towhee, Large sparrow with a thick bill and a long tail. Males have a black head, throat, and upperparts, with a white belly and rufous sides. The back and wings are spotted white.
Spragues_Pipit, Breeds in short grass native prairies. Has a plain faced and big-eyed look.
Spragues_Pipit, Breeds in short grass native prairies. Has a plain faced and big-eyed look.
Spragues_Pipit, Medium-sized grassland bird with a small head. The plain face and white eyering give it a big-eyed look. Note unstreaked flanks.
Spragues_Pipit, Slender grassland bird with a small head. Heavily streaked and scaly-looking above with a plain face.
Spragues_Pipit, Performs flight displays on the breeding grounds. White outer tail feathers visible in flight most of the time.
Spragues_Pipit, Breeds in short grass native prairies. Has a plain faced and big-eyed look.
Spragues_Pipit, Breeds in short grass native prairies. Has a plain faced and big-eyed look.
Spragues_Pipit, Breeds in short grass native prairies. Has a plain faced and big-eyed look.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.
Spruce_Grouse, The Franklin's subspecies of Spruce Grouse in Montana, Idaho, Washington, and British Columbia have a darker black breast without white barring.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Male has a gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.
Spruce_Grouse, Plump bird of spruce forests. Females come in two color morphs, gray and chestnut. This female has chestnut mottling throughout with strong horizontal barring on the underparts.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.
Spruce_Grouse, "Bathes" in dust, especially when molting body feathers.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.

Spruce_Grouse, Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly. The tail is either dark or tipped in chestnut depending on location. This individual from Maine has chestnut tips.
Spruce_Grouse, Eats primarily pine and spruce needles in the canopy, but also forages on the ground for insects, fresh growth on shrubs, and berries.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.
Spruce_Grouse, Feeds primarily on needles from spruce and pines, but when not eating needles they forage on the ground, eating fresh growth from shrubs and understory plants.
Spruce_Grouse, Medium-sized chickenlike bird. Males have a slate gray head and neck, a red eyebrow, a black chest, and white spots on lower belly.

Squirrel_Cuckoo, A large cuckoo with a long, tapering tail with prominent white spots. Upperparts are rusty orange, the throat is a lighter cinnamon, and the belly is a soft gray. The bill is greenish-yellow, and the bright red eye is surrounded by a yellow or red eyering.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, "Amazonian" Squirrel Cuckoo occurs in forests and wooded areas across much of South America.

Squirrel_Cuckoo, A large cuckoo with a long, fanlike tail. Rusty upperparts give way to a cinnamon head and throat and light gray breast. Adult's red eye has a yellow or red eyering (depending on location).
Squirrel_Cuckoo, "West Mexico" Squirrel Cuckoo, sometimes considered a separate species, has rusty undertail feathers (as opposed to black in other subspecies groups).
Squirrel_Cuckoo, The long, graduated tail can be up to 28 cm (11 inches) long—more than half the bird's total length.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Moves rapidly along branches high up in trees. Gives an abrupt, ratcheting call (heard at end of video) in flight.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Forages for insects in the midstory and canopy of forests and woodlands.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Occurs in dry and humid forests, from sea level to over 2,000 m (6,600 feet).
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Feeds on caterpillars and other insects.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, The widespread "Middle America" Squirrel Cuckoo ranges from eastern Mexico to northwestern Colombia.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Hops rapidly along branches like a squirrel.
Squirrel_Cuckoo, Often concealed in midstory or canopy vegetation, but occasionally glides across clearings and perches out in the open.
Stellers_Eider, Despite differences in color, both sexes have blocky head with flat crown and thick gray bill.
Stellers_Eider, Mostly white head with large black eye, black collar around neck, and creamy-buff belly with black spot on side.
Stellers_Eider, Males have a mostly white head, black back, and creamy-buff belly. Females are dark brown with a pale eyering and a heavy gray bill.
Stellers_Eider, Breeds in shallow tundra wetlands. Male has mostly white head with large black eye. Black back shows white stripes at rest; black rear.
Stellers_Eider, Male in flight has extensively white forewing. Female has blue-black secondaries bordered in white and white underwings.
Stellers_Jay, Hefty, crested bird with an attitude. They are half charcoal black and half blue. Adults along the Pacific Coast have blue streaks on their black crest.

Stellers_Jay, Bold, inquisitive, and noisy bird of western evergreen forests. Its black crest and blue lower body separate it from similar jays. Birds in the interior have white streaks on their crest.
Stellers_Jay, Hefty, crested bird with an attitude. They are half charcoal black and half blue. Adults along the Pacific Coast have blue streaks on their black crest.

Stellers_Jay, Plumage color of residents in Middle America varies, but most are bluer overall. Residents in Chiapas, Mexico south to Guatemala for example, have brighter blue bodies and shorter blue crests.
Stellers_Jay, Juveniles look similar to adults but have a smaller crest and are often paler gray.
Stellers_Jay, Hefty, crested bird with an attitude. They are half charcoal black and half blue. Adults along the Pacific Coast have blue streaks on their black crest.
Stellers_Jay, Steller's Jays often push their crest feathers up during courtship and aggressive interactions.
Stellers_Jay, Often forages on the ground, hopping around looking to eat almost anything that will fit in its mouth.
Stellers_Jay, Hefty, crested bird with an attitude. They are half charcoal black and half blue. Adults along the Pacific Coast have blue streaks on their black crest.
Stellers_Jay, Very vocal bird that makes growls, creaks, rattles, and squawks of all kinds.
Stellers_Jay, Found in evergreen and mixed-evergreen forests in the western U.S., as well as parks, campgrounds, backyards, and pine-oak woodlands in the Southwest.
Stellers_Jay, Hefty, crested bird with an attitude. They are half charcoal black and half blue. Adults along the Pacific Coast have blue streaks on their black crest.

Stilt_Sandpiper, Medium-sized sandpiper with long greenish legs and a long, slightly curved bill. During the breeding season, underparts are heavily barred, the back has dark blotches, and the cheeks are chestnut.
Stilt_Sandpiper, Nonbreeding Stilt Sandpipers are grayer overall than breeding birds. Note prominent white eyebrow, long yellow legs, and dark slightly drooping bill.
Stilt_Sandpiper, Breeds in sedge marshes of the arctic tundra. On migration and in winter found along mudflats, flooded fields, shallow ponds and pools, and marshes.
Stilt_Sandpiper, Juveniles have long yellow-green legs and a scaly look to their backs. The underparts are whitish with brownish streaking on the chest. Often wades in water up to its belly.
Stilt_Sandpiper, In flight, their long legs trail behind and their white rump patch is visible.
Stilt_Sandpiper, Long-legged shorebird with a long slightly drooping bill. Breeding birds have heavily barred underparts.

Stilt_Sandpiper, Medium-sized sandpiper with long greenish legs and a long, slightly curved bill. During the breeding season, underparts are heavily barred, the back has dark blotches, and the cheeks are chestnut.
Stilt_Sandpiper, Smaller than Lesser Yellowlegs (behind and to left) with a longer, slightly drooping bill.

Stilt_Sandpiper, Medium-sized sandpiper with long greenish legs and a long, slightly curved bill. During the breeding season, underparts are heavily barred, the back has dark blotches, and the cheeks are chestnut.

Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, A large flycatcher with bold black and white stripes on the face, a white throat, light yellow underparts with blackish streaks, a rufous tail, and a heavy bill with a hooked tip.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Upperparts are a mix of pale yellow and charcoal. Wing feathers have extensive white markings. Rufous tail feathers have dark shafts.

Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, A large flycatcher with a large head, heavy bill, striped face, rufous tail, and streaky yellowish underparts. Easily identified (and often located) by its distinctive "squeaky toy" call, given mainly during the breeding season.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Often perches in canopy foliage for extended periods before taking flight to pursue insects.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Note black mask through eye, whitish stripes above and below eye, and blackish malar stripes meeting on the chin.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Often occurs in pairs during the breeding season and in small family groups at other times.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Nests in tree cavities, with sycamores often used in southeastern Arizona.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Found in woodlands and forests ranging from thorn scrub and dry forest to rainforest, but generally not found in the interior of extensive forest.
Sulphur-bellied_Flycatcher, Typically remains high in trees, making short flights in pursuit of flying insects.
Summer_Tanager, Full-bodied songbird with a big head and a thick blunt-tipped bill. Adult males are brilliant red overall.
Summer_Tanager, Medium-sized songbird. Females are yellowish overall with a pinkish or horn-colored bill.
Summer_Tanager, Full-bodied songbird with a big head and a thick blunt-tipped bill. Adult males are brilliant red overall.
Summer_Tanager, Immature males are splotchy yellow and red. The amount of red depends on age as they molt into the red plumage of adults.
Summer_Tanager, Hefty songbird with a slightly crested head (not always visible). Females are yellowish overall with a pale horn-colored bill.
Summer_Tanager, Full-bodied songbird with a big head and a thick blunt-tipped bill. Adult males are brilliant red overall.
Summer_Tanager, Chunky entirely red songbird often found in the canopy where it catches bees and wasps.
Summer_Tanager, Found in gaps and edges of open deciduous or pine-oak forests.
Summer_Tanager, Full-bodied songbird with a big head and a thick blunt-tipped bill. Adult males are brilliant red overall.
Summer_Tanager, Full-bodied songbird with a big head and a thick blunt-tipped bill. Adult males are brilliant red overall.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized dark-brown sea duck with a large, sloping black bill. Two white patches on the face: one behind bill and the other behind the eye.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized sea duck with all dark wings. Note large orange bill and white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized brownish sea duck with all dark wings. Note large, dark, sloping bill and two white patches on the face.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Brownish sea duck with dark head and large, sloping bill, becoming orange as the bird ages.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Brownish sea duck with large, dark, sloping bill. Cap is darker than face. Two white facial patches are visible from long distances.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Medium-sized, mostly black sea duck with a large, sloping orange bill. Note white patch on back of neck.
Surf_Scoter, Can form large flocks. Typically found fairly near shore in saltwater, sometimes diving under breaking waves.
Surfbird, Stocky shorebird with short legs and a stout bill. Breeding birds have a speckled belly. Note yellow legs.
Surfbird, Stocky shorebird with short legs and a stout bill. Nonbreeding birds are gray overall. Note yellow legs.
Surfbird, Forages along rocky intertidal zones for bivalves, mollusks, barnacles, and marine algae during the nonbreeding season.
Surfbird, In flight, note white tail with a black band and a thin white stripe down the wings.
Surfbird, Stocky shorebird or rocky coastlines. Note yellow legs and stout bill.
Surfbird, Stocky shorebird with short legs and a stout bill. Breeding birds have a speckled belly. Note yellow legs.
Surfbird, Breeding birds have cinnamon spots on the back.
Surfbird, Most often found foraging on rocky shorelines, but sometimes uses sandy beaches during migration.
Surfbird, Forages along rocky shorelines.

Swainsons_Hawk, Distinctively long-winged large hawk with pointed wingtips. Usually soars with wings slightly raised (dihedral). Light morph adults have dark flight feathers creating a broad, dark trailing edge to the wing. Also note the brown upper breast, creating a hooded appearance.
Swainsons_Hawk, Note the distinctive long-winged shape with pointed wingtips—especially pronounced when the bird is gliding with wingtips swept back, giving an M-shape to the wings.

Swainsons_Hawk, A large hawk of the open country of western North America. Most individuals have a light belly, dark or reddish-brown chest, and brown or gray upperparts. Most males have gray heads, while females tend to have brown heads.
Swainsons_Hawk, Dark-morph Swainson's Hawks can vary from reddish-brown to uniform dark brown, but they usually have a rufous tone to the underwing coverts and pale undertail coverts, as shown here.

Swainsons_Hawk, Dark-morph adults usually have a two-toned appearance from beneath created by paler underwing coverts and darker flight feathers, similar to but less pronounced than the pattern of light-morph adults. Note the long wings with somewhat pointed tips.
Swainsons_Hawk, Large hawk with long, relatively slender wings with pointed tips. Typically soars with wings slightly raised (known as "dihedral"), often teetering in the wind.
Swainsons_Hawk, Large hawk with long wings. Head and upper breast are brown, creating a hooded appearance. Tail has narrow dark bands, with a broader dark band at the tip.
Swainsons_Hawk, Breeding pairs are solitary, but otherwise this is a highly social species, forming foraging flocks of 100+ birds and migratory groups in the thousands.
Swainsons_Hawk, Large hawk of open country. Note brown head and breast, with unmarked white belly.
