Swainsons_Hawk, One of the world's most variable hawk species, with a complete continuum of plumages from light to dark.
Swainsons_Hawk, Often perches on fence posts and utility poles in wide-open spaces of western North America.
Swainsons_Hawk, Hunts in open country; eats mostly mammals such as ground squirrels on breeding grounds.
Swainsons_Hawk, Dark morph birds can range from reddish brown to fully dark brown, but usually have some rufous tones to the plumage. Note long wings.
Swainsons_Hawk, Dark-morph immatures can be quite variable in degree of darkness, but usually have some buffy streaking on the body and show pale undertail coverts.
Swainsons_Hawk, Light-morph immatures are mottled brown above, with pale edges to the wing coverts, and have variable dark streaking on the breast. The head is often pale from bleaching.
Swainsons_Hawk, Young Swainson's Hawks have pale edges to the upperwing coverts creating a scalloped appearance.
Swainsons_Hawk, Dark-morph juveniles are variable but usually show buffy streaking on the body and often have pale head from bleaching. Note the distinctive long-winged shape.

Swainsons_Hawk, Often has brown streaks on the chest but may also show brown upper breast and dark flight feathers, like an adult. Juveniles have a narrower, less distinct terminal tail band than adults.
Swainsons_Hawk, Breeds in open country with occasional trees, including grasslands, croplands, pastures, hayfields, and sage flats.
Swainsons_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a round head and a short, straight bill. Olive-brown above with a distinct buffy eyering. White underparts with brownish spotting on the throat and breast.
Swainsons_Thrush, Individuals breeding in the Pacific states (often called the "Russet-backed" Thrush) are rustier above, with thinner, paler eyerings and medium-brown chest spotting.
Swainsons_Thrush, Note strong buffy eyering and lores, creating "spectacled" look, as well as buffy wash on breast.
Swainsons_Thrush, Individuals breeding in the eastern and northern parts of North America (often called "Olive-backed Thrush") are more olive-brown above with darker spotting on the breast.
Swainsons_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a round head. Olive-brown above with a distinct buffy eyering and brownish spotting on the throat and breast.
Swainsons_Thrush, Song is a distinctive, fluting, upward-spiraling melody.
Swainsons_Thrush, Breeds primarily in evergreen forests except in California where it also uses deciduous forests near streams.
Swainsons_Warbler, Large warbler with a heavy, straight bill. Brownish overall with a rusty cap and black eyeline. Sexes alike.
Swainsons_Warbler, Sexes alike and no seasonal differences in plumage. Long and sharply pointed bill, rusty cap, and black eyeline are distinctive.
Swainsons_Warbler, Song is a series of loud, descending slurred whistles, ending in 4 or 5 jumbled notes. "So, so, so, so, sweet-to-hear."
Swainsons_Warbler, Somewhat stocky, primarily ground-dwelling warbler with a long, pale bill. Brownish overall with a rusty cap and black eyeline.
Swainsons_Warbler, Breeds in densely vegetated areas in the southern United States. From below, note unstreaked belly.
Swainsons_Warbler, Large warbler with a heavy, straight bill. Brownish overall with a rusty cap and black eyeline. Sexes alike.
Swainsons_Warbler, Sings from perches in the understory.
Swainsons_Warbler, Very secretive bird, best located by its ringing song.
Swainsons_Warbler, Large warbler with a heavy, straight bill. Brownish overall with a rusty cap and black eyeline. Sexes alike.
Swainsons_Warbler, Large warbler with a heavy, straight bill. Brownish overall with a rusty cap and black eyeline. Sexes alike.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Slender and buoyant raptor with narrow, pointed wings and a deeply forked tail.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, When perched, note long and slender look and long forked tail. The gleaming white head contrasts with its black back.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Small-bodied, long-winged raptor with very buoyant flight style. Often twists tail to adjust position as it flies.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Most often seen in flight soaring on thermals with little flapping. Captures and eats prey in flight.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, A crisp black-and-white raptor with a deeply forked tail that soars gracefully over swamps, marshes, large rivers, and savannas with tall trees.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Graceful black-and-white raptor with long, forked tail and elegant soaring style. Wingbeats are smooth and slow.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Juveniles look very similar to adults but have a slight buffy wash on their head and breast.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Roosts with other Swallow-tailed Kites in tall trees often near swamps or wetlands.
Swallow-tailed_Kite, Builds nests of small sticks high in trees in open woodlands or swamps.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail. Gray face and collar with a rusty cap and a dark line through the eye. Extensive reddish brown in wings. Base of bill is yellow.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail. Neat white throat contrasts with gray-washed breast. Extensive reddish brown in wings.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail. Gray face and collar with a rusty cap and a dark line through the eye. Extensive reddish brown in wings. Base of bill is yellow.
Swamp_Sparrow, Rusty cap and matching reddish brown wings. Neat white throat contrasts with gray face. Flanks are washed with brown.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail and extensive reddish brown in the wings. Breeding adult has a reddish crown patch and a gray face and back of the neck.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail. Gray face and collar with a rusty cap and a dark line through the eye. Extensive reddish brown in wings. Base of bill is yellow.
Swamp_Sparrow, Immature and nonbreeding birds have blurry streaks on the chest and have a plain brown, not reddish brown, cap. Note the neat white throat patch.
Swamp_Sparrow, Medium-sized sparrow with a rounded tail. Gray face and collar with a rusty cap and a dark line through the eye. Extensive reddish brown in wings. Base of bill is yellow.
Swamp_Sparrow, Occurs in wetlands with standing water, including freshwater marshes, beaver ponds, and saltmarshes.
Tamaulipas_Crow, A small, glossy crow with a purplish sheen to the upperparts.
Tamaulipas_Crow, Largely restricted to northeastern Mexico, but occurs on occasion in southern Texas, most famously at the Brownsville landfill.
Tamaulipas_Crow, A small crow with a glossy purplish sheen and a distinctive froglike call.
Tamaulipas_Crow, Calling birds give a low-pitched, nasal croaking sound, often repeated several times.
Tamaulipas_Crow, A social species, often seen foraging in pairs or small groups.
Tamaulipas_Crow, Forages on food scraps, carrion, insects, seeds and berries, and more.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding females are yellow-green above with a gray cap and pale eyebrow. The underside is whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.

Tennessee_Warbler, Nonbreeding/immature birds are yellow-green overall, showing little contrast between the head and the back. Note thin, pointy bill, lack of distinct wingbars, and white undertail coverts.
Tennessee_Warbler, Nonbreeding/immature birds are more yellow-green overall with a pale eyebrow and a yellow-washed underside. Note whiter undertail coverts compared to the breast color.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.
Tennessee_Warbler, Gleans insects from outer foliage of trees and shrubs. Note thin, pointy bill.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.

Tennessee_Warbler, Nonbreeding/immature birds are yellow-green overall, showing little contrast between the head and the back. Note thin, pointy bill, lack of distinct wingbars, and white undertail coverts.
Tennessee_Warbler, Breeds in the boreal forest with evergreen and deciduous trees. Uses all types of woodlands during migration.

Tennessee_Warbler, Small, short-tailed warbler with a thin, pointy bill. Breeding males are yellow-green above with a gray cap and a pale eyebrow. The underside is plain whitish, although some have yellow-washed undersides. Note lack of strong wingbars.

Thick-billed_Kingbird, A large flycatcher with a huge, slightly hooked bill. Head is dark gray, with a blackish mask through the eye. Dark head contrasts strongly with white throat and breast, which gives way to pale yellow below.
Thick-billed_Kingbird, Upperparts are gray to brown. Wings and tail are dark brown, with some feathers edged in cinnamon.

Thick-billed_Kingbird, A big kingbird with a deep, wide bill. Whitish throat contrasts strongly with dark gray head and blackish mask. Underparts pale yellow. Perches high in trees in search of flying insects that it catches on the wing.
Thick-billed_Kingbird, Feeds mostly on flying insects, but also eats some fruit.
Thick-billed_Kingbird, Commonly found atop high perches, which it uses to survey for insects and launch foraging flights.
Thick-billed_Kingbird, A noisy, conspicuous bird, often seen and heard calling from treetops.
Thick-billed_Kingbird, In main Mexican range, occurs in open areas within tropical dry forest, along streams and rivers within dry scrub habitats, and in thorn forest.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Chunky, sparrowlike grassland bird. Breeding males have a black breast, gray belly, chestnut wing patch, and a gray-and-white face.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Chunky grassland bird with a stout bill. Females have a stout pink bill and chestnut wing patches that can sometimes be difficult to see. Note unstreaked whitish belly.

Thick-billed_Longspur, Song is a soft tinkling warble. Males usually sing while flying, as part of an aerial display, but also sing while perched on an elevated surface such as a rock, fence, or shrub.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Male flutters upward and descends on outstretched wings and tail during aerial displays on the breeding grounds. The outstretched tail is white with a black T.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Forms flocks outside of the breeding season. Note black T on the tail and black band on the breast of the males.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Breeding males have a black breast band and crown and a chestnut wing patch.

Thick-billed_Longspur, Immatures have a chunky bill, a broad stripe over the eye, a smudgy brown band across the breast, and unstreaked white underparts. They don't have rufous in the wing like adults do.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Juveniles look heavily mottled overall with white fringed feathers. Note stout pink bill.
Thick-billed_Longspur, Slightly smaller than a Horned Lark with a stout pink bill. Note faint black breast band on this molting male.
Thick-billed_Murre, Large and stocky black-and-white seabird with a thick bill. Nonbreeding birds are dark above and white below with a white throat and lower face.
Thick-billed_Murre, Stocky seabird with a thick bill and short rounded tail. Nonbreeding birds have white on the throat and the lower part of the face.
Thick-billed_Murre, Dives from the surface while foraging for schooling fish such as cod and smelt. Also feeds on bottom-dwelling fish, squid, amphipods, and shrimp.
Thick-billed_Murre, Large and stocky black-and-white seabird with a thick bill. Nonbreeding birds are dark above and white below with a white throat and lower face.
Thick-billed_Murre, Stocky seabird that typically flies just above surface.
Thick-billed_Murre, Nests along coastal cliffs in colonies. Black above and white below with a thin white line extending from the base of the bill. Note silver wing linings on underwings.
Townsends_Solitaire, Medium-sized thrush with a long tail, a short bill, and a small rounded head. Gray overall with a prominent white eyering. Note buffy patches in the wing.
Townsends_Solitaire, Round-headed thrush with a long tail. Juveniles are dark gray overall and heavily spotted with buff and white, giving them a scaly look.
Townsends_Solitaire, Drinks water regularly by taking a small amount of water in its bill and tipping its head backwards.
Townsends_Solitaire, Medium-sized thrush with a round head and long tail. Gray overall with a white eyering. Note white outer tail feathers, more noticeable in flight.
Townsends_Solitaire, Buffy wing patches and white outer tail feathers are often prominent in flight.
Townsends_Solitaire, Often flicks its wings in a nervous fashion.
Townsends_Solitaire, Adults are gray overall with a white eyering.
Townsends_Solitaire, In the winter, moves south or to lower elevations to feed on juniper berries which they aggressively defend.
Townsends_Solitaire, Perches upright atop trees and shrubs to advertise their territories all year long. This video has no audio.
Townsends_Solitaire, Found in open pine, fir, and spruce forests in mountainous regions from about 1,100–11,500 feet elevation.
Townsends_Solitaire, Perches upright giving them a long and slender appearance.
Townsends_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent below the eye.
Townsends_Warbler, The black markings on females/immatures are paler and the throat is mostly yellow. Note dark ear patch surrounded by yellow and streaked sides.
Townsends_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent below the eye.
Townsends_Warbler, The black markings on immatures are paler and the throat is yellow. Note dark ear patch surrounded by yellow and streaked sides.
Townsends_Warbler, The black markings on immatures are paler and the throat is yellow. Note dark ear patch surrounded by yellow and streaked sides.
Townsends_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent below the eye.
Townsends_Warbler, Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent beneath the eye.
Townsends_Warbler, The black markings on adult females are paler and the throat is mostly yellow (some have dark mottling on the throat). Note dark ear patch surrounded by yellow and streaked sides.
Townsends_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent below the eye.
Townsends_Warbler, Breeds in tall evergreen and mixed evergreen-deciduous forests.
Townsends_Warbler, Small songbird. Adult males have a black ear patch surrounded by yellow. Note thick white wingbars, black cap and throat, and yellow crescent below the eye.

Tree_Swallow, Small streamlined songbird with a tiny bill, long, pointed wings and a short, squared or slightly notched tail. Adults are blue-green above and white below with blackish flight feathers.

Tree_Swallow, Small streamlined songbird with a tiny bill, long, pointed wings and a short, squared or slightly notched tail. Adults are blue-green above and white below with blackish flight feathers.
Tree_Swallow, Frequently nests in artificial nest boxes.

Tree_Swallow, In flight, note streamlined body, squared or slightly notched tail and broad wings. Adults are blue-green above with a black mask around their eye and tiny white crescents on the sides of their rump.

Tree_Swallow, Small streamlined songbird with a tiny bill, long, pointed wings and a short, squared or slightly notched tail. Adults are blue-green above and white below with blackish flight feathers.
Tree_Swallow, Adult's metallic blue head contrasts with gleaming white underparts.
Tree_Swallow, Immature female is mostly brown above, with just a trace of iridescent feathers.

Tree_Swallow, Small streamlined songbird with a tiny bill, long, pointed wings and a short, squared or slightly notched tail. Adults are blue-green above and white below with blackish flight feathers.
Tree_Swallow, The wings are broad and the tail is squared or slightly notched. Juveniles are brown above with a small white crescent on the sides of its rump.
Tree_Swallow, Adults are iridescent blue-green with a thin black mask around the eye.

Tree_Swallow, Small streamlined songbird with a tiny bill, long, pointed wings and a short, squared or slightly notched tail. Adults are blue-green above and white below with blackish flight feathers.
Tree_Swallow, Juvenile is brown above and white below. Note the yellow gape typical of the juveniles of many species.
Tree_Swallow, Juveniles are brown above and white below, but some juveniles and females can show a weak, blurry gray-brown breast band.
Tree_Swallow, Breeds in open habitats such as fields and wetlands, usually adjacent to water. Nests in artificial nest boxes as well as holes in trees.
Tree_Swallow, Forms large flocks during migration and when foraging over wetlands, water, and agricultural fields.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Broad-shouldered blackbird with a hunchbacked look and a long conical bill. Males have a distinctive red shoulder patch bordered below by a white band.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Thicker bodied songbird with a slender, pointed bill. Females are dark gray-brown overall with streaks on the back and belly. Note pale eyebrow.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Males often have brown fringing to the feathers from September to August.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Broad-shouldered blackbird with a hunchbacked look and a long conical bill. Males have a distinctive red shoulder patch bordered below by a white band.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Broad-shouldered blackbird with a hunchbacked look and a long conical bill. Males have a distinctive red shoulder patch bordered below by a white band.
Tricolored_Blackbird, Broad-shouldered blackbird with a hunchbacked look and a long conical bill. Males have a distinctive red shoulder patch bordered below by a white band.
Tricolored_Heron, Medium-sized delicate-looking and rather colorful heron. Adults are a mix of blue-gray, purple, and white. The white belly and stripe down the neck are distinctive.
Tricolored_Heron, Long-necked heron with a sharp bill. Juveniles have a reddish neck with spots of reddish feathers on their wings and upper back.
Tricolored_Heron, Builds messy stick nests in small trees and shrubs near fresh or saltwater.
Tricolored_Heron, Mostly dark except for its distinctive white belly and white wing linings. Flies with its neck tucked in and legs trailing behind.
Tricolored_Heron, Medium-sized slim heron with a long neck and bill. Breeding birds have small white plumes extending from the back of their head.
Tricolored_Heron, Forages alone or at the edge of groups of mixed wading birds. Slowly stalks fish or pirouettes with sharp stops and turns with wings flapping.
Tricolored_Heron, Forages for small fish by running, stalking, or crouching with its neck tucked in before stabbing prey with its bill.
Tricolored_Heron, Found in estuaries, salt marshes, lagoons, swamps, freshwater marshes, and lake edges.
Tropical_Kingbird, Large and big-headed flycatcher with a long, heavy bill. Bright yellow below with a whitish throat. The head is gray with a darker gray ear patch.
Tropical_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a long notched tail. The tail is entirely brown unlike Western and Cassin's Kingbird. Bright yellow below with a gray head and darker ear patch.
Tropical_Kingbird, Like other tyrant flycatchers, Tropical Kingbirds perch on lone branches or wires in open areas where they hunt flying insects.
Tropical_Kingbird, Large tropical flycatcher that often perches in the open. Bright yellow below with a notched tail.
Tropical_Kingbird, Vocal, big-headed flycatcher with a long notched tail. Yellow below with a whitish throat and a gray head. Note long bill.
Tropical_Kingbird, Mainly eats insects, but will forage opportunistically for fruits.
Tropical_Kingbird, Found in open country with scattered trees and shrubs.
Tropical_Parula, A small, colorful songbird with gray to bluish upperparts and yellow to orange underparts. Adult male has a black facial mask and dark orangeish band across the breast.
Tropical_Parula, Female has the same color pattern as male but is duller overall, lacking a black facial mask and orangeish breast band.

Tropical_Parula, A small warbler with blue-gray upperparts, an olive patch on the back, and yellow-orange underparts. Adult male has a black mask and an orangeish throat and upper breast. Birds in the "South American" subspecies group (and most other groups) have two white wingbars.
Tropical_Parula, Most subspecies groups, including the "Northeast Mexico" group that reaches southern Texas, have two white wingbars. Both sexes have an olive patch on the back.
Tropical_Parula, The "South American" subspecies group is lighter blue-gray above, less orange below, and has two white wingbars.
Tropical_Parula, Forages in the canopy or subcanopy, where it picks insects and other arthropods from foliage.
Tropical_Parula, The "Middle American" subspecies group has deep blue upperparts, a small olive patch on the back, extensive yellow underparts, and at most a single white wingbar.
Tropical_Parula, Typically found high in trees in forest or woodland.
Trumpeter_Swan, Very large and entirely white with a long neck, black bill with broad area of black facial skin in front of the eye, and black legs.
Trumpeter_Swan, Older juveniles are mostly pale dusky-gray with white highlights, and a pink center to the black bill.

Trumpeter_Swan, North America's largest native waterfowl species, with a heavy body and a long neck typically held straight both on the water and in flight. The large bill slopes gradually down from the forehead.
Trumpeter_Swan, Very large and entirely white with a long neck, black bill with broad area of black facial skin in front of the eye, and black legs.
Trumpeter_Swan, Flies with neck outstretched. Entirely white with black legs and bill.
Trumpeter_Swan, Feeds by tipping up and reaching for submerged vegetation with its long neck.
Trumpeter_Swan, Entirely black bill with broad connection of black facial skin to the eye. The white head can be stained rusty, especially during the nesting season.
Trumpeter_Swan, In typical posture, holds neck very straight.
Trumpeter_Swan, Often feeds in wet grassy areas, sometimes far from open water.
Trumpeter_Swan, Occurs on a variety of waterbodies, from small ponds to large reservoirs.
Trumpeter_Swan, Pairs stay together for many years and often stay close to each other. Pairs display to each other, including head bobbing.

Tufted_Duck, Adult male is mostly black overall, with a black head, neck, breast, back, and tail. The head can look purplish or greenish depending on the light. Gleaming white sides contrast with the otherwise dark plumage. A feather tuft hangs off the back of the head (length varies). The bill is gray with an entirely black tip. Eyes are yellow.

Tufted_Duck, Female and immature are brown overall, with a darker brown back. The bill is short and broad, and sometimes bordered by a small amount of white at the base. The overall head shape is rounded, but with a steep forehead, flat top, and rounded back. Adult female usually has at least a small tuft.

Tufted_Duck, Adult male is mostly black overall, with a black head, neck, breast, back, and tail contrasting with white sides. A feather tuft hangs off the back of the head, which can appear purplish or green depending on the lighting. The bill is gray with an entirely black tip. This bird reveals its white wing stripe while preening.
Tufted_Duck, In flight, note the extensive white wing stripe set off against dark wings and a black back.

Tufted_Duck, Immature male starts to transition from female-like juvenile plumage to adult male plumage during its first winter. Note the short tuft; brownish-black head, back, and tail; and touch of white on the brownish side.

Tufted_Duck, Female is brown overall, with a darker brown head and back. The overall head shape is rounded, but with a steep forehead, flat top, and rounded back. Individual females are variable when it comes to tuft size, white at the base of the bill, and white under the tail.
Tufted_Duck, Overall head shape is rounded, but with a steep forehead, flat top, and rounded back. The short bill is mostly gray, with a lighter gray section adjacent to an all-black tip.

Tufted_Duck, Female and immature have a dark brown head and back, and lighter brown breast and sides. Some (but not all) show white under the tail. The broad gray bill has a light band next to a black tip. Adult female usually has at least a small tuft.

Tufted_Duck, Breeds in freshwater habitats, including ponds and lakes bordered by marsh. Chicks typically remain with the female for 45–50 days before fledging, but small ducklings can usually survive on their own if necessary.
Tufted_Duck, Breeds in a variety of freshwater habitats, including ponds and lakes bordered by marsh.
Tufted_Duck, Chicks remain with female for 45–50 days before fledging.

Tufted_Duck, In North America, Tufted Ducks are usually seen in the company of scaup and/or Ring-necked Ducks. Here, an adult male's black back, bright white sides, and namesake tuft help it stand out in a group of Lesser Scaup.
Tufted_Duck, A relatively small diving duck, smaller-bodied than Common Pochard (seen here) and Greater Scaup.
Tufted_Duck, Forms flocks in winter, sometimes numbering in the thousands.
Tufted_Puffin, Stocky black seabird. Breeding birds have a white face, long yellow plumes at the back of the head, and a large triangular red and orangish bill.
Tufted_Puffin, Large mostly black seabird with an unmistakable red bill. Breeding birds have yellow head plumes.
Tufted_Puffin, Mostly black seabird with large, triangular bill. Breeding birds have extravagant head plumes and face pattern, but this can be difficult to see at long range.
Tufted_Puffin, Nonbreeding birds are dark overall, with a gray face, reduced yellow plumes, and a smaller orange and gray bill.
Tufted_Puffin, In flight, entirely black below including underwings.
Tufted_Puffin, Nonbreeding birds have smaller bills, lacking the yellow plates visible during the breeding season. Appears entirely dark at a distance.
Tufted_Titmouse, Small, somewhat stocky bird with a big dark eye and a crest. Grayish above and white below with a peach wash on the sides.
Tufted_Titmouse, Adults have a black forehead. Some birds have dingier bellies than others and the peachy flanks are less visible on worn birds.
Tufted_Titmouse, Very vocal songbird that sings a clear peter, peter whistle during spring and summer.
Tufted_Titmouse, Tufted Titmice have larger heads, black eyes, and a gray crest that can be raised or lowered. Their flanks are washed in peach.
Tufted_Titmouse, Forages acrobatically, but a bit slower and more methodical than chickadees.
Tufted_Titmouse, Hammers larger seeds with its bill while holding it between its feet.
Tufted_Titmouse, Found in eastern forests, parks, and backyards. Peachy flanks are often not as obvious on worn birds.
Tufted_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees created naturally or excavated by woodpeckers.
Tufted_Titmouse, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes.
Tufted_Titmouse, Flits between twigs and branches, but moves a bit slower and more methodically than chickadees.
Tundra_Swan, Very large and entirely white with a long neck, with black bill showing a small yellow spot on the black facial skin in front of the eye.
Tundra_Swan, Very large and entirely white with a long neck, with black bill showing yellow at the base, and black legs. "Bewick's" is the Eurasian form.
Tundra_Swan, Yellow at base of bill is often hard to see and sometimes is absent. Note curved, not pointed, line above the eyes where bill meets forehead.
Tundra_Swan, Older juveniles are pale dusky-brown with extensive white highlights, and a mostly pink bill with black tip and base.
Tundra_Swan, Flies with neck outstretched. Entirely white with black legs and variable amount of yellow on the base of black bill.
Tundra_Swan, Adults of the "Bewick's" subspecies, found in Europe and Asia, always show significant yellow at the base of the bill.
Tundra_Swan, Young juveniles are fluffy, entirely grayish white, with a pale bill.
Tundra_Swan, Some birds have very little or no yellow at the base of the bill. Extent of facial skin connecting bill to eye variable, but usually not extensive.
Tundra_Swan, "Bewick's," the Eurasian form, has extensive yellow at the base of the bill.
Tundra_Swan, Flies with neck outstretched. Entirely white with black legs and variable amount of yellow on the base of black bill.
Tundra_Swan, Often occurs in flocks on ponds, rivers, lakes, estuaries, and bays.
Turkey_Vulture, Large and black with browner back (especially when worn), naked bright red head, and pale bill and legs.
Turkey_Vulture, Large brown vulture with small, bare red head. In good light or at close range both brown plumage and red head separate Turkey Vulture from Black Vulture (left).
Turkey_Vulture, Juveniles have an ashy-gray colored naked head.
Turkey_Vulture, Immatures have the naked head dusky red in color.

Turkey_Vulture, Note two-toned wing pattern with lighter trailing edge, fairly long tail, and teetering flight style. Soars with wings raised slightly (known as "dihedral") and rarely flaps. Red head can be hard to see.
Turkey_Vulture, Flies with a distinctive shallow "V" shape, and teeters side-to-side.
Turkey_Vulture, Juveniles have a dark head, lacking the bright red of adults, but share adults' underwing pattern and shallow V-shaped flight posture.
Turkey_Vulture, Soars on thermals, often circling in groups known as "kettles." Note dihedral (raised wings) and distinctive teetering style of soaring.
Turkey_Vulture, Large and black with bright red naked head and contrasting white collar.
Turkey_Vulture, Will perch with wings spread to dry off, or on cold days.
Turkey_Vulture, Roosts communally and warms up in the morning by facing the sun, spreading wings, and standing still for extended periods.
Turkey_Vulture, Sometimes found with crows at carrion or landfills.
Turkey_Vulture, Sometimes roosts communally, sometimes in large groups.
Upland_Sandpiper, A tall, skinny sandpiper of grasslands with a thin neck and small head. Speckled brown overall with a short, thin bill.
Upland_Sandpiper, Slender with a short, thin bill and long neck. Mottled brown above with spotting on flanks and neck. Note big-eyed look.
Upland_Sandpiper, A terrestrial shorebird that often perches on fence posts in grasslands.
Upland_Sandpiper, A tall, skinny sandpiper of grasslands with a thin neck and small head. Speckled brown overall with a short, thin bill.
Upland_Sandpiper, Often lands on fence posts, raising its wings after landing.
Upland_Sandpiper, In flight the outer flight feather is white, appears as a sliver of white on the upper wing, which can be difficult to see.
Upland_Sandpiper, A tall, skinny sandpiper of grasslands with a thin neck and small head. Speckled brown overall with a short, thin bill.
Varied_Bunting, Females are tan overall with unmarked wings and a clean breast. Note the thick bill with a curved upper mandible.
Varied_Bunting, Somewhat hefty finchlike songbird with a thick bill. Males are and unmistakable blue and reddish purple overall, but can appear dark from a distance.
Varied_Bunting, Females are pale brown overall with an unstreaked breast.
Varied_Bunting, Males have a blue body marked with reddish purple chest and nape. Occurs in scrubby woodlands, thorn forests, areas near streams, and desert washes.

Varied_Thrush, Stocky, large thrush with a round head and a straight bill. Adult males are blue-gray on the back and rich burnt orange below with a sooty-black breastband and orange line over the eye.
Varied_Thrush, Large full-bodied thrush. Females/immatures are browner overall than adult males but still have a burnt-orange breast, wingbars, and eyebrows.
Varied_Thrush, A large, full-bodied thrush. Male is dark blue-gray on the back and rich burnt-orange below with a sooty-black breastband and orange line over the eye.
Varied_Thrush, Juveniles look like females/immatures but have a paler eyebrow and a dingy grayish breast with spotting.
Varied_Thrush, Feeds mostly on berries and nuts during the winter.
Varied_Thrush, Female has the same patterns as male, but is paler gray-brown. Feeds mostly on berries and nuts during the winter.
Varied_Thrush, Stocky, large thrush with a round head and a straight bill. Females/immatures are paler than adult males with a browner back and a fainter gray breast band.
Varied_Thrush, Usually seen standing on the ground or perched horizontally in a tree. Note burnt-orange throat and belly separated by a dark breast band.
Varied_Thrush, Hops on the ground or low in shrubs and trees. Eats mainly insects and other arthropods in the summer.
Varied_Thrush, In flight, note pale wing stripe on both upperwing and underwing.
Varied_Thrush, Breeds in dark understories of humid evergreen and mixed forests along the Pacific Coast. In the winter, many move into dense parks, gardens, and backyards.
Varied_Thrush, A bird of western North America, but vagrant individuals regularly appear in the East during the winter.
Vauxs_Swift, Small with a tube or cigar-shaped body, long, arched wings, and a short tail. Brownish overall with a paler chest and slightly paler rump.
Vauxs_Swift, Small with a tube or cigar-shaped body, long, arched wings, and a short tail. Brownish overall with a paler chest and slightly paler rump.
Vauxs_Swift, Roosts in groups (sometimes very large groups) in chimneys, hollowed-out standing trees and other vertical openings. At dusk, swirling masses collect as the birds prepare to go inside.
Vauxs_Swift, Roosts in groups (sometimes very large groups) in chimneys, hollowed-out standing trees and other vertical openings. At dusk, swirling masses collect as the birds prepare to go inside.
Vauxs_Swift, Roosts in groups (sometimes very large groups) in chimneys, hollowed-out standing trees and other vertical openings. At dusk, swirling masses collect as the birds prepare to go inside.
Vauxs_Swift, Nests and roosts in hollow trees in evergreen or mixed forests as well as chimneys, especially during migration where thousands of Vaux's Swifts will funnel into a chimney for the night.
Veery, Medium-sized thrush with a plump body and a round head. Uniformly bright cinnamon-brown above with indistinct spotting on the chest and pale underparts.
Veery, Medium-sized thrush with a plump body and a round head. Uniformly bright cinnamon-brown above with indistinct spotting on the chest and pale underparts.
Veery, Typically found in forest understory or foraging in leaf litter.
Veery, Plump thrush with a round head and small, thin bill. Cinnamon-brown above with faint spotting on a creamy-colored throat.
Veery, Plump-bodied thrush. Cinnamon-brown above with faint spotting on a creamy colored breast.
Veery, A medium-sized thrush with bright cinnamon-brown head upperparts and white underparts with indistinct spotting on the chest.
Veery, Spotting on the breast is often stronger on more northern breeders. Note brown mustache stripe and grayish flanks.
Veery, Medium-sized thrush with a plump body and a round head. Uniformly bright cinnamon-brown above with indistinct spotting on the chest and pale underparts.
Veery, Breeds in rich deciduous woodlands and forests with well-developed understory.

Vega_Gull, A large, highly variable gull with a heavy bill. Breeding adult has bright yellow bill with red mark near tip, white head and underparts, and black wingtips with white spots. Upperparts range from medium to dark gray. Legs in breeding plumage are typically bright pink. Eye color is often dark but can be yellowish as in this individual.
Vega_Gull, Nonbreeding adult has variable streaking on the head, neck, and upper breast. Both the bill and legs are paler than in breeding adults.

Vega_Gull, A large, heavy-billed gull. Breeding adult has white head and underparts, a yellow bill with red spot near tip, pink legs, gray upperparts, and black wingtips with limited white visible at rest.

Vega_Gull, Adult in flight has black wingtips with white tips to the feathers and two large white spots ("mirrors") in the outermost primaries. Note also the fairly wide white trailing edge to the wings and the dusky underwings.

Vega_Gull, Juvenile has brown head and underparts with diffuse light markings. Brown upperpart feathers are heavily edged with buffy white, creating a scaly look. Note black bill, dark eye, blackish wingtips, and pale pink legs.
Vega_Gull, Nonbreeding adult is like breeding adult, but with streaking on head, neck, and upper breast. Typically occurs along the coast of East Asia during the winter.
Vega_Gull, In flight, note juvenile's whitish rump (contrasting with brown tip to tail) and conspicuous pale "panel" in the inner primaries.
Vega_Gull, Breeds exclusively in northeastern Siberia except for a small nesting population on St. Lawrence Island, Alaska, in the Bering Sea.
Vega_Gull, An opportunistic forager and scavenger, feeding on garbage, carrion, fish, marine invertebrates, mammals, and other seabirds.

Vega_Gull, Individuals typically take four years to attain full adult plumage. First-summer birds are highly variable, showing a mix of juvenile plumage, new feathers on the head, back, and underparts, and older feathers that can be significantly bleached.
Vega_Gull, Second-year birds gradually become lighter than juveniles, showing some gray on the back.
Vega_Gull, Mainly a coastal species of East Asia during the winter, visiting harbors, beaches, and coastal wetlands and estuaries.
Verdin, Tiny desert bird with a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches (not always visible).
Verdin, Tiny pale gray bird of the desert with a yellow head. Chestnut shoulder patches may not always be visible.
Verdin, Flits quickly among twigs of desert shrubs to forage for insects.
Verdin, Juveniles are pale gray overall and lack the yellow head of adults. The bill is yellow, especially when very young.
Verdin, Tiny desert bird with a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches (not always visible).
Verdin, Juveniles are pale gray overall and lack the adult's yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches. The short bill is thicker at the base and finely pointed at the tip.
Verdin, Small and delicate songbird with a small, sharply pointed bill. Adults have a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches.
Verdin, Tiny desert bird with a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches (not always visible).
Verdin, Tiny desert bird with a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches (not always visible).
Verdin, Tiny desert bird with a yellow head and chestnut shoulder patches (not always visible).
Verdin, Found in desert scrub, especially along washes with thorny vegetation.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Medium-sized flycatcher with a short tail. Adult males are brilliant red and black.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Compact flycatcher. Females are brownish above with a white breast and reddish belly and undertail coverts.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Found in open habitats including scrub, deserts, and weedy fields or edges, where it sits on low, exposed perches and scans for insects.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Immature females are duller than adults with a peachy belly and a streaky breast.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Immature males have variable patches of red feathers on the head and breast.

Vermilion_Flycatcher, Compact flycatcher. Juveniles are brown above with a heavily streaked belly and pale peach undertail coverts. Individuals in northern Chile are browner than birds in North America.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Medium-sized flycatcher with a shorter tail. Adult males are brilliant red and black.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Medium-sized flycatcher with a short tail. Adult males are brilliant red and black.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Compact flycatcher. Females are brownish above with a white breast and reddish belly and undertail coverts.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Back and breast color varies slightly throughout their range from brownish black to black and from red to red-orange.
Vermilion_Flycatcher, Found in scrub, desert, cultivated lands, and riparian woodlands.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Song consists of two to four long, clear whistles, followed by musical slurs and trills. Note prominent eyering.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with streaked breast, white eyering, white outer tail feathers. Rufous patch at shoulder is usually hard to see in the field.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with small bill and round head. Prominent white eyering. Rufous patch at shoulder is often hard to see in the field.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Fairly large sparrow of grasslands and fields. White eyering and pale spot outlined in dark just below and behind eye create distinctive face pattern.
Vesper_Sparrow, Medium to large sparrow with fairly small bill. Prominent white eyering and white outer tail feathers.
Vesper_Sparrow, Occurs in open habitats including prairie, grasslands, agricultural areas, sagebrush, old fields, and wooded edges.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Fairly large, slender hummingbird with clean white underparts. Note lack of gorget (both sexes) and straight orange bill with black tip.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Fairly large, slender hummingbird with white throat and iridescent purple head. Males and females look alike. Often visits hummingbird feeders.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Often feeds at hummingbird feeders. Males and females look alike, and both sexes lack colorful gorget (throat).
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Note nearly straight, long bill, orange at base and black at tip. Brown tail lacks white flashes.

Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Large, slender hummingbird with nearly straight, long, orange-based bill. Adults have glittering violet crown and lack a colorful gorget. Males and females look alike. Tail often appears notched.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Brownish hummingbird with clean white underparts (including throat) and straight orange bill with black tip.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Fairly large hummingbird with clean white underparts, including throat. Immatures have partially brown heads with some violet on the crown and hindneck.
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Fairly large hummingbird with nearly straight, long, orange bill with black tip. Immatures have partially brown heads with some violet on the crown and hindneck.

Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Note fairly large size and orange bill compared with other hummingbirds. Immatures have brown on the head with limited violet on the crown and hindneck. (Other species in this video: immature Black-chinned and Broad-billed Hummingbirds.)
Violet-crowned_Hummingbird, Feeds on flowers along wooded streams, meadows, and pine-oak-juniper forest. Also visits hummingbird feeders.

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.
Violet-green_Swallow, When not foraging in midair for insects, perches on exposed branches. Its long wings extend beyond the tail while perched. Note the white "saddlebags."
Violet-green_Swallow, In flight note short, squared or slightly notched tail and white patches on either side of its rump. All individuals have these "saddlebags."

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.
Violet-green_Swallow, Aerial insectivores that fly at various heights with rapid wingbeats, often over water bodies, in search of flying insects. Note white patches on either side of the rump.

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.
Violet-green_Swallow, Adult males are crisp white below with clean white cheeks.

Violet-green_Swallow, Sleek songbird with a small head and tiny bill. Adult females are drabber than males with a brown cap and paler green backs, though some females can be nearly as bright as males. Note dusky cheek patch.

Violet-green_Swallow, Small sleek birds with long pointed wings and slightly forked tails. Their long wings extend beyond their tail when perched. In good light, adult males have a greenish-bronze back and iridescent violet rump. Note white cheek.
Violet-green_Swallow, Found in open woodlands including deciduous, evergreen, and mixed species woodlands where they nests in holes in trees or in artificial nest boxes.

Virginia_Rail, Chickenlike bird of marshes that is smaller than King or Clapper Rails. Note gray cheek, reddish bill, cinnamon neck, and black-and-white barring on the flanks. Walks with its tail held up.
Virginia_Rail, Downy black chicks accompany parents until they are at least 7 days old. Probes surface of wetlands for invertebrates. Most often hidden from view.

Virginia_Rail, A chickenlike marsh bird with a long, heavy bill and a short, upturned tail. Adult is rusty overall with a gray face, coarse dark streaking down the back, and black-and-white barring on the sides.

Virginia_Rail, Chickenlike bird of marshes that is smaller than King or Clapper Rails. Note gray cheek, reddish bill, cinnamon neck, black-and-white barring on the flanks, and white undertail coverts.
Virginia_Rail, Laterally compressed bodies allow them to walk through dense wetland vegetation with ease.
Virginia_Rail, Slender marsh bird that feeds by probing in shallow marshes and wetlands. Easily vanishes into emergent vegetation, where it spends most of its time.
Virginia_Rail, Breeds in freshwater wetlands with dense emergent vegetation such as cattail and bulrush. Occasionally uses saltmarshes.
Virginias_Warbler, A small gray warbler with a white eyering and yellow highlights under the tail and on the chest.
Virginias_Warbler, Virginia's Warblers have a thin, pointy bill and a longer, thinner tail than other warblers. Note the yellow undertail feathers, white eyering, and overall gray color.
Virginias_Warbler, Virginia's Warblers frequently wag their tail up and down, a behavior that can help with identification.
Virginias_Warbler, Virginia's Warblers are grayish overall with pale yellow highlights under the tail. The amount of yellow on the chest varies and can be absent altogether.
Virginias_Warbler, Virginia's Warblers frequently pump their tail up and down while foraging.
Virginias_Warbler, Found in moist and scrubby drainages in pinyon-juniper and oak woodlands.
Virginias_Warbler, A small gray warbler with a white eyering and yellow highlights under the tail and on the chest.
Wandering_Tattler, Forages on rocky or sandy substrates, often within the intertidal zone, for small marine invertebrates, insects, and fish. Frequently bobs its tail up and down while walking.
Wandering_Tattler, In flight, entirely gray above.

Wandering_Tattler, Medium-sized shorebird with a long bill and thick legs. Typically walks with a horizontal posture while bobbing its tail. Nonbreeding birds are gray above with an unmarked gray chest. Note yellow legs.
Wandering_Tattler, Breeding adults have a heavily barred gray belly and a white line in front of their eye.
Wandering_Tattler, Larger and longer than Black Turnstones. Yellow legs and barred belly are diagnostic.
Wandering_Tattler, Forages along rocky shorelines where it blends in with the rocks.

Warbling_Vireo, A small, stocky songbird with a relatively thick bill and stout, blue-toned legs. The wing is mostly plain, and the face has an "open" look, lacking the strong dark eyeline shown by several similar species.

Warbling_Vireo, Often washed pale yellow below, with the brightest color on the flanks. Face contrast is low, with a weak stripe in front of and behind the eye. This makes the dark eye stand out strongly on the face. Though Eastern birds ( gilvus ) are generally more yellow below than Western ( swainsoni ), the differences are quite subtle and subspecies ID should rely primarily on song.

Warbling_Vireo, A drab vireo with grayish upperparts, a plain face with a white stripe over the eye, a white throat, and whitish to light yellowish underparts. Its fast, rollicking song—which differs noticeably between Eastern and Western birds, is its most distinctive feature.

Warbling_Vireo, A stout, plain-winged songbird with sturdy blue-gray legs and a blunt bill. Generally olive-gray above and whitish below with a low-contrast face pattern. Western birds ( swainsoni ) tend to be drab below with little yellow, but visual differences are slight and subspecies ID should be reinforced with song.

Warbling_Vireo, The slight yellow wash to the underparts is concentrated along the flanks instead of the center of the breast or throat, which helps to distinguish this species from Philadelphia Vireo . Visual differences between populations are slight, but this bird shows a darker gray crown typical of the Western subspecies group ( swainsoni ).
Warbling_Vireo, Forages by moving slowly through small branches, looking around carefully for insects. Note fairly thick bill and dark line through eye that fades out before it meets the bill.

Warbling_Vireo, The large head, relatively short tail, and stout bill with a hooked tip identify this as a vireo. This species has plain wings and a low-contrast face with bold dark eye. Western birds ( swainsoni ) show relatively dark gray crowns and olive green backs.

Warbling_Vireo, A stout, short-tailed songbird with a thick bill and plain wings. When viewed from the side, these vireos can appear fairly yellow on the flanks; however, note the white throat. The bold dark eye stands out on the relatively dull, low contrast face.
Warbling_Vireo, Breeding birds strongly prefer deciduous woodland near water; on migration the species uses nearly any vegetated habitat.

Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush with a thin bill and short tail. Usually perches upright. Males are shiny blue above with rust-orange extending from a vest on the breast onto the upper back. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush. Some females are duller than others. Dull females are gray-buff with a pale orange wash on the breast and blue tints to the wings and tail.

Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush with a thin bill and short tail. Usually perches upright. Males are shiny blue above with rust-orange extending from a vest on the breast onto the upper back. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Juveniles look like females, but have spotting on the back and streaking on the breast.
Western_Bluebird, Feeds mainly on insects during the summer and switches to eating mostly fruits and seeds during the winter.

Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush with a thin bill and short tail. Usually perches upright. Males are shiny blue above with rust-orange extending from a vest on the breast onto the upper back. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush. Some females/immatures are brighter than others. Bright birds are brighter gray-blue above with a pale chestnut breast and whitish belly.
Western_Bluebird, Round-bellied thrush with a small thin bill. Adult males have a rich rusty-orange vest that extends up over the wings onto the back. Note blue throat.

Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush with a thin bill and short tail. Usually perches upright. Males are shiny blue above with rust-orange extending from a vest on the breast onto the upper back. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Stocky and round-bellied thrush. Adult males have a rusty-orange breast and flanks and a pale blue belly that grades to grayish white. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Nests in holes in trees or nest boxes.

Western_Bluebird, Small stocky thrush with a thin bill and short tail. Usually perches upright. Males are shiny blue above with rust-orange extending from a vest on the breast onto the upper back. Note blue throat.
Western_Bluebird, Found in open woodlands, backyards, burned areas, and farmland.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Compact egret that often perches with its thick neck drawn in. Breeding adults have golden feathers on the head, breast, and back. Note short yellow bill and yellow legs.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Breeding adult has bright red legs and bill during a short period of peak breeding.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Smaller and more compact egret with a short yellow bill. Nonbreeding bird is entirely white with black legs.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Juvenile is entirely white with black legs and a black bill.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Usually flies with its neck tucked in like other herons.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Forages in groups in upland areas such as pastures and fields, generally in drier habitats than other species of white herons. Frequently associates with grazing animals.
Western_Cattle-Egret, Forages alongside grazing animals eating insects attracted to them as well as insects and small animals that flush from under their feet.
Western_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a peaked crown and teardrop-shaped eyering. Olive above and yellowish below, with two light wingbars.

Western_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher found in forested habitats. Olive overall, with individuals showing varying amounts of yellow below. Note peaked crown, teardrop-shaped eyering, and whitish wingbars. Bill is black above and orangish below.

Western_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a peaked crown, teardrop-shaped eyering, and two light wingbars. Olive above with varying amounts of yellow below. Flicks tail frequently (as do some other Western Empidonax flycatchers).

Western_Flycatcher, Rare visitor to eastern North America, usually in late fall. The combination of yellowish underparts and teardrop-shaped eyering helps in differentiating from eastern Empidonax flycatchers.
Western_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with olive upperparts, two light wingbars, peaked crown, and teardrop-shaped eyering. Fairly broad bill is orangish below.

Western_Flycatcher, Nests on banks (as well as in trees, shrubs, and cavities, or on buildings and bridges). The female builds an elaborate cup nest, adding mosses and lichens to the outside of the nest.
Western_Flycatcher, Small, olive-backed flycatcher with teardrop-shaped eyering, peaked crown, and white wingbars.
Western_Flycatcher, Usually yellowish below, with darker wash across breast (but some individuals have very limited yellow).
Western_Flycatcher, Calls include a short "tsip" and a piercing "seet."
Western_Flycatcher, "Cordilleran" group breeds in dry evergreen and mixed forests in interior western North America, mainly along the Rocky Mountains and Mexico's Sierra Madre.
Western_Flycatcher, "Pacific-slope" group breeds in humid evergreen forests, pine-oak forests, and dense second-growth woodlands.
Western_Grebe, Large, slender grebe with long, straight bill. Dark cap extends below eye. Bill is fairly dull yellowish-green.

Western_Grebe, Western Grebes perform a unique courtship behavior where a male and female lift their torsos out of the water and run across the surface side by side. This "rushing ceremony" completes their monogamous pair bond.
Western_Grebe, Large, slender grebe with long neck and sharp border between blackish upperparts and white neck and cheek. Bill is dull yellow; black cap surrounds the eye.
Western_Grebe, Pairs bond using several displays, including synchronized "running" on the water. Displays usually begin during migration and continue on breeding grounds.
Western_Grebe, Western Grebes typically give a harsh rattle call when advertising for or responding to a potential mate. They also call when separated from family members.
Western_Grebe, Large grebe with long, slender dull-yellow bill. In winter the bill is usually at its least bright, and the dark crown fades to grayish surrounding the eye.
Western_Grebe, Note long, thin neck, puffy head, and long, slender bill. Carries chicks on its back after hatching.

Western_Grebe, Parents initially feed their young small fish or insect larvae, but transition to larger prey items when they are old enough. Young begin gaining independence at several weeks of age where they are able to dive and feed themselves.
Western_Grebe, Breeds on freshwater lakes and marshes; winters mainly on seacoasts.
Western_Grebe, Adults forage in open fresh or saltwater for a wide variety of fish, crustaceans, aquatic worms, and insects.
Western_Gull, Large white-headed gull with a heavy bill and pink legs. Breeding adults have a dark gray back, on orange ring around the eye, and a red spot on the lower bill.
Western_Gull, Large white-headed gull with a slaty gray back. Nonbreeding birds have very little streaking on the neck, unlike other gull species of the same age.
Western_Gull, One of the largest gulls on the Pacific Coast of North America. Note bulky proportions, heavy bill, and dark gray back.

Western_Gull, Third-winter Western Gulls have a smudgy head and neck. Their wingtips are entirely dark, lacking the white spots seen on adults. Note the heavy bulbous-shaped bill with a dark band across the tip.
Western_Gull, Second-winter Western Gulls have a slaty gray back and light brown mottled wings. The underparts and head are mostly white.
Western_Gull, Second-winter birds have a mostly white head and underparts with slaty gray feathers coming in on the back and light brown wings. Note bulbous-shaped bill and pink legs.

Western_Gull, First-winter birds are heavily mottled in gray and brown with dark primaries. The extent of brown smudging on the breast varies among individuals. This individual has a fairly advanced molt with a whiter head and underparts.

Western_Gull, Large gull with a heavy bulbous bill and pink legs. First-winter birds are mottled brown and white in various amounts. This individual shows considerable brown smudging on the head and underparts.
Western_Gull, Juveniles are gray-brown below with checkered back and wings. Note pink legs, heavy bill, and large size.
Western_Gull, In flight, note broad wings with a narrow white trailing edge and small white spots on the outer primaries. The darker wingtips blend gradually into the slaty gray wings and back.
Western_Gull, From below, note the gray secondaries and narrow white trailing edge.
Western_Gull, On flying juveniles note the dark tail, pale barred rump, and dark brown primaries and secondaries.
Western_Gull, Breeds on rocky islands and forages in intertidal areas, harbors, beaches, garbage dumps, fields, and other areas with easy access to food.
Western_Kingbird, Large, hefty flycatcher with a thick bill, a pale gray head, and a bright yellow belly.
Western_Kingbird, Large, hefty flycatcher with a bright yellow belly, pale gray head, and whitish throat. Note white edging on outer tail feathers.
Western_Kingbird, Sits upright on exposed perches and scans for insects. Note white outer tail feathers and uniform gray throat and chin. Often returns to the same perch after flying out after prey.
Western_Kingbird, Large flycatcher with a long tail and thick bill. Note pale gray head and dark tail with white outer tail feathers (visible in flight).
Western_Kingbird, The tail is black with white outer tail feathers that are especially conspicuous in flight.
Western_Kingbird, Vigorously defends nest from potential predators, including ravens, hawks, and falcons.
Western_Kingbird, Found in open habitats such as grasslands, deserts, sagebrush flats, and agricultural fields, where they perch on utility lines, fences, and trees.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head, a long, slender bill, and a round-shouldered posture. Breeding adults have bright yellow underparts with a prominent black V on the chest.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head and a long, slender bill. Nonbreeding birds are heavily streaked above with pale yellow underparts and a faint brown V on the chest.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head, a long, slender bill, and a round-shouldered posture. Breeding adults have bright yellow underparts with a prominent black V on the chest.
Western_Meadowlark, In flight, mostly brown above, but note white outer tail feathers.
Western_Meadowlark, Chunky grassland bird with round-shouldered posture. Note white outer tail feathers, most obvious in flight.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head, a long, slender bill, and a round-shouldered posture. Breeding adults have bright yellow underparts with a prominent black V on the chest.
Western_Meadowlark, Flat-headed grassland bird with a long, pointed bill. Note entirely yellow throat.
Western_Meadowlark, Nonbreeding birds are paler yellow than breeding birds. Note paler head stripes and entirely yellow throat.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head, a long, slender bill, and a round-shouldered posture. Breeding adults have bright yellow underparts with a prominent black V on the chest.
Western_Meadowlark, Found in grasslands and agricultural fields.

Western_Meadowlark, Chunky, short-tailed grassland bird with a flat head, a long, slender bill, and a round-shouldered posture. Breeding adults have bright yellow underparts with a prominent black V on the chest.
Western_Sandpiper, Small, portly sandpiper with black legs and a black slightly drooping bill. Breeding birds have a rusty cap and rusty mottling on the back.

Western_Sandpiper, Small, rather chunky shorebird. The bill is long and slightly drooping, although bill length and shape is quite variable among individuals and is not diagnostic on its own. Nonbreeding birds have little streaking on the breast.
Western_Sandpiper, Tiny shorebird; feeds on aquatic invertebrates usually at the water's edge or in shallow standing water. Appears somewhat front-heavy; folded wings are same length as tail.
Western_Sandpiper, Small, portly sandpiper with black legs and a black slightly drooping bill. Breeding birds have a rusty cap and rusty mottling on the back.
Western_Sandpiper, Juveniles look like nonbreeding adults but have a more scaly-looking back with a whiter face.
Western_Sandpiper, Tiny shorebird with whitish face and little streaking on the breast. Often forages by probing into mud and sand at water's edge.
Western_Sandpiper, In flight, rusty shoulder bars on juveniles can be seen at close range. As in most other "peep" sandpipers, note black stripe down the center of the tail.
Western_Sandpiper, Small, portly sandpiper with black legs and a black bill. Looks rather large headed compared to similar species. Breeding adults have rusty highlights in the head and shoulders.

Western_Sandpiper, Juveniles have crisp scaly markings on the back as a result of their newly grown feathers. They also show a rusty bar on the shoulder at a time when adults are in their brown-and-white nonbreeding plumage.
Western_Sandpiper, Small shorebird with a short neck and larger head. Nonbreeding birds are grayish above and white below. Often forages with its head even with or above the body.
Western_Sandpiper, Breeding birds have a rusty cap and rusty mottling on the back. From a distance its whiter face stands out.
Western_Sandpiper, Often seen on migration and wintering grounds in large flocks, sometimes with other "peep" species.
Western_Sandpiper, Breeds in tundra with dwarf vegetation. Migrates and winters along mudflats, beaches, shores of lakes and ponds, and flooded fields.

Western_Screech-Owl, Small stocky owl with a squarish head and little ear tufts. Plumage color varies from gray to brown, but generally has dark streaks on the belly, a dark border around the face, and a dark bill.
Western_Screech-Owl, Small stocky owl with a squarish head and little ear tufts. Individuals in the southwestern U.S. tend to be paler gray.
Western_Screech-Owl, Active at night. Note small ear tufts and yellow eyes.
Western_Screech-Owl, Small owl with small ear tufts. Birds in British Columbia have more red-toned plumage.

Western_Screech-Owl, Small stocky owl with a squarish head and little ear tufts. Plumage color varies from gray to brown, but generally has dark streaks on the belly, a dark border around the face, and a dark bill.
Western_Screech-Owl, Call is a series of high, accelerating whistles, like the sound of a dropped ping-pong ball coming to rest. Usually males give the call, but sometimes females join in for a duet.
Western_Screech-Owl, Nests in holes in trees. Juveniles are covered in fluffy white down.
Western_Screech-Owl, Found in forests, particularly among deciduous trees. They spend daylight hours in a roost hole sometimes looking out from the entrance.
Western_Screech-Owl, Roosts and nests in cavities in trees—and cactus. Also uses birdhouses with appropriately sized entry holes.

Western_Tanager, Stocky songbirds noticeably larger and heavier-bodied than warblers. Breeding males are bright yellow with black wings and a flaming orange-red head. Note yellow shoulder and white wingbar.
Western_Tanager, Medium-sized songbird with a thicker bill. Females are yellowish overall with dark wings marked by 2 wingbars.
Western_Tanager, Quietly and methodically scans for insects and plucks them from twigs, branches, leaves, and flowers in the upper portions of forest trees and shrubs.
Western_Tanager, Nonbreeding males look similar to breeding males, but have a yellow head that slowly becomes red as they molt into breeding plumage.
Western_Tanager, Some females are paler than others. This female has pale grayish underparts and yellowish undertail coverts.
Western_Tanager, Female alone builds nest and incubates eggs.
Western_Tanager, Females are yellowish overall with a gray back and darker wings marked by 2 wingbars.
Western_Tanager, Immature males have a scalloped-looking back. Head color varies from yellow to patchy red.
Western_Tanager, Breeds in evergreen and mixed forests. During migration found in nearly any shrubby or wooded habitats, and even in fairly open country.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked crown and 2 wingbars. Note long wings and upright posture.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Typically hunts insects from an exposed perch, flies out to catch them, and then returns to the same or a nearby perch.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Grayish flycatcher with a gray vest and 2 wingbars.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Medium-sized grayish flycatcher with a peaked crown and 2 wingbars. Note long wings and upright posture.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Note dusky "vest," long primary feathers in the folded wing, and lack of eyering.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Often perches upright in the canopy and repeatedly returns to the same or a nearby perch.
Western_Wood-Pewee, Whacks prey against its perch either to kill it or to break off wings or other indigestible parts.

Western_Wood-Pewee, The female builds a compact nest on top of a branch using grasses, and other plant fibers bound with spiderweb, then camouflages the outside with mosses, bud scales, and insect skins.
Whimbrel, Large shorebird with a long body, long neck, and small head. Most distinctive features are the long curved bill and striped head.
Whimbrel, Large-bodied shorebird with a long, curved bill. In flight note brownish color overall.
Whimbrel, Probes into soft surfaces for invertebrates and small crabs, which it swallows whole.
Whimbrel, European subspecies have a white rump patch that is visible in flight.
Whimbrel, European subspecies have a whiter base color on the underparts than the Hudsonian subspecies, which is more buff colored below.
Whimbrel, Large shorebird with a long body and small head. Most distinctive features are the long curved bill and striped head.
Whimbrel, Heavy-bodied shorebird with a striped crown and pale eyebrow.
Whimbrel, Smaller than a Long-billed Curlew with a shorter bill. Note striped crown and pale eyebrow.
Whimbrel, In migration, frequents various coastal and inland habitats, including fields and beaches. Winters in tidal flats and shorelines, occasionally visiting inland habitats.
Whimbrel, Widespread shorebird. Breeds in the Arctic in the eastern and western hemispheres, and migrates to South America, Africa, south Asia, and Australia.

Whiskered_Screech-Owl, A small screech-owl with whiskerlike extensions to feathers around the eyes and bill, a yellow-olive bill, orange-tinged eyes, and feathered toes. The more common gray morph is typically gray with some rusty coloration, but a brownish variant also occurs.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, Coarse blackish markings give a spotted—rather than streaked—appearance.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, Both sexes sing a short series of 5–7 notes, all on the same low pitch.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, During the daytime often roosts next to a tree trunk or in dense foliage.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, Occurs in forest and woodland habitats, including sycamore-dominated canyons.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, Short ear tufts are often not visible.
Whiskered_Screech-Owl, A rufous morph occurs primarily from central Mexico southward, often in shaded cloud forest.

White-breasted_Nuthatch, Compact, no-necked and short-tailed bird with a long, sharply pointed bill. Note blue-gray back, stark white cheeks, and black cap. From below, it has a white belly and rusty spots near its rear.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Compact bird that clings to tree bark moving down, up, and around the trees. Females look like males but have a grayer cap. Note rusty patches near the rear.

White-breasted_Nuthatch, Famous for perching upside-down on tree trunks. While they don't always go downwards, this tendency gives them a very recognizable posture with the head craned upward and backward to reach horizontal.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Small and compact with a big head and short tail. Blue-gray above with a black crown and stark white cheeks.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, A common visitor to bird feeders, where they eat sunflower seeds, peanuts, and more.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Females have a gray crown and paler rusty underparts compared to males.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Western birds have darker upperparts and other subtle differences from Eastern birds, but the best way to differentiate groups is by voice.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Juvenile stays with parents for several weeks after fledging before dispersing.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, In flight, note the white patches in the tail and underwings.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Nests in holes in trees created naturally or excavated by woodpeckers.
White-breasted_Nuthatch, Found most often in older deciduous woodlands, but also found in parks, wooded suburbs, and yards.
White-crowned_Pigeon, Large dark gray pigeon with a white crown. Close looks reveal a pale eye and a red bill with a pale tip.
White-crowned_Pigeon, Stocky dark gray pigeon of the Caribbean. In good light the back of the neck has scaly-looking iridescent green feathers.
White-crowned_Pigeon, Eats mostly fruits from hardwood trees. Sometimes found in large groups, especially where fruit resources are concentrated.
White-crowned_Sparrow, Large grayish sparrow with a long tail and often peaked head shape. Adults have very bold white and black stripes on the head.
White-crowned_Sparrow, Large sparrow with a fairly small bill. Immatures have rusty brown stripes on gray head. Note two white wingbars on brown wings.

White-crowned_Sparrow, A large, gray-and-brown sparrow with a small bill and long tail. Adult has a striking pattern of black and white stripes on the head. "Dark-lored" White-crowned Sparrows have a pinkish bill and brighter white head stripes than "Yellow-billed" birds.
White-crowned_Sparrow, "Gambel's" White-crowned Sparrows breeding in Alaska and northwestern Canada have gray or white lores and an orange to pink bill.
White-crowned_Sparrow, Immatures have similar head pattern to adults, but stripes are brown and gray instead of black and white.

White-crowned_Sparrow, During migration and winter often found along edges of woodlots, hedgerows, thickets, weedy fields, suburbs, backyards, and city parks. "Yellow-billed" White-crowned Sparrows have duller head stripes and a yellowish bill.
White-crowned_Sparrow, "Yellow-billed" White-crowned Sparrows breeding along the Pacific Coast from British Columbia to California have duller head stripes and a yellowish bill.
White-crowned_Sparrow, A large, long-tailed sparrow. "Yellow-billed" White-crowned Sparrows have brown flanks, dull white heard stripes, and a yellowish bill.
White-crowned_Sparrow, Song varies between populations, but is always recognizable by the sweet, whistled introduction, a succession of jumbled whistles, and a buzz or trill near the end.

White-crowned_Sparrow, White-crowned Sparrow populations in western North America have developed song dialects, with young males learning the basics of the song they will sing as an adult during the first two or three months of their life.
White-crowned_Sparrow, Juveniles have heavily streaked underparts and finely streaked brown head stripes.

White-crowned_Sparrow, Breeds in patchy boreal forest, alpine meadows, coastal scrub, and other grassy areas with scattered shrubs or trees. Winters in brushy fields, agricultural areas, roadsides, and thickets.

White-eared_Hummingbird, A medium-sized hummingbird with a dark head, prominent white stripe extending downward from the back of the eye, greenish upperparts, and a medium-length, slightly curved bill. Male has a bright red bill with a black tip and a head that often appears blackish depending on the lighting.
White-eared_Hummingbird, Female has a white "ear stripe" on a dark face, a brownish cap, whitish underparts with green spots, and a darker bill with limited red.

White-eared_Hummingbird, A medium-sized hummingbird with a dark head and a bold white stripe extending downward behind the eye. Male has a bright red bill with a black tip and a head that often appears blackish.
White-eared_Hummingbird, In good light, male's forehead and chin are a brilliant purple and the throat is an iridescent green. Lower underparts are whitish with heavy green scaling.
White-eared_Hummingbird, In all plumages, the bold white "ear stripe" contrasts with a dark head.
White-eared_Hummingbird, In the right light, the area around a male's red bill turns a spectacular violet and the throat lights up in iridescent green.
White-eared_Hummingbird, Immature male is similar to female (note brownish crown), but also shows some adult male traits (red base to bill and some iridescent feathers on throat).
White-eared_Hummingbird, Upperparts are coppery green with some cinnamon edging near the rump.
White-eared_Hummingbird, Feeds mainly on nectar; also eats some insects.

White-eared_Hummingbird, Seen from below, the white "ear stripe" is less obvious, but note this male's dark purplish forehead and chin, green throat, whitish underparts with heavy green speckling, and red bill with a black tip and broad base.
White-eared_Hummingbird, Common in mountain pine-oak, oak, and pine-evergreen forests from northern Mexico to northern Nicaragua.
White-eared_Hummingbird, An uncommon but regular visitor to southeastern Arizona, where it often is seen at hummingbird feeders.
White-eared_Hummingbird, Feeds mainly on nectar and also eats some small insects.
White-eyed_Vireo, Small songbird with thick, straight, slightly hooked bill. Gray head contrasts with olive-green back. Yellow "spectacles" outline pale eye.
White-eyed_Vireo, Small songbird with thick, straight bill. Gray head and yellow spectacles contrast with white throat. Flanks are washed with yellow.
White-eyed_Vireo, Small songbird with thick, straight, slightly hooked bill. Gray head contrasts with olive-green back. Yellow "spectacles" outline pale eye.
White-eyed_Vireo, Small songbird with thick, straight, slightly hooked bill. Gray head contrasts with olive-green back. Yellow "spectacles" outline pale eye.
White-eyed_Vireo, Young birds have dark eyes that turn pale in their first winter or spring.
White-eyed_Vireo, Forages for caterpillars and other insects in shrubby tangles and other low, dense growth. Song is a fast jumble of notes, with a sharp chip at the beginning and end.
White-eyed_Vireo, Dark wings with two white wingbars. Pale underparts: white throat and center of belly, with yellow wash on flanks.
White-eyed_Vireo, White-eyed Vireos live in dense tangles including forest edges, wetland thickets, regrowing woodland, and overgrown fields.
White-eyed_Vireo, Small songbird with thick, straight, slightly hooked bill. Gray head contrasts with olive-green back. Yellow "spectacles" outline pale eye.

White-faced_Ibis, Large maroon wading bird with a long curved bill. Breeding adults have reddish legs and a bare patch of pink skin in front of the eye, which is bordered in white. In good light, note the metallic green and bronze wings.
White-faced_Ibis, Nonbreeding/immature birds look like adults but lack the bare skin patch and the white border around the eye. Note red eye.
White-faced_Ibis, Feeds in shallow marshes, wet ditches, and flooded or irrigated cropfields, often in large flocks.
White-faced_Ibis, Juveniles are paler brown overall with a paler cheek and patches of white feathers on the neck.
White-faced_Ibis, Flies with its neck outstretched and head slightly drooping.
