White-faced_Ibis, Large maroon wading bird with a long curved bill. Breeding adults have reddish legs and a bare patch of pink skin in front of the eye, which is bordered in white. In good light, note the metallic green and bronze wings.

White-faced_Ibis, Large maroon wading bird with a long curved bill. Breeding adults have reddish legs and a bare patch of pink skin in front of the eye, which is bordered in white. In good light, note the metallic green and bronze wings.
White-faced_Ibis, Pairs often preen each other during courtship, a behavior known as allopreening.
White-faced_Ibis, Often perches in low trees and shrubs at the edge of wetlands.
White-faced_Ibis, Found in fresh and saltwater marshes, wetlands, and flooded fields.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a white face and crown. Males have a small red rear crown patch.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Appropriately named woodpecker with a white head. Females lack red crown patch. Back is solid black with two white patches in the wings.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Immatures have a red patch in the middle of the crown instead of at the back of the head like adult males.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a white face and crown. Males have a small red rear crown patch.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Black woodpecker with a white head. White patches in the wing are not always visible on perched birds, but they are noticeable in flight.
White-headed_Woodpecker, The only North American bird with a white head and black body.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Medium-sized woodpecker with a white face and crown. Males have a small red rear crown patch.
White-headed_Woodpecker, Found in mixed evergreen forests dominated by pines. White head is distinctive.
White-headed_Woodpecker, White patch in wings is not always visible when the wings are folded.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Medium-sized grayish shorebird with a white eyebrow on its finely streaked head. Wingtips extend beyond the tail when at rest.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Juveniles look like adults, but have chestnut fringed feathers on their backs. Note the white eyebrow on the finely streaked head.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Long wings that come to a point past the end of the tail impart a streamlined look. At distance bill can look all dark.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Juveniles often have brighter chestnut fringed feathers on the back than adults.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Medium-sized grayish shorebird with a white eyebrow on its finely streaked head. Wingtips extend beyond the tail when at rest.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, On migration and during winter found in grassy marshes, mudflats, sandy beaches, flooded fields, and shores of ponds and lakes.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, The namesake white rump is visible in flight and sets it apart from other small sandpipers.
White-rumped_Sandpiper, Medium-sized sandpiper with wings that extend beyond the tail.

White-rumped_Sandpiper, Medium-sized grayish shorebird. Breeding adults have streaked flanks and a white eyebrow. The bill is black with a small amount of reddish orange at the base that is present in all ages, but the color can be difficult to see.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.
White-tailed_Hawk, Perched birds show a gray head, white belly, and dark wings with a chestnut patch on the shoulder. The wings extend beyond the tail when perched.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.

White-tailed_Hawk, Often soars in wide lazy circles with its wings held in a V or dihedral. Adults are dark above with chestnut shoulders and its namesake white tail marked with a black terminal band.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.
White-tailed_Hawk, When perched, note that the wings extend beyond the tail. Juvenile birds are dark above with a white breast patch.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.
White-tailed_Hawk, Juvenile birds in flight have a white tail, a dark head, a white throat, and dark inner wing linings. Acquires adult plumage after 4 years.

White-tailed_Hawk, In flight note short, white tail with dark band near the tip and broad wings that are pointed at the tips. Light morph birds have dark primaries, white inner wing linings, and a white belly.
White-tailed_Hawk, Juveniles are dark overall with a white throat patch and dark belly. The tail is very faintly barred.
White-tailed_Hawk, Occurs in a variety of open habitats from southern Texas to central Argentina.
White-tailed_Hawk, Found in open country, primarily savanna, prairie, and dry areas with mesquite, cacti, and bushes; very rarely in open forest.
White-tailed_Kite, Characteristic hunting behavior involves turning into wind and flapping in order to hover in place while scanning the ground.
White-tailed_Kite, Small hawk with narrow, pointed wings and long tail. Adults in flight are white below with black primaries and a dark spot on the "wrists."
White-tailed_Kite, Juveniles have a cinnamon wash on the breast and crown. Like adults they have a white face and dark shoulders.
White-tailed_Kite, Note dark patch on shoulder, dark eyes, and white underparts.
White-tailed_Kite, Juveniles have a mottled brown back and a cinnamon wash on the breast and crown. Note dark shoulder and white face.
White-tailed_Kite, Perches on exposed branches with a good view of the surroundings. Note white underparts and head.
White-tailed_Kite, During the nonbreeding season often roosts with other White-tailed Kites.
White-tailed_Kite, Found in savanna, open woodlands, marshes, desert grasslands, partially cleared lands, and cultivated fields.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Females are barred in brown and black with a yellowish wash.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill. Males and females turn entirely while during the winter.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. This individual is molting out of its breeding plumage into its winter white plumage.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Heavily mottled in brown, black, and white with an almost scaly-looking head.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. This individual is molting from its all white winter plumage to its mottled breeding plumage.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Found in rocky areas and meadows at or above treeline.
White-tailed_Ptarmigan, Smaller, stocky grouse with a short bill and tail. Breeding males are mottled gray and brown with a white belly and a red eyebrow (not always visible).

White-throated_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with long tail and fairly small bill. Bold face pattern with black and white crown stripes, yellow spot between eye and bill, and neat white throat patch on gray face and breast.

White-throated_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with long tail and small bill. In "tan-striped" form, individuals have lower contrast head pattern with brown stripes on the head instead of white. Often found among "white-striped" individuals.
White-throated_Sparrow, Sings a melancholy whistle that sounds like "Oh-Sweet-Canada-Canada" or "Old-Sam-Peabody-Peabody."
White-throated_Sparrow, Large, plump sparrow with small bill and rounded head. Immatures have brown-and-black head stripes, less yellow before the eye, and faint streaks on the breast.
White-throated_Sparrow, Tan-striped and white-striped individuals almost always mate with individuals of the opposite form.
White-throated_Sparrow, Readily visits feeders or pecks at fallen seeds beneath them. Eats millet and sunflower seeds.
White-throated_Sparrow, Large sparrow with small grayish bill. Upperparts are reddish brown with dark brown streaks. Underparts grayish with neat white throat patch.
White-throated_Sparrow, White throat sometimes outline with black line. Two white wingbars on rich reddish brown wings.
White-throated_Sparrow, Hops along the ground, scratching at the surface to uncover insects and seeds. This video has no audio.
White-throated_Sparrow, Juveniles are brownish overall with heavy streaking on the breast.
White-throated_Sparrow, Typically found on or near the ground in forests with dense shrubby understory.
White-throated_Sparrow, Often scratches at the ground with a double hop to uncover insects and seeds.
White-throated_Sparrow, Often seen in small flocks on the ground during migration and the winter.
White-throated_Swift, Larger-bodied swift with a long tail and long, arched wings. Note white throat, chest, and sides of rump.
White-throated_Swift, Chunky, tube-shaped swift with a long tail and wings. The throat, chest, and sides of the rump are white.
White-throated_Swift, Fast moving swift that flies on stiff, arched wings. Found near cliffs and canyon as well as human-made structures such as freeway overpasses, and bridges.
White-throated_Swift, Fast flying and acrobatic swift with a white throat and chest.
White-throated_Swift, Larger-bodied swift with a long tail and long, arched wings. Note white throat, chest, and sides of rump.
White-throated_Swift, Larger-bodied swift with a long tail and long, arched wings. Note white throat, chest, and sides of rump.
White-throated_Swift, Nests and roosts in crevices in cliffs, canyon walls, and large rocks as well as human-made structures such as freeway overpasses, and bridges.
White-tipped_Dove, Pale, pot-bellied dove with a fairly short, square-tipped tail. Brown wings with grayish pink neck and frosty gray face and underparts.
White-tipped_Dove, Birds across much of South America belong to the brasiliensis group, but look very similar to the White-tipped form.
White-tipped_Dove, White tips to the outer tail feathers can be hard to see except when the bird fans its tail or flies.
White-tipped_Dove, Pale, pot-bellied dove with a fairly short, square-tipped tail. Brown wings with grayish pink neck and frosty gray face and underparts.
White-tipped_Dove, Chunky dove often found on the ground. Note plain brown wings and grayish-pink breast grading into frosty belly.

White-tipped_Dove, Note pale, unmarked face and underparts with neck and breast that can appear buffy, grayish, or pinkish, and has a green iridescence at close range. White tail corners can be difficult to see except in flight.
White-tipped_Dove, Brown-backed dove with red legs, often found on the ground. Face and neck are unmarked.
White-tipped_Dove, Pale, pot-bellied dove with a fairly short, square-tipped tail. Brown wings with grayish pink neck and frosty gray face and underparts.
White-tipped_Dove, Usually forages on the ground in open forest or woodland understory; eats mostly seeds as well as some insects and berries.
White-tipped_Dove, Very pale with pale tips to the tail when viewed from below. From above the brown wings give a darker overall impression.
White-tipped_Dove, Typically found on the ground in open woods, woodland edges, shrubby areas, and parks. In the United States, range is limited to South Texas.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Females are yellowish with streaks on the back and belly. They also have 2 bold white wingbars, though one wingbar is often concealed.
White-winged_Crossbill, Uses the crisscrossed bill to separate the scales on the pine cone and extract the seeds.
White-winged_Crossbill, Immature males are patchy red and yellow with dark wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Juveniles are heavily streaked above and below with 2 white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Wanders nomadically across the boreal forest in search of cone crops, sometimes turning up much farther south during the nonbreeding season.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Medium-sized stocky finch with a crisscrossed bill. Adult males are bright red with a black tail and wings marked by 2 bold white wingbars.
White-winged_Crossbill, Found in evergreen forests, especially those with large crops of spruce and tamarack.
White-winged_Dove, Medium-sized dove with small head and short, square-tipped tail. Pale brown overall with white stripe along wing; becomes large white patch on inner wing in flight.
White-winged_Dove, Note large white crescent along wing when perched; in flight it becomes a large white patch.
White-winged_Dove, Medium-sized dove with short, white-tipped tail. Wingtips are blackish, contrasting with white inner wing.
White-winged_Dove, Medium-sized dove with distinctive flight pattern: gray-brown body; white inner wing with black wingtips; dark tail with white corners.
White-winged_Dove, Often found in dense, thorny forests, but increasingly common in towns.
White-winged_Dove, Typically found in dry habitats with mix of trees for nesting and open areas, grasslands, fields, or desert scrub for feeding.
White-winged_Scoter, Large mostly dark sea duck with bulge at base of orange-red bill. White in wings is often visible at rest. White comma-shaped patch (or "Viking horn") around eye.
White-winged_Scoter, Large brownish sea duck with large, sloping dark bill. Two white facial patches, both relatively round. White wing patch often visible at rest.
White-winged_Scoter, Feeds by diving for aquatic invertebrates, including mussels, clams, and oysters, which they swallow whole, shell and all. The hard shells are broken apart by the bird's gizzard.
White-winged_Scoter, Large blackish sea duck with orange-tipped bill. Large white patches in wings (secondaries) are prominent in flight.
White-winged_Scoter, Large brownish sea duck with large dark bill. White patches in the wings (secondaries) are prominent in flight.
White-winged_Scoter, Immature males lack the white markings of either adult males or adult females. White wing patch often visible at rest.
White-winged_Scoter, Adult male is dark bodied; immature has whitish belly. Both show prominent white wing patch in flight.
White-winged_Scoter, Often found on coastal water bodies in winter. May appear on inland lakes during migration.
White_Ibis, Large, long-legged wading bird with a football-shaped body and a long, curved bill. Adults have white bodies, bright red legs, a bare patch of red skin around the eye, and a red bill.
White_Ibis, Immature birds are a patchwork of white and brown with a pink bill and legs.
White_Ibis, A large wading bird with long legs and a long, curved bill. Adult is almost entirely white, with black-tipped wings and brilliant reddish-pink legs and bill.
White_Ibis, Large wading bird with a curved bill. Juveniles are brown above with a paler brown streaky neck and white below. Juveniles have an orangish pink bill.
White_Ibis, Flies with its neck out straight and its legs trailing behind. Note black wingtips.
White_Ibis, Mixed flocks of adult and immature individuals form in coastal and inland habitats, such as marshes and mangrove swamps.
White_Ibis, Heavy-bodied wading bird with broad wings. Immatures in flight are white below with brown primaries and secondaries.
White_Ibis, Probes for insects and crustaceans beneath the surface of wetlands with their long curved bill. Note pale blue eye of adult birds.
White_Ibis, Immature birds are mottled white and brown. As they age they acquire more white plumage.
White_Ibis, Found in freshwater marshes, coastal estuaries, mangroves, flooded pastures, mudflats, and swamps.

White_Wagtail, A small, slender songbird with a long tail and gray, black, and white plumage. Appearance varies across the nine subspecies groups, which can co-occur on the wintering grounds. Breeding male in the " ocularis " subspecies group, which breeds across northern Asia to western Alaska, has a white face with a black line running through the eye, a black chin and throat, gray upperparts, and white wingbars that can form a large white panel.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in all subspecies groups has a mostly black tail with white outer tail feathers. Breeding male in the "White-faced" subspecies group, which breeds across continental Europe, has a white face bordered by a black crown and throat, gray upperparts, and two white wingbars.
White_Wagtail, A slender songbird with a short, pointed bill and a long tail. Always some combination of gray, black, and white, though plumage details vary across subspecies, season, age, and sex.
White_Wagtail, Juvenile is dusky brownish gray, lacking adult's crisp black-and-white markings.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "British" group, which breeds in Ireland and the United Kingdom, has a white face bordered by a black crown and throat, black upperparts, and two prominent white wingbars.

White_Wagtail, A small, active songbird that calls and wags tail frequently. Feeds mainly on insects and spiders. Breeding female in the "White-faced" subspecies group has a grayer crown than breeding male.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Hodgson's" group, which breeds in the Himalayas and southern China, has a white mask surrounded by a black crown and throat, black upperparts, and a large white wing panel.
White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Chinese" subspecies group, which breeds in East Asia, has a mostly white head, a white throat, black upperparts, and a large white wing panel.
White_Wagtail, Typically forages on the ground, often near water, wagging long tail almost nonstop. The "Black-backed" subspecies group is a vagrant to Pacific Coast states and provinces.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Black-backed" subspecies group, which breeds in northeastern Asia and Japan, has a white face with a black line running through the eye, a black breast and lower throat, a white chin, black upperparts, and a large white wing panel.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Transbaikalian" subspecies group, which breeds in southern Siberia, Mongolia, and northeastern China, has a white face and throat, black breast, gray upperparts, and a large white wing panel. All White Wagtails feed primarily on insects and spiders.
White_Wagtail, Juvenile is drabber than adult, showing faint markings on the head and breast.

White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Masked" subspecies group, which breeds in Central Asia, has a limited white facial mask surrounded by a black crown, nape, and throat; gray upperparts; and a large white wing panel.
White_Wagtail, Breeding male in the "Moroccan" subspecies group, found only in northwestern Morocco, has a mostly black face, gray upperparts, and two white wingbars.
White_Wagtail, Note long tail, frequently wagged, with black center and white outer feathers.
White_Wagtail, Frequently occurs in parks, gardens, and other settings around people.
Whooping_Crane, Very tall with long legs and neck. Adult has an entirely white body with a red crown and mustache stripe.
Whooping_Crane, Large with long wings. Flies with neck and legs outstretched. Black wingtips only visible in flight.
Whooping_Crane, Very tall with long legs and neck. Adult has an entirely white body with a red crown and mustache stripe.
Whooping_Crane, Juvenile has a mostly orange head and upper neck and buffy cinnamon markings on the wings and "bustle."
Whooping_Crane, Large, long-legged, white crane. Feeds in shallow wetlands and pastures. Juveniles have a rusty brown head and mottled back.
Whooping_Crane, Very tall with long legs and neck. Adult has an entirely white body with a red crown and mustache stripe.
Whooping_Crane, Larger than Sandhill Cranes with a white body and black wingtips.
Whooping_Crane, Winters mainly in coastal marshes and estuaries and sometimes forages in crop fields.
Whooping_Crane, Very tall with long legs and neck. Adult has an entirely white body with a red crown and mustache stripe.
Wild_Turkey, Very large game bird. Displaying males look almost spherical, with naked, red-and-blue head and fanned tail.
Wild_Turkey, Very large game bird with long neck and legs. Females are dark brown overall with even darker barring.
Wild_Turkey, Very large game bird with small, unfeathered head covered with blue and red wattles. Displaying males give a throaty, jumbled call known as a "gobble."
Wild_Turkey, Often roosts in trees. These heavy birds fly short distances to take cover. Takes flight with a flurry of loud, labored wingbeats.
Wild_Turkey, Male has a relatively small, bare head with blue skin and red wattles.
Wild_Turkey, Very large game bird. Females have bare skin on the head and are dark brown overall, with a coppery sheen to the rump and tail. When open, the wings show white barring.
Wild_Turkey, Travels mainly by walking, but also runs, especially to escape predators.
Wild_Turkey, Juveniles can leave the nest upon hatching, but mothers care for their young into the first fall.
Wild_Turkey, At sundown turkeys fly into the lower limbs of trees and then move upward to a high roost spot. They usually roost in flocks, but sometimes individually.

Wild_Turkey, Occurs in woods mixed with open country; often forages by scratching in leaf litter. Females and adult males typically form separate flocks; female flocks can be up to 30 in summer, larger in winter.
Willet, Large, stocky shorebird with long legs and a thick, straight bill. Breeding birds in the East have heavy barring on the breast and heavy mottling on the back.
Willet, Large, stocky shorebird with long legs and a thick, straight bill. Breeding birds in the West have lighter barring on the breast and lighter mottling on the back.
Willet, Found along open beaches, bayshores, marshes, mudflats, and rocky coastal zones. Often sleeps with its bill tucked under its wing.
Willet, Large shorebird with a long, straight bill. Nonbreeding birds are grayish brown overall with few markings.
Willet, Large, stocky shorebird with long legs and a thick, straight bill. Breeding birds in the East have heavy barring on the breast and heavy mottling on the back.
Willet, Birds in flight have a distinctive black-and-white wing pattern.
Willet, Large, stocky shorebird. Juveniles in the West are grayer overall than those in the East. They also tend to be larger, but some overlap in size exists.
Willet, Juveniles in the East are browner overall than juveniles in the West. Eastern birds tend to be smaller, but there is some overlap.
Willet, Plain brownish gray shorebird often found along beaches and rocky coasts during migration and winter months.
Willet, During the winter found on beaches and rocky coasts, as well as mudflats and marshes.

Williamsons_Sapsucker, Large sapsucker. Males are mostly black above with vertical white wing patches and 2 white stripes on the face. Note small red throat patch and yellow belly (not visible in photo).
Williamsons_Sapsucker, Females have fine horizontal black-and-white barring on the back and a brown head. Females also have a black breast patch (not visible in the photo).

Williamsons_Sapsucker, A medium-sized woodpecker with a stout, medium-sized bill. Adult male is velvety black above, with a white wing patch and a yellow belly. Male's striking head pattern includes a white line behind the eye, a white stripe from the base of the bill to the lower cheek, and a red throat.
Williamsons_Sapsucker, Large sapsucker. Black above with vertical white wing patches, 2 white stripes on the face, and a red throat patch. The lower belly is yellow.

Williamsons_Sapsucker, Large sapsucker. Males are mostly black above with vertical white wing patches and 2 white stripes on the face. Note small red throat patch and yellow belly (not visible in photo).

Williamsons_Sapsucker, Excavates holes in trees, often those with a fungal infection, which makes excavating the hole easier. Males and females feed the nestlings and carry away fecal matter from the nest.

Williamsons_Sapsucker, Large sapsucker. Males are mostly black above with vertical white wing patches and 2 white stripes on the face. Note small red throat patch and yellow belly (not visible in photo).
Williamsons_Sapsucker, Juvenile females look like adult females but are paler overall and lack the black breast patch.

Willow_Flycatcher, Small, slender flycatcher. Brownish olive overall with a slight yellow wash to the belly. It has two whitish wingbars and a white throat that contrasts with the brownish olive breast.
Willow_Flycatcher, The white throat contrasts with the gray chest band. The eyering is very narrow or nonexistent.

Willow_Flycatcher, A small brownish-olive flycatcher with a slight yellow wash to the belly, two whitish wingbars, and a white throat. Willow Flycatcher's emphatic " fitz-bew " song is the best way to differentiate it from the extremely similar Alder Flycatcher.

Willow_Flycatcher, Small, slender flycatcher. Brownish olive overall with a slight yellow wash to the belly. It has two whitish wingbars and a white throat that contrasts with the brownish olive breast.

Willow_Flycatcher, Small, slender flycatcher. Brownish olive overall with a slight yellow wash to the belly. It has two whitish wingbars and a white throat that contrasts with the brownish olive breast.
Willow_Flycatcher, Gives a soft, dry whit often from exposed perches.
Willow_Flycatcher, Individuals breeding the the Southwest often paler than those in the East and Pacific Northwest.

Willow_Flycatcher, Small, slender flycatcher. Brownish olive overall with a slight yellow wash to the belly. It has two whitish wingbars and a white throat that contrasts with the brownish olive breast.
Willow_Flycatcher, Brownish olive overall with a slight yellow wash to the belly (can be brighter, especially on birds in fresh plumage). Best identified by voice.
Willow_Flycatcher, Perches upright and often sings from the tops of bushes. Song is the best way to identify it.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short tail and a short, stout bill. Breeding males have a red eyebrow, a chestnut neck, and a white belly.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Males and females turn white in the winter and blend in with their snowy surroundings.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Calls include a low series of clucks that can accelerate into an odd nasal growl.
Willow_Ptarmigan, This individual is molting into its white winter plumage. Its brown and rusty patches are being replaced by white feathers. Note feathered feet.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short and stout bill. Females are mottled in brown, black, and white during the breeding season.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short tail and a short, stout bill. Breeding males have a red eyebrow, a chestnut neck, and a white belly.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short tail and a short, stout bill. Breeding males have a red eyebrow, a chestnut neck, and a white belly.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Found in open tundra, especially in areas heavily vegetated with grasses, mosses, herbs, and shrubs.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short tail and a short, stout bill. Breeding males have a red eyebrow, a chestnut neck, and a white belly.
Willow_Ptarmigan, Medium-sized stocky bird with a short tail and a short, stout bill. Breeding males have a red eyebrow, a chestnut neck, and a white belly.

Wilsons_Phalarope, Small shorebird with long legs, a slender neck, and a very thin, straight, bill. Breeding females are more brightly colored than males with a dark stripe down the neck, a blue-gray back, and a peachy neck.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Slender shorebird with a thin bill. Males are often duller than females, lacking the black neck stripe.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Classic foraging behavior is to swim in tight circles, creating a vortex that brings prey items up toward the surface.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Juveniles have a dark cap and scaly-looking backs that vary in color from grayish to rusty.
Wilsons_Phalarope, In flight, note white rump, grayish tail, and plain grayish wings.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Slender shorebird with a long, thin bill. Juveniles have a dark cap and a scaly-looking back that varies from grayish to rusty. Sits high in the water.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Juveniles and nonbreeding adults have yellow legs. When foraging on land moves quickly and frantically.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Larger than "peep" sandpipers (like Semipalmated, at right). Juveniles and nonbreeding adults have yellow legs. Juveniles have a dark cap and white neck and belly.
Wilsons_Phalarope, When foraging on land moves quickly, often in a crouched position.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Note white neck and belly, thin bill, and slender-bodied look.
Wilsons_Phalarope, Regularly swims in open water and often spins in circles to bring small food items within reach of its slender bill. Sits high in the water.

Wilsons_Phalarope, Breeds in marshes and spends winters in South America, mainly on high lakes in the Andes. On migration, large numbers congregate on salty lakes and coastal marshes of western North America.

Wilsons_Plover, Medium-sized shorebird with a big-headed look, and a long, thick bill. Breeding adults have a black band around the neck. Bill is black in all seasons. Often stands with a hunched horizontal posture.
Wilsons_Plover, Nonbreeding birds have a pale brown collar. Note the thick black bill and pale legs.
Wilsons_Plover, Superficially like Semipalmated Plover, but with a longer and thicker, almost oversized bill that is all black.
Wilsons_Plover, Nonbreeding birds have a pale brown collar. Note the thick black bill and pale legs.
Wilsons_Plover, In flight tip of tail is black with white edges and wings are long and slender.
Wilsons_Plover, Often gathers in groups during the nonbreeding season. Hunkers down in the sand to rest away from the water's edge.
Wilsons_Plover, Breeding adults have a black neck band. The long, thick black bill is diagnostic.
Wilsons_Snipe, Medium-sized pudgy shorebird with short, stocky legs. Intricately patterned with 3 long buffy streaks down the back and a striped head.
Wilsons_Snipe, Displaying males make a curious whistling noise ("winnowing"), created by air passing over modified outer tail feathers.
Wilsons_Snipe, In breeding season, often perches on fence posts to sing.
Wilsons_Snipe, Medium-sized chunky shorebird with a long bill. Note white belly, barred flanks, and dark underwings.
Wilsons_Snipe, Long-billed shorebird of inland wetlands. Usually found foraging on the ground, but also perches on posts or stumps.
Wilsons_Snipe, Intricately patterned in buff and brown stripes and bars, which provide camouflage in muddy pond edges, damp fields, and other wet, open habitats.
Wilsons_Snipe, Smaller than a Long-billed Dowitcher (left) with shorter legs and a pudgier body. Note buffy streaks down the back and striped head.
Wilsons_Snipe, Pudgy shorebird with a long bill and short tail. Note barring on the sides and 3 buffy streaks down the back.
Wilsons_Snipe, Found in muddy pond edges, damp fields, and other wet, open habitats often with thick, low vegetation where these well-camouflaged birds can quickly disappear.

Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny seabird with swallowlike proportions and flight. Note small head and bill, fairly short, broad wings, and long legs. Yellow webbing between toes is difficult to see but diagnostic.

Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny seabird with small bill and long legs. Charcoal brown with large white patch on rump and upper tail coverts, wrapping around onto undertail coverts. Widespread in world's oceans except North Pacific; fairly common in North Atlantic.

Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny seabird with small bill and relatively short, broad wings. Toes project beyond tail tip in flight. Note pale grayish bands on wings, created by pale tips of greater coverts.
Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny seabird with short tubenosed bill. White rump patch wraps around onto undertail coverts. Molts flight feathers sequentially, creating gaps in the wing outline.

Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Characteristic feeding behavior involves fluttering low over the water and pattering feet on the surface to maintain balance and stir up food particles. Note extensive white on undertail coverts.

Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny seabird with small tubenosed bill and fairly short, broad-based wings. Toes project beyond tail in flight. Large white rump patch wraps around onto undertail. Some individuals show very prominent pale bars in the wing.
Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Tiny charcoal brown seabird with prominent white rump patch. Toes project beyond the tail in flight.
Wilsons_Storm-Petrel, Often forms flocks at sea and feeds by pattering on the water and plucking food items from the surface.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Females and immatures have an olive crown. Some females show a small black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Females and immatures have an olive crown, but some females can have a small black cap. Note small patch of black feathers on the crown of this individual.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small entirely yellow warbler save for the black cap on adult males. Spends most of its time in the understory.
Wilsons_Warbler, Breeds in wet meadows and thickets near streams, especially those with willows and alders. Also found in aspen stands and young stands of evergreen trees.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Wilsons_Warbler, Small warbler with a small, thin bill and beady black eye. Entirely yellow below with an olive back. Adult males have a black cap.
Winter_Wren, Plump round ball with a stubby tail that it usually holds up. Brown overall with barring on the belly, tail, and wings. Paler below.
Winter_Wren, Small wren with a short tail and thin bill. Brown overall, but paler below with darker barring on the wings, tail, and belly.

Winter_Wren, Often bobs its entire body as if doing squats while they nervously look around in the forest understory. In flight they rapidly beat their tiny wings to move short distances between cover.
Winter_Wren, Plump round ball with a stubby tail that it usually holds up. Brown overall with barring on the belly, tail, and wings. Paler below.
Winter_Wren, Plump, round wren with a thin bill. Brown overall with darker barring on the wings, belly, and tail. Note pale white eyebrow.
Winter_Wren, Often bobs entire body as if doing squats while they nervously look around in the forest understory.
Winter_Wren, Plump round ball with a stubby tail that it usually holds up. Brown overall with barring on the belly, tail, and wings. Paler below.
Winter_Wren, Found in deciduous and evergreen forests with plenty of downed logs, standing dead trees, larger trees, and understory vegetation.
Wood_Duck, Gorgeous duck with intricate plumage: green, crested head, chestnut breast and other bold markings.
Wood_Duck, Warm brown plumage with grayer, slightly crested head. White teardrop around the eye; white also along the edge of dark blue "speculum" patch in the wings.

Wood_Duck, Male is spectacularly colored, with a glossy green head, chestnut breast, buffy sides, reddish bill, and red eyes. Wood Ducks have a unique shape among ducks—a boxy, crested head, a thin neck, and a long, broad tail. In flight, they hold their head up high, sometimes bobbing it. Overall, their silhouette shows a skinny neck, long body, thick tail, and short wings.
Wood_Duck, Grayish brown plumage with whiter throat, bright red eye, and red and white bill.
Wood_Duck, In flight the blue secondaries with a bold white stripe on the trailing edge are obvious.
Wood_Duck, Found on shallow lakes and ponds, often swimming near the edges among emergent or overhanging vegetation.
Wood_Duck, Gray underwings of breeding males contrast with the rest of the plumage.
Wood_Duck, Immature is similar to female in coloration.
Wood_Duck, Female lacks bright patterns of male, but has unique crested head shape and large white teardrop patch around eye.
Wood_Duck, Glossy green head with prominent crest at the rear, white throat, bright red eye, and red-and-white bill.
Wood_Duck, Fluffy young are dark above with pale yellowish underparts and face.
Wood_Duck, Often perches on tree limbs. Note white line at edge of blue "speculum" patch in the wing
Wood_Duck, Nests in cavities, including artificial nest boxes.
Wood_Duck, Often perches on branches, sometimes far from water.
Wood_Stork, Massive wading bird with long legs and a long and heavy curved bill. White overall with black flight feathers. The head is bare and scaly.
Wood_Stork, Juveniles look similar to adults, but have a pale bill that darkens over time and grayish feathers on the neck that are slowly lost as they get older.
Wood_Stork, Nests in colonies where it builds a messy stick nest in trees near water.
Wood_Stork, Massive wading bird with an enormous wingspan. White overall with black flight feathers. Often soars in thermals like raptors, with long neck extended and long legs trailing behind.
Wood_Stork, Massive wading bird with long legs and a long and heavy curved bill. White overall with black flight feathers. The head is bare and scaly.
Wood_Stork, Often seen soaring in thermals with vultures or other raptors.
Wood_Stork, Tall wading bird with a bald and scaly head and neck. White overall with black flight feathers.
Wood_Stork, Massive wading bird with long legs and a long and heavy curved bill. White overall with black flight feathers. The head is bare and scaly.
Wood_Stork, When approaching a roosting site, it drops its legs and awkwardly comes in for a landing.
Wood_Stork, Colonial nester in trees and shrubs in flooded woodlands or coastal sites.
Wood_Stork, Walks slowly through wetlands with its bill in the water feeling for fish and other prey. This video has no audio.
Wood_Thrush, Pot-bellied thrush with a short tail and a upright posture. Reddish-brown above and white with bold blackish spots below.
Wood_Thrush, Medium-sized thrush with a large round belly covered in spots. Sings a flutelike clear song from understory and canopy perches.
Wood_Thrush, Song is a musical series of flutelike notes. Typically sings from high branches at dawn and dusk.
Wood_Thrush, Reddish brown above with a white eye ring and streaky cheeks.
Wood_Thrush, Strong brownish black spotting on the underparts. Note white eyering.

Wood_Thrush, Parents typically feed nestlings a mixture of soft-bodied insects and fruits. The adults redistribute items that are not swallowed by nestlings, feeding it to other nestlings or consuming the leftovers themselves.
Wood_Thrush, Breeds in deciduous and mixed forests in the East with large trees and a moderate shrub layer.
Wood_Thrush, Forages for ground-dwelling insects by removing leaf litter and probing the forest floor. Usually pauses intermittently to check for insect movement before probing continues.
Wood_Thrush, Commonly breeds in matures forests of eastern North America with a high variety of deciduous tree species such as maples (Red Maple shown in video), oaks, and gums.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Large, lanky songbird with a long tail and a stout bill. Adults are light blue and gray above, with a whitish throat, grayish belly, and thin, partial breast band of pale blue.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Long-bodied songbird. Juveniles have a grayer head than adults, but otherwise look similar.

Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Note fairly thin, pointed bill, which works well to extract pinyon pine seeds from their cones. Bill is shaped differently than closely related California Scrub-Jay, which eats more acorns.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Residents in southern mainland Mexico are brighter blue above and whiter below with a darker ear patch and a less distinct necklace.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Pale blue and gray above with gray underparts and a thin partial necklace across the chest.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, In good light, they can look much brighter blue.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Often perches on exposed branches watching its surroundings. Note the partial and indistinct blue necklace.
Woodhouses_Scrub-Jay, Found in open habitats and pinyon-juniper woodlands of interior western North America, as well as backyards and pastures.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small rather drab warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes on its flat head.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small rather drab warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes on its flat head.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small rather drab warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes on its flat head.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Brownish warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes. Its tail is shorter than most warblers and is square tipped.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small warbler with a flat, black-and-buffy striped head. Brownish olive overall with pale legs.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small rather drab warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes on its flat head.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Spends much of its time in the low understory. The bill is pale and long.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Breeds in thickly vegetated steep slopes. From a distance note the flat head and long bill.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Small rather drab warbler with black-and-buffy head stripes on its flat head.
Worm-eating_Warbler, Breeds in deciduous and mixed forests with a dense understory and steep hillsides.
Wrentit, Plump birds with a long tail and tiny bill. Plain brownish-gray with paler, slightly streaked, pale pinkish bellies. Note pale eye.
Wrentit, Plump birds with a long tail and tiny bill. Plain brownish-gray with paler, slightly streaked, pale pinkish bellies. Note pale eye.
Wrentit, Small and plump with a long tail and pale eye. Brownish gray overall with a lightly streaked, pinkish belly.
Wrentit, Plump birds with a long tail and tiny bill. Plain brownish-gray with paler, slightly streaked, pale pinkish bellies. Note pale eye.
Wrentit, Plump bird with a long tail that it often holds up away from its body.
Wrentit, Found in coastal scrub and chaparral along the West Coast. Interior birds found in thickets along creeks, oak woodlands, mixed-evergreen forests, and dense shrublands.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Small, compact flycatcher. Yellowish olive overall with a strong white eyering and two whitish wingbars.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Small, compact flycatcher. Yellowish olive overall with a strong white eyering and two whitish wingbars.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Sings an abrupt and somewhat hoarse che-lek .
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Breeds in boreal evergreen forests and peatlands. Found in the understory of deciduous forests during migration. Note white eyering and yellow wash across belly.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Small flycatcher with a slightly peaked head. Yellow-olive above and yellowish below, but some worn birds may lack yellow wash below.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Flies out to grab insects from foliage or in midair sometimes returning to the same perch, a foraging behavior called flycatching.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Compact flycatcher with a white eyering and two white wingbars (but note that young birds can have yellowish wingbars).
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Often perches relatively still, only looking around with quick movements of the head.
Yellow-bellied_Flycatcher, Small, compact flycatcher that is yellow olive overall with a white eyering and whitish wingbars.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Woodpecker with a stout bill and vertical white wing patches. Males have a red crown and throat.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Sapsuckers have vertical white wing patches along the side of the folded wing. Underparts vary from whitish to pale yellow. Females have a red crown and a white throat.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Males typically drill holes in dead hardwood trees for nesting spaces.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Juveniles have a brownish wash over their bodies and a finely spotted crown. Like adults they have vertical white wing patches.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Drills neat rows of shallow holes to access tree sap.
Yellow-bellied_Sapsucker, Found in mixed evergreen and deciduous forests with aspen and birch trees.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long, slim bird with a long tail. Brownish above with rusty patches in the wing. From below, note large white spots on a black tail.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Large, slim birds with a long tail, a long yellow bill, and a hunchbacked appearance. From below, note large white spots on a black tail.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Often forages on tent caterpillars.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long-tailed bird with a curved yellow bill and rusty wing panels.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long and long-tailed with large white spots on the underside of the tail.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long, slim bird with a long tail. Brownish above with rusty patches in the wing. From below, note large white spots on a black tail.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, May wander north or east of breeding range in fall before migrating south.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Juvenile is similar to adult, but duller overall and with an all-dark bill until around 60 days of age.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long, slim bird with a long tail. Brownish above with rusty patches in the wing. From below, note large white spots on a black tail.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Found mainly among the canopies of deciduous trees; look for them in woodland patches with gaps and clearings.
Yellow-billed_Cuckoo, Long, slim bird with a long tail. Brownish above with rusty patches in the wing. From below, note large white spots on a black tail.
Yellow-billed_Loon, A large loon with a flat head and heavy, daggerlike bill. Breeding adult has a pale yellowish bill, red eye, black head, and extensive white markings on black upperparts.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Nonbreeding adult/immature is pale overall, with light brown upperparts, a whitish neck and throat, and an ivory-colored bill.
Yellow-billed_Loon, The world's largest loon species. Breeding adult has powerful yellowish bill, striking black-and-white plumage, and red eye.

Yellow-billed_Loon, Breeding adult has an incomplete necklace of white bars around the sides of the neck and a series of white spots on the upper throat. Depending on the head posture, can appear to have a prominent bump above the eye.
Yellow-billed_Loon, The upper half of the bill is straight, giving an overall look of an upturned bill.

Yellow-billed_Loon, Breeds on the arctic tundra, nesting on the ground very close to clear lakes. Loons' legs are positioned very far back on the body, aiding swimming and diving but making walking difficult.

Yellow-billed_Loon, Typically a bird of the far north, but rare individuals occasionally stray farther south, both along the coast and on inland lakes and reservoirs. Note pale overall appearance and upturned, ivory-colored bill.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Flies strongly on rapid wingbeats, with neck outstretched and feet trailing behind body.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Nonbreeding adult/immature has brownish upperparts, a light-colored neck, and a heavy, upturned bill with a pale tip.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Breeding adult intricately patterned with white necklace, checkered upperparts, and fine white spots on flanks.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Typically breeds on clear lakes on treeless arctic tundra.
Yellow-billed_Loon, Nonbreeding adult/immature is larger and paler overall than similar Common Loon. Note Yellow-billed Loon's larger and paler bill (especially at tip).

Yellow-billed_Magpie, Striking long-tailed bird of California's Central Valley with a yellow bill. Its white belly and wing patches stand out against its black head and iridescent blue wings and tail.

Yellow-billed_Magpie, Striking long-tailed bird of California's Central Valley with a yellow bill. Its white belly and wing patches stand out against its black head and iridescent blue wings and tail.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Vocal and conspicuous bird of the Central Valley. Often found with other magpies perched in the open and calling.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, In flight, the wings flash white and the long tail streams behind.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Often seen hoping or walking on the ground foraging for grain, acorns, carrion, and small mammals. Note long tail and bright yellow bill.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Forages on the ground in pastures and fields. Eats insects, carrion, and seeds.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Often seen hoping or walking on the ground foraging for grain, acorns, carrion, and small mammals. Note long tail and bright yellow bill.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Striking black, white, and blue member of the corvid family with a long tail and yellow bill. Highly social bird that forages, nests, and roosts in groups.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Frequently heard and seen calling from atop trees or fence posts. Note yellow bill and long tail.
Yellow-billed_Magpie, Restricted to the Central Valley in California. Found in oak savannas, open areas with large trees, and along streams. Also forages in grassland, pasture, fields, and orchards.

Yellow-billed_Magpie, Striking long-tailed bird of California's Central Valley with a yellow bill. Its white belly and wing patches stand out against its black head and iridescent blue wings and tail.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Large and bulky with a long tail and big head. Note yellow breast, white spectacles, and white mustache stripe.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Large and bulky with a long tail and big head. Note yellow breast, white spectacles, and white mustache stripe.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Small but bulky songbird with big chest, long tail, and heavy bill. Makes many kinds of calls, including a low, chattering scold and more musical. burbling notes.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Large and bulky with a long tail and big head. Note yellow breast, white spectacles, and white mustache stripe. Eastern birds have a shorter mustache stripe.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Rarely seen in sustained flight. Note rounded wings and light yellow lining to underwings.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Tends to skulk in low, dense vegetation, where it can be difficult to see.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Often eats fruit outside of the breeding season.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Found in thickets and scrubby areas. Often stays hidden in dense shrubs.
Yellow-breasted_Chat, Small but bulky songbird with big chest, long tail, and heavy bill. Calls, including a low, chattering scold.

Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Stocky and compact heron with a blocky head and thick neck. Adults have a boldly marked black-and-white head with a yellow crown, though the yellow can be hard to see depending on lighting conditions. Note gray underparts.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Juveniles are brown and streaky overall with fine streaking and spotting. Note the hefty black bill.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Thick-necked and relatively short-legged heron with a thick, all-dark bill.

Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Immatures take 3-4 years to attain adult plumage. Immatures are browner overall than adults with an adultlike head pattern that develops over time. This individual is starting to show a whitish cheek patch.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Flies with neck tucked in and feet trailing behind, sticking out past the end of the tail.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Feeds mainly on crabs and crayfish.

Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Males perform a neck-stretching display for females by slowly raising and quickly retracting their head while fanning their long shoulder plumes. Females sometimes reciprocate displays.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Compact heron with an upright stance; often stands with its neck tucked in. The bold head pattern and yellow crown are distinctive.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Stands still patiently waiting for prey or slowly walks in search of crabs, frogs, and aquatic invertebrates.
Yellow-crowned_Night_Heron, Found in coastal wetlands, barrier islands, saltmarshes, drainage ditches, mangroves, swamps, and sometimes wet lawns or fields.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, A medium-sized sparrow with a rusty back and a characteristic yellow eye. Residents from southern Arizona and New Mexico south to northern Jalisco, Mexico, have whiter underparts.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Gray overall with a rusty back, yellow eye and white outer tail feathers.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Males sing a 2–3 parted trill from elevated perches.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Plumage darkens from north to south with northern individuals having a whiter belly and a rustier back than individuals in Chiapas, Mexico, and Guatemala.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Juveniles are grayish overall with a rusty back and dark streaks above and below.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Walks, hops, and shuffles on the ground foraging for seeds and insects.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, A medium-sized sparrow with a rusty back and a characteristic yellow eye. Residents from southern Arizona and New Mexico south to northern Jalisco, Mexico, have whiter underparts.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, A medium-sized sparrow with a rusty back and a characteristic yellow eye. Residents from southern Arizona and New Mexico south to northern Jalisco, Mexico, have whiter underparts.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, Like other juncos, Yellow-eyed Juncos have white outer tail feathers that are most often seen in flight.
Yellow-eyed_Junco, A medium-sized sparrow with a rusty back and a characteristic yellow eye. Residents from southern Arizona and New Mexico south to northern Jalisco, Mexico, have whiter underparts.

Yellow-footed_Gull, A large gull with a heavy, bulbous-tipped bill. Adult has a white head, neck, and underparts; dark-gray upperparts; black-and-white wingtips; a yellow bill with a red spot; and bright yellow legs.

Yellow-footed_Gull, Individuals reach adult plumage after three years. Second-year birds are similar to adults, but have a black mark at the tip of the bill. During the winter months they have some light streaking on the head.

Yellow-footed_Gull, A large, long-necked gull with a heavy, bulbous-tipped bill. Breeds only in Mexico's Gulf of California. Adult has dark-gray upperparts, a clean white head and underparts, and a yellow bill with red mark.

Yellow-footed_Gull, Second-year birds have dark gray upperparts like adults, but with some brown feathers mixed in. During the winter, second-year birds have some streaking on the head and neck, while adults have a white head and neck year-round.
Yellow-footed_Gull, A large gull with a long neck and a thick bill with a bulbous tip.

Yellow-footed_Gull, Second-year birds are similar to adults, but show some brown in the gray upperparts and have a black tip to the bill. This species forages on beaches, in intertidal areas, in harbors, and at sea, feeding on fish, marine invertebrates and more.
Yellow-footed_Gull, Forages in intertidal areas, on beaches, in harbors, and at sea.
Yellow-footed_Gull, First-year birds have mostly white underparts, with some streaking on the side of the breast.
Yellow-footed_Gull, First-year plumage is variable, but note the heavy, mostly black bill; dark gray mask around the eye; black wingtips; mostly white underparts; and pink legs.
Yellow-footed_Gull, In flight, adult shows a white tail, white trailing edge to the inner wing, mostly black wingtips, and a white spot on the tip of the outermost primary.
Yellow-footed_Gull, In flight, the white rump of first-year birds contrasts with a black tail.

Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a stout body, a large head, and a long, conical bill. Adult males have a bright yellow head and breast and a black body. Note white patch on wings, obvious in flight.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a big head. Females are brown instead of black, with a duller yellow head and breast.

Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a stout body, a large head, and a long, conical bill. Adult males have a bright yellow head and breast and a black body. Note white patch on wings, obvious in flight.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Immature males are brownish black above with a paler yellow head and breast.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large, stocky bird with a conical bill. Females are brownish with a yellow throat and a patchy yellow head.

Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a stout body, a large head, and a long, conical bill. Adult males have a bright yellow head and breast and a black body. Note white patch on wings, obvious in flight.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Juveniles have buffy heads and underparts with a buffy and black scalloped-looking back.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Males sing a song that sounds like a rusty farm gate opening.

Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a stout body, a large head, and a long, conical bill. Adult males have a bright yellow head and breast and a black body. Note white patch on wings, obvious in flight.
Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Breeds and roosts in freshwater wetlands with dense, emergent vegetation such as cattails. Often forages in fields, typically wintering in large, open agricultural areas.

Yellow-headed_Blackbird, Large blackbird with a stout body, a large head, and a long, conical bill. Adult males have a bright yellow head and breast and a black body. Note white patch on wings, obvious in flight.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Adult males (Audubon's) have a yellow throat and rump and yellow patches on their sides.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Residents in Guatemala and eastern Chiapas, Mexico have black breasts and heads unlike individuals from the north that have grayer heads.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, "Myrtle" and "Audubon's" Yellow-rumped Warblers breed with each other where their rangers overlap, resulting in intermediate forms (also known as intergrades)
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Small songbird. Females (Myrtle) are brownish above with yellow patches on their sides, a yellow rump, and a white throat.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Females (Audubon's) tend to be grayer above with a yellow throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.

Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Resident females in Guatemala and eastern Chiapas, Mexico are darker brown-gray above with a yellow throat, yellow patches on their sides, a yellow rump, and a dark breast patch.

Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Immatures (Myrtle) are brownish and streaky throughout with pale yellow patches on their sides and a yellow rump. Amount of yellow on the sides and the amount of streaking varies.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Females (Myrtle) are brownish above with yellow patches on their sides, a yellow rump, a white throat, and a darker ear patch. Intensity of yellow varies.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Full-bodied Warbler. Adult males (Myrtle) have a black mask, a white throat, yellow patches on their sides, and a yellow rump.
Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Yellow-rumped Warblers have a characteristic yellow rump that is often visible when perched.

Yellow-rumped_Warbler, Found in open evergreen forests and edges, and to a lesser extent deciduous forests during the summer. In fall and winter found in open woods and shrubby habitats, including coastal vegetation, parks, and residential areas.

Yellow-throated_Vireo, Brightly colored vireo with a thick bill. Note the bright yellow eyering and lores ("spectacles"), and unstreaked yellow throat. The belly and undertail coverts are white while the head is olive-green
Yellow-throated_Vireo, Brightly colored vireo with bright-yellow spectacles, yellow throat, and white belly and undertail coverts. Typically seen in treetops.
Yellow-throated_Vireo, Song is a slow-paced series of rising and falling notes with a burry tone.
Yellow-throated_Vireo, Typically forages in treetops. Chunky, short-tailed appearance with a thick bill. Note the unstreaked yellow throat.

Yellow-throated_Vireo, Brightly colored vireo with a thick bill. Note the bright yellow eyering and lores ("spectacles"), and unstreaked yellow throat. The belly and undertail coverts are white while the head is olive-green
Yellow-throated_Vireo, Nests in a cup made of bark strips, dry grass, and pine needles, suspended in a horizontal fork of slender branches or twigs.
Yellow-throated_Vireo, Brightly colored vireo with a thick, hooked bill. Gray wings with two white wingbars; unstreaked yellow throat; white belly and undertail.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Large warbler with a long body and bill. Adults have a bright yellow throat, a black face mask, and a white eyebrow.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Forages by creeping along tree branches, probing into cracks, crevices, and bundles of pine needles. Note yellow throat, black mask, and white eyebrow.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Typically forages high in the canopy where it hops along branches, but sometimes forages on the ground during migration.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Adults have a bright yellow throat, a black face mask, a white eyebrow, and white underparts bordered by black streaking.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Large warbler with a long body and bill. Adults have a bright yellow throat, a black face mask, and a white eyebrow.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Occasionally visits feeders.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Breeds in pine forests, sycamore and bald cypress swamps, and riparian woodlands. Often forages high in the canopy.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Hops on top of branches foraging in crevices and pine needles for insects.
Yellow-throated_Warbler, Males sing a clear series of notes that descend slightly in pitch most often from high perches in the canopy.
Yellow_Rail, Small rail with a short tail, bill, and neck. Yellowish below and dark above with yellowish stripes down the back. Extremely secretive; runs quietly through wetland vegetation.
Yellow_Rail, Small rail with a short tail, stubby bill, and buffy yellow streaks down the back. Breeds in fresh and brackish sedge-filled marshes.
Yellow_Rail, Small, secretive rail of marshes that is very difficult to see. This video has no audio.
Yellow_Rail, In flight note white secondaries and stocky rather football-like shape.
Yellow_Rail, Small rail with a short tail, bill, and neck. Yellowish below and dark above with yellowish stripes down the back. Extremely secretive; runs quietly through wetland vegetation.
Yellow_Rail, Small rail with a short tail, bill, and neck. Yellowish below and dark above with yellowish stripes down the back. Extremely secretive; runs quietly through wetland vegetation.
Yellow_Rail, Small rail with a short tail, bill, and neck. Yellowish below and dark above with yellowish stripes down the back. Extremely secretive; runs quietly through wetland vegetation.
Yellow_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a beady black eye and stout bill. Adult males are bright yellow overall with a yellow-green back and chestnut streaks on the breast.
Yellow_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a beady black eye and stout bill. Females are yellow overall with a yellow-green back and mostly unstreaked yellow underparts.
Yellow_Warbler, Hops between branches to forage for insects on leaf surfaces: typical warbler behavior.
Yellow_Warbler, Adult male "Mangrove" Yellow Warblers have chestnut heads and chestnut streaking on the breast.
Yellow_Warbler, "Mangrove" Yellow Warblers occur in mangroves from Mexico to northern South America. Females/immatures are drab overall and have a grayish nape.
Yellow_Warbler, Commonly occupies riparian thickets or young forests during migration and in the breeding season.
Yellow_Warbler, Most Yellow (Golden) Warblers have a chestnut-capped and are residents in mangroves in the West Indies.
Yellow_Warbler, Immatures are paler yellow overall, although some can be almost entirely grayish.
Yellow_Warbler, Builds a deep cup nest constructed with grasses, strips of bark, and spider webs.
Yellow_Warbler, Immatures vary from pale yellow to brownish to grayish. Note large beady black eye and stout bill.
Yellow_Warbler, Small, round-headed warbler with a beady black eye and stout bill. Adult males are bright yellow overall with a yellow-green back and chestnut streaks on the breast.
Yellow_Warbler, Only female Yellow Warblers incubate the eggs, while males continuously forage to feed their mates.
Yellow_Warbler, Breeds in shrubby thickets and woods, particularly along watercourses and in wetlands.
Yellow_Warbler, Distinctive entirely yellow warbler. Often found foraging in shrubby understories.

Zone-tailed_Hawk, Medium-sized raptor with broad wings. Often mistaken for a Turkey Vulture, but note large white band on tail and dark trailing edges on wings. With good looks upper bands on tail are also visible.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Medium-sized all-dark raptor with yellow legs and bill.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Arched wings and a "tippy" flying style makes Zone-tailed Hawks resemble Turkey Vultures in flight. However, a bold white tail band helps separate these species in the field.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Immatures have finely barred outer flight feathers and a barred tail. Immatures also show dark trailing edges on the wings.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Perched immatures look all dark with a barred tail.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Zone-tailed Hawks build their nests within dense mixed evergreen-deciduous forests often on north-facing mountain slopes or near cliffs adjacent to streams.
Zone-tailed_Hawk, Found in dry, semiopen country, especially deciduous or pine-oak woodlands, often nesting in tall trees along streams.

Zone-tailed_Hawk, Medium-sized raptor with broad wings. Often mistaken for a Turkey Vulture, but note large white band on tail and dark trailing edges on wings. With good looks upper bands on tail are also visible.

Zone-tailed_Hawk, Often soars high with Turkey Vultures (top) when banding on the tail can be difficult to see. The bird at the bottom center shows one broad white tail band indicative of Zone-tailed Hawk.

Zone-tailed_Hawk, Medium-sized raptor with broad wings. Often mistaken for a Turkey Vulture, but note large white band on tail and dark trailing edges on wings. With good looks upper bands on tail are also visible.
